the merce cunningham dance company, celebrating its 35th anniversary with its longest new york engagement _ four weeks _ presented a premiere by cunningham on wednesday night
the dance at the joyce theater, for 11 dancers, is titled ``eleven.'' the music, by robert ashley, his first for the company, is titled ``problems in the flying saucer.'' the dance does not act that out
as always with cunningham, the dancers are proficient and fluidly graceful. they shift weight and hold poses without stiffness. a viewer may not know why one set of moves follows another, but the dancers are entirely purposeful in performing them
cunningham choreographs to use the entire stage, giving his dancers the look of freedom. a couple dancing together may not touch often but they stay in each other's general area. circles are negotiated slowly or spun with arms swinging broadly. often one leg is extended, while a dancer's body turns profile then turns again to face the audience
once, a woman dancers enters, walking with bent knees. it's amusing because it's so different from the expansive movements that other dancers on stage at that moment are doing
the ``music'' is two men talking, michael pugliese, with a french accent, and takehisa kosugi, in a near monotone. kosugi composed the music for the other two dances on the evening's program, ``doubles'' and ``grange eve.'' cunningham danced in ``grange eve.''
pugliese speaks first, saying a sentence fragment like ``there is no sound'' or ``off in the daytime.'' before he finishes a phrase, kosugi comes in on top of it, saying something like ``the south of france.'' even if one listens only to one speaker, phrases don't add up to sentences and not all words can be understood
there are many pauses between sets of phrases. since cunningham choreographs without music anyway, the dance flows on
program notes explain that ashley's work is an excerpt from a screenplay for an opera, ``odalisque,'' in which a lieutenant in a flying saucer explains to his captain something about a musician they have on board. the cunningham dance foundation commissioned this arrangement and instructions for performance
the present season, which ends march 27, also includes the new york premiere of ``carousal,'' done last summer at the jacob's pillow dance festival; a revival of the 1968 ``rainforest,'' and ``septet,'' which cunningham created in 1953, his company's first year. ``septet'' is danced to satie music; it was revived last year after a 23-year absence from the repertory
after the joyce season, the company will dance in san paolo, rio de janeiro and belo horizonte, brazil, from april 8 through 15. starting june 4, it will play seven german cities in two weeks, including presenting a premiere commissioned by the berlin festival
another dance will premiere at the avignon, france, festival, between july 30 and aug. 3. u.s. summer dates include july 21 through 23 at the american dance festival in durham, n.c., and aug. 22 through 27 at saratoga springs, n.y
many prominent panamanians say the nation's entire system needs changing, not just the leader, and even if gen. manuel antonio noriega goes the united states may be backing the wrong replacement
eric arturo delvalle, the ousted president washington supports, tried to dismiss noriega on feb. 25 as commander of the panama defense forces. noriega arranged for the legislature to dismiss delvalle instead, and the political and economic crisis has deepened since
the united states is mistaken in putting so much behind delvalle,'' said luis moreno, former manager of chase manhattan bank's local operations and until january 1987 a member of the government banking commission. moreno, an independent, met regularly with the president and cabinet ministers
delvalle and his people are spent,'' he said. ``noriega is laughing at this rallying behind delvalle, saying `this guy can't bring me down.'''
the reagan administration continues to recognize delvalle, now in hiding in panama, as the country's legitimate leader and is is applying economic pressure in an effort to get him back in office
noriega was indicted in florida last month on narcotics and money-laundering charges, which he denies, and the reagan administration portrays him as little more than a gangster. washington has indicated the economic heat will end if he steps down or is removed
roderick esquivel, who was delvalle's vice president and was removed with him, said: ``the object is not to change the face on the regime but to dismantle an entire corrupt and repressive apparatus of state.'' esquivel, who also is in hiding, made the comment during an interview at a safe-house
a former top official who left the government in a dispute with noriega said: ``in order to achieve democracy, it is the structure that has to be broken, not mr. noriega
the colonels and majors are involved in the same businesses he (noriega) is involved in. that implies a great degree of solidarity.''
the defense forces control the executive and legislative branches of government through the two political parties linked to them and all judges are political appointees, including the supreme court justices
not only does the military control the three branches of government, but it also controls the fourth estate, the media,'' said the former official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
noriega has closed all opposition media: three newspapers, two radio stations and a television channel
many people ask why delvalle, who had followed noriega's ordered until the february revolt, is seen as the man to change things
delvalle is important in that he changed the sense of hemispheric support for the government (with his attempt to depose noriega), but he has always been on the sidelines,'' said roberto brenes, a leader of the national civic crusade
the crusade, an alliance of about 200 business, professional, labor and political organizations, has led opposition to noriega since it was formed last june
on monday, it joined opposition parties in calling for a government of national reconciliation and transition. the document they issued did not say delvalle would head such a government, but recognized him as ``he who exercises the office of president.''
questions about what will and should happen next also dominate the daily lives of average citizens in this country, which has the panama canal as an integral part of its economy and uses u.s. dollar as its national currency
miguel correa, a truck driver, noted that delvalle, like others of noriega's recent critics, had been involved in his regime
why the sudden change of heart, when they were all part of the same dirty business?'' he said
among noriega's accusers hare retired gen. ruben paredes, his predecessor as defense forces commander; jose blandon, a former top adviser, and retired col. roberto diaz herrera, noriega's former chief of staff
the joint statement by the crusade and the opposition parties said delvalle, by his actions, ``committed himself to the changes necessary for establishment of a legitimate democracy.''
this caution came from the former high official: ``the more time that passes, the less viable becomes the delvalle solution.''
douglas grant mine, former ap news editor in buenos aires, argentina, now reports for the associated press from central america
two brothers pleaded guilty to attacking the son of comedian-activist dick gregory and three other black youths in an assault the judge called a sign of ``a cancer that is growing in our society.''
kevin ferreira, 23, and his brother vernon, 19, pleaded guilty tuesday to assault and violating the civil rights of christian gregory and the other blacks
charges are pending against two other white men in the november 1986 attack at a party in plymouth after a high school football game
kevin ferreira said the fight occurred because he was told that gregory and his friends referred to the other youths as ``white honky trash.''
brockton superior court judge george n. hurd jr. set sentencing for april 15
in this city, jesse jackson is the well-known social activist, a canny player in the back rooms of a world-class political hotbed
in greenville, s.c., he's the hometown celebrity who hasn't forgotten his roots
jackson hopes to cash in on both images and turn hometown sentiment into votes in two contests in the next week
south carolina holds democratic caucuses on saturday; the illinois primary is tuesday
arriving under chilly gray skies back in chicago on wednesday, jackson was triumphant, telling a rally of factory workers, `we get stronger every day.''
here, he founded the social action organization people united to serve humanity. here he makes his home, in a large comfortable house on a pleasant residential street, with his wife jacqueline and five children
halfway across the nation is jackson's other hometown. it was greenville where jackson stopped last week as he launched his final swing through the south on the road to the critical super tuesday contests
jackson came in first in the popular vote in those primaries and caucuses, and second to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the delegate count
in greenville, they remember jackson as the youngster who went off to be a college football quarterback, then launched a career as a minister and civil rights activist who followed dr. martin luther king jr
jackson saw familiar faces when his motorcade pulled up to the springfield baptist church last week to address a convention of ministers. it was this church, he told them, that he attended as a boy while his mother sang in the choir
greenville, a medium-sized city set among rolling hills with a rural atmosphere, was a major textile center in those days. but it fell on hard times as the mills began to close, jackson says
jackson took reporters to the projects where he lived as a boy. he went into his old apartment, a spartan brick unit with plastic flowers on display, the home today of a single mother of two who earns minimum wage putting pleats on skirts
the project's residents came out to shake jackson's hand as he strolled through the streets, secret service agents and tv cameras in tow
today, jackson's mother lives in a comfortable split-level home _ walls covered with tastefully framed photo layouts depicting jackson's life _ in a far more affluent neighborhood of greenville
there, a group of friends and family members celebrated jackson's night at home with a feast of sweet potatoes, corn bread, turkey, dressing, cobblers and other home cooking the likes of which is seldom seen on jackson's breakneck campaign
the next morning there was more home cooking _ biscuits and grits, this time with white farmers on a dairy farm near town
south carolina farmers told jackson how the nation's farm policy has brought them hardship. but they were noncommittal about whether they would vote for him
there is no such reticence when jackson gets home to chicago, a big industrial city whose people hurry along skyscraper-lined sidewalks, bundled up against the icy blasts that whistle along the streets and beneath the elevated rail cars
here the crowds that come to see him are his fans
at the general electric plant rally, the crowd knew what they wanted the candidate to do
jesse, help us save our jobs,'' their signs read
i've been working here 23 years,'' said mack fundes, a truck driver for ge's hotpoint refrigerator plant that is scheduled to close in a couple of years
nothing has changed here. it's time for change. i believe jesse would make a change,'' he said
richard gephardt grimaced a bit as he stood in a pole barn on a soggy afternoon, pondering a question from the tiny knot of democrats
the question was: ``do you really think you can beat jesse jackson and al gore here?''
after a pause, gephardt said: ``we're going to try very hard.''
throughout wednesday, the day after his disastrous super tuesday performance, gephardt doggedly trudged across rain-drenched south carolina, trying to explain his showing and pleading with democrats to give him a boost in saturday's caucuses
unless you're willing to stand up for change, it's not going to happen,'' gephardt said. ``if you will stand with me on saturday, we'll change those facts of life.''
only a month ago, gephardt was riding high after a win in the iowa caucuses. from there, he went on to a second-place finish in new hampshire, and won south dakota's primary a week later
but suddenly, he is fighting to keep his campaign alive
the difficulty facing gephardt was summarized at the jim harwell farm just outside this eastern south carolina town
as the recorded strains of country singer willie nelson wailed mournfully in the background, gephardt mingled with a couple of dozen party activists in what was billed as a farm rally for him to push some basic campaign themes he hopes will sway farmers in this heavily rural state
gephardt insisted throughout the day that his problem during the 20-state round of voting earlier in the week was the sheer size of the event. he said it prevented him from telling his story, leaving him victorious only in his home state
when i get my message out to the voters, i win,'' gephardt said. ``they didn't hear what i had to say; that was the problem.''
but when gephardt sounded his familiar tough-talking trade themes they got a lukewarm response
that was partly because the audience was tiny. only a couple of dozen people showed up at the farm. at an event earlier in the day at a threatened textile plant, his audience was composed almost entirely of elementary-school students bused in for the occasion. an evening rally in greenville found the room half empty
that's the price gephardt paid for his showing on the campaign season's biggest event, as attention focuses on other candidates like gore, jackson and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis who have reaped big harvests of delegates
we did not have a good outcome yesterday,'' gephardt said in a significant understatement
but he spent a lot of his time insisting he's in the race for the long haul
the race is on,'' gephardt said. ``i'm not where i'd like to be, but i think i have ample opportunity to make up lost ground and get back in the middle of this race and win.''
gephardt and his aides conceded their campaign could badly use a boost, and they busily drew up scenarios for keeping the effort alive
it's going to be tough; it's an uphill battle,'' said deputy campaign manager joe trippi. ``but that's what we're going to try to do.''
throughout the super tuesday campaign, gephardt was outspent by both gore and dukakis, and campaign consultant bob shrum conceded that a fourth-place showing won't make raising money any easier
it won't be as easy to raise money, but we'll raise money,'' shrum said. ``we're not penniless.''
gephardt insisted his financial picture is not all that bleak. his debts are modest, he says, and more federal matching funds are on the way
we didn't borrow, as others did, to run on super tuesday,'' gephardt said. ``maybe in retrospect we should have.''
but gephardt faces big hurdles if he's to regain momentum
south carolina is where jackson was born, and gephardt aide concede that he best they can hope for saturday is a second-place finish
the gephardt campaign has been downplaying next week's illinois primary, saying results will be muddled by home-state sen. paul simon's presence on the ballot
that leaves gephardt with a long stretch before he's likely to get any positive campaign news
he's pinning his hopes on michigan, which holds caucuses march 26, as a key blue-collar state where he hopes his tough trade talk will sell
it also drastically raises the stakes for gephardt
we're going to do well in michigan,'' he said. ``i need to do well in michigan.''
playboy publisher hugh hefner, standing arm-in-arm with his new girlfriend, announced a countersuit against his ex-lover, alleging she was unfaithful and her $35 million ``palimony'' lawsuit was a publicity stunt
but model carrie leigh's attorney says her action was brought to stop hefner from using and discarding young women
the 61-year-old hefner, who filed the $1 million cross complaint wednesday, said ms. leigh filed her lawsuit to advance her own career and that of her lawyer, marvin mitchelson
you're talking about the criminal misuse of the judicial system,'' hefner told reporters as he stood with his new girlfriend, 24-year-old kimberley conrad, at the playboy mansion. ``i want to put a stop to that.''
ms. leigh could not be reached for comment because her phone number is unlisted
mitchelson, on vacation in paris, said from his hotel:
this is my 32nd year as a lawyer, and i've never filed a lawsuit in my life that didn't have merit
the palimony suit was really developed to remedy situations involving people like hugh hefner,'' he continued. ``he has made a lifelong practice of getting involved with teen-age girls, living with them for a few years and then discarding them.''
ms. leigh's suit filed last month claims hefner reneged on promises to marry her, father her child and support her
hefner's attorney, anthony glassman, said he filed two legal actions wednesday in superior court
one was an answer to ms. leigh's palimony suit in which the founder of playboy magazine denied his former girlfriend's allegations
the second was the cross complaint seeking $1 million plus court costs, attorney fees and an amount of punitive damages to be determined by the court
glassman said the $1 million represents the value of cash, jewelry, furs and other gifts hefner gave to ms. leigh, now 24, while the two were together from april 1983 to january
hefner's complaint also accuses ms. leigh of fraudulently telling hefner she loved him and was faithful to him
on repeated occasions, ms. leigh was sexually unfaithful to him,'' glassman told reporters
hefner said he bears no animosity toward ms. leigh, but believes now that she had planned for years to eventually sue him for palimony
i think what is happening now is something that was in her mind from the beginning,'' he said
he added that friends, relatives and business associates tried to warn him about her but he didn't listen to them
i just saw what i wanted to see,'' he said
hefner, meanwhile, said he has not asked ms. conrad to sign any legal papers absolving him of financial responsibility should their relationship eventually disolve
he said he met the tall, blonde model, playboy magazine's january playmate of the month, when she came to the mansion last may to pose. he said the two didn't become involved until after ms. leigh left the mansion
ms. conrad declined comment on ms. leigh
i'm just here to support hef, and i came after carrie leigh, so i really have no comment,'' she said
anti-apartheid banners adorn the halls at the university of the western cape, and the main plaza is called freedom square. an exile once jailed for terrorism is receiving an honorary degree this week
western cape is the most radical university in south africa. its chief administrator, professor jakes gerwel, said when installed as rector last year that he plans to preside over ``an intellectual home for the left.''
the militance of students and staff contrasts sharply with the government's intent in 1960, when it established a college near cape town for mixed-race students as part of its segregated education system. j.g. miering, a white professor who headed the school in the 1960s, said, ``the white guardian was obliged to provide these facilities for his colored (mixed-race) ward.''
the university remains predominantly mixed-race, but gerwel is determined to increase black enrollment beyond the current 13 percent. his administration is openly committed to preparing students for a post-apartheid south africa led by the now-voteless black majority
we are a political thorn in their sides,'' gerwel said of the government. ``the establishment doesn't know how to deal with us.''
a case in point is the university's decision to award an honorary degree friday to breyten breytenbach, a white poet who left south africa in 1982 after serving seven years in prison for terrorism. the government denied breytenbach a visa, and a relative is to accept the award on his behalf
at the same graduation ceremony, one of the main speakers will be cyril ramaphosa, general secretary of the militant black national union of mineworkers
last month, the university's governing council elected anglican archbishop desmond tutu as chancellor. tutu, winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize for his anti-apartheid campaigning, is the first black chosen for the honorary post
gerwel, who as professor of afrikaans literature was a leading faculty activist, is the second mixed-race rector. the first, richard van der ross, led from 1975-87 and is credited with establishing the school's anti-apartheid orientation
most of south africa's 3 million mixed-race people live in the cape town region. the university's enrollment has soared from 6,128 in 1984 to 11,500 this year, and multiple construction projects can't keep pace with the need for more facilities
sometimes we cannot teach our students because there's no place to put them,'' said owen van den bergh, a white who is dean of education. ``we have to hope they don't come to class.''
the government has cut subsidies to all universities by about 25 percent this year and adopted regulations to allow further cuts at schools that fail to curb campus protest. the university of the western cape and the predominantly white university of cape town successfully challenged the regulations in court, but gerwel expects the government to try other tactics to tame his school
one of gerwel's priorities is to expand the university's ties with the anti-apartheid movement. the campus often serves as a venue for meetings of militant organizations
going to uwc is considered by students to be part of the political struggle,'' said di bishop, vice president of the black sash civil rights organization and a university sociology researcher. ``you're not going off to an ivory tower for a couple of years.''
security forces have entered the campus several times in recent years to break up protests with tear gas and whips. there is animosity among some students toward remaining conservative professors
there also is conflict over language. some of the 600 teachers lecture in english and others in afrikaans, the language that many mixed-race people have inherited from the mainly dutch-descended whites who run the government
van den bergh forsees increasing tension as black enrollment rises. he also sees internal pressures building up in individual students
there are a lot who say the right things politically but are fundamentally conservative,'' he said. ``they are worried about getting a job, getting a house.''
gerwel said the university could ``arm itself'' against government pressure by adding more professional schools. it now offers graduate degrees in law, pharmacy and dentistry. but he also wants the curriculum to accommodate those who have been excluded from power and privilege
in a changed south africa, it's not going to be a first world, high-tech society,'' he said. ``what is this new south africa we are working for? we're trying to find out. the english-language universities are geared to capitalism. we research alternatives.''
although the government provides most of their funds, the university and the 10 predominantly white universities have almost total control of curriculum and campus policies. the black universities are tightly controlled by the government and cooperative administrators, and student protests at these schools has been repressed
gerwel said his job ``keeps one awake at night.''
but i wouldn't want to be in any other position. we're at the cutting edge of adjusting to a black-led society.''
despite prospects for an economic boom the next few years, the northern industrial states face a creeping erosion of their political clout and claim on federal dollars: a demographic bust
a study by the northeast-midwest institute, a public policy group with ties to the region's members of congress, says the industrial north is enjoying bigger income gains but has far less population growth than the sunbelt
the population of the 18 northern states stretching from minnesota to new england will grow by 3.8 percent through the 1990s, only about half the national average, according to the study titled ``the state of the region'' and released wednesday
in recent years, the south and west have drawn industries and jobs from the north. even though the northeast's overall economy has rebounded, the region will not be able to keep up with the competing areas' population growth, the study said. it estimated that the population of the west and south will grow 10 percent in the next decade
for the northeast, the lagging population growth will translate into fewer representatives in the house and fewer federal dollars from programs based on the number of people in a state or area, the study said
political influence, from the selection of the president in the electoral college to appropriation fights in the house of representatives, will shift further to the south and west,'' the study said
the northeast could lose 14 house seats after the 1990 census, the report said. the region lost 15 seats after the 1980 census, for a total projected loss in representation of 13 percent in the 1970s and 1980s, the study said
the lagging population gains in the northeast and midwest result both from lower birth rates and migration to southern and western states, the study said
the short-term economic outlook for the entire region is positive,'' the study said. the northeast shared in the national return to prosperity from 1983 to late 1986, with new england benefiting the most
unemployment has dropped below the national average in parts of the region, but the northeast is unlikely to regain many of the 1.3 million manufacturing jobs lost between 1980 and 1986, the study said. the population that remains, however, is enjoying faster per capita income growth than that of southerners and westerners
the south and west for the first time topped the northeast and midwest in manufacturing employment in 1986. the sunbelt had 9.5 million employees on manufacturing payrolls, compared with 9.4 million in the northeast and midwest
other points made by the study were:
_the northeast and midwest invested more in public school education than did other regions
_the trend toward an older population was more evident in the northeast and midwest than in the rest of the country
northeast states covered by the report were: connecticut, delaware, illinois, indiana, iowa, maine, maryland, massachusetts, michigan, minnesota, new hampshire, new jersey, new york, ohio, pennsylvania, rhode island, vermont and wisconsin
the privately funded northeast-midwest institute was formed in 1977 at the request of members of the house and senate from the region. the study also was sponsored by two legislative groups: the northeast-midwest congressional coalition and the northeast-midwest senate coalition
international travelers arriving at some major u.s. airports this summer will be greeted by agriculture department inspectors operating x-ray machines to see if their baggage harbors illegal food or plants
the x-rays, in addition to sharp-nosed canine sniffers, will be used to check arrivals at 11 u.s. international airports for illegal sausages, mangoes and other contraband
imported meats can carry exotic diseases that could devastate american livestock,'' james w. glosser, head of the department's animal and plant health inspection service, said wednesday. ``fruits and vegetable coming into the country can carry pests that could seriously damage american crops.''
agency inspectors have used x-ray equipment in puerto rico and hawaii for departures for several years, with interceptions of prohibited agricultural items doubling, he said
the new systems for arrivals were recently installed at international airports in miami; honolulu; san juan, puerto rico; houston; and chicago
additional equipment soon will be installed at international airports in atlanta; new york; washington; boston; los angeles; and san francisco
the usda agency also is installing large signs at the 11 airports telling travelers that x-rays are being used to check their baggage
although most people willingly declare their agricultural products, we do come across some intentional violators,'' glosser said. ``that's only natural, considering that we encountered an estimated 43 million air travelers in 1987. some ignore the regulations and others are not even aware of them, despite all our information efforts.''
glosser said the agency uses several methods to find smuggled agricultural items, including trained beagles to sniff out the errant braunschweiger here, the occasional mango or two there
finally, we rely on the deterrent effect of penalties,'' he said. ``we fine violators $25 to $50, payable on the spot. we currently collect about $30,000 per month, and we have collected nearly $1.8 million since 1984. fines are deposited in the u.s. treasury.''
glosser said the travel industry plays an important role in helping educate the traveling public, including the distribution of booklets about agricultural items that may be brought into the united states
a brochure also can be obtained by writing: travelers tips, usda-aphis, g-187 federal building, hyattsville, md. 20782
an absorbent called super slurper invented in the 1970s is helping tiny worms kill destructive root weevils that threaten citrus trees, according to an agriculture department scientist
william j. schroeder, an entomolgist in the department's agricultural research service, said wednesday the super slurper keeps soil moist so that the microscopic worms, or nematodes, can survive and kill weevils that chew the tree roots
in tests, 60 percent of the weevils were killed, compared with only 25 percent without the help of the worms. schroeder said that weevils can kill up to 30 percent of the trees in a grove if not controlled
the nematodes haven't been used before as a natural weevil control because they die quickly if soil dries out, schroeder said
other agency scientists are looking into the use of super slurper and nematodes to see if they can control pests of corn and vegetables
agency scientists in peoria, ill., invented the cornstarch-based super slurper 14 years ago. it has been successfully used in dozens of commercial products, including body powder, medical dressings and many other items
schroeder, who works at the department's horticultural research laboratory in orlando, fla., said he thought of super slurper in 1985 when he observed nematodes dying in dry soil
i realized that in order to use this biological control (nematodes), we would have to keep the soil moist,'' schroeder said
with its ability to hold up to 2,000 times its own weight in water, superslurper provided the answer, schroeder said.
companies could mass-rear nematodes and ``package billions of them alive'' for sale to growers, who then could mix the worms with super slurper for application on tree roots before planting, he said
for citrus groves already inhabited by the beneficial nematodes, schroeder said he is looking into the possibility of injecting super slurper into the soil with a nozzle
the tiny worms, which survive as long as the soil is kept moist, penetrate the weevils and release lethal bacteria, which don't harm plants or other organisms, schroeder said
a man accused of trying to sexually assault miss usa pageant co-host tracy scoggins contends she invited him to her room, a claim the actress dismissed as absurd
tracy scoggins has turned some very serious charges into a very cheap publicity stunt in a desperate attempt to benefit her sagging career,'' said attorney jose montes jr., who is representing the man
montes said tuesday that miss scoggins met his client, pedro concepcion padilla, in traffic on interstate 10 on feb. 25 and invited him to her hotel room. montes declined to elaborate on the highway encounter
the actress, best known for her role as monica colby in tv's prime-time soap opera ``the colbys,'' told police padilla attacked her that day in a hotel elevator
padilla was arrested and gave police and a judge a false name and address, authorities said. after posting $100 bail, he was rearrested, and then released on $100,000 bail
miss scoggins, who was here for the pageant, described the attack at a news conference on feb. 26, and a first-person account with her byline is in the latest edition of the national enquirer
miss scoggins, in a statement released tuesday by her publicist, said she had never seen padilla until he got on the elevator
the allegations made by mr. padilla's attorney are so blatantly absurd they should not be dignified by comment. but i do want to say, though, that it's a pity a woman has to be a victim twice,'' she said
leave it to ronald reagan to find something good to say about budget deficits
for decades, reagan has denounced the big-spending crowd in washington that he said was dooming future generations to a life of debt and penury
in his seven years in office, he has promised repeatedly to do something about it and blamed democrats in congress for the deficits that nevertheless flourished
in a recent interview with lou cannon of the washington post, however, reagan was reminded of the sizable deficit he will leave behind, and was asked:
do you think that this is going to have a negative consequence on the next generations? is this going to be a real burden for the country?''
reagan's reply:
it's a burden. there's no question about that. but ... not the disaster some people proclaim. ... one of the major factors in our budget right now is the interest. but who gets that interest? and you find out then that a great many institutions, universities, educational institutions of all kinds, that part of their endowment are government bonds. and so a lot of that interest is going to them ... (and) to individual americans ...(as) part of their savings, instead of putting it in the bank or something
so, instead of it being something that's just disappearing down a rat hole, it's a kind of a redistribution ... of national wealth in that these institutions and so forth are getting this interest from the government. now maybe some of them would have to be getting straight grants from the government if they were not getting that interest. so, no, i don't think it's a disaster.''
reagan, still saying that he was ``disappointed that we haven't been able to do better'' and that ``the congress added to that budget,'' conceded that his position was ``really a reversal of roles'' for him
it sure is
as the president noted: ``way back before i ever thought i would be governor, when i was just out making speeches on the mashed-potato circuit about things that i thought should be changed ... i was complaining about the fact that, for almost 60 years now, with only eight single-year exceptions, this country has been running a deficit.''
it still is running a deficit, but now reagan calls it a redistribution of wealth
as the president would say, it reminds one of a story. in fact, one of reagan's favorite stories
the story is about two boys, one a pessimist and one an optimist, who are taken to a psychiatrist. he puts the pessimist in a room full of shiny new toys and finds him crying because he's afraid the toys might break. the optimistic child is put in a room with piles of horse manure and is found joyfully exclaiming, ``i know there's a pony in here someplace.''
it's the same way with deficits. ronald reagan always knew there was a pony in there someplace
a telephone repair crew balked at fixing a downed wire until their customer agreed to hold the lion
they wrote on their work report, `lion in yard. no way,''' said dannie carper, 51, an indiana bell supervisor from south bend who helped indianapolis clean up from an early march ice storm that roared in like a you-know-what
carper verified on monday that the householder owned a year-old lioness named chasta. the owner agreed to leash her so that carper could reattach the wire. ``it was just a big old 225-pound puddy tat,'' he said
carper had his picture taken with chasta. ``i have one where i've got my arms around her and she's chewing on my shoe,'' he said. ``i wasn't scared. but when she was chewing on my shoes i was afraid maybe she thought they were pigskin.''
chasta has found a new home on a farm in suburban noblesville
the man known as the godfather of east european dissidents says the reforms of mikhail s. gorbachev and the promised soviet withdrawal from afghanistan are nudging other warsaw pact nations toward greater independence from the kremlin
eastern european nations will insist on trying to find ways toward greater autonomy from the soviet union,'' said milovan djilas, whose native yugoslavia parted with moscow in 1948
similar nationalistic impulses also are being expressed in the non-russian republics of the soviet union, such as armenia, azerbaijan, and the baltic states, where the kremlin has been cracking down on demonstrations
in the west, said djilas, people ``should have hope, but not illusions, should be strong but not unreasonable'' in reacting to gorbachev's foreign and domestic policy initiatives
djilas, now 77, began his dissidence in 1953, a year later quit his posts as yugoslavian vice president and member of the communist party politburo, and was imprisoned from 1956-61 by yugoslavia's then-president, josef broz tito
from prison, he wrote his best known work, ``the new class,'' in which he argued that communist leaders in the soviet union and throughout eastern europe had created a system in which power, wealth and privilege were as abused as in the governments they replaced. his writings made him an icon in the west, and became a model for dissidents throughout the communist world
djilas, who addressed the heritage foundation last week and later was interviewed by the associated press, last visited the united states in 1968. the government of yugoslavia took away his passport in 1970 and did not restore it until 18 months ago
i am not a good boy,'' he said, grinning impishly despite his advanced age and a nagging heart condition. the yugoslavian government, he said ``is not very happy about my speaking'' but apparently has given up its futile efforts to silence him
western attention to his predicament made life easier, he said
i think the west and america saved me,'' he said. ``certainly, my fate would have been much worse if public opinion had not been aroused on my behalf.''
djilas had warm words for gorbachev, whose reforms he said were an attempt to end the repressive system imposed on the soviet union and eastern europe by soviet dictator josef stalin
even if kremlin conservatives topple gorbachev, djilas predicted, the process will continue
gorbachev is a man in the middle of the party, between the hardliners and more radical elements like (boris) yeltsin,'' who was forced to quit his post as the communist party first secretary for the city of moscow because he criticized gorbachev for going too slow
the reforms and the promised ``soviet withdrawal from afghanistan will strengthen democratic elements in the soviet union'' and encourage other warsaw pact nations in their own economic and political experiments, said djilas
east european leaders are trying to avoid a confrontation with moscow while seeking greater independence, he said. ``there is no sign of an uprising.''
yugoslavia is farthest along in this crisis of communism,'' retaining a communist government while allowing market forces to play a powerful role in the economy, he said
the crisis is also acute in poland, where the army stepped in to preserve communist rule in 1981, and where the economy is mixed between state and private ownership, said djilas
we cannot exclude that poland would develop a different (non-communist) social system, and still remain within the warsaw pact'' and thus pose no military threat to the kremlin, said djilas
world experts on children's health are gathered in a french alpine town to review an immunization project that has been saving millions of young lives and to plan ways of helping more
anyone who is anyone in international aid will be at this meeting,'' said dr. ken warren of the rockefeller foundation. ``people want to come because this is a group that is actually doing something and not just talking.''
the three-day meeting in talloires, france, opens today
among those expected to attend are dr. jonas salk, discoverer of the polio salk vaccine; barber conable, president of the world bank; james p. grant, the unicef executive director; former world bank president robert mcnamara, and joshua cohen, director of the world health organization
they will join leaders of other international aid agencies, physicians and health ministers from at least 13 countries
the symposium is sponsored by the task force for child survival, whose members are the united nations children's fund, who, the world bank, the united nations development program and the rockefeller foundation
these organizations have been working together since the early 1980s on an international campaign to immunize children against polio, diphtheria, whooping cough and tetanus. the project, aimed particularly at developing countries, has been a stunning success
the percentage of children vaccinated against the five deadly diseases has risen from 5 percent in 1974 to 50 percent today. experts predict that by the early 1990s, nearly every child in the world will be immunized
in a little over a decade a public health revolution has quietly taken place,'' said dr. ralph h. henderson, director of who's expanded program on immunization
henderson said the vaccination campaign against measles, neonatal tetunus and whooping cough is saving the lives of more than a million children each year in the developing world. another 200,000 children are being saved from the paralysis of polio, he said
warren, in a telephone interview from london, called the project ``the single most remarkable example of international interagency cooperation i've ever seen.''
one of the 11 papers to be reviewed at the meeting deals with the anticipated eradication of polio from the americas y 1990
if this effort is successful, it may be possible to launch a global polio eradication campaign early in the 1990s,'' said henderson. ``a world without polio would be a fitting gift from the 20th to the 21st century.''
the participants also will discuss controlling diarrheal diseases, caring for pregnant women and providing low-cost vaccines to impoverished nations
dr. william foege, executive director of the task force and former director of the centers for disease control in atlanta, will open the meeting with background for discussions on population control
health ministers or their representatives are expected from china, india, indonesia, brazil, nigeria, pakistan, mexico, egypt, senegal, colombia, morocco, peru and uganda. together, the countries account for well over half the world's children
representatives of donor agencies will represent the united states, japan, switzerland, france, west germany, britain, canada, italy, the netherlands, denmark, norway, sweden and finland
the nuclear regulatory commission has fined the owner of the north anna nuclear power plant $100,000 after operators failed to respond promptly to a equipment malfunction, officials said wednesday
monitoring instruments on two pipes carrying steam to the plant's generators malfunctioned, and operators did not respond for about 10 hours, according to the nrc, which imposed the penalty against virginia power co
under nrc rules, operators must take action within an hour
the incident, which occurred nov. 4 when the utility was restarting north anna unit 2 after refueling, caused no injuries or release of radiation
the nrc said that the violation, involving part of a non-nuclear system, did not pose a direct safety hazard
however, the instruments provide information necessary to reactor safety, and if steam is not moving correctly to generators, the nuclear systems could overheat, utility and nrc officials said
the instruments could also be used in responding to steam-line ruptures. in 1986, at virginia power's surry nuclear plnat, four workers were killed by scalding steam and water from a failed pipe
the commission said because similar incidents occurred previously at north anna, the fine was doubled from $50,000, the typical amount for such violations
the utility said it would not contest the fine and it disputed only the nrc's contention that previous violations were similar
virginia power has taken action to ensure a violation will not happen again, including improved training of operators, said utility spokesman james e. mcdonald jr. no workers were dismissed or disciplined, he said
the north anna nuclear unit has three main steam lines, and each has two of the instruments. in the november incident, one instrument failed on each of two lines
mcdonald said operators initially were unaware the instruments were malfunctioning
virginia power has been fined 13 times since it began operating nuclear plants in 1972
for a brief moment, president reagan was transported back in time _ hurling a pigskin to a wide receiver at a sentimental celebration of notre dame's knute rockne and his own days as a hollywood star
the gipper'' returned to the notre dame campus wednesday to pay tribute to the late football legend and dedicate a 22-cent stamp issued in honor of the coach's 100th birthday
it was a nostalgic trip into the past for ronald reagan, the one-time actor, sports announcer and college football player who clearly reveled in the crowd's friendly applause
the notre dame gathering of students and faculty _ including many wearing roman collars _ roared approval as they were treated to clips from reagan's 1940 film portrayal of notre dame football star george gipp in ``knute rockne: all american.''
the film showed the fresh-faced reagan, playing gipp, as he playfully kicked footballs high above the playing field while pat o'brien, playing rockne, persuades him to join the team
another clip showed o'brien, as rockne, giving a pep talk to his players at halftime of a 1928 game against army, with both sides scoreless. gipp had died eight years earlier, but the coach tells his charges that on his deathbed the young athlete said, ``some time when the team is up against it and the breaks are beating the boys, tell them to go out there with all they got and win just one for the gipper.''
army went ahead in the third quarter, 6-0, but notre dame went on to win the game, 12-6. army was one yard from the tying touchdown as time ran out
reagan's supporters adopted the ``win one'' phrase during his presidency to help garner support for his programs. and the nickname ``the gipper'' has since stuck
at the end of his speech, the filled-to-capacity crowd was silent as reagan tried to repeat the lines from gipp's deathbed scene. few, however, noticed that reagan flubbed the line and instead of saying ``gipper,'' actually pronounced it ``gippet,'' since his listeners erupted in a joyful cheer at the sentimental moment
handed a football, reagan hurled it towards members of the notre dame football team seated strategically near the podium
aiming at one young man who held his arms high, reagan heaved the pigskin _ directly, it turned out, at heisman trophy winner tim brown. again, the crowd roared approval
reagan had told his audience that the role of gipp ``was a young actor's dream'' but that playing in a film about rockne ``was more than that'' to him
i know that, to many of you today, rockne is a revered name, a symbol of greatness and, yes, a face on a postage stamp,'' he said
but my generation, well, we actually knew the legend as it happened _ we saw it unfold. and we felt it was saying something important about us as a people and a nation,'' the 77-year-old president said
most of all, the rockne legend meant this: ... that on or off the field, it is faith that makes the difference, it is faith that makes great things happen.''
rockne, a graduate of the roman catholic college, was its head football coach from 1918 to 1931. he compiled a record of 108 victories, 12 losses and five ties. during his tenure, the fighting irish were undefeated in five seasons and won six national championships
the white house has worked for years to produce picture-perfect events to frame the president as the nation's leader _ but few could have been as nostalgic
he loved it,'' said agriculture secretary richard lyng, a 1940 notre dame graduate who traveled with reagan aboard air force one
the cabinet secretary said reagan particularly enjoyed tossing the football
the president threw a perfect strike,'' lyng added with a laugh
an autopsy determined that heart disease caused the death of divine, the 375-pound female impersonator who starred in the cult film classic ``pink flamingos,'' the coroner's office says
there was no evidence of drugs or alcohol. he died in his sleep of an enlarged heart, probably due to the obesity,'' steve stewart, a los angeles county coroner's spokesman, said wednesday
the cause of death was listed as hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, or enlarged heart, stewart said. the coroner's report showed that divine, whose real name was harris glenn milstead, weighed 375 pounds
the 42-year-old actor, who appears in the current release ``hairspray,'' was found dead in his bed monday at the hollywood regency plaza hotel
manager bernard jay said milstead had a long-term weight problem, but otherwise was found to be in excellent health during a medical checkup friday
the democratic party's losing presidential candidates have found one bright spot in the darkness of their defeat: the odds are that nobody will be able to claim victory by the time the primaries are over in june
the big winners in this week's round of primaries and caucuses dismiss that as wishful thinking
if you get within a decent distance, you're not going to be stopped,'' said rick hutcheson, who oversees delegate selection for tennessee sen. albert gore jr.'s campaign. ``i don't think there's any doubt in the world that there are plenty of delegates out there for a first-ballot nominee to develop.''
true, there are enough delegates yet to be allotted that a clear winner could emerge. but the odds certainly are growing longer that any candidate can come up with the magic number needed to win on the first ballot at the democratic convention in atlanta
mathematically and politically this process is in gridlock,'' said terry michael, spokesman for illinois sen. paul simon, who suffered a shutout in tuesday's round of primaries and caucuses
hutcheson, who worked in former president jimmy carter's 1976 presidential campaign, said the then-candidate carter wound up the primary season with about 85 percent of the delegates he needed to win the democratic presidential nomination. the remaining delegates gravitated toward a winner, he said
i think that same scenario will develop here,'' hutcheson said
simon, who held just 35.5 delegates both before and after tuesday's balloting, is banking on nobody being able to gain the 2,082 delegates needed to win the democratic presidential nomination when the primaries conclude on june 7, with california and new jersey, two of the largest states with a total of 423 delegates at stake
the person or persons with the greatest potential to negotiate his way to a first-ballot victory will be the candidate who is hottest at the end,'' michael said
the democrats have yet to allocate 2,524 of their national convention delegates, and another 258.65 delegates list themselves as uncommitted. thus the available pool of delegates to be won between now and early june would be 2,782.65. partial figures result from party rules that divide up some votes at the convention
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who was leading the field of democratic candidates with 456.5 delegates, needs to win another 1,625.5 to wrap up the presidential nomination. or, put another way, he has to win more than 58 percent of all the delegates that are still left to be won _ roughly twice as well as he's done so far
dukakis was followed in the delegate count by jesse jackson with 395.55 and gore with 346.8
the virtual three-way tie prompted carter to observe that ``i think it's accurate to say the chances are less likely that one of the candidates will arrive in atlanta with a clear majority.''
new york gov. mario cuomo, a non-candidate who nonetheless has said he would consider stepping into the void at a deadlocked convention, still says he wants to see his party hold a ``quiet convention.'' but he concedes that it will be difficult for any of the current candidates to secure a first-ballot victory based on results of the primaries and caucuses
michael said if no candidate holds a majority by the time the primaries conclude, the rule of conscience that binds delegates to the candidates will begin to bend and break
but susan brophy, an aide to dukakis, called that assertion ``ridiculous.''
these people get into the process because they believe, a, in the process and, b, in the candidate _ and not necessarily in that order.''
and, jude barry, an aide to missouri rep. richard gephardt's presidential campaign, agreed, saying, ``i think there's going to be loyalty and commitment. we're prepared to protect what we have, as i'm sure the other candidates will as well.''
gephardt, who had 143 delegates after super tuesday, is hoping to hang on with a strong showing in the michigan caucuses on march 26 and the congressional democratic caucuses on april 19 and 20. gephardt also expects to win big when his house colleagues pick 210 of their own to be national convention delegates. another 43 delegates will be picked by senate democrats
our hand certainly will not be weak with that wild card,'' barry said
simon, meanwhile, is hoping to score a victory next tuesday in his home state of illinois
texas on wednesday sued to bar shipments of florida citrus in an attempt to protect its fruit crops from citrus canker
u.s. district judge filemon vela on wednesday denied the state's request for an emergency stay of a federal order feb. 11 lifting a 3-year ban on shipments of fresh florida citrus into texas and other citrus-producing areas
vela scheduled a hearing for monday on the suit, which accuses the u.s. agriculture department of lifting the quarantine without giving proper notice and an opportunity for a public hearing
florida citrus was quarantined after an outbreak of citrus canker in florida in 1984. the bacterial disease can cause defoliation, lesions that render the fruit unmarketable and premature dropping of the fruit from the tree
on feb. 15, four days after the quarantine was lifted, texas imposed an emergency 30-day ban on florida citrus, but a federal court in austin on overturned the ban, ruling that federal action takes precedence over state
paul martin, director of pest management for the texas department of agriculture, said texas at least would like to keep florida fruit out of the lower rio grande valley, where the state's $65 million citrus industry is concentrated
the issue is, we're dealing with a real serious disease in this case that is a threat to the industry,'' he said
florida producers maintain that the canker presents a minimal threat to the texas citrus industry, and some growers there sued to stop the texas quarantine
a major business lobbying group is trying to keep congress from passing new nationwide clean air legislation, claiming it will cost too much, reduce jobs and increase the trade deficit
david m. roderick, chairman of the environment committee of the business roundtable, said wednesday that any legislation should be targeted only at areas with dirty air
however, he did not offer specific suggestions for such regional measures, and said the decisions should be left to the environmental protection agency
roderick commented as the business group released a report claiming that clean air legislation passed by the senate environment and public works committee earlier this year would cost the economy between $15 billion and $73 billion. it said the most likely figure is $32 billion, and also claimed that the measure would eliminate between 300,000 and 600,000 manufacturing jobs
roderick, who is chairman of usx corp., complained about acid rain provisions in the bill. he said the government should wait for the final report of the national acid precipitation assessment program, a 10-year, 12-agency research effort that isn't due for completion for another 18 months
he said complying with the committee-passed bill would cost his own company's u.s. steel corp. subsidiary $1.5 billion to $2 billion
we would import more semi-finished product,'' worsening the trade deficit, he said
roderick said the business group also objects to tougher new controls on toxic chemical and auto emissions
a person who buys a round for a drinking companion may be held liable if the companion gets into an auto accident, an oregon appeals court ruled wednesday
the decision involved a suit filed by the red steer bar in portland against richard howard, whose stepson lonnie d. johnson got into a accident in 1982 that injured another man
the bar settled with the injured man, james solberg, for $425,000 and then sued howard, who according to the suit accompanied johnson to three bars, the two buying drinks for each other, on the day of the collision
lawyers for the bar claim howard should be responsible for some of the damages because he knew or should have known johnson had a drinking problem, had been convicted of drunken driving and had been in accidents while drinking
multnomah county circuit judge lee johnson dismissed the lawsuit, finding noi legal basis for it. but the court of appeals on wednesday reinstated the case
the appeals court said howard could be found to owe damages under a common law negligence theory that says someone who ``substantially assists or encourages'' negligent conduct by another can be held liable
the decision is believed the first ruling in oregon to deal with liability of a drinking companion at a commercial establishment
in dismissing the lawsuit, the lower court judge said it would ``an unprecedented and unwarranted extension of common law liability to hold that howard had a legal duty ... to solberg.''
when a nurse in a hospital waiting room called the name gnau, two cousins who hadn't seen each other in 60 years stood up
i looked at him and asked him his name,'' said 73-year-old elmer gnau, a retired tool and dye maker. ``i knew if he said kenneth, he would be my cousin. not many people are named gnau.''
tuesday's chance meeting was an emotional experience for the two soft-spoken men, who last saw each other when they were children in louisville, ky. elmer was 13 and kenneth 3
i never thought i would have recognized him,'' said kenneth gnau, 63. ``but i looked up, and my stomach came right up to my throat. he has the face of my father. i almost cried.''
elmer gnau, who lives in la grange, ky., said he was in florida to visit his son, jerry gnau, in north lauderdale when the after-effects of a bout with pneumonia sent him to the hospital
kenneth gnau, who retired to margate with his wife, was waiting for an x-ray of a shoulder injury
the cousins, whose fathers were brothers, planned to visit each other later this week after kenneth gnau has shoulder surgery
union members in the south have given the heave-ho to one of the two democratic presidential candidates who courted them most actively and sent a strong signal to their once reluctant leaders to play ball with the other
jesse jackson, shunned by the afl-ci0 in 1984 in its failed effort to help put walter mondale in the white house, received a 37 percent plurality of votes from union households in 12 southern super tuesday primaries, according to abc-tv exit polls
only 10 percent of union voters in the same primaries cast ballots for rep. richard gephardt of missouri, point man the past three years for organized labor's top priority in congress _ retaliatory trade legislation
with massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and sen. albert gore of tennessee equally sharing the other half of the union vote tuesday, the afl-cio is no closer to making a democratic presidential endorsement than it was a year ago
unlike 1984 when mondale's challengers pinned a ``special interest'' tag on labor after its early endorsement of him, union leaders have proclaimed all of the still viable democratic candidates this year as acceptable to them
consequently on tuesday there were none of the union volunteers and phone banks brought into action in the southern primaries four years ago to stop then-sen. gary hart's threat of taking the nomination away from mondale
also absent tuesday was union rank-and-file worker turnout. only 5 percent of those voting in the democratic southern primaries came from union households, according to the exit polls
we have a problem of labor being with everyone, so nobody is doing anything,'' said joan baggett, political director of the bricklayers union who took her vacation the past three weeks to work as a volunteer for dukakis in the south
the up side is we haven't alienated any of our members by endorsing,'' she said. ``the down side is that we haven't excited them either. we're just not getting people to the polls.''
jackson's strong showing among those union members who did vote tuesday indicates he may be the exception. while blacks compose 14 percent of the u.s. population, they represent a larger 20 percent share of 19 million unionized workers nationwide and an even greater proportion in the south
still, for jackson to get 37 percent of the union vote, some of the support had to come from white workers, whose cause jackson has championed on hundreds of picket lines over the past four years
he's been out there on the lines and in the strikes every time labor has called on him and this is a healthy response to that,'' said jerry clark, political director for 1.1-million-member american federation of state, county and municipal employees
loretta bowen, who holds the same title for the communications workers of america, said white members of her union were slated as jackson delegates in the south and have expressed a keen interest in him in new york as well
as a spokesman for the gut issues that affect organized labor, he's articulating them better than any of the candidates,'' she said. ``and the fact there has been no endorsement has helped him a lot.''
but ms. bowen, who personally favors dukakis, and other labor political activists believe jackson's plurality of support will fade as the primaries move next week to illinois and then on to other rust belt states like michigan, pennsylvania and ohio, where unions are much stronger
the buzzword already is electibility, and i've never seen that kind of november strategy ever emerge this early before in our union,'' she said
allen zack of the united food and commerical workers union, noting gore's increased use of tv spots emphasizing his pro-worker record in congress, said all of the democratic candidates are now going after the labor vote
jesse's talking their language better,'' zack said. ``he's not trying to tell some laid off steel worker in alabama about some high-tech job in the future. he's talking about restoring their standard of living today.''
for that reason, zack said he was surprised that gephardt with his emphasis on slashing trade imbalances through retaliatory quotas against foreigners who restrict their imports of u.s. goods got no better than 10 percent of the union vote tuesday
of course he didn't have the money to get on the air as much,'' zack said of gephardt. ``if super tuesday confirms anything, it's the power of tv advertising. it's quite obvious from the turnout and the results that a parade hasn't formed yet for labor leaders to rush out in front of.''
officials for the afl-cio said members of its affiliated unions running on delegate slates for jackson, dukakis and gore all won seats tuesday at the democratic national convention in july after failing to get a single delegate in new hampshire's primary three weeks ago
we didn't do much with gephardt because gephardt didn't do much,'' said rex hardesty, a spokesman for the federation
keith geiger, a vice president of the national education assocation, the nation's largest union with more than 1.7 million members and not a part of the afl-cio, said it also won convention delegate seats for each of the three democratic front-runners tuesday
