civil rights pioneer rosa l. parks has received a pacemaker, and is expected to leave the hospital in a few days, a spokeswoman says
mrs. parks was in satisfactory condition wednesday, a day after the operation at johns hopkins hospital, said hospital spokeswoman ghita levine
the 75-year-old detroit woman, who was admitted to the hospital sunday, was in baltimore for medical tests and to help plan a birthday tribute to her in june, ms. levine said
in 1955, mrs. parks was arrested for refusing to give up her seat to a white man on a segregated bus in montgomery, ala. the black community retaliated by boycotting the buses
former gov. charles robb was among the casualties of the super tuesday presidential primaries, and he wasn't even running for anything
robb, one of the architects of the multistate primary election, said he was knocked out tuesday night when he walked into a closed glass door while trying to leave his washington office as he talked to a television cameraman
i haven't had a sensation like that since the last time i played in a football game,'' said the democrat
the door, which is normally open, did not break
robb said he ``blacked out for a few moments'' but did not require medical attention. minutes later, he cut short an appearance on cable news network. ``i couldn't remember why i was there for a few minutes,'' he said. ``finally, i said on the air that i wouldn't be doing the viewers a service by continuing.''
robb said he talked to other news organizations throughout the night, but asked that interviews be kept brief
people kept trying to get me to go to the hospital, but i was hard-headed,'' he said
new york designer alexander julian plans a return to his native north carolina this summer with a new men's clothing store that he hopes will be the beginning of a national chain
julian will open a retail store here in july, said barry miguel, creative director for alexander julian inc. of new york
as a native north carolinian, alexander has a great affinity for the state,'' miguel said in a telephone interview. ``at the same time, he feels charlotte is a growing city and a growing marketplace.''
the new stores will sell an upscale line of clothing and accessories called the alexander julian collection. ``we've expanded our men's collection,'' miguel said. ``we have more sportswear now than previously.''
although, julian, the 39-year-old son of a chapel hill haberdasher, lives just outside new york in greenwich, conn., he makes no secret of his love for north carolina
he's designing uniforms for the charlotte hornets, a new national basketball association franchise. for that work, julian is being paid 10 pounds of north carolina barbecue, delivered once a month to his new york office
actor tom selleck, tv's thomas magnum on ``magnum p.i.,'' is hanging up his pistol this may, and not even the writers guild strike is getting in the way of the show's final episode
fortunately, we already have a completed shooting script,'' producer chris abbott said tuesday. ``what we're trying to do is get the last episode done to the very best of our ability.''
abbott said work on the final episode should end in april. a date for the two-hour episode of the 8-year-old show has not been set, but it will be in may
about 9,600 movie and television scriptwriters went on strike monday after rejecting a final offer by the alliance of motion picture and television producers
non-medical factors like patients' insurance coverage and marital status may influence how aggressively they are treated for lung cancer, a study of more than 1,800 cases suggests
the research raises the possibility that doctors may be influenced by more than simply patients' medical needs in deciding how to treat them
however, more treatment may not always mean better care. the study found that people who received surgery, radiation or chemotherapy for lung cancer lived no longer than those who do not, ``suggesting that the additional treatment was given largely to those who had little or nothing to gain from it.''
other experts cautioned that discrimination against the unwed and uninsured are not the only possible explanations for the study's findings
the study published in today's new england journal of medicine was written by dr. e. robert greenberg and other doctors from dartmouth and the university of vermont
it was based on 1,808 lung cancer cases, virtually all of those reported in new hampshire and vermont between 1973 and 1976
treating lung cancer is often futile. surgery offers the only chance of cure, but in most patients the disease has spread too far for it to help. radiation and sometimes chemotherapy may be used to ease symptoms
the study found that cancer patients were more likely to undergo surgery if they were married or had private medical insurance. those who didn't get surgery were more likely to receive radiation or drug therapy if they had insurance
some doctors may be disquieted to learn that potentially curative or palliative (symptom-relieving) treatments were not provided to patients who seemed less able to pay or who lacked a spouse,'' the researchers wrote. ``our findings do suggest that the presence of inequities in the medical care of poor and socially isolated patients with lung cancer.''
however, in an accompanying editorial, drs. robert j. mayer and w. bradford patterson of dana-farber cancer institute in boston said there are other possible explanations
for instance, they raised the possibility that married people might seek medical attention earlier, when their disease is more treatable, because their spouses are sensitive to symptoms that otherwise might have been ignored. and instead of assuming that the poor get too little treatment, it's possible that those with insurance get too much, simply because they are able to pay
mayer and bradford wrote that it would be ``clearly undesirable'' for such factors as insurance coverage to influence medical treatment
they added, ``it would be premature and potentially dangerous, however, to conclude that worrisome factors such as these do contribute substantially to the decision-making process,'' based on review of doctors' handling a kind of cancer that cannot be effectively treated
jesse jackson collected 2.5 million votes on super tuesday, more than any other democrat and enough to cause a re-examination of the conventional wisdom that a black cannot be nominated for president in the america of 1988
if jackson were white, i think he'd be president,'' says howard university political science professor ronald walters, who was jackson's deputy campaign manager in 1984 and is the author of a new book, ``black presidential politics in america.''
if he were white, he wouldn't be in the race,'' says ben j. wattenberg, a scholar at the american enterprise institute and co-editor of public opinion magazine
walters says jackson's experience in the civil rights movement is more than the equivalent to service in legislative halls. and he cites jackson's electrifying quality
charisma _ say what you will, it still counts in politics,'' he says. ``just ask ronald reagan.''
wattenberg, on the other hand, contends that a black could be elected president in the america of 1988, but not one with jackson's lack of experience holding public office nor his controversial record
jesse jackson went to cuba and said, `viva che guevara,' praising a man who dedicated his life to the export of communism to south and latin america,'' wattenberg said. ``had any other politician in american life ever said anything like that, he might have been scandalized and drummed out of the race.''
the question of jackson's electability takes new relevance in light of his super tuesday showing. network polls said jackson won between 8 and 10 percent of the white vote in the south, twice as much as four years ago
forty-four percent of republican voters and 29 percent of democratic voters polled by abc news in a dozen southern states said they would not vote for jackson if he were the democratic nominee. by comparison, 37 percent of republican voters and 45 percent of democrats ruled out a vote for pat robertson. gary hart was rejected by 44 percent of republicans and 35 percent of democrats
jackson drew more votes than michael dukakis or than albert gore jr., who boycotted the earlier primaries but nonetheless was propelled into the ranks of democratic front-runners on the strength of his showing tuesday
lucius barker, a political science professor at st. louis' washington university who was a jackson delegate in 1984, said the he-cannot-win argument is becoming a code for opposition to jackson on racial grounds
it is going to look more and more odd for people to say that,'' he said. ``if you had a white candidate who had the kind of support jackson has, he would be picking up endorsements, he would have momentum and you would have the next nominee.''
jackson acknowledges the existence of a racial barrier to his winning the nomination. in campaign speeches, he tells the apocryphal story of two hard-hit farmers in iowa. one says to the other he likes jackson's message and politics, ``but...''
declares jackson: ``i want those people to move from `but' to `therefore.'''
some surveys show 15 to 20 percent of the population would reject any black on racial grounds
it is probably higher,'' said robert smith, professor of afro-american politics at howard university, who nonetheless believes the positions jackson takes are a handicap as substantial as that of race
i would say he would not be nominated or elected if he were white,'' he said. ``a substantial number of white persons who object to jackson do so more because of his ideology than his race.''
agreed al thornton, jackson's maryland issues director: ``it may just be that any liberal would have a problem getting elected.''
but paul peterson, director of the center for the study of american government, said, ``whenever any candidate has enthusiastic support within the black community, it is going to cost him support within sectors of the white community.''
joseph grandmaison, democratic chairman in new hampshire, believes the disadvantage jackson suffers from race is offset by the loyalty of his natural constituency
look at super tuesday _ 25 percent of the voters could immediately identify with him,'' grandmaison said
i think that's good. it's healthy,'' he said, comparing jackson's gains from race to the loyalty americans of recent ethnic origin feel toward dukakis, son of greek immigrants
wattenberg said he regards jackson ``as a political genius.'' he says a black ``would surely get the nomination'' if he combined the political skills of a jackson and the moderate positions of a tom bradley, the black mayor of los angeles who narrowly missed being elected governor of california
i'm not saying there is no racism in america; we all know there is,'' wattenberg said. ``but the right candidate could deal with it.''
the earl of carnarvon said egyptian relics found in his family mansion were brought to britain legitimately by his grandfather and howard carter, the man who discovered the tomb of tutankhamen
antiquities officials in egypt have said they may try to recover the trove of 300 objects discovered recently in highclere castle, the ancestral home of the fifth earl of carnarvon, grandfather of the current earl
but they said they will take no action until more is known about the find
the fifth earl, himself an egyptologist, financed the expedition led by carter which found the almost intact and gold-filled tomb of the pharaoh in egypt in 1922
the records we have discovered show these items were brought to england legitimately, with the knowledge of the egyptian government, by my grandfather and howard carter,'' said lord carnarvon
he said he had informed the egyptian ambassador in britain of the find ``but i don't expect any serious claim to be made by the egyptian government as this could involve the major part of my grandfather's collection, which is in the metropolitan museum of new york.''
ibrahim el-nawawy, undersecretary of state for the egyptian antiquities organization, said in cairo on tuesday that he was excited by the find but wants to determine what it includes before taking action
it is difficult to say what steps we will take,'' he said. ``we will have to go back through our records to see if the items were registered and legally taken out of egypt.''
the fifth earl died in 1923 from an infected mosquito bite, nurturing a myth that the 19-year-old pharaoh who died in 1323 b.c. had put a death curse on anyone who violated his tomb
secretary of state george p. shultz says he will press efforts to revive the middle east peace process because he is ``absolutely convinced there is an answer out there.''
talking to reporters after meeting wednesday with the house foreign affairs committee, shultz said his plan for peace between the israelis and palestinians is ``a pretty good and balanced concept.''
shultz had just briefed the committee privately on his recent mission to the middle east
what we really need to have happen is to get started, get started on negotiations,'' shultz said. ``i'm absolutely convinced that if we can ever get the key people talking and negotiating that there's an answer out there.''
committee chairman dante fascell, d-fla., said afterward that ``there was tremendous support for what the secretary has undertaken.''
fascell said stern israeli action to quell persistent violence in the occupied territories has convinced most members of congress of the urgent ``need to find a way into a peace process that will provide security for all of the inhabitants of the middle east.''
if a vote had been taken in there it would have been unanimous in support for what the secretary is trying to do,'' fascell said
the vote of confidence in shultz comes a week before the planned visit here by israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, who on wednesday expressed astonishment at a letter from 30 senators who said israel should be willing to give up control of occupied land in return for middle east peace
shamir has blocked attempts inside the israeli cabinet to force a vote on the shultz plan. the plan calls for an international conference, to be followed by talks on self-administration for palestinians in the occupied territories and negotiations on the final status of the west bank and gaza strip
your letter came as a surprise, at a crucial moment in the peace efforts,'' shamir wrote in a three-page response. ``we were astonished by the words of criticism you leveled at us on the formula of `territory for peace.'''
shamir's letter was sent to sens. carl levin, d-mich., and rudy boschwitz, r-minn., said levin administrative assistant gordon kerr. both senators, strong supporters of israel, were out of town and unavailable for comment wednesday night
twenty-three democratic and seven republican senators had sent a letter to shamir last week in which they noted that israel in the past had supported the idea of ``land for peace'' by returning the sinai peninsula to egypt
they noted that shamir had rejected ``this expression of territory for peace'' and expressed hope that the prime minister's statement ``did not indicate that israel is abandoning a policy that offers the best hope for long-term peace.''
shamir, in his response, said israel accepts the u.n. security council resolution that provides for an israeli withdrawal from land captured in the 1967 war but he did not agree to israel's eventual withdrawal from the west bank and gaza
shamir has opposed an international conference on the middle east on grounds it would put israel at serious disadvantage
but fascell suggested that it might be possible to hold an international conference that would not disadvantage israel, especially if the ground rules for the meetings did not permit an imposed solution or give participating countries veto power
sen. bob dole sounded the first negative note of the tv campaigns leading up to next week's illinois presidential primary with an attack on vice president george bush's iran-contra role
with his candidacy at stake in illinois after losing all 17 super tuesday contests, the kansas senator on wednesday revived an ad that says ``bush approved selling arms to the ayatollah'' at the same time he chaired a terrorism task force that said america would never sell arms for hostages
the ad says bush has ``changed his story nine times'' and owes voters ``an honest answer'' about his role in the affair
bush was nearly two-thirds of the way to the gop nomination after sweeping the super tuesday states. he is hoping to ride tv ads and local endorsements to an illinois victory that would end the senate republican leader's bid
bush's initial tv ads in illinois emphasized his connection with president reagan. in one ad he and reagan are shown walking together, arms around each other, projecting an old-pals image
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis led the democratic field after super tuesday with victories in seven states. he and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee said they would compete full-tilt in illinois despite the presence of favorite sons jesse jackson and sen. paul simon
dukakis started two ads tuesday night in illinois. in one, a massachusetts official of the international bricklayers union says dukakis's economic policies ``put people to work.'' the other ad highlights dukakis' experience as a chief executive and says it is unique to the democratic field
dukakis spokesman steve akey said dukakis spent $1.5 million on tv advertising for super tuesday. ``we haven't made the decision on a total media buy for illinois but we'll be on a significant amount,'' akey said
gore spent close to $3 million on super tuesday media and won six states. spokesman paul risley said that ``we fully intend to run a full (media) campaign up there'' in illinois, but no spending figure has been fixed
there was some possibility that missouri rep. richard gephardt would buy illinois television time, but spokesman mark johnson said the congressman would save most of his resources for the march 26 caucuses in michigan
we'll definitely do a full-scale (tv) effort in michigan,'' johnson said. as for illinois, ``we're still considering that option.''
gephardt suffered devastating losses on super tuesday, spending $1.1 million on television ads but winning only his home state. part of his problem was being the target of negative ads by both dukakis and gore
akey said the dukakis campaign went negative on super tuesday to counter ``distorted gephardt campaign ads.'' asked if the campaign is ready for a gore offensive, he replied, ``we are always prepared to respond.''
jackson and simon said they planned little or no advertising in their home state. ``i offer illinois 30 years of service rather than a 30-second commercial,'' said simon, who skipped the super tuesday contests
jackson won five states on super tuesday with a minimal $100,000 media campaign and is expected to do well saturday in south carolina, where he was born. his campaign is in debt but raised a substantial amount of money in february and may buy more media time in new york, california and other large states later in the election season, according to campaign manager gerald austin
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,617.82 points, up 12.43 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on thursday
george bush and michael dukakis both have large cash reserves to protect their delegate leads as their rival presidential hopefuls must refill campaign coffers depleted by the super tuesday marathon
dukakis, who leads the democratic delegate chase, was sitting on a cache of $2 million and anticipating $1 million more in matching funds next week, said campaign finance chief robert farmer
it was not known exactly how much cash bush has on hand as he tries to follow up his sweep of 16 gop primaries with a knock-out punch against sen. bob dole of kansas in next tuesday's illinois primary and beyond
but bush's campaign has been better heeled and more frugal all along than dole's or pat robertson's
bush had more than $9 million in the bank at the start of february, the bush campaign's director of operations, ede holiday, said wednesday. the bills are still coming in from the super tuesday states, she said, but ``we clearly have plenty of money left.''
at dole headquarters, spokeswoman dale tate said: ``we aren't in the hole. we have cash on hand.'' she declined to say how much. the dole campaign was anticipating staff cutbacks
thomas rath, a senior dole strategist, said in chicago that the campaign will have enough money to run commercials in illinois. he said the kansas senator raised more than $240,000 last week
robertson said tuesday night: ``i do have resources left. we have the largest donor base of any candidate and i can carry all the way to new orleans.''
the former television evangelist had spent $17.6 million through january, and ended that month with $5.5 million in cash but debts of $6 million
what jesse jackson calls his ``poor campaign with a rich message'' has raised $600,000 since the iowa caucuses feb. 8, according to campaign manager gerald austin. that is more than the civil rights leader has ever raised before in such a short time
austin said the jackson campaign has $250,000 in cash on hand and anticipates $600,000 in federal matching funds in mid-march
jackson said his wins in five democratic primaries in the south came despite being outspent 20- and 30-to-1 by al gore jr. and dukakis on television ads. jackson says he spent just $100,000 on ads in the super tuesday states
austin said jackson will be buying more television time in large states like new york and california, and he anticipates earmarking $30,000 of his $200,000 illinois budget for television
a gore campaign spokesman, paul risley, said the tennessee senator spent ``somewhere close to $3 million'' on ads in the super tuesday states. the dukakis campaign said it spent $1.5 million, while rep. richard gephardt bought $1.1 million worth of air time
gephardt blamed his meager returns on super tuesday _ he lost everywhere but at home in missouri _ on his inability to counter the drumbeat of gore and dukakis ads
with 20 states and a million dollars, we just could not get our message ... in front of the voters,'' gephardt said. he claimed they spent up to $7 million to defeat him
gephardt's deputy campaign manager, joe trippi, said gephardt has $250,000 on hand and debts of only $75,000. trippi said the campaign hopes to raise $500,000 over the next two weeks
illinois sen. paul simon, who bowed out of the super tuesday contests to make a low-budget stand at home, said of his campaign, ``it's kind of a hand-to-mouth operation.''
the simon campaign has missed one payroll and is in danger of missing a second. but simon raised $932,000 in february and soon will get $364,000 in matching funds, spokesman terry michael said
simon owes $145,000, but ``we are in much better financial condition right now than either the gore or the gephardt campaigns,'' claimed michael
the cigarette girl has returned to the fabled rainbow room on the manhattan skyline like a vision from an old movie of wasp-waisted men in tails and gorgeous dames in sequined gowns
cigars, cigarettes?'' she coos to the swells sipping cocktails, a girl with a tray of smokes, a jaunty pillbox hat, puffed sleeves, pumps and fishnet stockings, a neckline down to there and a skirt slit up to here
this is the 1980s, though, and you may call her a ``cigarette woman.'' the people who run the rainbow room atop the art-deco rca building use both terms
the rehabilitation of the famous rockefeller center nightspot reportedly cost $25 million, much of it for new plumbing, lighting, kitchens, carpets and custom work. but there was enough left over to hire cigarette girls
they seem to fit in beautifully,'' said joseph baum, the restaurateur who masterminded the restoration intent on recapturing the nightclub's glory days of the '30s and '40s. ``it's a lighthearted expression of the time
they're in their wonderful flouncy dresses and their little pageboy hats _ it just makes everyone smile. i think that is just part of the scene,'' he said
the four girls _ and cigarette girl katherine reddick prefers that term _ were chosen from the ranks of pagers and coat-checkers. ``it sounded interesting,'' said ms. reddick, 24, of manhattan
i'm here not so much to sell cigarettes, but i'm really adding elegance to the room,'' she said, though sales are brisk, with occasional $100 nights and plenty of generous tips. ``i get lots of comments. people say it brings them back to the '30s and '40s. i'm glad to be able to reminisce with them.''
her costume is a 1930s style created by theatrical costume designer carrie robbins. ``i saw it and said, `no problem,''' ms. reddick recalled with a smile
i wanted it so that it was suggesting rather than suggestive,'' baum said. ``it's lighthearted, rather than what a lot of people have in mind when they think of a cigarette girl. there's plenty of romance without having to add to it.''
and just what do people have in mind? judging from the movies, perhaps a bit of a tart, a young woman in the wrong kind of place at too late an hour?
i've run into so many ladies who were cigarette girls in the '40s,'' said ms. reddick. ``they were flabbergasted to see me. if i help bring back those memories, that's a great feeling. they say being a cigarette girl in those days was a very, very important thing
of course, they did it without having their parents find out _ they were working in bars.''
patrons of the new-old rainbow room welcome the women who sell the cigarettes at $2 a pack with smiles
whenever i thought of a cigarette girl, it was in a 1930s movie, with a big, chic nightclub,'' said tom cordisco, 27, of brooklyn. ``that's what it reminds you of.''
that's just what baum had in mind. ``a lot things that were part of that scene disappeared,'' he said. ``costs went up, places didn't do these sort of things for a long time.''
bringing back cigarette girls, he said, ``brings back the sound of astaire, and lobster thermidor, and dancing, and the rainbow.''
the head of an opposition cultural group was sentenced to two months in prison because of the troupe's latest ``street happening'' satirizing the government, an opposition activist said
in another development, solidarity leader lech walesa criticized police for using force to break up student demonstrations in warsaw and krakow
about 50 supporters of the opposition group orange alternative, some carrying a banner reading ``missiles _ no, sanitary pads _ yes,'' handed out cotton pads to women in wroclaw on tuesday, said jacek kuron, a warsaw opposition activist. feminine hygiene products are in short supply in poland and tuesday was international women's day
police moved in quickly and halted the demonstration in the southwestern city, arresting orange alternative leader waldemar frydrych, 34, and five other people, said kuron
on wednesday, frydrych was sentenced to two months in prison on a charge of causing public unrest. the action marked one of the few times since a september 1986 amnesty for political prisoners that a lower court has sentenced someone to prison for a politically motivated offense
in almost all cases, people were held up to 48 hours and released after being fined
kuron said two other orange alternative supporters were each fined the equivalent of $80
he said the orange alternative members joked with the court by arguing that karl marx, the founder of communism, was actually a bearded lady
frydrych has been detained at least half a dozen times since september for organizing various orange alternative ``happenings'' in wroclaw in which demonstrators have dressed up as santa claus, lenten penitents and even secret policemen to satirize government policies
walesa's comment on wednesday came one day after club-wielding riot police clashed with youths demonstrating for more academic freedom on the 20th anniversary of student protests against censorship and political repression
on tuesday, police charged into hundreds of demonstrators in warsaw and krakow. the government said 83 people were arrested and all but 15 had been released
the students were calling for restoration of academic freedoms won during the 1980-81 solidarity labor upheaval and for legalization of the independent students union
the federal aviation administration has declined to issue tighter restrictions suggested by another agency on planes and helicopters flown by the news media and others over major accident sites
the faa said the restrictions suggested by the national transportation safety board would be impractical
the ntsb had urged that the faa prohibit aircraft flights over major accident sites, especially when they involve spills of hazardous flammable materials or a fire and rescue workers might be endangered
the ntsb had cited a series of accidents - most of them involving train wrecks in which toxic substances were spilled -where news media helicopters flew so close to the accident scene that they endangered rescue workers
but faa administrator allan mcartor wrote to ntsb chairman jim burnett recently that the agency saw no reason to change the rules. a copy of the letter was made available wednesday
current faa regulations require the agency to issue a formal notice in each individual case to pilots when flights over an accident site must be prohibited because of a potential danger
the safety board said that the notice is often not readily available to pilots and that some pilots may specifically avoid asking about a notice so they may legally fly over an accident site
in responding to the safety board, which is in charge of investigating major transportation accidents, mcartor called the current restrictions that are tailored to each accident ``the most effective approach.''
to change the regulations as the ntsb had recommended it ``would be necessary to describe every type of potential disaster or hazard that may occur,'' mcartor said. he also said pilots may not know when such restrictions are in force
while rejecting the ntsb's call for broader restrictions, the faa, nevertheless, said it was calling for tighter enforcement of existing restrictions. it said the faa intends to aggressively enforce sanctions against pilots who intentionally violate the terms of the mandatory notice when it is put into effect at an accident site
violators would have their pilot's license suspended for a minimum of 180 days
the ntsb had said that a number of accidents dating back to 1978 demonstrated a problem with how the faa restricts aircraft at accident sites. in several of the cases the downwash from helicopters interfered in rescue attempts by fanning the flames of a fire or blowing toxic vapors in the direction of workers, the safety board said
there recently have been several incidents in which helicopter pilots helped in rescue attempts or - as was the case in denver -helped apprehend a criminal
faa spokesman fred farrar said, however, that these incidents had no bearing on the agency's response to the ntsb recommendations
the agency agreed with two ntsb recommendations aimed at offering guidance to pilots on obtaining information about flight restrictions that are put in place and developing ways to better educate pilots about the dangers of flying too close to an accident site. terrorists</head>
nuclear regulatory commission officials say the agency's rules provide commercial reactors adequate safeguards against terrorist attacks but its staff will additionally look at the potential threat from truck bombs
nrc chairman lando w. zech told a house subcommittee wednesday that the commission has confidence in the current safety rules, but recently instructed its staff to draft a series of options related to a truck-bomb threat ``as a prudent measure.''
the disclosure came as nrc officials clashed with rep. sam gejdenson, d-conn., chairman of the house interior and insular affairs subcommittee on general oversight and investigations, over commission security requirements
gejdenson urged the commission to beef up its security standards, which require plant operators to protect against a hypothetical threat of ``several'' terrorists armed with hand-held automatic weapons and aided by an accomplice inside the plant
fuel from traditional u.s. commercial reactor cannot be stolen and used to make nuclear bombs. but gejdenson said he feared terrorists could break into a nuclear reactor, hold it and the surrounding region hostage or trigger a nuclear meltdown that would release deadly radiation into the atmosphere
rep. peter a. defazio, d-ore., pointed to a threat last june from state-run tehran radio that said iran could attack u.s. reactors in retaliation against american forces in the persian gulf
you have people here who want to be martyrs,'' defazio said
gejdenson said the regulations should protect against a car or truck bursting through a plant's chain-link fence, attackers invading from a boat, and truck bombs like the ones used in terrorist attacks overseas
simple prudence and common sense dictate that the nrc assume that terrorist have cars and that licensees should be required to protect against this level of threat,'' gejdenson said. in an interview last week, the congressman said ``the gang that couldn't shoot straight could take any one of these facilities'' under the current standards
zech said the regulations are ``adequate and appropriate at this time.'' and he said the nrc is in daily contact with u.s. intelligence agencies monitoring any potential threats
but he added that the nrc told the staff last month to prepare ``a range of options'' regarding a truck-bomb threat for commission consideration. such recommendations could eventually become regulations, said nrc spokesman bob newlin
zech said the staff review stems from a december classified report by the national security council, but gejdenson contended the move was a response to his investigation
gejdenson said that the agency began working on a truck-bomb regulation following the october 1983 bombing of the marine barracks in lebanon, but that the commission never approved the proposal
a top haitian army officer reportedly indicted with his ex-wife and brother on drug charges was the second caribbean military leader in four weeks to be accused here of helping cocaine smugglers
a federal grand jury wednesday indicted col. jean-claude paul, commander of the largest unit in haiti's 6,000-man army; paul's brother antonio; and ex-wife merielle delinois, sources close to the case said on condition of anonymity
a witness has said the colonel allowed cocaine smugglers to land at his ranch
u.s. magistrate william c. turnoff ordered the indictment sealed immediately, but federal authorities were expected to unseal it today
there was no comment wednesday from the colonel or haiti's government
paul heads the feared 700-man dessalines battalion in the capital of port-au-prince. soldiers in the battalion ruthlessly suppressed anti-government demonstrations last year and were accused of protecting gunmen who disrupted haiti's november presidential elections, killing 34 people
paul was considered close to the military-dominated junta that ruled haiti from early 1986 until a military-supported civilian president took office feb. 7
on feb. 5, panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega was indicted in miami and tampa on charges he accepted $4.6 million in protection money from colombian cocaine dealers, laundered money, supplied drug laboratories and shielded drug kingpins
the investigation of paul has been widely reported for weeks. haitian army officials and the government-controlled media have defended him against reports of his involvement in cocaine trafficking
asked during a recent interview about reports of drug smuggling by the army, president leslie manigat said, ``i can't base my judgment on rumors.''
all interviews with army officials must be cleared through army chief of staff gen. carl nicolas, who refused a written request from the associated press to speak with paul
the junta replaced dictator jean-claude duvalier in february 1986, when he fled to exile in france
during the junta's two-year rule, paul seldom appeared in public
when he did, it often was to serve as bodyguard for two junta members, lt. gen. henri namphy, the junta president and now military chief, and brig. gen. williams regala, now defense minister. paul also appeared on the stage during manigat's inauguration at which the president pledged to stop drug trafficking. the colonel was among the military guards who escorted manigat back to the presidential palace after the inauguration
one of the witnesses in the case was miami businessman osvaldo quintana, 35, who told a news conference last month that the colonel helped him smuggle cocaine into the united states in december 1986
we flew (the shipment) out of his own personal ranch in haiti'' about 90 miles outside port-au-prince, said quintana, who has testified for the government in drug trials
quintana has said haitian military officials routinely aided drug flights from colombia, allowing them to land and be serviced before proceeding to the bahamas to drop their loads
he said he originally was approached by ms. delinois to take part in the smuggling
ms. delinois was arrested in miami on drug charges last march, but skipped bond and is believed to be hiding in haiti, according to the u.s. drug enforcement administration
dea affidavits filed in the delinois case said quintana met with paul and his brother antonio at the ranch, and watched while a plane carrying 220 pounds of cocaine took off
democratic presidential contender michael dukakis, saying he's in an ``uphill battle'' in ilinois, attacked rival sen. albert gore jr. as a regional candidate who would have little chance to win the general election in november
the massachusetts governor is also touting himself as the candidate who has the best track record on the economy
dukakis began airing a television spot here in which a bricklayers' union official tells voters that if they want to go out for a beer they should call their buddy, but ``if you care about your job, mike dukakis is your guy.''
in tuesday's illinois primary, illinois sen. paul simon is expected to garner favorite-son votes and the chicago-based jesse jackson is likely to tap black support in his hometown
that leaves dukakis battling gore for the remaining share. and dukakis suggested that he was a better choice to represent the party as the nominee
i'm not so sure he's a major contender,'' dukakis said of gore. ``a guy from massachusetts beat him in texas, beat him in florida. he wasn't willing to go into the early primaries. but i still take everyone seriously.''
michael bakalis, dukakis' illinois campaign chairman, said white blue-collar voters in chicago could form dukakis' base in illinois
paul simon in the 1984 senate race did not do very well in chicago, particularly in the white, ethnic precincts,'' bakalis said
those were precisely the precincts dukakis targeted wednesday in his first full day of campaigning in illinois in the week leading up to the primary
he met over breakfast with laid-off steel workers and then visited the metron steel warehouse in chicago, owned by one of dukakis' many greek-american supporters, andrew athens
illinois will send 173 delegates to the democratic national convention in atlanta. of those, 113 will be decided next tuesday. the rest are held by various party and elected officials. bakalis said 74 of the 113 will come from the greater chicago area
the dukakis camp plans to wage a traditional campaign in illinois, with an appearance at tonight's democratic party dinner, a spot in chicago's famous st. patrick's day parade and a message geared toward working men and women, said dukakis national political coordinator charles baker
win, lose or draw _ and we don't expect to win _ you want people here to care about this race,'' baker said
the dukakis campaign remains the financial front-runner after the media spending of super tuesday. campaign finance chief robert farmer said dukakis is raising half a million dollars a week. coming out of super tuesday, he said, dukakis has $2 million in the bank and another $1 million on the way in federal matching funds
bakalis said the governor has budgeted $300,000 to $350,000 for the state leading up to next tuesday. that amount could increase, he said, if dukakis decides to increase his media advertising
with two illinois residents in the race, ``obviously it's going to be an uphill battle,'' dukakis said
at this point i think that most people would think that third place would be respectable,'' he said. ``but i want to do better than that.''
the federal aviation administration is coming under criticism from its boss for not being aggressive enough in issuing civil fines against airlines because of airport security shortcomings
transportation secretary jim burnley says he is disturbed that the faa has not been complying with a directive issued last summer and reiterated in october, calling for ``aggressive enforcement'' actions against airlines that allow mock weapons to go undetected at an airport screening point
the faa has been testing security at the nation's airports by passing phony weapons through the checkpoints to see if they are found. last year a report concluded that as many as one in five mock weapons in faa tests go through undetected
the discovery prompted the transportation department to order the faa to get tough with airlines so that security is improved. the airlines are responsible for airport security checkpoints, although the stations are usually staffed through a contractor
burnley said wednesday that the department specifically told the faa to take enforcement actions, including a possible fine, when a security checkpoint allows a mock weapon through without detection
burnley aides released a sharply worded memorandum sent earlier this week to faa administrator allan mcartor. in it, the transportation secretary said he was ``deeply disturbed'' that five months after the crackdown was ordered, ``the faa is only taking action if carriers fail three out of five tests at a checkpoint and is only issuing a fine for the third failure.''
i am troubled by continuing reports of failure by the faa to fully implement these directed improvements and to strictly enforce security requirements,'' he wrote
mcartor said in a statement, ``i absolutely share secretary burnley's concern that faa aggressively implement all security recommendations. i have instructed faa personnel that the rules must be strictly enforced.''
agency officials had no further comment
the incident, however, is likely to further strain relations between burnley and mcartor
the washington post reported earlier this week that burnley was displeased with the faa's top public affairs officer because some regulatory action involving commuter airlines had been disclosed prematurely just when burnley wanted media attention focused on a speech he was making at the national press club
wendy democker, who is burnley's spokesman, denied that burnley had anything to do with the departure of air force lt. col. james c. jannette from the post. jannett, who had been at the job only three months and had been a personal choice of mcartor, was asked by the pentagon to return to his military duties, she said
meanwhile, there have been differences between mcartor and burnley on other aviation matters. last year mcartor told reporters he planned by april to submit legislation to congress on a national policy to deal with noise problems at airports
burnley said wednesday no such plans are in the works and that mcartor had changed his mind. burnley often has said he believes such legislation would be foolhardy because congress has no desire to tell local officials what to do about airport noise
a gully caved in on three teen-agers as they were playing in it, killing two, police said. the third was able to dig his way out from the 5 feet of dirt and summon help
a witness said the cave-in occurred moments after he warned the boys not to play in the gully
joel rogers and damon deakin, both 13 and from albuquerque, were killed in wednesday's accident, said police spokesman tony herrera
herrera said police received a call about 6 p.m. from residents of a north side trailer park who saw the boys digging in the gully, then saw a cloud of dust
a 14-year-old boy who also fell in managed to dig himself out and go for help, said herrera, who would not release the boy's name
neighbors had pulled rogers out and were trying to revive him when officers arrived, herrera said. paramedics then pulled the other boy out
deakin was pronounced dead at the scene and rogers at the university of new mexico hospital
police said the boys were trapped about 20 minutes. a witness estimated they were under about 5 feet of dirt
dave wild, a resident of the trailer park, said he warned the boys it was dangerous to dig in the arroyo
he said the boys continued to play in it and moments later he saw the dust cloud
i didn't think anything of it,'' he said. ``then i remembered the kids digging. i ran out and one of them was yelling that the other two were trapped inside. i jumped into the arroyo and started digging
i kept digging until i got to a foot, then i reached his head,'' he said. ``i pulled him out and he wasn't breathing.''
trailer park manager kaylin morris said she heard the boys talking earlier in the day about digging a tunnel
she described them as good kids who often volunteered to do odd jobs around the trailer park
the three were inseparable,'' she said. ``it was just like the three musketeers.''
a twin-engine plane crashed into a residential neighborhood shortly after takeoff early thursday, killing at least three people, authorities said
the plane took off from detroit city airport and struck one or two houses about five miles to the northwest, said tim stayer, a worker at universal macomb ambulance service inc. of warren
he said the plane was heading for oakland-pontiac airport at the time of the crash
it was not known how many passengers were aboard the plane or in any of the homes involved, stayer said
officials said at least three people were killed
the crash occurred at 12:30 a.m., warren police sgt. richard pytlak said
the plane had been in the air one-to-two minutes before it crashed, said barbara gardner-martin, air traffic manager for city airport. she said that type of aircraft normally is used to carry freight, but she said she did not know what or who was aboard the flight
two years after they crashed the state democratic party and helped to make their leader a household name, lyndon larouche's illinois disciples have resurfaced again on the state primary election ballot
despite challenges from the democratic party, larouche and more than 20 of his supporters are in the running in the party's primary on tuesday for posts ranging from president to county recorder of deeds
for state party leaders, it's an unwelcome reminder of the upset victories of two larouche followers in the 1986 democratic primary, an event that threw the party into disarray
we fell down on our job in `86,'' said state sen. vince demuzio, who became state democratic party chairman after the primary debacle. ``nobody gave them much chance to do anything and we ended up with two of them on our ticket. we don't intend to allow that again.''
for the larouche supporters, it's another chance to air the perennial presidential candidate's world view, in which various conspiracies link aids, drugs, international bankers and the british royal family
the 1986 victories of larouche's illinois followers marked the beginning of a period of heightened scrutiny that culminated in raids by authorities on larouche's leesburg, va., headquarters and his indictment in boston on federal obstruction-of-justice charges
his supporters see these actions as a conspiracy by the democratic party and the soviet union, who they believe are trying to block larouche from gaining political power
if this man is such a wacko fringe candidate, why is the democratic party spending all of this money to keep him out of the election?'' said sheila jones, a leader of the larouche organization in illinois
demuzio has a ready answer
he has repudiated the platform and leadership of the party nationally and in illinois,'' he said. ``we're not going to afford these fringe candidates the chance to have the democratic party as their haven.''
but illinois democrats succeeded in only one of a flurry of challenges to larouche-backed candidacies, leaving larouche and a platoon of followers on the ballot:
larouche's name will appear throughout the state on the march 15 democratic presidential preference ballot. in four chicago-area congressional districts, larouche followers have filed full slates of would-be delegates to the democratic national convention
larouche supporters will be on the ballot for congress in at least five districts, mostly in the chicago area
and janice hart, one of the larouche supporters who won in 1986, is running for cook county circuit court clerk
perhaps as a result of their 1986 success, larouche supporters seem to have focused their efforts in illinois, political observers say
in the 10 other states where democratic primary election filing deadlines have passed, only four congressional candidates have been identified as larouche disciples, said peggy connolly, spokeswoman for the national democratic congressional campaign committee
it's a natural consequence of what they perceive as their success there (in illinois) in 1986,'' she said. ``they've lost their wind in every other region of the country.''
democratic party leaders and candidates say the larouche followers' campaigns in illinois seem to have begun and ended with the filing of nominating petitions to get on the primary ballot
with their legal challenges stymied, democratic party leaders have focused their anti-larouche efforts on mailings to voters in the areas where larouche followers are on the ballot
cook county democrats are circulating almost 3 million brochures warning voters that ``the larouchies have invaded'' the ballot and urging them to be careful when casting their votes
some democrats have discussed the possibility of rewriting state election law to allow party leaders to ``screen'' candidates seeking to run in the party primary, though they acknowledge doubts about the constitutionality of such a measure
but demuzio and other party leaders believe public disdain is the only effective political weapon against larouche followers
i don't know how you keep them from getting on the ballot,'' demuzio said. ``this is america, you know.''
george bush, with the support of gov. jim thompson and most republican party leaders, will stump his way ``through all corners'' of illinois, his campaign says
after a one-day respite from campaign rigors, bush was flying to chicago today to begin an intensive five days of vote-seeking as he tries to pad his formidable lead in the race for nominating convention delegates
between now and next tuesday, bush will have criss-crossed the state several times, with thompson, a four-term governor, at his side most of the way
he was beginning his campaign with a speech to the gop governors club luncheon in chicago, to be followed later in the day with lincoln day dinner appearances in champaign and alton. bush has the endorsements of 93 of 102 county gop chairmen in illinois
the bush campaign style will be similar to the one he used successfully in new hampshire, south carolina and the super tuesday states. he is scheduled to discuss agricultural issues friday and visit a methanol plant later that day
with thompson at his side, bush will enjoy the benefits of having the support of the state's top office-holder
in advance of bush's campaign foray, thompson's press secretary, david fields, said the governor had virtually cleared his schedule of any conflicting events
the governor and bush will be together pretty much through the whole five days,'' fields said. ``we're talking about the length and breadth of illinois _ a pretty good cross-section.''
pete teeley, bush's chief spokesman, said of thompson: ``he's a terrific campaigner and we sure want him to be with us.''
bush campaign manager lee atwater said earlier this week that the vice president, seeking to win the 82 convention delegates illinois offers, would ``go through all corners of the state, campaign directly and forthrightly, discuss issues and get his message out.''
bush, who has amassed 805 of the 1,139 delegates needed for nomination, has refused to accept sen. bob dole's demand that the two meet in one-on-one campaign debates in illinois
rep. lynn martin, r-ill., co-chairman of the bush campaign, said that while bush would travel throughout the state, he would focus on the stronghold of the state republican party, the ``collar communities'' surrounding chicago
she said that dole ``has a right to say to the illinois farming communities, `i'm one of you' and george bush can't do that.''
but martin also said that ``illinois is not iowa, and our farming communities did not have the same difficulties.''
bush finished a distant third behind dole and pat robertson in iowa, and a part of the reason was disenchantment there with reagan administration farm policy
martin said: ``i don't think there's any question that bush will win the popularity vote, but dole will do well in some districts.''
ken wright, one of bush's principal strategists in florida, said: ``i think, going to illinois, we've got a great organization up there. gov. thompson is enormously popular there, and i think he'll do very well.''
forty-four ghanian immigrants occupied a varig airlines's main office and demanded to be taken to canada, upsetting furniture and scuffling with reporters before leaving, the airline said
the 42 adults and two children arrived feb. 3 in rio for a stopover en route from lagos, nigeria, to canada
federal police discovered their passports from trinidad-tobago were false, and the canadian government refused to let them enter the country, varig said in a statement
the group was staying in a hotel but the airline recently stopped paying the bill for meals and accomodations
varig said it would take the group back to ghana, in west africa, if they obtained the necessary travel papers from the ghanian embassy in brasilia
state police surrounded the airline's office but the group left after several hours
here is a list of some of the crashes of the uh-60 blackhawk helicopter, the model involved in a collision tuesday at fort campbell, ky., that killed 17 soldiers
crashes of the blackhawk, used by the army, air force and marine corps, have killed about 40 people since 1978, but the manufacturer, sikorsky aircraft, says the craft is about four times safer than the one it replaced
sept. 16 _ one killed when army helicopter strikes power line during nato exercises at hanover, west germany
aug. 14 _ four killed when air force helicopter crashes at fort bragg, n.c
march 11, 1986 _ three killed during army training flight at fort rucker, ala
dec. 9, 1985 _ one killed when army helicopter strikes power line and crashes 68 miles south of seoul, south korea
april 18, 1985 _ three killed in crash on army training flight at fort rucker
march 13, 1985 _ eight killed in army training flight at fort bragg
feb. 2, 1984 _ four killed when army helicopter crashes during war games in honduras
oct. 18, 1983 _ four killed in crash during army night training mission near mount ranier in washington
oct. 4, 1983 _ two killed when army helicopter crashes in caribbean sea near entrance to panama canal
the fashion king of milan, giorgio the gorgeous, achieved the impossible and bettered his own best
armani's fall-winter collection, shown wednesday, was a power house of ideas. he showed the tiniest jackets, cropping them just above the waist. sleeves were long and tight. the definitely marked the demise of wide armholes and overly-padded shoulders
always a jacket specialist, he offered more new shapes than ever before. the choice ranged from a jacket that was raised in front and dipped at the back. then there was the one with the soft cowl neckline and yet another that sported a side-zipped bandolier in matching fabric
pants were plentiful. they came cuffless in smooth wools, falling loosely from unpressed waist pleats. he also showed some bermuda shorts and accompanied them with the thigh-high suede wader boots that have been a main feature of these milan shows
there were lots of different hat shapes, ranging from a coal miner's cap to a broad-brimmed, flat-crowned felt of the sort that clint eastwood usually favors in his cowboy movies
fabrics, designed thread by thread by armani the perfectionist, were superb
laura biagiotti, the designer who lives and works out of a medieval castle nestled in the countryside outside rome, showed styles that were perfect for an elegant castle dweller
there were soft cashmere ``horse blankets,'' ideal for keeping out the chill along the ramparts. they wrapped up comfy sweater-dresses, oversize twinsets or slim-fitting pants, all in flat knit
daytime colors were rustic: oatmeal, moss-green and maize. and there was moderation in the details with a more natural shoulderline, flat-heeled footwear and skirt-lengths just a fraction above the knee
biagiotti took paisley-patterned fringed head scarves in fine wool and fashioned them into wraparound skirts and did an attractive series of that fashion indispensable _ the ever-popular little black dress in velvet or silk crepe
on a completely different wavelength was the baby doll look of the collection designed by muriel grateau for complice. models, with elfin hairdos, wore short, high-waisted styles with tight-fitting bodices and jauntily gathered skirts
a brand-new girlish look for coats in double wool crepe featured a shoulder-framing cape collar and a broad martingale belt that tied tightly in a bow at the waist in back
party dresses came in the same style with waist gathers transferred to just under the bust while mini-skirts were decorated with frills and ribbon cockades
almost all the clothes at complice came in a rich titian red, lace-up shoes and stockings included
there is a certain style that the italian designers have always done beautifully: understated but elegant tailored blazers, well-cut pants and loose top coats in men's-type smooth woolens
it is a look that is timeless and unbeatable, and the women of milan love it. basile did it for them again, tucking pants into the newly fashionable winter boots and putting velvet on collars for an even more well-bred air
stock prices rose on the tokyo stock exchange in heavy trading today, and the dollar rose slightly
the 225-share nikkei stock average advanced 12.43 points, or 0.05 percent, closing at 25,617.82. it had gained 139.66 points on wednesday
trading was heavy at 1.6 billion shares, compared with 1.3 billion shares wednesday
the dollar closed at 128.20 yen, up 0.12 yen from wednesday's close. it opened at 128.25 yen and ranged between 128.13 yen and 128.42 yen
dealers said dollar trading was affected little by the finance ministry's report late in the day that japan's trade surplus had declined from year-earlier figures for the 10th consecutive month. they said the size of the surplus in february, $5.24 billion, was within the range expected by the market. the surplus was $7.13 billion in february 1987
the u.s. primary elections also provided no surprises, they added, and there has been a lack of interest in trading ahead of the march 31 end of japan's fiscal year
an official of nomura securities co., who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that in stock trading, large-capital issues, including shipbuilding, chemicals, textiles, steel and banks, were popular with investors, reflecting an oversupply of money
construction, real estate and rubber issues were weak, the official said
toshiaki yui, a stock analyst at nomura, said the popularity of the large-capital stocks resulted in part from local government plans to develop waterfront areas along tokyo bay. the plans are scheduled to be announced later this month, he said
