shevardnadze briefed the participants at that meeting on his talks with shultz on feb. 21-22. ...' with 6 grafs to restore dropped material about aquino not seeking re-election. picks up 8th graf pvs bgng, `in its report .... adds byline.</note>
president corazon aquino today called ``one-sided'' a report by amnesty international alleging widespread human rights abuse in the philippines during her two years in office
also today, mrs. aquino said she had no plans to run for re-election when her term expires in june 1992. it was the clearest statement of her political intentions to date
mrs. aquino said there have been delays in punishing human rights violators because the philippines respects the rights of the accused to due process
on wednesday, the london-based human rights organization alleged that mrs. aquino's government had used torture, murder and illegal arrests in fighting the country's 19-year communist rebellion
amnesty international called on the government to end killings by military and paramilitary forces, saying they represented the country's most serious human rights problem since mid-1987
i think the amnesty international report was very one-sided,'' mrs. aquino told filipino reporters. she said the organization had relied only on social activist groups, such as the church-backed task force-detainees, in compiling its report
the president urged such groups to cooperate with the government's commission on human rights in providing documented evidence to help find and punish human rights violators
on wednesday, task force-detainees said its investigation showed that 7,444 filipino civilians were arrested illegally in 1987, eclipsing the 5,967 arrests in 1985, when ferdinand marcos was president
mrs. aquino came to power when marcos' authoritarian regime collapsed in february 1986. there has been speculation mrs. aquino would seek a second term, using a technicality in the new constitution
i don't think so,'' she told filipino reporters. she added: ``i have never had political ambitions.''
the constitution, drafted by an aquino-appointed commission and approved in a plebiscite last year, limits the president and vice president to one six-year term
but ``transitory provisions'' in the constitution, temporary measures designed to ease the transition of power, also state that the first regular elections for president under the new charter will be held on the second monday of may 1992
some political observers and aquino supporters have interpreted the wording of the transitory provision to mean mrs. aquino is not bound by the one-term limit
in its report, amnesty international praised the aquino government for ``some very real progress'' in human rights, particularly in restoring legal safeguards and in greatly reducing the use of torture
but it called on the government to reaffirm publicly its commitment to protect human rights. the report said amnesty international knew of no cases where soldiers had been punished for human rights violations
it cited the february 1987 killing of 17 civilians in lupao. the military said the killings took place after a lieutenant was killed by a communist sniper during a patrol in lupao
with regards to no soldier being convicted, in fact charges have been filed against the soldiers involved or implicated in the lupao massacre,'' mrs. aquino said
we are living in a democracy. while it is true there is evidence ... everyone is entitled to due process of law. even those who are accused should have their day in court.''
mary concepcion bautista, chairwoman of the commission on human rights, also criticized the amnesty international report as ``exaggerated.''
she said the government was investigating about 200 cases of human rights abuse, claiming ``there is a serious effort to clean up.''
mrs. bautista said investigations of human rights abuses against the military were often not publicized to avoid demoralizing soldiers who are fighting the rebels
the insurgents don't follow the rules,'' she said. ``soldiers complain that when they fight the insurgents, they have one hand tied behind their back.''
last year about 150 police and soldiers were fatally shot on manila streets. communist rebels claimed responsibility for about half the killings
an average of 10 soldiers, civilians or police officers are killed daily in clashes between government and rebel forces
