chinese universities will sharply cut the rate of growth in enrollment to cope with problems of overcrowding and inadequate facilities, an official newspaper said today
college enrollment increases will be held to between 2 percent and 5 percent annually from this year through 1990, compared to a growth rate of 17 percent in the 1981-85 period, the china daily said
it said college administrators attending a national conference agreed that the current goal of 750,000 undergraduates in 1990 is not practical, and opted for a figure of 680,000
they said junior colleges, correspondence schools and other programs will help satisfy the great demand among young chinese for higher education
