although the superpower missile treaty has not been ratified yet, the soviet union is already adjusting its nuclear missile force to regain firepower lost through the accord, nato's top commander said
the commander, u.s. gen. john r. galvin, said on wednesday that the moves were expected and were not in violation of the treaty signed last december to eliminate the superpowers' medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles worldwide. missiles covered by the treaty have ranges from 300 to 3,000 miles
they are restructuring their missile force,'' galvin said in an interview with the associated press in his spartan office at supreme headquarters allied powers europe. galvin likened the soviet moves to reshaping a wall from which some stones have been removed
i don't want to get too specific ... but i get some indications that the soviets are readjusting the stones on the wall,'' he said, adding that the western allies would do this, too
galvin added: ``(the soviets) will retarget other warheads into western europe'' to cover military targets previously assigned to the hundreds of ss-20 rockets to be dismantled under terms of the superpower accord
he said it was not yet clear how the soviets would accomplish this. ``they may have to take ... warheads that were aimed in another direction and aim them toward western europe,'' galvin said
the net result, he said, is likely to be that the soviets will partially offset the loss of their ss-20s, which are triple-warhead ballistic missiles capable of striking all of western europe
the overall capabilities of the soviets would still be somewhat lower _ a small amount lower _ because of the treaty,'' galvin said. ``but the adjustments ... will to some degree cover that.''
the north atlantic treaty organization also is seeking to adjust and modernize its remaining nuclear forces in europe to partially compensate for the loss of the u.s. cruise and pershing 2 missiles. but there is disagreement in nato over how and when to do this
according to galvin, it was important for nato eventually to replace its aging lance short-range nuclear missiles, which are not covered by the treaty, with a more modern version of longer reach. but he said a final decision on replacing the lance missiles in west germany was not needed before 1990
he said nato arms modernization is necessary to help defeat one of soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's chief aims: to rid europe of all nuclear weapons
despite gorbachev's recent pronouncements about seeking a more peaceful relationship with the west, galvin said, the kremlin leader has not abandoned the long-standing soviet aim of dominating western europe
he's moving in exactly the same direction,'' he said
galvin said many westerners are responding to gorbachev's softer stance in the same way a hostage feels kindly toward his captor after being released
maybe we're seeing a little bit of that psychology where we have felt ourselves under the pressure of the powerful military forces of the soviet union and the warsaw pact for so many decades ... that when we get some indication of a friendly nod in our direction we respond enormously because it's such a change,'' he said
according to galvin, western governments should not move too quickly to encourage gorbachev's efforts to modernize the soviet economy, since a stronger economy could make moscow a more formidable enemy
nbc must surrender to a judge outtakes from an interview with a former lyndon larouche consultant who said an aide to the political extremist discussed a plot to assassinate henry kissinger, a federal appeals court ruled
the decision wednesday by the 1st u.s. circuit court of appeals upheld a lower court order that videotape of the entire interview must be surrendered for possible use at the conspiracy and fraud trial of larouche, six aides and five political organizations
the court also upheld a contempt citation against the network
nbc had contended that surrendering portions of the interview that were not broadcast violated its first amendment right against judicial intrusion into news gathering and editorial decisions
u.s. district judge robert e. keeton ruled that the rights of the defendants to have access to the interview with forrest lee fick outweighed those of the network
at stake in the defendants' side of the equation are their constitutional rights to a fair trial under the fifth amendment,'' the appeals court wrote in concurring with keeton, whose original order called for him to review the entire interview and determine its relevance to the case
nbc attorney floyd abrams said the network would decide within a few days whether to appeal to the u.s. supreme court
it is an opinion which we believe does not sufficiently recognize the first amendment rights of broadcasters,'' abrams said
keeton had issued a similar order requiring cbs to surrender outtakes of an interview it conducted with another larouche aide. cbs complied
nbc interviewed fick for 100 minutes and in april 1986 broadcast a one-minute portion of the interview in which fick said he and larouche aide paul goldstein discussed a plot to assassinate kissinger, the former secretary of state
fick, of reading, pa., worked as a larouche security consultant with another reading man, roy frankhauser. frankhauser was convicted in december of conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury investigation of alleged credit card and loan fraud by larouche followers during his 1984 presidential campaign
fick was a prosecution witness against frankhauser. both are expected to be called as witnesses at the trial of larouche and aides including goldstein
defense lawyers contend the entire nbc interview will help show fick and frankhauser were among scores of operatives planted in larouche organizations by the fbi and cia to gather information and ultimately to ruin larouche and cripple his fund-raising operation
after a long, hard day of fighting crime on the streets of los angeles, police detective norman nelson gets his kicks by climbing onto the back of a 2,000-pound brahma bull
bull riding's a high,'' explains nelson, 44, a three-time lapd bull-riding champion. ``you can't imagine it if you haven't experienced it. but once you know that thrill, you don't want to give it up.''
and there's more than just kicks
since taking up the sport in 1983, nelson has been hooked, horned, stepped on and knocked senseless. but he says there's a big difference between busting crooks and riding brahmas in a rodeo
with the bull, the danger comes from something you respect,'' nelson said. ``you respect its strength, its power, its ability. the bull doesn't care whether it kills you or not. it's a clean contest between you and the bull.''
a 25 percent increase in attendance at the democratic caucus here was cause for rejoicing among party stalwarts in owyhee county, population 8,272
it meant they'd have a quorum. murphy, a tiny community in idaho's southwestern corner, is reputed to be the smallest county seat in the nation, consisting of the owyhee county courthouse and several mobile homes
sheriff tim nettleton, was one of four democrats who attended the caucus at the courthouse, locally famous as the site of murphy's one parking meter
when a man in a cowboy hat walked into the meeting room, his arrival was seen as increasing attendance by 25 percent. ``i knew there was something i liked about you,'' nettleton said. ``you must be a democrat.''
no,'' he replied. ``i just wanted to see the sheriff for a minute.''
eventually, however, the democrats rounded up a quorum
that put them one up on democrats in heavily republican custer county in central idaho. they had a caucus scheduled tuesday night, but nobody came
the seawolf, the pentagon's newest nuclear attack submarine scheduled to begin production later this year, will help the united states dominate the soviet union at sea long into the next century, the navy says
the ssn-21 will have double the fire power and be faster, quieter and more survivable than the ssn-688 los angeles class sub, which the seawolf is expected to replace as the nation's chief attack submarine, vice adm. bruce demars, assistant chief of naval operations for undersea warfare, told a house panel wednesday
the seawolf, which has been in the research and design stage for six years, has been criticized by some lawmakers who fear the sub is not advanced enough for the soviet's planned successor to their akula attack sub
but demars dismissed that notion, telling the house armed services sea power subcommittee that the seawolf is ``the foundation for far-term submarine superiority.''
last year, a house subcommittee tried to delay funds for the project, but congress restored the money. navy officials have warned that such a delay could severely damage the seawolf program and cause massive cost overruns
demars said the project now is on schedule and on budget
early models of the baby buddy clip-on pacifier holder are being recalled by the consumer product safety commission because of a potential choking hazard
about 9,000 of the holders were distributed nationwide in 1986 and 1987, officials said. they sold for about $3.95 each
while no injuries have been reported involving the holders, parents were urged to return them to the store where purchased for a free replacement. when tested, the small bear figure separated from the holder and thus could pose a choking hazard, officials said
new model holders can be distinguished by the two round holes in the back of the clip. there are no holes in the clip of the holders being recalled
recalled pacifier holders include those with a pink ribbon and white bear, blue ribbon and bear, yellow ribbon and brown bear, red ribbon and white bear and red ribbon and brown bear
persons needing more information can contact baby buddies inc., 615 jasmine avenue north, suite i, tarpon springs, fla., at 1-813-934-3359 or the safety commission at 1-800-638-2772
the justice department has filed notice hat it will appeal a federal judge's decision to suppress the confession of a former lebanese shiite amal militiaman accused of leading an airline hijacking
the government's move wednesday to appeal the ruling by u.s. district judge barrington d. parker stays the march 22 trial of fawaz younis pending a ruling by the u.s. circuit court of appeals here
parker ruled last month that the fbi illegally obtained a confession from younis when he was arrested and interrogated for four days aboard a navy munitions ship in the mediterranean after being lured into an fbi-chartered yacht
the judge ruled that prosecutors could not use the confession as evidence that younis led four other hijackers who seized a royal jordanian airliner on june 11, 1985 at beirut international airport
the plane was destroyed a day later after the passengers and crew were taken off the aircraft. jack ryan</head>
author tom clancy hopes to learn in june whether he or the naval institute press of annapolis, md., calls the shots for cia operative jack ryan
the washington post reported today that clancy and the naval institute are in a dispute over the rights to ryan, a character in clancy's best-selling books ``the hunt for red october'' and ``patriot games.''
the small institute had never before published an original work of fiction when it brought out ``red october'' in 1984 and copyrighted the work in its own name. clancy later signed a three-book, $3 million contract with putnam, a new york publishing firm
the institute now is challenging putnam's publication of ``the cardinal of the kremlin,'' a new novel by clancy with the ryan character. it also is seeking payment for use of the ryan character in last year's ``patriot games'' and wants a percentage of any earnings from a proposed television mini-series of that novel, the post said
clancy refused to comment on the advice of his lawyers, the newspaper said. he took the case to the american arbitration association last month, with a binding decision expected in june
a man bent on revenge after being convicted of reckless driving and weapons violations died in a courtroom gunfight after threatening to kill his prosecutor and critically wounding a bailiff, authorities said
jeremey sigmond, 35, a decertified chiropractor from sepulveda, returned wednesday to los angeles municipal court where he was convicted the day before, and accosted his prosecutor, jessica perrin silvers, 49, threatening to kill her
he's just, in layman's terms, violently crazy, and i knew it,'' the prosecutor said. ``so when i heard him talking in his delusional voice and saying i should come with him i just thought there's no way i'm going to do that.''
a bailiff drew a gun on sigmond. sigmond threatened to shoot ms. silvers and the bailiff dropped the weapon. but ms. silvers broke away and deputy marshal cliff wofford burst into the room and shot sigmond
wofford, 30, of palmdale, was wounded in the abdomen in the gunbattle and was in critical condition after surgery to repair damage to his liver, said betty neilson, spokeswoman for st. joseph's medical center in burbank
police searched sigmond's suburban home wednesday for firearms or explosives, but found only empty gun vaults. a neighbor, maurice netter, said sigmond had told him he was part of a federal witness protection program and living under an assumed name
sigmond was convicted tuesday of four misdemeanors _ reckless driving, evading police, carrying a loaded weapon and carrying a concealed weapon _ stemming from an oct. 22 high-speed chase
he testified at his trial that he thought he was being chased by the mafia instead of the california highway patrol. he claimed the mafia was harassing him in retaliation for a lawsuit he filed against the board of chiropractors, alleging price-fixing and restraint of trade
he had been appealing the revocation of his state license to practice as a chiropractor
when arrested, sigmond was wearing two bullet-proof vests and a crash helmet and carrying a loaded .38-caliber revolver. he was wearing a bullet-proof vest wednesday, said police lt. charles massey
sigmond's attorney, norman edell, described his client as an air force veteran who held a second-degree black belt in karate and was a collector of guns, most of which he recently had sold
he was very distraught because the case meant a lot to him. he didn't take it passively but there was no indication of this,'' he said
at his sentencing, which was scheduled for may, sigmond could have been ordered imprisoned up to 18 months
the courthouse is in the san fernando valley community of van nuys, about 15 miles northwest of downtown los angeles. population to 55,800. picks up 5th graf pvs, `a security ...</note>
port-of-spain, trinidad (ap) _ a strong earthquake shook people awake on the caribbean island of trinidad early today but police said they had no reports of injuries or damage
the quake, the strongest in the area in 78 years, measured 6.9 on the richter scale and struck at 2:17 a.m. about 50 miles southeast of the capital of port-of-spain, said the u.s. geological survey's national earthquake information center in golden, colo
no damage, no injuries. we just got a little shake and that's all,'' said lt. velfukr muhammed at police headquarters in the capital of 55,800 people
i was in bed at the time and that woke me and everyone else in the house,'' said lionel dixon, news editor of radio trinidad in port-of-spain
a security guard at the station, san keralli, said the building shook for about 40 seconds. dixon said some people ran into the street in the suburb where he lives
frank baldwin, a usgs physical science technician in golden, said the epicenter appeared to have been in the caribbean about 420 miles east of caracas, venezuela, in a seismic area lying on the boundary between the caribbean and the south american crustal plates of the earth
the quake was the area's largest since a magnitude 7.2 temblor on jan. 23, 1910
trinidad is an island in the republic of trinidad and tobago, a member of the british commonwealth. about 1.2 million people live in the oil-producing republic, which covers an area about the size of delaware and is one of the caribbean's most prosperous countries
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude
an earthquake of 3.5 on the richter scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. a 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage
for the first time, the cuban government has invited delegates of the u.n. human rights commission to visit cuba to investigate the human rights situation on the island nation
one united states delegate called the offer a ``diversionary tactic,'' while another questioned the way it was brought before the commission
the chief cuban representative to the 43-nation commission, raul roa kouri, said on wednesday that six members could go to cuba ``in order to see ... the situation prevailing there in human rights and to inform the commission.''
roa, who is also a deputy foreign minister, said the commission members allowed to visit would be the chairman, alioune sene of senegal, and five other delegates, one from each of the regional groups
reading what he said was a letter to sene from his government, roa indicated that the cuban government would arrange ``the necessary contacts and interviews with the officials and competent authorities of our country who would answer all their questions.''
he also said the representatives would be given access to ``penitentiary establishments,'' but did not elaborate. roa did not give a date for the planned visit
roa's remarks in spanish were translated into english by an interpreter. u.s. delegate daniel pipes said the cuban invitation was made to draw attention away from a u.s.-proposed resolution, which calls for the u.n. secretary-general to investigate charges of human rights abuses in cuba and for cuba to allow the international red cross to visit cuban prisons
they're afraid of the vote'' on that resolution, pipes told the associated press
another u.s. delegate, lewis anselem, told the commission the cuban invitation was ``the first time that the cuban government has shown a willingness to have a united nations organ look into the human rights situation in that country and into the allegations about that situation.''
but anselem said some of the procedures used to bring it before the commission were ``highly irregular.''
the proposed visit was introduced in the commission meeting by colombia, reportedly with the support of argentina, mexico and peru, all members of the commission. cuba is an observer this year
anselem said the united states would not accept the proposed visit as a substitute for its own resolution
the united states for the second year in a row is pursuing its goal of having the commission examine alleged human rights abuses in cuba. this year the u.s. government appointed a former cuban political prisoner, armando valladares, to head the u.s. delegation
the cuban government has attacked the appointment of valladares, a poet who wrote a book about torture and degrading treatment he said he suffered during 22 years in cuban prisons
valladares has said the united states, in pressing the cuba issue, is trying to fight a ``selective sensitivity'' in the commission, which routinely condemns human rights violations in the israeli-occupied territories, chile and south africa
the united states maintains that human rights abuses in cuba include torture, clandestine executions and religious and political persecution
the u.s.-sponsored resolution cites allegations of human rights abuses in cuba made by other international groups, including amnesty international and the organization of american states
the resolution is to be voted on before the commission ends its annual meeting on friday
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, says he's sent telegrams congratulating all the democratic candidates who won delegates on super tuesday and asking them to eschew negative ads from now on in the campaign
candidates with viable ideas and strong ideals do not need to rely on negative campaigning which only tarnishes and muddles the processes of democracy,'' wright said
wright said the use of negative ads had become a ``vogue,'' intensified by the short time between the new hampshire primaries and tuesday's 20-state extravaganza
super tuesday, the brainchild of moderate and conservative democrats, wright said, ``put a great premium on having an enormous amount of money to spend in little quickie tv spots'' and denied candidates the chance to be evaluated by voters on the merits of their ideas
the rush left ``no time to make a sensible ... appeal,'' wright said, and led candidates to ``succumb to the wicked blandishments of those in the advertising fraternity'' who specialize in attack ads
former television evangelist pat robertson finished fourth among republican presidential candidates in a preference poll of board members at the national association of evangelicals' annual convention
vice president george bush received 40 percent of the vote wednesday. kansas sen. robert dole received 32 percent, new york rep. jack kemp 17 percent and robertson 12 percent
the results ``confounded conventional wisdom that he would be the near-unanimous choice of evangelical leaders,'' said richard cizik, research director for the nae in washington
among democrats, missouri rep. richard gephardt was supported by 37 percent of the board members. tennessee sen. albert gore received 33 percent of the vote, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis 16 percent, illinois sen. paul simon 11 percent and the rev. jesse jackson 5 percent
wednesday's voting, conducted without discussion, was by denominational presidents, organizational executives and lay leaders from across the country
assembly speaker willie brown says jesse jackson could win the california primary, which could decide the democratic presidential nomination
brown, jackson's national campaign chairman, also said his candidate could have won two or three more states on super tuesday if he had had money for television advertisements
we may well determine the democratic nomination with the california vote,'' brown told reporters wednesday
probably jackson is the favorite at the moment'' in the june 7 california primary, one of the last in the country, brown said
brown, d-san francisco, said jackson will be in california on march 19 and 20, including a visit to the state democratic convention in palm springs that weekend
brown, who said he will be putting together a series of nationwide concerts, featuring stars who support jackson, to raise money for the campaign, added that jackson will be in california ``four or five times in april and on a regular basis in the month of may
with no seats and no food for the guests of honor, everyone agreed that lunch at sardi's had gone to the dogs
two dogs, to be specific, the city's top police dog and the nation's top show dog
the dog fanciers club organized the event wednesday to honor champion great elms prince charming ii, a fluffy little pomeranian, and nero, a big, amiable bruiser of a german shepherd
he's a very friendly dog,'' said nero's master, officer joseph faraguna. ``in all the arrests i've made with him, he's only bitten four times.''
nero specializes in sniffing out bombs and narcotics. he has helped the police department make hundreds of arrests and has ``apprehended'' more than 50 felons
nero was kept on his long leather leash while prince emerged from his elegant, padded carrying case only long enough to pose for photographers
the pomeranian was named best in show at the prestigious westminister kennel club show in madison square garden last month
prince, long used to being coddled and primped, seemed oblivious to all the attention until nero grew bold enough to prod him on the chin. then he blinked and drew back
but neither nero nor prince got any lunch from the luncheon at sardi's, a prominent midtown manhattan restaurant
