high winds howled through sections of the west today after gusts up to 70 mph felled trees and damaged cars in southern nevada as snow moved into parts of the rockies and rain continued falling in the southeast
a tree knocked down by wind late wednesday injured one person in the las vegas, nev., area and did major damage to a trailer and some parked cars. the winds also caused numerous power outages
in southwest utah, the wind reached 58 mph in st. george and a brief, heavy snow hit the area wednesday night. two inches fell in cedar city between 8 p.m. and 10 p.m
light snow fell in other parts of utah and in western wyoming. two inches fell in west yellowstone, mont., in six hours overnight
winds gusting to 50 mph were recorded in california's tehachapi mountains near bakersfield and in foothill communities along the north side of the san fernando valley
a high wind warning or wind advisories were in effect today in southern california and southern nevada
a heavy snow warning was issued for the colorado mountains, where a foot or more was expected. advisories for snow or blowing snow were up in western colorado and the mountains of utah and southwest wyoming
winter storm watches were in effect through tonight for northeast colorado, eastern wyoming and western sections of south dakota and nebraska, and were expected to be issued tonight in central parts of south dakota and nebraska
scattered light rain extended from the mid-atlantic states to new england, with some wet snow in northern maine. light rain fell in parts of tennessee, kentucky and west virginia
vermont experienced its first snow melt problems of the season wednesday night, when water ran over roads in two parts of westford due to frozen culverts and rising streams
today's forecast called for snow from northern arizona and utah to the northern and central rockies and the northern high plains; scattered rain and snow in eastern sections of the dakotas and parts of minnesota; a few flurries over northern maine; rain showers from the mid-atlantic states to the carolinas and georgia and thundershowers in southern florida
high temperatures were expected to be in the 30s and 40s from new england across the great lakes and the northern plains to the rockies; 70s or lower 80s in southern florida and the southern plains; 70s through the desert southwest and southern california and the 50s or 60s in the rest of the nation
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 18 degrees at marquette, mich., to 77 degrees at key west naval air station, fla
