here are some comments wednesday from candidates for the presidency;

jack kemp, who is expected to announce today his withdrawal from the gop race: ``there were rumors we would withdraw after iowa. but i'm not a quitter. i'm an ex-quarterback, and i don't enter a contest lightly.''

bob dole, on the importance of next tuesday's illinois primary to the viability of his campaign after his total defeat in the super tuesday republican primaries and caucuses: ``i've got to win in illinois. i feel like i've just taken the finals, and i didn't flunk but i didn't do too well either.''

george bush, in a telegram to dole after super tuesday's primaries and caucuses gave him two-thirds of the delegates necessary to win the gop nomination: ``i believe it is now time to look ahead to the issues which distinguish us from the democrats.''

paul simon, on why his cash-poor campaign would not run television advertisements before next week's illinois primary: ``i offer illinois 30 years of service rather than a 30-second commercial.''

jesse jackson, who captured five states and the most popular votes in the super tuesday democratic primaries and caucuses: ``we get stronger every day.''

albert gore, on his electability: ``i'm not going to say that any of our candidates are unelectable. but i have the best chance.''

michael dukakis, on gore as his primary rival: ``i'm not so sure he's a major contender. a guy from massachusetts beat him in texas, beat him in florida.''

pat robertson, who had said he would win the south but won only the washington state caucuses in the 20-state super tuesday contests: ``it isn't over yet.''
police clashed today with 200 tibetan refugees who tried to march to the chinese embassy in new delhi, and seven tibetans and nine policemen were injured, authorities said
the refugees gathered near the parliament house and chanted ``china, stop killing tibetans'' in a rally commemorating the 29th anniversary of the abortive uprising against chinese rule in lhasa, tibet's capital
police intervened when the crowd surged toward a police barricade to attempt a march to the chinese embassy
we were not only stopped, but badly beaten,'' said tashi namgyal, secretary-general of the tibetan youth congress. ``the policemen poked bamboo sticks and hit us on our heads.''
it was on march 10, 1959, that tibetans rose in revolt against the chinese red army that invaded tibet in 1949. china claims the region was part of china since the 13th century. tibetans dispute that claim
after the uprising, the dalai lama, spiritual and temporal leader of the tibetans, and 100,000 of his followers fled to india. the tibetan god-king has since maintained exile headquarters in dharmasala in northern india
in a statement issued today from dharamsala, the dalai lama called on tibetans to ``honor the courage of our brethren in tibet who have taken to the streets to draw attention to their suffering under chinese colonial rule.''
it is indeed a sad reflection of the state of the world that violence seems to be required for the international community to pay attention.''
he was referring to a clash in lhasa last saturday which left as many as five tibetans and three police dead
the rally site in new delhi was strewn with stones, shoes, sandals and sticks after the clash with police. the chinese embassy in the nearby diplomatic district was cordoned off
police accused the tibetans of starting trouble
for no reason the tibetans became violent and started hurling rocks at us,'' said police officer shanti kumar jain. ``we had to stop them.''
it was the second rally by tibetans in new delhi this week. on monday, hundreds of tibetans held a demonstration and chanted ``we shall overcome.'' they were prevented monday from marching on the chinese embassy
i've got to win in illinois. i feel like i've just taken the finals, and i didn't flunk but i didn't do too well either.'' _ republican presidential contender sen. bob dole of kansas, on his crushing loss to vice president george bush in the super tuesday primaries
