it was just a big, old 225-pound puddy tat.'' _ indiana bell supervisor dannie carper, who reattached a downed telephone wire after a year-old pet lioness in the yard was put on a leash
without knowing the exact size of the soviet arsenal, the u.s. intelligence community could effectively verify soviet compliance with the intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty, according to a classified report by the arms control and disarmament agency
the washington post reported today that the acda study, which was sent tuesday to members of the senate foreign relations committee said, the pact's ``verification measures posed significant risks for the soviets of u.s. detection'' even though ``u.s. intelligence cannot achieve a total count'' of soviet medium-range and shorter-range nuclear-armed missiles and lauchers that are to be eliminated under the agreement
the post said the acda report seemed to answer criticisms by sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., and others who maintain that soviet compliance with the inf treaty cannot be verified because the u.s. intelligence community is uncertain about how many ss20 medium-range missiles the soviets have
the report also said that u.s. officials have assumed ``soviet declarations for total numbers, locations, and characteristics of their treaty-limited items could be false'' so they would not be used to verify soviet compliance
the soviets said last year they planned to destroy 650 deployed or stored ss20s but analysts at the defense intelligence agency, an arm of the defense department, have said the soviets have at least 165 additional ss20s. helms said this was an indication the soviets may have hidden some of the missiles for potential use against u.s. european alllies
the report acknowledge that soviet retentions of some missiles couldn't be ruled out but noted that the united states would scrutinize the destruction of ``all launch-critical equipment'' and that all test flights would be barred six months after the treaty takes affect
