striking scriptwriters agreed to resume negotiations today with both sides under a gag order not to disclose details of the talks, while producers of the oscar ceremonies vowed the show must go on
the writers guild of america went on strike sunday after rejecting the latest offer by the alliance of motion picture and television producers. the dispute centered on artistic control of scripts and money received from reruns
commissioner leonard farrell of the federal mediation and conciliation service imposed a gag order on negotiators for both sides tuesday, blocking any disclosures about the bargaining
it's a mediation session and that's all i can say,'' guild spokeswoman cheryl rhoden said after the gag order was imposed
it's not an unusual situation in a strike,'' she said. ``it's important that those topics on the table be kept there, rather than be aired in the media.''
writers working on the academy awards show slated for april 11 said they left its script half written when they walked out. but producer samuel goldwyn jr. said: ``the show must go on, and it will.''
the academy was denied a guild waiver to let writers finish the show
about 125 east coast scriptwriters picketed outside the mgm building in new york city on wednesday. it was the first protest by the eastern arm of the guild
in the manhattan protest, three writers of ``late night with david letterman,'' wearing jackets bearing the show's logo, walked the picket line
william peter blatty, who wrote ``the exorcist,'' joined pickets, as did screen actors guild member barbara feldon of ``get smart'' fame
the union is only as strong as its ability to strike,'' said marcher john patrick shanley, a best original screenplay oscar nominee for ``moonstruck.''
some rock climbers at hueco tanks state historical park have been gluing stones to the sheer rock walls to create handholds and footholds, officials say
the practice has forced a ban on rock-climbing while officials survey the damage and decide whether to allow climbers back on the rocks, parks and wildlife department spokeswoman suzanne carter said wednesday
hueco tanks was created to protect prehistoric rock drawings. the area attracted people as long as 10,000 years ago because of the water that collects in ``huecos,'' or hollows, in the granite rock formations
the defaced walls were discovered in mid-february and the park was closed indefinitely on march 1 to technical climbers, who use ropes, bolts and wedges. climbers use the equipment at hueco tanks because some of the park's climbing routes are among the most challenging in north america
bolts are screwed into stone to secure safety ropes. the practice is banned at hueco tanks, but park workers have struck an unofficial truce with climbers: if climbers don't drill any more bolts, the existing bolts won't be removed
wedges are placed in cracks and also secure safety ropes. they are supposed to be removable, but some climbers apparently have been trying to make the wedges permanent
they put a wedge in a crack, then they will glue it into place with the epoxy glue if it's not secure,'' ms. carter said
even worse, she said, is evidence that some climbers have glued rocks to the rock faces to create handholds _ a practice that would shock most climbers, who take pride in using nothing but chalk on their hands and soft-rubber-soled shoes to aid their ascents
hueco tanks is about 25 miles east of el paso. its brown cliffs were created after molten rock intruded into overlying limestone millions of years ago and the limestone eroded away. some of the formations rise 150 feet
northwest airline's decision to impose a contract on its 6,700 flight attendants has put the airline and the union on a ``collision course,'' says a teamsters official
the contract that the airline said it will impose april 1 is substantially the same as the proposal that negotiators fashioned in talks before the feb. 26 strike deadline passed, northwest said wednesday
we're not asking them to accept this. they've already rejected it. we're putting it into place,'' said terry erskine, the airline's vice president of law and labor relations
erskine said the airline has not talked with the union about its plan to impose the contract, but he said if attendants decide to strike, the airline is prepared to hire permanent replacements
they're on a collision course, and everybody's going to get hurt,'' william genoese, director of the teamsters airline division and the flight attendants' chief negotiator, told wcco-tv wednesday
when asked what the chances of a strike next week are, genoese said: ``i would say they're pretty close to 100 percent. i would say unless somebody gets the people to the bargaining table ... the company's the one that's going to hurt itself.''
teamsters have called a strategy meeting monday in washington, d.c., for local union officers and strike captains at northwest, he said
the main obstacle to reaching a settlement between the airline and the flight attendants has been disagreement over how to raise lower-paid b-scale attendants to higher paid a-scale wages
northwest has proposed extending the b-scale from five years to eight years, meaning lower-wage flight attendants would have to wait an additional three years before earning top-scale wages, erskine said
b-scale flight attendants have said the airline is trying to break a promise that they would earn a-scale wages after five years
the union also has objected to two-tier wage agreements, saying they pit junior workers against senior workers
the issue has intensified since northwest acquired republic airlines in 1986. roughly one-third of the 2,600 former republic attendants work for b-scale wages and the other two-thirds have said they wouldn't get enough out of northwest's latest wage offer
under the contract proposal that will be implemented, the entry-level wage will go from more than $13,000 a year to $15,000 a year, and the top base wage will go from the current $32,000 up to $35,000 a year, erskine said
our door, of course, will always be open for further collective bargaining,'' erskine said
four cambodian guerrilla leaders accused of human rights abuses have been dismissed from their military posts, a spokesman for the resistance group said today
son sann, president of the khmer people's national liberation front, ordered the dismissals of chea chhut, liv ne, gen. dien del and gen. hing kunthon in early february, said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the front is one of three major resistance groups fighting vietnamese forces in cambodia. it operates from bases along the thai-cambodian border
we want to let the people investigate the alleged human rights abuses, what was done,'' he said in a telephone interview
another reason (for the dismissals) is we want to reorganize and clear up the climate at the border,'' he said. the spokesman did not specify the alleged abuses
in recent years, international aid workers and organizations like the u.s. lawyers committee for human rights have accused some khmer people's national liberation front commanders of dispensing justice arbitrarily and allowing abuses against cambodian civilians and local thais
some front soldiers also have been arrested by the thais for banditry
the four officials have been moved to inactive posts and were replaced by their assistants, the spokesman said. asked about their whereabouts, the spokesman said: ``they are surely not at the border.'' president. pickup 6th graf pvs, `suharto came...' one name cq for suharto and sudharmono.</note>
the national assembly today unanimously re-elected president suharto, but a military general angrily protested the selection process for vice president in which a suharto aide is favored
the people's consultative assembly re-elected suharto, the only presidential candidate, to a fifth five-year term. suharto, 66, has led the nation of 170 million people since 1967. his re-election indicates he is in firm control of the island republic and its 400,000-member armed forces
the 1,000-member assembly, the nation's highest policy-making body, meets every five years to choose the president and vice president and issue new guidelines for state policy
state secretary sudharmono, one of suharto's most trusted aides, was expected to be elected vice president on friday, the 11th and final day of the assembly session. sudharmono, 61, chairs the governing golkar party
military sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the army was opposed to sudharmono's nomination and wanted the newly appointed armed forces commander, gen. try sutrisno, 52, to fill the post
the opposition moslem united development party nominated its chairman, jailani nario, 59, for vice president
shortly after suharto's re-election, a military general sprang to the podium to charge the selection process for vice president was unfair
brig. gen. ibrahim saleh of the government-nominated military faction grabbed the microphone at the podium and said:
we indonesian soldiers who believe in god and defend honesty and justice, have heard rumors saying that the nomination of the vice president is not being fairly and correctly carried out.''
saleh said, ``there are certain things that we feel are against our conscience.'' he did not elaborate
saleh was shouted down and later taken away by fellow officers and wang suwandi, secretary-general of the national assembly
later, the commander of the powerful national security agency, gen. benny murdani, told reporters that saleh's statement did not represent the official view of the armed forces and that he was speaking for himself
suharto was not present during the session
suharto came to power following a 1965 communist coup attempt in which six army generals were killed before the challenge was smashed by forces he then led as commander of the army strategic command
suharto is expected to form a new cabinet later this month that will have to tackle urgent problems of economic development, including how to cope with a $42.1 billion foreign debt
indonesia's economy was hit hard in the last five years by economic recession and a sharp drop in the price of oil, a major foreign exchange earner. the country has to set aside $6.4 billion _ nearly a third of its annual budget _ to pay its loan installments for the fiscal year beginning in april
the people's consultative assembly is comprised of a 500-member parliament and 500 provincial and district officials
in elections last april, the golkar party won 299 seats in parliament, which also has 100 government-nominated members from the military. the moslem united development party has 63 seats and the indonesian democratic party 38 seats
in the assembly, golkar has 548 seats as well as 151 government-nominated members from the military and 147 from the provinces. the moslem united development party has 93 and the indonesian democratic party 61
experts testifying about possible causes of a continental airliner crash did not rule out disturbance from a plane landing on an adjacent runway, but said winds could have swept away any such effect
turbulent winds lead to the early demise of vortex,'' said james hallock, who has studied the air currents caused by plane landings for the department of transportation
hallock testified wednesday during the second day of a national transportation safety board hearing into the nov. 15 crash of continental flight 1713, which killed 28 people and injured 54 at denver's stapleton international airport
george greene of the national aeronautics and space administration's langley research center, who also has studied vortex, agreed that winds generally diminish the effect of such turbulence
federal aviation administration officials tried to elicit from greene a definite statement on whether vortex caused the stapleton crash. but ntsb board member joseph t. nall, chairman of the inquiry, would not allow him to answer
nall said conclusions about what caused the crash must be made by the ntsb when it completes its investigation. a final report is not expected until later this year
continental spokesman bruce hicks said the witnesses' testimony did not mean vortex should be ruled out as a possible cause. ``nobody shot down anything today,'' he said
earlier wednesday, an airplane engineer testified that enough snow fell during the 24 minutes that continental 1713 awaited takeoff for ice buildup on the wings to have been a possible factor in the crash
continental officials said they believe wing icing can be ruled out as a factor because the plane exceeded the speed at which it likely would have stalled from ice
ralph brumby, manager of aerodynamics and acoustics for mcdonnell douglas corp., which manufactured the dc-9, said 0.032 inches of precipitation, or about one-third of an inch of snow, fell in the 24 minutes between de-icing and takeoff
if all that snow turned to ice on the wings, the dc-9 could have stalled after takeoff, brumby said. ice can change the shape of a wing, affecting lift
brumby, under questioning by continental officials, said that the amount of precipitation that fell between the time the plane was de-iced and takeoff was enough to cause the plane to stall at about 150 knots, or a little more than 170 mph
but he said it was impossible to draw a definite conclusion that ice on the wing was a factor based on the theory that all the snow had turned to ice
there are so many open parameters,'' he said. ``we don't know the amount of roughness generated by the water collection.''
he also said officials do not know how long the de-icing fluid was able to prevent buildup before the plane took off
at least 19 people were reported killed in punjab state today and wednesday despite government efforts to give militant sikhs a freer hand in trying to resolve the region's problems
sikh gunmen killed three sikh policemen standing guard outside a high school where examinations were under way today in the village of dari wala, amritsar district police chief mohammed izhar alam said
he said the four gunmen, who used chinese-made ak-47 assault rifles, arrived and fled on a tractor
two people were killed in the village of mehsampura early today when sikh gunmen sprayed the sleeping village with gunfire, the united news of india reported. the identity of the victims was not immediately available
dari wala and mehsampura are near the town of mehta, about 25 miles east of amritsar
on wednesday, seven people were killed by sikh extremists in the amritsar district. seven other deaths were reported in the state, including police slayings of two suspected extremists in shootouts
the deaths came as militant sikhs on wednesday installed jasbir singh rode as chief priest at the golden temple in amritsar, sikhism's holiest shrine
on friday, the government released rode, who had been held since 1985 on accusations of sedition but never tried. on sunday, the government said it was dissolving the punjab state assembly, which had been controlled by a moderate sikh party
both moves were seen as an effort by prime minister rajiv gandhi's administration to try to involve militant leaders in bringing an end to the increasing violence in punjab state
the latest killings raised to at least 417 the number of people killed in attacks blamed on sikh extremists since the start of the year
last year, more than 1,000 people died in sikh attacks in the state
most of the victims have been hindus or moderate sikhs
sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an alternative to hinduism and islam, claim they are discriminated against by india's majority hindus. sikhs make up less than 2 percent of india's population, but are a majority in punjab. hindus are more than 80 percent
sikh extremists have been agitating for more political autonomy or an independent state since 1982
joseph franceschi, a socialist deputy in the national assembly and former secretary of state for public security, died today after a long illness, the socialist federation announced. he was 64
franceschi, a close friend of president francois mitterrand, died about 7 a.m. at his home in alfortville southeast of paris. he had been hospitalized for the past month. the federation said he died after a ``long and cruel illness,'' without adding further details
franceschi held three cabinet posts under mitterrand
the first was as secretary of state for the elderly. in august 1982, he was named secretary of state for public security. after two years, he returned to the post of secretary of state for retired persons and the elderly, which he held until the socialists lost power in march 1986
franceschi was born jan. 15, 1924 in tunis, tunisia and had a degree in letters and a doctorate in political science. he became mayor of alfortville in 1965 and was elected a deputy in the national assembly on the socialist ticket in 1973, serving as a vice president of the assembly in 1977-78
the funeral was scheduled for saturday at the notre dame church in alfortville
a political opposition leader who was ordered freed after four months in prison was arrested again as he was headed home, his wife and police said today
karpal singh was released wednesday after a court ruled that one of the charges used in his original arrest was erroneous. singh is vice president of the opposition democratic action party and a member of parliament
the party condemned the rearrest ``in the strongest terms possible.''
a statement issued by party deputy secretary general lee lam thye said the action shows the disregard the executive arm of the government has for the judiciary
karpal and his wife, gurmit kaur, were traveling home from ipoh after his release when police stopped their car at a roadblock and arrested karpal, kaur said
she said they were stopped near nibong tebal, a village near karpal's hometown of penang. penang is 180 miles northwest of kuala lumpur
later at the penang police station i was told that he was being detained under the internal security act,'' kaur said in a telephone interview
a police spokesman at the federal police headquarters today confirmed the arrest
karpal originally was arrested under the internal security act on oct. 27, together with the leader of the opposition in parliament, lim kit siang, and others. the act allows imprisonment without trial
the national news agency bernama said the regional high court in ipoh, 120 miles north of kuala lumpur, found earlier wednesday that the detention order was made without care, caution and a proper sense of responsibility
karpal was one of 119 people detained under the internal security act between october and december, government officials said. the act allows imprisonment without trial
prime minister mahathir mohamad has said the arrests were necessary to prevent malay-chinese racial clashes
on tuesday, deputy home affairs minister megat junid megat ayub told parliament that 86 people were still being held under the act
