the author of a letter from democrats on the house judiciary committee calling for the temporary resignation of attorney general edwin meese iii said today there is ``considerable sentiment'' for even harsher action against meese
a republican on the committee, however, called the letter ``an outrageous political move,'' and a meese spokesman said the attorney general would not comply
meanwhile, swiss oilman bruce rappaport has testified under oath before independent counsel james mckay in the criminal investigation involving meese and a proposed $1 billion iraqi pipeline project, according to sources familiar with the probe
eleven democrats on the judiciary committee called wednesday for meese to step down until that and other independent counsel investigations into meese's conduct are completed
rep. edward feighan of ohio, who was introduced as the letter's author on ``cbs this morning'', said the committee members did not specifically consider impeachment of meese, but ``there was considerable sentiment for even harsher action than the letter we sent.'' he did not say what other steps might be taken
feighan said that although no republicans on the committee signed the letter, meese had become a ``major embarrassment'' to his party. he also said morale was low in the justice department which meese heads
rep. william mccollum, r-fla., also interviewed on cbs, noted that meese has been cleared every time he has been investigated
this is an outrageous political move on the part of some democrats in a political year,'' he said. mccollum denied that morale was low in the justice department
the pervasive perception that you have allowed personal considerations to encroach on your constitutional responsibilities threatens to breed contempt for your office, your administration and the rule of law itself,'' the letter said
justice department spokesman terry eastland said the letter proposed ``a politically partisan idea and a thoroughly bad idea.''
he said meese ``has every intention of serving to the end of this term. he has spent some time with his lawyers on the investigation, but there has been no serious subtraction of his time or effort from leadership of the department of justice.''
mckay and his deputy, carole bruce, took the statements from rappaport in london on tuesday, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. mckay has granted immunity from prosecution to rappaport
meese's former chief of staff, john richardson, who left the justice department several months ago, also testified separately tuesday afternoon before the federal grand jury in washington which is receiving evidence from mckay's office
richardson, who has joined a richmond, va., law firm, declined on wednesday to discuss his testimony
the independent counsel is investigating whether meese may have violated the foreign corrupt practices act which prohibits paying bribes to foreign officials by u.s. companies and authorizes the attorney general to intervene to block them
the investigation stems from a 1985 memo to the attorney general from his longtime friend, e. robert wallach, who had been hired as legal counsel by rappaport to help secure u.s. support on the pipeline project
wallach's memo says that payments were planned to the israeli labor party in connection with the pipeline. rappaport, a partner in the proposed pipeline, has denied that any such payments to the labor party were contemplated
meese has said he doesn't recall reading the portion of the memo mentioning planned payments to the labor party
rappaport was brought into the project because of his close ties to then-israeli prime minister shimon peres to aid in getting assurances for the iraqi government that israel would not attack the pipeline
the pipeline was never built but was to have been constructed by the san francisco-based bechtel group inc
mckay's investigation of meese which began last may 11, has delved into meese's involvement with scandal-plagued wedtech corp. and the regional bell telephone companies as well as with the pipeline project
the moscow circus rolled out dancing bears and jugglers to announce that it is scheduling its first north american tour in 10 years
company representatives, appearing at radio city music hall on wednesday, said the famous soviet circus will open in toronto on aug. 15 and end their 15-city tour in san francisco on jan. 1. the 200 shows will include 44 performances at radio city between sept. 12 and oct. 9
the circus acts expected include a dozen dancing bears, 17 acrobatic tigers and a quadruple somersault by the cranes aerialist troupe
the troupe has not appeared in north america since 1978, with u.s.-soviet cultural exchanges frozen after the 1979 soviet invasion of afghanistan
