low doses of an anti-cancer drug may help people with severe asthma reduce their need for harmful amounts of cortisone, a study published today suggests
despite the promising results, however, experts cautioned that more study is needed to test the long-term effects of the therapy before it is used routinely
in the study, published in the new england journal of medicine, doctors gave the drug methotrexate to 14 people with severe bronchial asthma. while they took the drug, they were able to reduce their use of prednisone, an artificial form of cortisone, by 36 percent
an estimated 5 percent to 7 percent of americans have asthma. a small minority of these people require daily doses of steroid drugs so they can breathe. prednisone is among the most common of these medications
however, long-term use of high doses of prednisone can lead to obesity, cataracts and weakening of the bones, among other things
dr. michael f. mullarkey of virginia mason clinic in seattle tested methotrexate as an alternative to prednisone for relieving inflammation, an underlying cause of asthma
they found preliminary evidence that methotrexate works. but they cautioned, ``longer and larger studies are needed to define the ultimate benefits and risks associated with the use of methotrexate in severe asthma.''
in an accompanying editorial, drs. gary r. cott and reuben m. cherniack of the university of colorado agreed with that warning
many questions remain to be answered before low-dose methotrexate therapy should be considered as more than an experimental form of treatment for steroid-dependent asthma,'' they wrote
the seattle doctors stopped their study earlier than planned because of the dramatic effects of treatment with methotrexate. nine patients continued to take methotrexate after the study was formally halted and four of them have completely stopped taking prednisone
four patients suffered mild nausea for several hours after taking methotrexate. this problem went away within a few weeks in all but one of them
besides its use in cancer treatment, methotrexate also is given to psoriasis and arthritis sufferers. berlin to potsdam, sted east berlin; adds that truck carried empty propane tanks. picks up 5th graf pvs, `the three...</note>
three men in a flatbed truck today smashed through steel barricades blocking glienicker bridge in communist east germany and roared over the ``bridge of spies'' into west berlin, police said
the dramatic escape across the bridge made famous by numerous east-west spy exchanges over the years occurred shortly before dawn, said a west berlin police spokesman
police at the scene said the 7{-ton truck was loaded with empty propane gas tanks in an attempt to discourage border guards from firing their weapons
the east german border police apparently did not open fire, and the three men fled uninjured, said a police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the truck crashed through two steel gates and an electrified fence on the east german side, raced across the bridge and smashed through another control gate in west berlin, police said
glienicker bridge connects potsdam, east germany with west berlin. potsdam is on berlin's southwest outskirts
the three men _ two of them age 37 and the other 27 _ then reported to west berlin police
among the most famous swaps on glienicker bridge was the feb. 10, 1962 exchange by the united states of convicted soviet kgb master spy col. rudolph abel for francis gary powers, whose u-2 surveillance plane was shot down over the soviet union
jack lemmon, who will be honored tonight by the american film institute with a life achievement award, says luck helped him win good parts and fear helped bring out his best performances
lemmon, 63, landed starring roles in his debut appearances on stage, in film, and on television
there's a tremendous boost in playing a lead, especially in a first job,'' lemmon said, ``because slips of confidence are built into an actor's life. you go from thinking you will never work again to thinking you're the greatest young actor in america.''
after graduating from harvard college, lemmon started in television in ``the arrival of kitty.'' from there, his lead role in a broadway revival of ``room service'' led to his starring performance in the film ``it should happen to you.'' he was only 29
lemmon, talking in his beverly hills office this week as he prepared his acceptance speech for the afi award, said a successful acting career depends on making the most of every opportunity
the very reason we are sitting here talking is that i was able to deliver,'' the two-time oscar winner said. ``but first the doors had to open. i had to get the part.''
after the luck of the draw decides casting, fear takes over, lemmon said
i think you do better work if you're afraid,'' he said
lemmon won academy awards in 1955 and 1973. he was honored first for best supporting actor in ``mister roberts,'' then received a best actor oscar for ``save the tiger.''
a measure designed to put a gambling casino on alcatraz island, once the site of a federal prison that housed some of the nation's most notorious criminals, has been approved for the city ballot
i'd never turn my back on something that would bring money to the city legally,'' said supervisor wendy nelder, one of six city supervisors who voted wednesday to put the advisory measure on the june 7 ballot
the measure asks whether the city should encourage changes in state and federal law to allow a gambling resort on alcatraz, for 29 years a prison for for 1,576 criminals who included al capone and george ``machine gun'' kelly
the prison that was dubbed ``the rock'' was closed in 1963 when attorney general robert kennedy called the facility inhumane
it isn't the first time a casino has been suggested for the island
in 1969, more than 300 recommendations were submitted to mayor joseph alioto about the future of the island in san francisco bay
suggestions included a casino, a home for hippies and a site for a replica of the eiffel tower. alioto favored a giant monument symbolizing ``justice'' on the outcropping a mile off fisherman's wharf that would be a west coast counterpart to the statue of liberty in the new york harbor
the latest casino plan stemmed from a luncheon meeting tuesday of labor leaders, city supervisors and warren hinckle, a san francisco examiner columnist who made an unsuccesful bid for mayor
the casino complex could bring in at least $150 million a year to help san francisco solve a projected budget deficit, said hinckle, whose plan would include a tunnel under the bay to the casinos
the state constitution would need to be changed by voters to exempt the island from state laws that forbid gambling, hinckle said
the federal government would also have to be petitioned to remove alcatraz from the golden gate recreation area, which covers vast stretches of federal open space on both sides of the golden gate bridge. federal officials would then have to sell the island to san francisco
hundreds of tourists visit alcatraz each year for a guided tour of the island that is conducted by park rangers
a man with a criminal record that would have barred him as a foster parent and his wife were ordered held without bail today on charges of shaking their 2-year-old foster son to death, authorities said
walter ``sonny'' hairston, 26, and his wife, maryanne, 33, were arraigned early this morning on charges of murder and involuntary manslaughter in connection with the death of joey huot, said bail commissioner garnita selby
hairston also was charged with providing false background information on foster placement applications, ms. selby said
hairston pleaded guilty in 1981 to charges of rape, aggravated assault and burglary in washington county, but social workers did not know of his record when joey was placed with the couple, authorities said
the boy was placed in the couple's home by catholic social services under a contract with philadelphia's department of human services
since january 1987, 18 children who had been under the care of the city department have died of suspected abuse or neglect
the alleged falsifications on hairston's foster-parent applications prevented caseworkers from identifying him as a former criminal, a source in the state's child welfare system told the philadelphia inquirer. the source said catholic social services had checked with state police and the state's registry of reported child abusers, as required, but hairston was cleared
catholic social services spokeswoman ursula o'reilly declined to comment on the agency's background checks because of the legal proceedings
joey died on jan. 27 at the children's hospital of philadelphia after he was declared brain-dead and his mother gave doctors permission to take him off a respirator
the hairstons were arrested at their home wednesday morning, police said
police said the hairstons told them joey was injured when he fell from a couch during an apparent epileptic seizure. quotes, identities of victims.</note>
a cargo plane flying erratically dove into a residential area, struck a garage and a house and exploded early today, killing a couple in the house and the pilot, officials said
the couple's three children, who were sleeping in an upstairs bedroom, were unhurt and were led to safety by neighbors, said herbert kauffman, assistant police chief for this detroit suburb
the twin-engine beechcraft plane had just taken off from detroit city airport, not the city's main airport, about 12:30 a.m. when it went into a nosedive and struck a garage, propelling a van into the first-floor bedroom of the house next door before crashing into that house and bursting into flames, said police lt. orba underwood
there are parts of the aircraft and car inside the bedroom,'' underwood said
the plane was seen faltering in the air by two warren scout cars, and they were literally on the scene immediately after impact,'' mayor ron bonkowski said. ``they thought at first he might have hit the school playground on the other street. you look another 60 feet, and he'd have been in the street.''
kauffman said police officers craig garwood and alex sywak saw the airplane shortly before it crashed
the aircraft appeared to be flying lower than normal and was ascending and descending erratically.'' kauffman said, quoting a report by the officers. ``it disappeared out of sight, and seconds later they saw a fire flash.''
kauffman identified the victims as norma and harold richardson, both 29. their neighbor whose garage was struck was unharmed, but her house was damaged by flames
the airplane, loaded with automobile axles, was flying from detroit to fort wayne, ind., kauffman said. it crashed about five miles northwest of city airport, which is northeast of downtown detroit. the pilot, thomas bussard of pontiac, was the only person aboard
kauffman said officials at lafayette aviation at the oakland-pontiac airport confirmed the airplane was theirs. a man who did not identify himself answered the telephone at the company and declined comment
it took firefighters about 45 minutes to put out the blaze that engulfed the two-story house and damaged the one-story house and garage next door in this macomb county community, bonkowski said
doug stockel ran across the street and was met at the front door by another neighbor, who kicked down the front door
the kids were already downstairs screaming. he took the kids out, i checked the upstairs. somebody had to go upstairs to make sure there was nobody up there,'' stockel said
as i'm thinking about it, with the gas mains in back, that house could have exploded right there. we could have opened that front door and the flames could have nailed us,'' stockel said. ``the thing is, that was only done on an impulse.''
the children _ randi, 9; erin, 5, and debra, 4 _ were taken to grandparents in warren
don hunt said he was in his house two doors away from the victims' home when he heard the explosion
we were just getting ready for bed,'' he said. ``one minute i hear a real loud roar coming in like a low-flying plane and then real fast ... this is too loud, this is too low. and crash and flames and everything. so you could tell right away it was a plane
at first i thought it could have been a helicopter going by, like a police helicopter, but then it was the wrong kind of sound. it was coming in too fast, like something dropping fast.''
kauffman said the area surrounding the crash site was sealed off and officials from the federal aviation administration and the national transportation safety board were at the scene investigating. offering to end missile duel. no pickup.</note>
iraq fired its 50th long-range missile into tehran today and then iraqi president saddam hussein offered to halt the deadly missile duel if iran did the same
but he warned in a baghdad radio broadcast, monitored in nicosia, that iraq will go on pounding iranian cities with missiles if iran continues to hit population centers, launch ground offensives or attack ``any arab city.''
iran said some civilians were killed in the latest attacks. iraq fired two long-range missiles into the iranian capital, raising to 50 the number it claims to have shot into tehran in 11 days
iran claims to have fired 25 missiles into baghdad and other iraqi cities in the same period
the latest iraqi bombardment was in retaliation for an overnight iranian artillery attack on the southern iraqi cities of basra and qurna, baghdad's official iraqi news agency reported
the agency, monitored in nicosia, said ``a number of civilians'' were killed in basra and qurna, which is 40 miles north of basra
hussein's statement, read by an unidentified military spokesman, followed a joint meeting in baghdad of the ruling revolutionary command council and the regional command of the arab baath socialist party, at which saddam presided
it said the iraqi bombardment of tehran and other iranian cities would halt at 4 p.m. friday if the iranians stop firing
the statement charged that tehran triggered the latest flare-up in the ``war of the cities'' by hitting baghdad with two missiles feb.29
so the last bombardment should be iraq's before the cease-fire goes into effect,'' the statement said
there was no immediate response from tehran, which has appealed to the united nations and other world bodies to force iraq to halt the bombardment
hundreds of civilians on both sides have been killed or wounded in the missile duel, the first time tehran has been hit by long-range surface-to-surface weapons since the iran-iraq war broke out in september 1980
if the enemy iranian regime attacks any of our cities with missiles, warplanes or artillery in retaliation for the last iraqi bombardment, we will continue attacking and teach the rulers of tehran the appropriate lessons,'' the iraqi statement said
it said that if the iranians launched any new ground assaults, ``we shall retaliate ... by attacking all iranian cities ... with all means.''
the iraqis have been braced for weeks for a major iranian offensive in the southern sector of the battlefront, where tehran has been massing troops
the iranians have also been attacking in the mountainous northern sector for several weeks
the iraqi statement called on the u.n. security council to impose sanctions, including an arms embargo, on iran for failing to comply with the council's july 20 cease-fire resolution
earlier, tehran radio reported that iraqi warplanes bombed the central city of isfahan, former capital of ancient persia, hitting a mosque and a school and killing or wounding some children
the radio reported other air raids on hamadan, arak, dezful, shustar, shahr-e kord and burujerd in western iran. it claimed one iraqi jet was shot down by anti-aircraft fire over arak. baghdad denied losing any planes
the official islamic republic news agency said the iraqi missiles hit residential areas of tehran. it said a number of civilians were killed or wounded, but it gave no figures
irna also said iranian fighter-bombers attacked iraqi military positions and economic targets in basra and al-amarah, further north, in three raids today. it said iran inficted ``heavy casualties and damage.''
iranian authorities say at least 157 civilians have been killed and more than 420 wounded in missile attacks on tehran alone in the past 11 days
iraq has not given any casualty figures
in basra, women vowed to have more babies to help their country's war effort, the iraqi news agency said. it said the women promised hussein to ``increase reproduction'' in response to his call for bigger families last november
a police squad leader accused by fellow officers of ordering the execution of a black youth testified that he was drunk at the time and had assaulted the victim
warrant officer leon de villers, 36, concluded his testimony wednesday after six days on the stand during a trial that began in october
the trial is unusual because it focuses on testimony by policemen against their fellow officers. five members of the all-white, 10-member unit have alleged that de villiers and his codefendant, constable david goosen, were responsible for the execution and a fatal stabbing that occurred a few hours earlier. de villiers and goosen are charged with murder in both deaths
according to the five officers, goosen stabbed one black man, andile plaatjie, 45, during an unauthorized foot patrol and later shot 18-year-old mlungisi stuurman in the head after being told by de villiers that the badly beaten youth should be ``taken out.''
de villiers and goosen contended that stuurman was shot accidentally after being taken to a riverside to wash off blood from injuries inflicted when officers assaulted him
de villiers testified that he had drunk most of a bottle of brandy shortly before his unit's two forays into the black section of the cape province town of cradock in july 26, 1986. other members of the unit also drank heavily, according to testimony, and engaged in a blood-oath ceremony in which they swore to keep secrets
de villiers said he was too drunk to accompany his men during the predawn foot patrol, when the stabbing allegedly occurred
during the second foray, de villiers said, he lost his temper because stuurman refused to answer questions, hit the youth and then stood by as other members of the unit beat and kicked him
de villiers said he decided not to report the subsequent shooting of stuurman because he was ``shocked'' and under the influence of alcohol
he said he could not explain why, if the shooting was accidental, five members of the unit alleged it was deliberate
in separate developments:
_ the new nation, a black-oriented weekly newspaper, reported thursday that a black activist was abducted from his home near johannesburg by eight white soldiers last month, taken to a cemetery, and interrogated while lying on a grave with a gun pressed to his neck. police and military spokesmen said the allegation was under investigation
_ a johannesburg police sergeant on trial for murder testified wednesday that he was ordered by his co-defendant, a police captain, to kill three men last year. two of the men were shot dead and one was injured
sgt. robert van der merwe said he carried out the assignment after capt. jack la grange told him the three targets were working for the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement. testimony in the trial has indicated the murders were related to drug smuggling and had no connection to the anc
gallaudet university's new president, told by an influential congressman she may have no choice but to step down, said today she will meet with instructors and students who oppose her appointment as the head of the nation's only university for the deaf
the congressman, rep. david bonior, d-mich., said he told dr. elisabeth zinser, the school's new president, on wednesday that federal aid for the school may be jeopardized if she refuses to leave the post
there's a variety of scenarios and that's one,'' bonior told the washington post afterward. ``i prefer that she make the decision through a period of meeting with students and faculty and arrive at a decision that's best for the university.''
zinser later acknowledged to an interviewer that ``a very strong signal is being sent to me to resign, but i'm not sure that's uniform.''
her selection has been opposed by students, instructors and alumni who contend it is time for gallaudet to have a deaf president. zinser hears normally and does not know sign language
interviewed today on abc-tv's ``good morning america,'' zinser said ``my deepest concern is to see the university continue its good work and get back to educating students and carrying out its research mission.''
today is the day in which i'm going to attempt to establish the communication that is needed with the students and the faculty. ... my concern at this stage is that as president of the university, that i exercise the leadership to get the university back to business and engaged in the good work that it is doing.''
but such talks are doomed, said the president of the national association for the deaf
gary olsen, himself a graduate of gallaudet, said on the abc-tv program that ``there's no way there will be an open dialogue amongst the faculty, staff and students with her. ... if she wants business to continue, then she should really be honest about it and back down.''
the appointment of zinser, who has been chanceollor of the university of north carolina at greensboro, was announced sunday night. protests closed the university monday; boycotts left classrooms empty tuesday and wednesday
protest leaders had said they were considering a mass student withdrawal today. but one leader, tim rarus, said this morning, ``''we've decided not to do that. we would lose our leverage.''
one deaf student said the protests recall the classic civil rights demonstrations of the 1960s
this is the selma of the deaf,'' gallaudet graduate student kathy karcher said at a rally wednesday, referring to the alabama city where civil rights demonstrators were bloodied by club-wielding police 23 years ago. ``this is a very important moment.''
protest leaders say demonstrations will continue until zinser is replaced. they are also demanding the replacement of jane bassett spilman, the chairwoman of the board of trustees, and the implementation of a plan to make deaf people a majority on the school's 20-member board of trustees. the board has just four deaf members
the gallaudet protesters have encountered none of the violence of the selma demonstrators, but they say their struggle is akin to the trials endured by blacks in their fight for equality
on wednesday, more than half of gallaudet's 274-member faculty attended a meeting and voted overwhelmingly to ask the school's board of trustees to oust spilman. the faculty group also endorsed the students' demands
those are the people i think who are really deaf,'' deaf actress marlee matlin said on ``nightline,'' referring to gallaudet's board of trustees. matlin won a 1986 academy award for her performance as a dropout from a school for the deaf in ``children of a lesser god.''
gallaudet was founded by an act of congress in 1864, and receives three-quarters of its $76 million annual budget in federal funds
investigators in the tawana brawley case have uncovered new details about events during the four days she claims she was abducted and sexually abused, but they are still uncertain exactly what happened, according to a report published today
in a related development, child protection officials are investigating whether miss brawley's welfare has been endangered since she was whisked into seclusion by the rev. al sharpton, according to another report
miss brawley, who was 15 at the time she disappeared for four days starting last nov. 24, has said she was held in a wooded area and sexually abused by at least two and as many as six white men, one of whom flashed a police-type badge. she was found in a plastic bag with racial slurs scrawled on her body and smeared with animal feces
gov. mario cuomo appointed robert abrams, state attorney general, as special prosecutor. but sharpton and miss brawley's attorneys, c. vernon mason and alton maddox, have withheld her cooperation from the investigators
today's new york times reported that interviews with witnesses indicated that:
_ miss brawley made an abrupt decision to get off a bus near her home in wappingers falls, which apparently ruled out the possibility that someone deliberately ambushed her
_ investigators found traces of marijuana and hashish in an apartment near where she was found and that her family had recently been evicted from. the denim jacket she was wearing when she disappeared was also found there and had traces of the drugs in it. but tests performed on miss brawley showed no signs of drug use
_ just before she was found, her mother went into the apartment to look for her. although she found no one, she said she suspected someone had been there because the heat was turned on. a local investigator who entered the apartment described it as ``blisteringly hot.''
_ a charcoal substance that might have been used to write racial slurs on miss brawley's body was found on leather gloves underneath the garbage bag
_ dog feces were found inside and outside her clothing, suggesting to investigators that she might have been naked when they got on her. the yard of the apartment was littered with such feces
in addition, more evidence has surfaced indicating that miss brawley spent at least part of the four days around the apartment, according to the times
on wednesday, child protection officials began investigating whether miss brawley has suffered ``emotional and educational'' neglect, insufficient psychiatric and medical care and inadequate supervision, according to a report in today's daily news
a ``possible neglect'' complaint was filed last week by 79-year-old conrad lynn, chief counsel of the mid-hudson region of the national association for the advancement of colored people. wappingers falls is 50 miles north of new york city
but matthew strong, miss brawley's uncle and legal guardian, said miss brawley is receiving the care she needs
she's going to school and she's in therapy,'' said the monticello police officer
a woman who apparently was part of a crowd that grabbed more than $700,000 that fell from an armored truck has had a change of heart and turned in $28,000, police said
she said she picked up the money and then got kind of scared, so she decided to turn it in,'' sgt. william herndon said late wednesday
the woman, identified only as a 30-year-old postal worker, gave police two clear plastic bags containing a total of $28,000 wednesday, more than 24 hours after a crate filled with money fell from the back of a loomis armored inc. truck
however, most of the estimated $771,000 that was in the crate is still missing, and police warned opportunists they could face felony theft charges if they don't return the cash
the woman, who may have been the one seen throwing money bags into her car and driving away, could be charged with failure to return property to its lawful owner, a misdemeanor, herndon said. she was interviewed by police
since talking with the woman, police think more people than they originally believed were involved snatched the estimated 20 bags still missing. on tuesday, they thought only three to five people took advantage of loomis' misfortune
she did say ... there were so many people picking up sacks that she didn't believe it,'' herndon said. ``it makes sense, because when we interviewed people at the scene, no one knew anything.''
one man at the scene, television repairman luis lopez, managed to save two bags containing $20,050 each and took them straight to loomis' nearby offices
investigators were working to trace license plate numbers and vehicle descriptions reported by witnesses and trying to compile a list of the lost bills' serial numbers
a spokesman for oakland-based loomis declined comment on the incident
the armored truck, carrying more than $1.7 million collected from 20 banks in the san francisco bay area, was headed for loomis' offices from downtown
lt. barry johnson said the driver claimed the rear door had been locked, but that a dolly containing a crate of bills slammed against the door and forced it open
the driver, whose name was not disclosed, did not learn of the mishap until a honking motorist pointed it out two blocks away. police described him as ``white as a ghost and real upset.''
before the driver could return, a crowd gathered around the fallen bags. some people put money back into the crate but others hung onto it, including one man who witnesses said tossed numerous bags into his pickup truck and drove off
police declined to be specific wednesday about the amount involved, saying only that it was more than $500,000. the san francisco examiner reported that $771,000 in $10, $20 and $50 bills fell out of the truck while close to $1 million remained inside
security forces in sao tome and principe shot and killed a suspected american mercenary and captured another in an aborted coup in the west african nation, the head of the national news agency said today
a south african official denied earlier reports that his country was involved in the coup attempt in sao tome and principe, a marxist-ruled island nation off the coast of gabon
stp-press director manuel dende told reporters in the angolan capital of luanda one of two foreign mercenaries presumed to be american was killed when the invaders attacked the central police station in sao tome, the capital, early tuesday. he said the other was captured by government troops
authorities in the two-island nation say two armed raiders were killed, one wounded and 43 captured after they landed on beaches close to sao tome in an abortive attempt to overthrow the government of president manuel pinto da costa. a policeman also was wounded
dende did not provide any further information on the suspected american mercenaries
he told angolan reporters the leader of the invading force, indentified as the head of a sao tome opposition group, was among those captured, along with mercenaries from several other african countries. he said the vessel used to drop the raiders in fishing boats also was seized
he said the coup leader was afonso dos santos, head of a group calling itself the liberators of sao tome and principe. angolan television, radio and newspaper reports quoted unidentified official sources as saying the invading force may have been landed close to the islands by south africans
the south african foreign affairs deparment's director for west africa said that south africa was ``absolutely and categorically not involved.''
reports have appeared recently in west european newspapers about the presence of south africans in equatorial guinea, about 180 miles north of the island of sao tome
in lisbon, portugal, a sao tome government opponent said dos santos was a former colonel in the portuguese colonial army who led an opposition movement based in walvis bay, a south african enclave on the coast of south-west africa
johannesburg's sunday star newspaper last may quoted ``a report circulating in lisbon'' that up to 90 sao tome refugees who arrived in walvis bay seeking political asylum a year before were being trained to launch an armed revolt against their government
the south african government immediately denied the report and said it was trying to find a country which would accept the refugees. they reportedly have been held in custody for the past year as illegal immigrants
the citizen, a pro-government johannesburg newspaper, quoted a roman catholic priest in walvis bay as saying 74 of the refugees were still in the enclave, 1,750 miles south of sao tome and principe
dende quoted military authorities as saying the capture of most of the invading party ``might not have been possible without the help of the people of the island.'' earlier reports said fishermen alerted authorities about four armed men, believed to be on reconnaissance for the coup attempt, two weeks previously
in recent months, pinto da costa has called on government opponents to return from exile. wooed by u.s. and west european aid, he has also unveiled plans to allow small private companies to operate within the state-controlled economy
the president also has announced plans to hold the first general elections since the country gained independence from portugal in 1975. his sao tome and principe liberation movement has ruled as the country's only political party since then. graf pvs, ``all the...'</note>
soldiers shot and wounded three palestinians today in a pre-dawn riot that arabs said was started by jewish settlers who shot at arab homes and vandalized their cars
jewish settlers said the clash began after they were awakened by arab rioters shouting ``slaughter the jews!'' and ``god is great!'' fearing the arabs wanted to attack their homes, some settlers said they rushed into the streets of hebron and fired warning shots
the army said the violence by arabs was aimed only at the military
arab residents said they were awakened at about midnight by carloads of settlers raiding their neighborhoods
all the city was sleeping, nobody was in the streets,'' mustafa natsche, the former mayor, told the associated press. ``it was a dreadful night. there was a sort of battle under the windows of my house, shooting, crying, moaning.''
he said the arabs responded to the attack by throwing rocks at the settlers and israeli troops who arrived
but rabbi moshe levinger told the ap, ``they (the arabs) ran down near the synagogue. they wanted to enter jewish homes. they carried stones. we responded by throwing stones and firing in the air.''
the area military commander disputed levinger's claim
it's important to stress that the riots were directed at the army, and at no stage was there an intention or attempt to attack jewish homes,'' the commander said on israel radio. he did not give his name, in keeping with military regulations
an ap reporter saw dozens of vandalized arab cars, including a station wagon with all its windows broken. arab residents showed several revolver cartridges they collected after the clash and said they turned over nearly 100 to the israeli authorities as evidence
levinger, who has lived in hebron nine years, is one of the founders of the 40-family beit hadassah settlement inside the predominantly arab city of 50,000. there is a second jewish enclave in hebron, the hillside neighborhood of tel rumayda
levinger claimed 500 arabs were involved in the rioting and came to within about 100 yards of jewish homes,. he said about 50 settlers defended the homes
if we hadn't stopped them ... there would have been a slaughter of jews, men, women and children,'' levinger said
but natsche and other arab witnesses said the clashes occured without provocation in arab neighborhoods several miles from jewish homes
natsche pointed to the smashed windows and slit tires of his car parked outside his home, about one mile from the jewish settlements
army spokesmen said 20 to 30 arabs were involved in each of three disturbances in hebron. they said the arabs erected stone barricades, set tires ablaze and threw rocks
according to the army account, the unrest began about 11 p.m. wednesday and lasted until about 3 a.m. at one point, a jeep with soldiers was trapped by the rioters, the army said
in the course of the riots, the lives of the soldiers were endangered, and they were forced to shoot,'' the area commander said
three arabs were lightly wounded in the legs by army gunfire, and two women were taken to a hospital suffering the effects of tear gas, he said
the army said one arab car was set ablaze, but that the unrest was instigated by palestinian rioters, not jewish settlers
the arab-run palestine press service said israelis from the nearby kiryat arba settlement started to smash car windows about midnight and arab residents went outside to see what was happening. the first arabs to go outside were beaten by settlers, said the agency
on wednesday, defense minister yitzhak rabin said the army's efforts to curb three months of palestinian unrest have been hampered by the presence of jewish settlements in the occupied lands
also wednesday, the 10-member inner cabinet refused to endorse a u.s. peace plan designed to end the violence in which at least 87 palestinians have been killed since dec. 8
rabin, speaking on israel television, said the presence of jewish settlers made it difficult for israeli soldiers to put down the unrest
the problem could have been simpler if the whole territory was arab, without jewish settlements. it would have been very easy to close it and not to deal with the problem of roads,'' he said
the navy has pulled the plug on helping production of the abc-tv ``supercarrier'' series, saying the show inaccurately portrays the lives of the crew and officers on a fictional aircraft carrier
after lengthy deliberations the navy determined that the scripts for `supercarrier' did not accurately portray the navy and its people; therefore cooperation was withdrawn,'' a navy spokesman said
navy officials declined to comment on specific plot summaries that prompted concern, but one reportedly involved a tale about gun-running military action in central america
navy spokesman capt. michael sherman said abc could regain the navy's support if future scripts are in line with navy interests
show producer charles fries said, ``i think they're in a wait-and-see mode.''
the show, likened to the movie ``top gun'' with its hard rock sound track and f-14 jet fighters, premiered sunday with a 90-minute movie and took a 13.0 rating and 19 percent audience share. it will be broadcast at 8 p.m. sundays over the next seven weeks
fries said the show at first was planned to focus on the lives of the men and women aboard the carrier, but then shifted to action-adventure
from that point on, the navy became more and more disenchanted because essentially they're concerned about their perception (by the public,)'' he said
right now, the navy is in a peacetime mode ... but to do an action-adventure show we had to get off the carrier and bring in some conflict and jeopardy.''
two episodes remain to be shot, and fries said he had ample shipboard footage left to continue production without navy help
the navy charged fries' company $50,000 for the use of navy personnel, planes and facilities for the scenes that have been shot so far
the show is loosely based on the best-selling non-fiction book of the same name by george wilson, a washington post reporter
i was kind of distressed that they didn't get it a little more realistic in terms of what really goes on out there,'' said wilson, who said one admiral told him: ``you ought to sue abc for not plagiarizing your book.'' step</head>
doctors used a laser in clearing a woman's clogged coronary artery but cautioned that there was no evidence that the beam of energy cleared away the fatty despoits
we put a fiber down there, we gave it energy and we did it safely,'' dr. leonard nordstrom said wednesday of the procedure performed at methodist hospital
doctors performed the procedure tuesday on a 38-year-old woman whose right coronary artery was 90 percent clogged
i don't want to overstate what we've done,'' nordstrom stressed at a news conference. ``i think in cases to come we'll have good documentation that we have removed tissue.''
nordstrom said he stopped the non-surgical laser procedure and inflated a balloon to enlarge the vessel opening before there was evidence that the laser had removed any tissue clogging the artery
lasers have been used previously during open-heart surgery, he said. janis konze said she had no second thoughts about being the first patient to undergo the new procedure
everything went fine,'' said konze, who said she first experienced heart pain last summer and consulted with a doctor about a month ago
i feel wonderful. i'm anxious to go home,'' konze said before her release wednesday. ``i expect to be back to work within a week.''
in the procedure, a specially-designed catheter or slender tube is inserted into a patient's arterial system and guided to a position in the coronary artery where a direct beam of laser energy is directed at the blockage
then the catheter is moved forward to position the balloon in the newly enlarged opening. the physician inflates the balloon and spreads the remaining blockage apart to re-open circulation through the artery
the hourlong procedure, during which nordstrom used one-second bursts of laser energy for two to three minutes, was the first coronary application of the system developed by gv medical inc., of plymouth
gv's lastac system is the first integrated system that combines the use of direct laser energy, fiberoptics and balloon angioplasty catheters, the company said
the procedure was pioneered on larger leg arteries. more than 130 procedures have been performed on leg arteries since may 1986 and the system is now in use at 17 sites around the world, gv said in a statement
with the leg arteries, ``the initial success rate was better than 90 percent, with a success percentage rate in the mid 70s on keeping the vessels open,'' james grabek, gv president and chief executive officer, told reporters
the u.s. food and drug administration has given permission for 10 test coronary procedures to be done, nordstrom said. findings from these clinical studies will be reviewed by the fda before approval is granted for additional procedures, or for procedures to be done at other sites, he said
clashes among rival political groups left at least five people dead today during local elections in india's southern andhra pradesh state, a newspaper reported
three people died in fighting between groups from rival communist parties, and a supporter of prime minister rajiv gandhi's congress party was killed by gunfire from a member of the rival telugu desam party, the united news of india reported
another person was reportedly killed by police gunfire
