the former girlfriend of the leader of the right-wing group the order testified that she helped him distribute $2 million of $3.6 million stolen in an armored car robbery in california in june 1984
zillah craig said wednesday that she also helped robert mathews, killed in a december 1984 shootout with fbi agents on whidbey island near seattle, pass counterfeit bills
craig testified wednesday in the sedition-conspiracy trial of 14 men. ten of them are charged with sedition, five are accused of conspiring to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent, and two are accused of interstate transportation of stolen money
craig said that in august 1984 she and mathews traveled to cohoctah, mich., where they spent the night with defendant robert miles, head of the mountain church. she said mathews took a briefcase with him to a meeting with miles that lasted several hours
craig said she and mathews also met in arlington, va., with william pierce, head of the national alliance, a reputed white supremacist organization
pierce is the author of ``the turner diaries,'' a book that government witnesses have testified formed the basis for the order's plans to overthrow the government and establish an all-white nation in the northwest
miles gave mathews a letter of introduction to glenn miller, head of the white patriots party in north carolina, she said. she and mathews visited miller at his home and gave him about $25,000 to $30,000, she testified
miller, who recently agreed to appear at the trial as a prosecution witness, is to testify this week
craig testified that she gave birth to mathews' baby, a girl, about two months before mathews was killed in the shootout with fbi agents. shortly after mathews' death, she said, miles began sending her money with the notation ``widows and children aid fund.''
she also testified that after visiting defendant richard scutari in federal prison at memphis in october 1986, she relayed to miles a message from scutari that he feared james ellison would cooperate with federal agents
ellison, former leader of the arkansas-based survivalist group, the covenent, the sword and the arm of the lord, did testify for three days two weeks ago. he's considered the prosecution's star witness in the case
in other developments, defendant bruce pierce said wednesday he had changed his mind about his statement tuesday that he would plead guilty to conspiring to overthrow the government
u.s. district judge morris arnold ruled tuesday that pierce had voluntarily confessed to fbi agents shortly after his march 1985 arrest in georgia; that statement prompted pierce to announce his guilty plea
pierce contended that he was coerced into confessing, claiming that authorities told him that his wife would be arrested and his three children placed in foster homes in he did not talk to the fbi
pierce, 34, is serving 100 years for racketeering and 150 years for violating the civil rights of outspoken jewish radio talk show host alan berg, who was shot to death in denver
a judge says he sentenced two rabbis and the wife of one of the men to prison because they ``reaped millions'' as part of a $130 million garment industry tax fraud in which more than 200 companies participated
but u.s. district judge john m. walker said wednesday he took into account a lengthy appeal for leniency by lawyers for the three defendants, all members of the ultra-religious lubavitch sect of judaism and active in their brooklyn community
the three were convicted dec. 4 of one count of conspiracy and 44 counts of aiding and assisting the filing of false federal tax returns
rabbi schnejer zalman gurary, 76, who walker called the ``kingpin'' of the scheme, was sentenced to three years in prison and five years on probation, and was fined $2 million
you reaped millions,'' walker told him. the sentence would have been stiffer, but for gurary's failing health and a thick file of letters attesting to gurary's good community deeds, walker said
gurary's son-in-law, nochum sternberg, 43, was sentenced to 18 months in prison and five years on probation. his wife, esther sternberg, 43, gurary's daughter, was sentenced to 120 days in jail and five years on probation
the sternbergs also were fined $1 million
they faced up to five years on the conspiracy count and three years in prison on each of the 44 aiding and assisting counts
the sternbergs have 11 children, four of whom still live at home, and walker said sternberg was not to begin serving his prison sentence until his wife had completed hers
the judge also accommodated the woman's strong religious beliefs by allowing her to leave jail each week for the jewish sabbath
during the six-week trial, the government said the scheme involved phony invoices from a group of 36 companies known collectively as the ``zalga companies.''
the defendants sold phony zalga invoices, primarily to companies in the garment center, indicating that goods had been purchased when in fact no goods were involved
the garment company would then issue a check to the zalga company issuing the phony invoice. the defendants then returned cash to the company, keeping 10 percent to 15 percent of the amount of the check as a commission
representatives of the other companies, a number of whom testified against the three, were sentenced earlier on various tax fraud charges
according to trial testimony, the defendants issued more than $130 million in fraudulent invoices to more than 200 companies between 1979 and 1986
a lyndon larouche associate says he will assume the traditional duties of harris county democratic party chairman, the office he won in an upset
party leaders, meanwhile, said wednesday they are taking steps to thwart claude jones' influence
jones, an associate of the political extremist, threw the democratic party into turmoil tuesday when he narrowly defeated incumbent larry veselka in the primary. jones received 54,394 votes, or 51.46 percent, to veselka's 51,318 votes, or 48.55 percent
the result shocked party leaders who face working under a chairman associated since 1975 with a fringe presidential candidate strongly opposed by the national and state party
members of the party's steering committee met wednesday night to consider a plan by which the party executive committee would empower the party secretary to run the party rather than jones, who takes office may 2. the 664-member executive committee is made up of elected precinct chairmen
former county party chairman barbara stanley, who attended the meeting, said state law places most of the party's power with the committee rather than the chairman, who has no inherent power
party leaders won't challenge jones' right to hold the office, she said, adding she presumes they will not try to stop him from conducting three legally required county party executive committee meetings during his term
jones said he desires to work with the party, help register voters and defeat the republicans, particularly george bush, whom he described as the likely nominee
larouche associate harley schlanger, appearing with jones, asked, ``do the leaders of the democratic party have a right to tell the voters who their party chairman will be?''
jones dismissed as ``a silly question'' an inquiry about analysts' views that jones' common name and the obscurity of the race accounted for his win
he won, he said, because he has ``been working hard pushing larouche's issues, and those issues finally hit a nerve.''
democratic national committee member billie carr of houston said jones was elected because the voters didn't know of his association with larouche. she said she doesn't blame veselka, who didn't campaign for re-election and was out of the city in the weeks before the campaign
jones, who was defeated by veselka in 1986, said his sole occupation is working for larouche. he said he staffs solicitation booths the larouche organization sponsors at airports and other public places
jones said he will back the democratic presidential nominee although he supports larouche
larouche has accused queen elizabeth of drug trafficking and espouses a quarantine of aids patients
one person happy about the flap was texas republican chairman george strake
i wish them (the democrats) every success under their new leadership,'' he said wednesday
contra rebels have released an american volunteer worker for witness for peace after holding him for 10 days in northern nicaragua, a spokesman for the organization said today
dennis marker, washington director for the group, said richard boren, 30, was released to other witness for peace volunteers wednesday evening near the remote town of quilali
witness for peace opposes contra military aid and documents human rights abuses in nicaragua
boren and 11 nicaraguans were captured march 1 in mancotal, about 25 miles from where he was released and 75 miles north of managua. all but one of the nicaraguan captives had escaped and returned to their villages and the other may have been released with boren, marker said
he said the volunteers still had to travel through the remote region where contra ambushes are frequent but were expected to arrive in managua sometime this evening
he is still in an area that is often under contra attack,'' said marker, ``so we do not yet consider him safe.''
based on radio transmissions from the volunteers to other witness for peace workers in managua, marker said, the only thing he knew about boren's condition was that he has a cold. he said that, depending on his condition, boren plans to hold a news conference in managua on friday
marker said the group had conducted a nationwide phone-in campaign wednesday to the state department demanding that u.s. officials tell the contras to release boren immediately
betsy cripes, witness for peace executive director at its headquarters in durham, n.c., also said boren had been released
we just found out ourselves,'' ms. cripes said. ``it'll take several hours to drive there (to managua),'' she said
a contra spokesman in miami said he could not confirm the report, and there was no immediate word from the state department
the contras earlier had said the american was being ``detained.''
on monday, a spokesman for the state department said contra leaders in washington and florida had agreed to release boren as soon as the rebels could do so safely in front of reliable witnesses
boren had been working in jinotega in northern nicaragua since november, documenting contra activity for witness for peace, the group said. ms. cripes said he would return to north carolina by monday. groups</head> with appellate ruling about nbc, from a0505. picks up in 5th graf, `the prosecutor ...'</note>
three intelligence operatives said fbi and cia officials asked them to infiltrate the political organizations of extremist lyndon larouche, a declassified document shows
the document was made available wednesday to defense lawyers in the fraud and conspiracy trial of larouche, six aides and five of his political groups
the defense, which claims the criminal charges emerged from a white house-directed plot to ruin larouche, won a delay in the trial as a result of the document and a previously disclosed memo indicating two key players in the iran-contra scandal discussed collecting evidence against larouche
a federal judge ordered the prosecutor to search government files for any additional evidence that should be surrendered to defense lawyers
in a separate decision, a federal appeals court ruled wednesday that nbc must surrender to a judge outtakes from a 100-minute interview with a former larouche consultant who said an aide to the political extremist discussed a plot to assassinate henry kissinger. the network broadcast a one-minute excerpt of the interview in april 1986
the decision wednesday by the 1st u.s. circuit court of appeals upheld a lower court order that videotape of the entire interview must be surrendered for possible use at the conspiracy and fraud trial
the court also upheld a contempt citation against the network
nbc had contended that surrendering portions of the interview that were not broadcast violated its first amendment right against judicial intrusion into news gathering and editorial decisions
however, u.s. district judge robert e. keeton ruled that the rights of the defendants to have access to the 100-minute interview with forrest lee fick outweighed those of the network
the prosecutor, assistant u.s. attorney john markham, has at times ridiculed defense claims that larouche was a target of infiltration by the fbi and the cia, which is prohibited by law from spying domestically. the defense claims marine lt. col. oliver north, the former national security council aide fired for his role in the iran-contra affair, directed the infiltration because larouche refused to support the nicaraguan rebels
defense attorneys are seeking dismissal of charges on the ground that prosecutors deliberately withheld evidence that the defense later learned of through freedom of information act requests
the fbi document declassified wednesday refers to gary howard and ron tucker, founders of a private, now-defunct dallas company, peregrine international associates
peregrine reportedly was involved in an aborted attempt to sell arms to iranians who planned to assassinate their nation's leader, ayatollah ruhollah khomeini, and helped train contra forces and elite military units in el salvador, honduras and peru
the document also refers to retired sgt. maj. fred lewis, who defense lawyers in the larouche case say also worked for peregrine
when asked about their possible ties to larouche, they (howard, tucker and lewis) claimed they had previously been requested by the fbi and cia to penetrate the larouche organization,'' said the document
lewis, a former member of the army's elite special operations delta force, was said by the fbi document to be an employee of rhyolite management systems of dallas. rhyolite is the name of a spy satellite, the government acknowledged several years ago
a memo to north from retired air force maj. gen. richard secord, one of north's main operatives in the private network to aid the contras, said ``our man here claims lewis has collected information against larouche.''
the defense lawyers said they have been informed by the government that the ``our man'' reference is to oliver revell, an fbi assistant director involved in counterintelligence
fbi spokesman ray mcelhaney said the agency would not comment on the memo during the trial
this was an activity that was headed up by oliver north and mr. secord in a political attempt to stop the larouche people,'' defense attorney michael reilly said wednesday
tucker, a former texas department of public safety narcotics agent, and howard, a former border patrol agent, claim in a lawsuit filed last summer against the customs service that they have been government informants since 1979. tucker and howard are seeking $1.4 million for their expenses in a sting operation that led to the arrest of a man allegedly buying arms for iran
they say the government backed off the case because it would have revealed the reagan administration's arms shipments to iran and the diversion of profits to the contras
the fbi document also said that during interviews with fbi agents in san antonio and el paso, tucker and howard said they had approached family and friends of soviet dissidents andrei sakharov and his wife, yelena bonner, and told the family they could free the couple from the soviet union for $2 million
solidarity leader lech walesa today accused the polish government of violating union rights for denying him a passport to attend an international labor meeting in australia
the leader of the outlawed federation of labor unions said the government had so far ignored his request to attend the meeting march 14-18, according to solidarity spokesman janusz onyszkiewicz. walesa said he was convinced his request was being denied, given recent political statements by the government
government spokesman jerzy urban said two weeks ago that solidarity shouldn't be allowed to send delegations abroad because it has been outlawed
walesa, who won the nobel peace prize in 1983, had asked to go to the meeting of the international confederation of free trade unions in melbourne with three aides
