charles' wife, princess diana, and her pregnant sister-in-law, the duchess of york, who are with him at the swiss ski resort of klosters were in a chalet and were safe, the palace spokesman said
japan's unadjusted trade surplus fell in february from a year ago, the finance ministry reported today
the ministry said foreign sales exceeded foreign purchases by $5.24 billion last month, compared with a surplus of $7.13 billion in february 1987
the february surplus was up $3.08 billion from january, but the ministry said trade usually dwindles in january because of the long new year holiday
imports shot up 48 percent from a year ago to a record $14.96 billion in february, while exports rose 17.2 percent to $20.2 billion. the previous high for imports was $14.76 billion in december 1987
japan's surplus in trade with the united states fell to $3.40 billion from $3.97 billion in february 1987. exports rose 9.7 percent to $6.81 billion dollars, while u.s. imports soared by 51.9 percent to a record $3.41 billion
u.s. aircraft purchases accounted for a large portion in the imports, totaling $477.86 million, up 194.2 percent from a year earlier
the previous monthly high for u.s. imports was $3.12 billion set in june 1986
scientists reported encouraging results today in the first human tests of an experimental vaccine that fights a malaria-causing parasite at the stage when it infects red blood cells
studies in young men found that the experimental inoculation delayed or suppressed the development of the disease, colombian scientists reported in today's issue of the british journal nature
last year, other scientists reported partial success for a malaria vaccine that attacks the parasite at an earlier stage, when it is injected by mosquito bites
while malaria is not a major disease in the united states, it strikes an estimated 300 million people each year worldwide
the colombian scientists said their human work followed experimental success in monkeys that were injected with the malaria parasite, called plasmodium falciparum
they experimented in humans with two proteins to spur the immune system to raise defenses against the parasite in its blood-cell stage. nine volunteers were injected two or three times with one or the other, while four more were given no inoculation
the volunteers were also injected with red blood cells infected with the malaria parasite
three of the five volunteers who got one protein had mild infections, but with a steady decrease in parasite counts and total recovery by three weeks. another showed no protection, and the fifth left the study early
two of the four volunteers vaccinated with the other protein showed partial control of the infection for about two weeks, but then the infection progressed and they were cured with drugs. the other two who got that protein showed no protection. that austrians approved anschluss in vote. pick up 8th graf pvs: `austria's nazi...'</note>
president kurt waldheim, commemorating austria's annexation by germany 50 years ago, today apologized for the crimes committed by austrian nazis but ignored his own controversial wartime past
we must not forget that many of the worst nazi hangmen were austrians,'' waldheim said in a televised speech. ``there were austrians who were victims and others who were perpetrators
obviously, there is no collective guilt'' for the war crimes committed by austrians, the president declared. ``nevertheless, as head of state of the republic of austria, i wish to apologize for nazi crimes committed by austrians.''
it was the first time that waldheim has used such language in public to acknowledge austria's share in world war ii and the holocaust
waldheim did not acknowledge until two years ago that he served in world war ii in a german army unit implicated in wartime atrocities, and he has resisted pressure to resign since it became known
in his speech, the president insisted that ``as a state, austria was hitler's first victim. that is indisputable.''
austria was wiped off the map when nazi troops invaded on march 11, 1938. adolf hitler then returned in triumph to austria, his native land, cheered by hundreds of thousands of countrymen
in april 1938, the nazis said 99 percent of austrians approved the anschluss in a nationwide vote. more than half a million austrians joined the nazi party, and many of the brutal guards in the concentration camps were austrians
austria's nazi past _ largely suppressed here over the past four decades _ has dogged this neutral country since the disclosure in march 1986 of waldheim's wartime service
vienna's socialist mayor, helmut zilk, opening an exhibition looking back at the nazi era in austria, sharply criticized the government for reneging on a promise to help fund the display
zilk charged the coalition government of socialists and conservatives had behaved ``like a dog that shakes off fleas'' by shrugging off the exhibit
he speculated aid was withheld because the conservatives objected to descriptions of the prewar rightist regime called ``austrofascism'' by liberals and socialists
in his speech, waldheim left unmentioned his wartime years in yugoslavia and greece and the furor triggered last month by a historians' report questioning waldheim's integrity during the war
the report did not furnish evidence to clearly back allegations waldheim participated in war crimes, but it said he was ``in close proximity'' to war crimes and did nothing to prevent them
public pressure after the report's release forced waldheim to drop plans to speak at a solemn remembrance of the nazi annexation on friday
waldheim recalled the anschluss, as the nazi annexation of austria is known, as an event that ``triggered an avalanche of suffering.''
it was an avalanche of suffering that buried those who thought differently and, in a terrible racial mania, buried our jewish fellow citizens,'' waldheim declared. ``millions of jewish people were annihilated in the concentration camps
nothing can explain or excuse those crimes,'' said the president. ``i bow in deep respect to those victims who must always serve as a reminder and a duty'' for austria
the controversy over waldheim has divided austria and tarnished the country's image. the u.s. justice department last year barred waldheim from the country as an undesirable alien
waldheim asked foreign critics ``to see austria not only in the light of the horrors of the past but in the light of standing the test'' of the present
turning to his domestic critics, waldheim said, ``i ask you to refrain from blanket charges and from unqualified accusations'' and instead to see austria as a country looking into the future ``open to the world, ready to assist and self-assured.''
he appealed to austrians to ``wrestle with the shadows of the past'' and, repeating earlier statements, called for ``reconciliation.''
waldheim also outlined what he called a program of discussion with politicians of all parties to reform public life and do away with a wave of corruption and other scandals that have hit headlines in recent months
the moral standards of all who work in public life should improve, he said. ^eds: subs 2nd graf with 2 grafs to add year of trial, other background. inserts 1 graf after 6th graf pvs, ``his faith ...,' with defense lawyers not reachable for comment.</head>
the massachusetts supreme court today upheld the convictions of four men found guilty in the 1983 gang rape of a woman on a barroom pool table
in a pair of unanimous rulings, the state's highest court rejected defense arguments about the fairness of the lengthy 1984 trial in bristol superior court that attracted national attention
the case, which originally involved six young men of portuguese descent, drew angry protests by women's groups in support of the victim and brought agony to the portuguese-american community in the fishing city of new bedford, 60 miles south of boston
in ruling against the defendants, the court upheld the punishments handed out to daniel silvia, who was sentenced to nine to 12 years in the state prison at walpole; joseph vieira, who drew six to eight years; and john cordeiro and victor raposo, who were sentenced to nine to 12 years each. two other defendants were acquitted
defense attorneys raised a series of arguments attacking the handling of the trial by judge william g. young, but the high court rejected each one, saying young did not abuse his discretion
bristol county district attorney ronald pina said through a spokeswoman that he was ``very pleased'' with today's rulings
his faith in the judicial system has been substantiated, in spite of all the public turmoil in this case. he's pleased that the community can finally put this issue behind them,'' said spokeswoman charlotte enoksen
none of the four defense attorneys involved in the case were in their offices this morning
the justices noted that the jury could have found credible evidence that on the evening of march 6, 1983, the victim was attacked at big dan's tavern in new bedford and was forced to have sex as she was held down on the pool table
on appeal, vieira and silvia raised several arguments. they claimed that the prosecutor failed to make a timely disclosure of certain evidence that might have helped the defense, depriving them of constitutional rights to due process
they also argued that the bristol county district attorney suppressed until after trial a witness's recorded account of the victim's condition and statements shortly after the rape
and they argued that young prejudiced their ability to present a defense based on the theory that the victim consented to the sexual encounter. on that claim, vieira and silvia complained about the exclusion of an allegedly false prior complaint of rape by the woman, and other evidence
each claim was rejected by the unanimous supreme court
in their separate appeal, cordeiro and raposo argued that young's order prohibiting coverage of the victim on camera at the televised trial was an abuse that prejudiced their right to a fair trial
they also claimed that young erred in refusing to instruct the jury on the defense of consent to rape. in addition, raposo raised claims about young's decisions on trying the defendants together and on allowing evidence of a prior conviction
again, the high court dismissed each claim. unable to do business, bishops appealing to military to allow civilian rule, new quotes. no pickup.</note>
most banks said today they didn't have the cash to open despite a government go-ahead to resume limited transactions. roman catholic bishops urged the military to bow to civilian rule
the national banking association, representing 97 of the approximately 120 banks doing business in panama, said its members ``are not in condition to renew services'' and will remain ``closed temporarily.''
according to the statement, banks reiterated to their depositors ``the security of the funds entrusted to them and their inalterable decision to find the conditions that might permit the most prompt return to normality of the banking system.''
it was the eighth straight day of a nationwide bank closure, which came a few days after the ouster of president eric arturo delvalle by supporters of military strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
on wednesday, the nation's roman catholic bishops appealed to the military to subordinate itself to civilian rule
in a statement distributed by archbishop marcos mcgrath, the religious leaders also urged fellow panamanians to put personal and party interests aside in finding a solution to the crisis
it said the bishops believe necessary ``the strict observance of constitutional standards, the full and effective subordination of military forces to civilian authority, the search for conditions and structure that make possible national elections that deserve the credibility of all the voters, the restoration of the exercise of all human and civil rights and ... the reopening of the communications media.''
also wednesday, the nephew of the late omar torrijos, panama's previous strongman, disclosed that he had broken with the noriega government. santiago torrijos said he left his post as chief of panama's consulate in los angeles and was joining forces loyal to delvalle
diplomatic sources in washington, speaking on condition of anonymity, said torrijos' defection was significant because of the close identification of his relatives with the defense forces
the government's national banking commission told local and international financial institutions late wednesday they could reopen but only to accept deposits and transfer funds among themselves and other banks around the world
none did
the cash shortage was caused by the freezing of millions of dollars in panamanian funds in u.s. banks. the united states continues to recognize delvalle as the leader of panama and has called for the resignation of noriega, under indictment in florida on drug trafficking charges
rufina escobar, a 55-year-old schoolteacher, said she had enough food on hand at home to make it through the week. ``but if the banks don't open next week, i'll have to ask friends for a few dollars just to eat.''
arial simons, 17, complained that his mother had cut off his weekly $10 allowance
i guess i won't be going to the movies or any parties this weekend,'' he said. ``i don't even have the money to buy a beer.''
clerks at sarah's, one of panama city's most fashionable department stores, spent their time dusting shelves, chatting among themselves and waiting on an occasional customer
people aren't buying anything unessential,'' said one young clerk, whose name tag identified him as esteban. ``they're being very cautious with their money. business is way, way down.''
the young man declined to give his last name ``because i don't want any trouble.''
people everywhere were hoarding their cash, which was the only thing most businesses were accepting because they couldn't process checks or credit card transactions
a lone customer at sarah's cosmetics department was buying lipstick, occupying the attention of only one of five bored saleswomen. the customer explained her purchase almost defensively as she left the store
i work in an office and i have to look nice,'' she said. then she dug into her purse, pulled out an empty tube of lipstick and declared: ``look, this was all i had left. i just had to buy more. but something like new shoes, that's out.''
the woman, whose husband admonished her with a wagging finger not to give her name, said she hadn't bought anything else except household essentials since the banks closed last week
i bought large bags of beans and rice, a lot of milk for the kids and things like that,'' she said. ``but we're being careful, too, because we don't know how long this thing will last.'' four grafs, picking up in 5th graf pvs, kemp departed</note>
rep. jack kemp quit the race for the republican presidential nomination today after a string of poor performances in the early primaries and caucuses, but vowed to ``carry the flag high'' for his conservative causes
we have not failed because our ideas are winning,'' the new york congressman said at a capitol hill news conference where he clearly signaled his interest in the 1988 vice presidential nomination
flanked by members of his family and house members who supported his white house bid, kemp said he would not seek re-election to a 10th term in the house from his district in upstate new york, and had no plans to run for the senate
asked about the no. 2 spot on this year's ticket, he said, ``obviously you don't make plans to run for vice president.'' asked again, he called the idea ``a very flattering and awesome thought. ... would i think about it, the answer is yes.''
kemp departed the race with a pledge to campaign for the republican nominee _ and a blast at the democrats
we must never compromise with the liberal democratic congress,'' he said to applause. ``we must replace the liberal democratic congress.''
kemp made his exit after failing in his bid to emerge as the true heir to the reagan revolution and the conservative alternative to gop front-runner george bush and sen. bob dole of kansas
his efforts were thrwarted by former television evangelist pat robertson, whose surprise second-place finish in the lead-off iowa caucuses was a blow from which the congressman never recovered
even so, he claimed success for his efforts, noting bush's statement that he opposes tax increases to cut the deficit and dole's support for the nicaraguan contra rebels and the star wars initiative pushed by president reagan
kemp bowed out two days after winning just four delegates from 712 at stake in 17 super tuesday contests. his best finish in the 17 gop contests was a dismal 7 percent showing in the massachusetts primary
kemp had 35 committed delegates _ but most of those were handed to him by bush in a michigan compromise designed to prevent robertson from claiming a victory
campaign spokesman john buckley said kemp spent $15 million on his effort, and departs with debts of less than $100,000
some aides to kemp had urged him to get out even before the super tuesday voting across the south and elsewhere, following his fourth-place finish in south carolina's primary
as recently as monday kemp insisted he would press on, but he acknowledged he had to reassess his candidacy after the tuesday voting
there were rumors we would withdraw after iowa,'' he said. ``but i'm not a quitter. i'm an ex-quarterback, and i don't enter a contest lightly.''
kemp, a former professional football player, campaigned as a candidate of ideas and claimed to be heir to president reagan's conservative legacy
but his emphasis on economic opportunity and talk of returning to something like a gold standard didn't excite many conservatives who were concerned about more emotional issues. despite years of work for his white house aspirations, kemp was never able to light a spark outside his small group of loyalists
his problem was summed up last year by angela jackson, who tried to persuade her brother, conservative commentator patrick j. buchanan, to enter the presidential race
jack kemp's been out there for two years,'' she said. ``he's gone from 7 percent to 7 percent.''
kemp, 51, formally entered the gop race on april 6, 1987
he was a strong proponent of deploying the strategic defense initiative, reagan's space-based missile defense system, and a tough opponent of any tax increase
he blasted both bush and dole in a debate in dallas in february, saying they were identical tax raisers whose election would signal the end of the ``reagan revolution.'' his rivals countered that in his zeal, kemp was ignoring the danger of huge budget deficits
larry rosenthal, a newsman in the baltimore bureau of the associated press since 1981, has been named correspondent in new haven
hartford chief of bureau mary anne rhyne announced the appointment wednesday
rosenthal, 33, was a reporter for the central maine morning sentinel in his hometown of waterville, maine, before joining the ap. he is a graduate of hobart college
