republican presidential hopeful jack kemp quit the race today, saying ``we may have suffered a political defeat but our principles have not been defeated.'' democrat gary hart was ready to drop out a second time as the shrinking field converged on illinois for the next big campaign test
kemp was crushed in the super tuesday landslide of vice president george bush, who rejoined the campaign trail today after taking a day off to rest and celebrate
the new york congressman congratulated bush and said he would ``be proud to campaign'' for whoever wins the nomination, but he endorsed none of the three remaining gop contenders
i am folding up my tent, but i plan to continue to carry the flag high,'' said kemp, the former pro football quarterback who portrayed himself as the natural conservative heir to president reagan, whose economic programs have included many of kemp's ideas
he said both bush and sen. bob dole have embraced conservative positions, partly because of his presence in the presidential campaign
kemp said he would not seek a new term in congress and was ``not making any plans'' to run for the senate or to pursue the vice presidency. however, he called the idea of the vice presidential nomination ``a very flattering and awesome thought. ... would i think about it, the answer is yes.''
dole, who also was all but buried in the bush victories on tuesday, campaigned in chicago today, trying to sow seeds of doubt about bush's chances in november if he should win the gop nomination
i would be a much stronger candidate,'' dole said
democratic sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee was also in chicago, and was making similar comments about his chief rival. ``for those who want another election blowout and see the democratic party losing 49 of 50 states, vote for mike dukakis,'' he said
on wednesday, bush suggested to dole, his closest competitor, that the race for the gop nomination was becoming just a bit beside the point. it might be time, he said, to turn the attention toward the general election in november
i believe it is now time to look ahead to the issues which distinguish us from the democrats,'' the vice president told dole in a telegram in which he rebuffed the kansas senator's request for a series of one-on-one debates
good luck,'' bush added
dole was having none of that, as he searched for a share of illinois' 82 gop delegates at stake in tuesday's primary
i've got to win in illinois,'' he said. later, he told law students: ``i feel like i've just taken the finals, and i didn't flunk but i didn't do too well either.''
and he taunted bush for refusing to agree to the no-moderator debates, saying: ``here's a chance, george, to finish me off right here in illinois.''
dole said wednesday that kemp telephoned him to tell him he would drop out on thursday and to say he would endorse none of his rivals
it looked like the end of the line for hart as well. the colorado senator refused to talk to reporters about the super tuesday results. but he scheduled a denver news conference friday morning, and sources said he was abandoning his bid
the super tuesday races left hart disqualified for further federal matching funds. he technically lost his eligibility last month, but could have restored it with a 10-percent draw in any of the day's primaries
hart had already dropped out of the democratic race once. in may, he quit amid reports of his relationship with a miami model, and he amazed political observers by declaring in december that he was back
let the people decide,'' he said. but the people accorded him few votes in any of the early contests
the rest of the democrats were gathering for a forum tonight sponsored by illinois democrats
two of the democrats _ sen. paul simon and jesse jackson _ were campaigning on home turf in illinois, with its prize of 173 democratic delegates. simon, who bypassed tuesday's contests and said he must do well in illinois to continue, wasn't planning to spend any money on television advertising
i offer illinois 30 years of service rather than a 30-second commercial,'' he said
jackson, for his part, made a triumphant homecoming to chicago on wednesday, still thrilled by his showing the day before. he placed first in the popular vote, splitting a big delegate haul with massachusetts gov. dukakis and gore
we get stronger every day,'' jackson told plant workers in suburban chicago
at a rally later, he promised to eschew attacks on the other democrats. ``i'm moving ahead,'' he said. ``i'm going to fight george bush. that's my opposition.''
gore, however, pronounced himself the democrat most likely to succeed in november
i'm not going to say that any of our candidates are unelectable,'' he said in an interview on cable news network. ``but i have the best chance.''
the theme of electability was also sounded by dukakis. ``i hope when the people of illinois cast their votes they'll do so for someone who can clearly win the presidency,'' he said
rep. richard gephardt, who carried only his home state of missouri in tuesday's contests, said he was still in the running
pat robertson, his gop campaign flagging, said wednesday he would take a day off before heading for illinois. ``it isn't over yet,'' he said
here is the text of new york rep. jack kemp's statement thursday on his withdrawal from the republican presidential race:
last april, when i was explaining to my family about our race for the presidency, we had a moment of family time. jeffrey was there at the time, as well as jimmy and judith and jennifer, and joanne of course. and i quoted the book of ecclesiastes. i'd like to share it with you today. it tells us that in everything there is a season and a time for every purpose under heaven. there's a time to fight, a time to do battle
well, ladies and gentlemen, we've fought the good fight. we've fought long and hard and well. i want to thank from the bottom of my heart my family, my colleagues and comrades-in-arms, the large family of kemp supporters across the country. i want to tell each and every one of you that you can hold your heads high. we've waged an honorable, spirited, a principled campaign on issues and ideas, and frankly, in many ways, that's the most important victory of all
but then there's a time to refrain, a time to not fight, a time to accept defeat in one battle, so we can move on to fight again. i want to salute my fellow candidates: george bush, bob dole, pat robertson, and pete du pont and alexander haig as well. and joanne and i particularly want to congratulate today george and barbara bush for their great victory across the south on super tuesday. today, i'm withdrawing from the race for president. i'm folding up my tent, but i want you to know i'm going to continue to carry the flag high now and in the future
far more important than personal success in an election is the cause in which we believe. i ran for the presidency to ensure that the torch that we lit in 1980 in detroit, michigan, when we nominated ronald reagan and revolutionized the republican party, would burn even brighter and help light the way into the 1990s
we may have suffered a political defeat, but our principles have not been defeated. we have not failed because our ideas are winning. we know our ideas are winning when george bush says we must not reduce the deficit by raising taxes, that we need to cut the capital gains tax, that we need to enact free enterprise zones to unleash the talent of the inner city and to create more jobs, and when he says that we need to strengthen free and open trade throughout the world
we know our ideas are winning when bob dole pledges to support the freedom fighters and deploy the strategic defense initiative. we know our ideas are winning when every single republican candidate says that he supports the inalienable right to life for the born and the unborn, and pledges to fight for a pro-family, and a drug-free future for america. i want you to know, i'll be proud to campaign for any republican nominee who carries that banner, and i will fight at his side as long and as far as he carries that banner on the field of friendly strife
to my fellow republicans, i would say that in politics as in the marketplace, winning means staying ahead of your competitors. it means not only having better ideas, but carrying them through to completion. our party must never drift back to mindless austerity. we must never close our eyes to economic and moral challege. we must never break faith with the family or with senior citizens, or ignore the threat from a dangerous enemy that remains at war with freedom and democracy throughout the world
let the liberal democrats try to raise the burden of taxes on the workers and the families of america. let liberal democrats turn their backs on the freedom fighters around the globe. let liberal democrats raise tariffs on our allies and friends while they shirk the responsibility to preserve peace through strength. the american people will reject such a party, just as roundly and overwhelmingly in 1988 as they did in 1980 and 1984
ladies and gentlemen, we must not compromise with the liberal democratic congress. we must replace the liberal democratic congress with a free-enterprise congress. ours is a greater cause. our ideas can move america and the whole world forward, but like the good shepherd, we can't leave anyone behind
we can't rest until our economy is so strong that there's a job for every man and woman in america who wants to work, until our dollar once again is as good as gold and the budget is in balance. we can't rest until we've helped freedom fighters to victory and until we've researched, tested, developed, deployed, and built a strategic defense for the united states of america and our allies in europe and israel. we can't rest until all of us, black and white, christian and jew, rich or poor, are living in an america that is more prosperous but more tolerant, more decent and more generous, an america bound together as the founder of our party, abraham lincoln, envisioned the republican party _ as a people party, as a freedom party, as an emancipation party, to help make america one nation under god with liberty and justice and equality of opportunity for all
i want to close, if i can, my remarks by pulling from my pocket something i've carried around with me since super tuesday. joanne and i went to bed tuesday night and found a little note on our pillow from one of our children. it was from our daughter jennifer, and she told us that she loved us and that she was proud of us. and then, as a typical kemp child, she ended by quoting winston churchill. and it wasn't because they all went to winston churchill high school; it's because all the kemps love churchill, as freedom-loving men and women do throughout the world
jennifer ended her little letter by saying, ``finally, dad, as winston churchill said, `success is never final, failure is never fatal, it's courage that counts.' and you're the most courageous people i know.'' well, i want you all to know that no father, no candidate, no human being could ask for more than to have a courageous family, courageous comrades-in-arms, and courageous men and women around this country who believe in the ideas upon which america was built in the past, and upon which, alone, we can build a great victory for america and the world in the future
thank you, jennifer. thank you to my family. thank you to each and every one of you. and may god continue to bless america. thank you very, very, very much. hundreds arrested. pick up 3rd graf pvs: `she said...'</note>
thousands of police patrolled the tibetan capital of lhasa on foot and in trucks today on the anniversary of a bloody uprising. foreigners in lhasa said hundreds of people were arrested in the past six days
the anniversary of the outbreak of the 1959 tibetan uprising against chinese rule passed without major incident, said foreigners in lhasa contacted by telephone from the southwest china city of chengdu
but more than 100 trucks carrying armed police drove through the main streets of the city of 150,000 in a show of force and several dozen police with machine guns stood in front of the city's holiest buddhist temple, the jokhang, said benjamin watson of new york city, a tourist
watson, who speaks tibetan, said tibetans estimated at least 300 people had been arrested since a clash saturday between police and tibetans demanding independence. up to eight people were reported killed in the clashes
the official news agency xinhua also said the situation in lhasa today was normal. it said 100 top tibetans gathered in lhasa to denounce the riots and ``those who conduct evil doings under the guise of lama (monks).''
another foreign traveler in lhasa, who said she spoke some tibetan, said tibetans had told her of a police sweep today on the jokhang temple in which monks were arrested. she spoke on condition of anonymity
she said armed police were stationed at every corner of the barkhor market square around the jokhang, and there was no recurrence of saturday's daylong battle between police and monk-led tibetans
march 10 is the 29th anniversary of a tibetan revolt against chinese rule that resulted in the flight of the dalai lama, spiritual leader of the tibetans, and 100,000 followers, and a bloody crackdown by the chinese army
a nepalese-tibetan interviewed today in the southwestern china city of chengdu, air gateway to lhasa, said he had seen signs in lhasa written in tibetan and posted before saturday's disturbance calling for people to rise up on march 10
on that day in 1959, thousands of tibetans surrounded the norbulinka, the dalai lama's summer palace in lhasa, after hearing rumors that their god-king would be kidnapped by the chinese army
on march 17 the dalai lama fled from the palace and led his followers to exile in india. on march 20 the army attacked the palace, and quashed the rebellion after three days of bloody fighting
in new delhi today, about 200 tibetan refugees clashed with police during a rally marking the anniversary of the abortive uprising. seven tibetans and nine policemen were injured
in a statement issued from his home in exile in dharamsala, northern india, the dalai lama called on tibetans to ``honor the courage of our brethren in tibet who have taken to the streets to draw attention to their suffering under chinese colonial rule.''
china, which took control of tibet in 1950, claims the mountain region has been part of chinese territory for seven centuries. many tibetans disagree, and hold deep antagonisms toward the chinese because of the communist government's past suppression of tibetan language, customs and religion
tibetans, led by monks from lhasa's main monasteries, staged three pro-independence demonstrations last september and october, including a violent clash on oct. 1 in which at least 14 died
after those disturbances, chinese authorities closed off some monasteries and subjected monks to re-education campaigns
there were no other major shows of resistance and authorities decided to go ahead with the annual 10-day ``moinlam qenmo'' prayer festival, one of tibetan buddhism's most important events
the disturbances saturday began on the final day of the festival, when monks stood up at the jokhang temple, began shouting pro-independence and pro-dalai lama slogans and throwing rocks at police
except for sporadic rock-throwing incidents on sunday, lhasa has reportedly been calm since saturday
texas fired a new salvo in its war against florida citrus by suing u.s. agriculture secretary richard e. lyng
the suit, filed wednesday in federal court in brownsville, accuses lyng of violating federal law when the u.s. department of agriculture ended a 3{-year quarantine on shipments of fresh florida citrus to texas and other citrus-producing areas
texas wants to keep the florida fruit out because of a fear of bacterial citrus canker, officials said. canker prompted the ban on florida citrus after an outbreak of the disease in some areas there in august 1984
u.s. district judge filemon vela denied texas' request for an emergency stay of a usda rule that on feb. 11 ended the florida citrus ban
vela scheduled a hearing for monday morning when federal attorneys will have an opportunity to comment on the action brought wednesday by officials of the texas attorney general's office and state agriculture department
usda officials in washington declined comment on the lawsuit this morning, said department spokeswoman tammy bragg
the suit accuses lyng of violating the federal administrative procedure act by lifting the quarantine without publishing notice and providing a chance for a public hearing
the bacterial canker disease can cause defoliation of citrus trees, lesions that render the fruit unmarketable, and premature dropping of the fruit from the tree. the disease exists in several forms, with some considered less dangerous than others
a gulf coast area of florida where the aggressive asiatic strain of canker was discovered remains under quarantine
last september, the usda published a proposal to lift the quarantine against florida fruit, but on jan. 5 withdrew the proposal after new canker outbreaks were discovered in florida
on feb. 15, four days after lyng lifted the ban, texas imposed an emergency 30-day quarantine on fresh florida citrus
florida producers maintain that canker presents a minimal threat to the texas citrus industry, and some florida growers filed suit last month to stop the texas quarantine. the quarantine would have expired next saturday
a federal court in austin on march 1 overturned the texas quarantine, and ruled that the federal rule took precedence over the state's action
the suit filed on wednesday accuses lyng of violating federal law by not giving the public or the state opportunity to comment
the texas suit seeks reinstatement of the quarantine and a formal hearing process if usda makes a new proposal to end the quarantine on florida citrus
the lawsuit says texas at least would like to keep florida fruit out of the lower rio grande valley, where the state's $65 million citrus industry is concentrated on about 30,000 acres in hidalgo, cameron and willacy counties
here are the latest statistics on acquired immune deficiency syndrome in the united states, as reported this week by the national centers for disease control:
total cases reported since june 1981: 55,167
cases, year to date: 4,826
total deaths: 30,932, or 56 percent of all cases
homosexual or bisexual males: 34,925, or 63 percent
intravenous drug abusers: 9,564, or 17 percent
homosexual male and drug abusers: 4,045, or 7 percent
heterosexual cases: 2,189, or 4 percent
transfusion or blood cases: 1,433, or 3 percent
hemophilia patients: 559, or 1 percent
undetermined transmission cause: 1,685, or 3 percent
childhood cases (under age 13): 886, or 2 percent
cases among whites: 32,999, or 60 percent
cases among blacks: 14,089, or 26 percent
cases among hispanics: 7,575, or 14 percent
cases among other: 504, or 1 percent
(note: these statistics are through march 7 and have been rounded by the cdc to the nearest whole percent. cumulative totals are for aids cases reported since june 1981, and include 75 cases subsequently found to have occurred prior to that date. the ``other'' classsification under age and race includes asians, american indians and native alaskans.) withdraw troops doesn't mean end to afghan aid. no pickup.</note>
the soviet union said today that an agreement on the withdrawal of its troops from afghanistan is not a commitment to end military aid to the kabul government
soviet ambassador nikolay kozyrev said the question of a halt to soviet assistance has ``not arisen'' in the almost 6-year-old u.n.-sponsored afghanistan peace talks
he said the draft agreement would not bar any kind of soviet aid, except the sending of new troops into afghanistan, where the soviets intervened in 1979. an estimated 115,000 soviet troops are helping the marxist government fight u.s.-backed moslem insurgents
kozyrev rejected the u.s. demand for a ``symmetrical cessation'' of military aid to both sides in the war. kozyrev said it was an attempt to interfere in the internal affairs of afghanistan and in the bilateral relationship between kabul and moscow
he said the demand would be tantamount to moscow calling for an end to u.s. military aid for pakistan
kozyrev also warned that if a geneva settlement were not signed, a ``new flare-up of bloodshed and fratricidal war cannot be excluded.''
kozyrev, a specialist on asian affairs, came to geneva as head of a soviet team of experts to follow the peace talks. his remarks followed a statement by afghan foreign minister abdul wakil, who said wednesday that moscow had helped afghanistan for years and would continue to do so after the troop withdrawal
wakil has said earlier that the draft agreements provided only for a halt to arms shipments to the guerrillas fighting the kabul government. the united states is considered the insurgents' main supplier, with deliveries totaling a reported $700 million last year
kozyrev said the peace talks have ``bogged down'' because of pakistan's insistence on having a settlement linked to the formation of a transitional government in kabul to oversee the withdrawal of the red army troops
pakistan, which represents afghan rebels in the peace talks, says that a government to replace the present soviet-backed one would ensure stability and the safe return of more than 5 million afghan refugees
kozyrev sidestepped a question on whether negotiations could continue after next tuesday, a target date set by moscow. soviet leader mikhail gorbachev said last month that the troops would leave afghanistan starting may 15 if an agreement were reached march 15
i can only hope that the other side (pakistan) will show enough common sense and responsibility,'' he said, adding later, ``it is too early to say what will happen after that date.''
wakil and the pakistani delegations have both made plain that they do not consider march 15 a deadline and that a settlement at a later date would just put off the start of the withdrawal. in 2nd graf pvs, ``well we</note>
republican presidential candidate bob dole sought today to sow doubts about the party's front-runner, saying vice president george bush will face a ``tough, tough race'' in november if he is the gop nominee
i would be a much stronger candidate,'' dole said as he campaigned in the chicago area. ``that's the message we're going to try to make in the next couple of days.''
dole planned to concentrate today on suburban chicago before heading downstate for a swing friday through farm country where the kansas senator considers his support the strongest
he started the day with a tour of the rehabilitation hospital of chicago, which is near another hospital where dole underwent surgery 40 years ago for injuries he received in world war ii
this is going to be the political recovery state just as it was the personal recovery state 40 years ago,'' dole said on wednesday. ``that may be more symbolism than anything, but to me it is an indication that it can be done.''
on wednesday, one day after dole's super tuesday drubbing, a senior campaign adviser was quizzed whether the results had triggered a ``meltdown'' in the kansas republican's presidential candidacy
well, we might have started evacuating around the reactor,'' quipped the aide, thomas rath
his reply reflected the perilous situation as dole's campaign works toward the march 15 illinois primary, which even the candidate openly acknowledges is a do-or-die contest if he is to have any chance of beating vice president george bush for the gop presidential nomination
dole, campaigning in the chicago area on wednesday, said he must win at least 65 percent of all remaining delegates nationwide as well as those who are uncommitted if he is to emerge victorious. his first objective is illinois, a state where bush has the backing of gov. james thompson and 93 of the state's 102 gop county chairmen
i've got to win illinois,'' dole said bluntly at one campaign stop. later, speaking to northwestern university law school students, dole made it even more clear that his political survival was at stake. he renewed a challenge to bush to participate in a series of freewheeling one-one-one debates
i just appeal to george bush. here's a chance, george, to finish me off right here in illinois,'' dole said. the debate challenge is mentioned at every campaign stop and is a key part of dole's strategy to try to draw bush into a discussion of issues and break his link to president reagan. dole attributes bush's sweep of the 17 super tuesday primaries and caucuses to reagan's popularity
george bush is running like ronald reagan,'' said dole. ``it's tough to beat ronald reagan. i can't beat him. i can beat bush, but beating ronald reagan is impossible. bush has wrapped himself around reagan and it's been very effective.''
dole never misses an opportunity to chip away at bush's record and to raise questions about the vice president's ability to defeat a democrat in the november general election
i don't have any real quarrel with george bush except i think i'm a stronger person. i think i know more about the issues. i think i'm a better leader,'' bush told a group of lawyers at a downtown chicago reception
already, the dole campaign is airing television advertising in illinois that touts dole's leadership in the senate and focuses on what the kansan says are nine different answers by bush to his role in the iran-contra arms-for-hostages affair. similar ads were used to no avail against bush in the south
but increasingly, dole is highlighting the ``electability'' question in his attempts to revive his campaign _ even though he concedes ``it's hard to make that an issue.''
i think there is one person between me and the white house and that is george bush,'' dole quipped at the lawyers' reception. ``i think there are a couple of people between him and the white house.''
dole told supporters ``if i can turn it around in illinois ... then the momentum changes.''
the republicans, i think, will take a deep breath and reconsider the choice before them,'' he said. ``and that's why i take heart that i'm sort of back in the heartland.''
here are excerpts of a televised speech thursday by president kurt waldheim as austria remembers the nazi annexation of march 1938. the text was translated from german by the associated press

in these days, we are remembering the events which 50 years ago led us into the darkest epoch of our recent history
... there were also hundreds of thousands of austrians, who welcomed the anschluss, who feted hitler and the invasion and pinned many false hopes on it
it was a mass psychosis of a kind that only totalitarian regimes can create. today we know that one should resist the very beginnings of intolerance and instigation. today we know where the fanning of fanaticism, hate and violence lead
today we know that, with march 11, 1938, an avalanche of suffering was triggered
it was an avalanche of suffering that buried those who thought differently and, in a terrible racial mania, buried our jewish fellow citizens. the holocaust is one of the greatest tragedies of world history. millions of jewish people were annihilated in the concentration camps. nothing can explain or excuse those crimes. i bow in deep respect before these victims, who must always be a reminder and a duty for us
the avalanche of suffering also caught up countless men and women of the resistance, who had to give their life for the freedom of austria
we must not forget that many of the worst nazi hangmen were austrians. there were austrians who were victims and others who were perpetrators. let us not give rise to the impression that we had nothing to do with this. obviously there is no collective guilt. nevertheless, as head of state of the republic of austria, i wish to apologize for nazi crimes committed by austrians
but as a state, austria was hitler's first victim. that is indisputable. though it resisted hitler's political and economic pressure for years, it went under. the international community of states gave us no help against the aggression
our country is open to criticism. as the head of state of our republic, however, i would ask the critics to be fair and objective. i would ask them not only to see austria in the light of the horrors of the past, but in the light of how it has stood the test in the present
i ask you to refrain from blanket charges and from unqualified accusations and to look at austria as it stands in the late 1980s: secure and open to dialogue, open to the world, ready to assist, self-assured and pointed toward the future
but as your elected president, i also appeal to you, my dear countrywomen and countrymen, to wrestle with the shadows of the past. the meaning of these days lies in reflection, not in dispute. ... the meaning of these days can be only one thing: reconciliation
the ugly storm of scandals which has confronted us in the last years underlies the necessity of a basic reform of public life ... of an improvement of moral standards for all who have to act and work in the public interest. in the coming months, i will use the authority of this office to discuss the perspectives and contours of such a reform with representatives of all political institutions in austria
the moral renewal of our republic is an undertaking which can only have the desired success if it is supported and carried by all those responsible
let us assume resonsibility for our mistakes in a way that would encourage avoiding mistakes in the future. let us love our country without false shame and arrogant pride so that austria also finds a place in the hearts of youth:
_ as a country that has come to terms with itself,
_ as a country which has learned from history,
_ as a country that despite some mistakes deserves affection,
_ as our common ``much tested, much loved'' austria
a dermatologist removed a small patch of skin from nancy reagan's upper lip and tests show it to be non-cancerous, her spokeswoman said thursday
it was from too much sun,'' mrs. reagan's press secretary, elaine crispen, said
the first lady ``had a little scraping'' done to remove the skin patch and no stiches were required, mrs. crispen said. she was informed of the results of the tests on monday, the spokeswoman added
the procedure was performed at the white house over the weekend by adm. william narva, a u.s. naval dermatologist who is the attending physician to congress, the spokeswoman said
the first lady wore a small adhesive bandage for two days but is no longer wearing one, mrs. crispen said
the procedure marked the second time the first lady has had a growth removed from the area. in 1982, a growth was removed that was diagnosed as a basal cell carcinoma
last august, president reagan had a skin cancer identified as a basal cell epithelioma removed from the tip of his nose. it was his third procedure in three years dealing with skin cancer
in their younger days and as residents of california, reagan and his wife spent many hours in the sun. since their bouts with skin cancer, they have changed their habits, wearing sunblock and hats when they venture outdoors and advising others to do the same
fans of robin hood are up in arms and the city of nottingham has been accused of shooting itself in the wallet by putting out a tourism brochure debunking the legend of the medieval outlaw
the glossy color brochure takes a skeptical academic line on robin hood, his love affair with maid marian, the existence of his faithful lieutenant friar tuck and that he robbed the rich to give to the poor
we are not debunking anything. we are putting robin hood in historical context,'' insisted city council spokesman tim jones
the city fathers have done a disservice to their own city,'' countered malcolm barker of the robin hood society, who took up the cudgels on the outlaw's behalf
barker doesn't claim that the story, as handed down by hollywood, is true. he simply objects to tinkering with a beautiful legend that also is a major tourist attraction
if mickey mouse can bring a fortune into florida, why shouldn't robin hood bring a fortune in to the people of nottingham?'' he said in a british radio interview
the affair came to light thursday in london's daily telegraph in a report headlined ``robin hood is robbed of myth and romance.''
the brochure undermines many of the popular notions about robin hood and his band of merry men, not to mention his favorite woman
maid marian, it says, comes from a 13th century french poem, while chubby friar tuck is probably an amalgam of two characters from different parts of england
as for robin himself, the brochure notes that in the earliest tales, he was a highwayman who robbed travelers in neighboring yorkshire and was in business strictly for himself
graham black, curator of nottingham castle museum and a historian whose work contributed to the brochure, was quoted by the telegraph as saying: ``one of the problems about robin hood is that the legend is 700 years old, a story handed on by word of mouth, and it was 200 years before people became literate.''
his philanthropy was ``the fashionable academic interpretation of the 1950s,'' black said. ``but there is no evidence for this.''
jones said in an interview that the legend took its present form under the 19th century victorians
it remains a potent one. when raisa gorbachev, wife of the soviet leader, visited nottingham in 1984, city officials said she asked about robin hood, apparently regarding him as a socialist who believed in the redistribution of wealth
barker, the outlaw's defender, said: ``does it really matter? ... it's an adman's dream. we've got something here that is wonderful. visitors come from all over the world that know about robin hood and maid marian, and i think that the city fathers have done a disservice to their own city.''
nottingham, a city of 290,000 people in central england, can hardly be accused of neglecting the legend. its main beltway is called maid marian way, and two rival consortiums are planning robin hood exhibition centers for the city
hordes of tourists visit the sherwood forest center where they can see displays of medieval lifestyles and gaze at the oak tree where the merry men may or may not have relaxed after a hard day's archery
brian marshal, chairman of the city tourism council that produced the brochure, says the debate about maid marian is largely irrelevant. people are more interested in robin hood versus the sheriff of nottingham, he said, ``because it's always the good guy against the bad guy, isn't it.''
i think people will feel what they feel. if they want to believe in maid marian then they'll do that,'' he said
the pentagon doesn't know whether the sale of japanese machine milling equipment helped the soviet union build quieter submarines, according to a top defense department official
the soviet union was building quiet propellers for its subs three years before the toshiba equipment was exported between 1983 and 1985, said richard armitage, assistant secretary of defense for international security affairs
armitage's assessment was contained in a letter outlining the pentagon's opposition to congressional proposals which would limit or ban the sale of toshiba products in the united states
toshiba officials admitted last year that a subsidiary company had sold the soviet union machine tools for making quiet submarine propellers
navy officials have said in the past that soviet subs were noisier than their american counterparts, making it easier for the united states to keep track of the soviet subs. both sides are continually seeking to develop quieter submarines
armitage's views were outlined in a letter to rep. les aspin, d-wis., chairman of the house armed services committee. the letter was released thursday
the indignation felt in the united states is understandable,'' armitage said. he added that ``perhaps some americans don't fully realize that many japanese feel a similar indignation complemented by acute embarrassment.''
the actual damage done from the toshiba machinery diversions is difficult to assess,'' armitage said
despite allegations of tens of even $100 billion in damages, our navy cannot determine the direct costs of this diversion to u.s. national security because the soviets had quiet propellers three years before the first diversion and we had already planned programs to deal with this development,'' he said
a conference committee of 20 house members and seven senators is trying to work out house-senate differences on an omnibus trade bill, and one of the unresolved issues involves toshiba
the house bill contains no sanctions against the company, while the senate version would ban the sale of any toshiba products in the united states for two years to five years. toshiba has annual u.s. sales of $3 billion to $4 billion
actions by the u.s. government against toshiba would be interpreted in japan as motivated by trade imbalances, rather than by national security concerns,'' armitage said
he predicted that japanese efforts to protect sensitive technology ``will greatly improve as a result of what has happened, but only if we don't undercut the post-toshiba actions'' by the japanese government, which he described as ``unprecedented.''
the pentagon is considering whether to sell the japanese navy four aegis ship defense systems, costing $1 billion each. the system contains the navy's most sophisticated anti-aircraft electronic gear, and some critics in congress have questioned whether the aegis sale is a good idea in the wake of the toshiba case. is</note>
the house today overwhelmingly demanded the ouster of panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega and urged president reagan to impose strong sanctions to encourage restoration of civilian rule in panama
before the 367-2 roll call vote on an anti-noriega resolution, the panamanian military ruler was denounced during floor debate as ``a gunrunning thug'' and ``one of the most ruthless tyrants of our time.''
voting against the resolution were representatives george w. crockett jr., d-mich., and henry b. gonzalez, d-texas
now is the time for gen. noriega to step down and open the door for true democracy in panama,'' said rep. benjamin gilman, r-n.y
said rep. dan mica, d-fla.: ``noriega must leave, and he must leave quickly.''
the resolution, sponsored chiefly by mica, said the house ``is deeply concerned about the deterioration of united states-panamanian relations'' and calls on noriega to comply with president eric arturo delvalle's order dismissing him as commander of the panamanian defense forces
the resolution also ``calls on the president to consider seriously the range of additional economic and political sanctions available to the united states that could be used to encourage the re-establishment of civilian authority in panama.'''
the house action came as the reagan administration studied tough new sanctions against panama, and two prominent panamanian diplomats deserted the noriega government
santiago torrijos, nephew of former panamanian leader omar torrijos, abandoned his post as consul general in los angeles and flew to washington to join forces with allies of the ousted delvalle
torrijos' late uncle was widely esteemed in panama for negotiating with president carter for the treaty under which the panama canal will revert to panama by the year 2000. the former consul general accused the noriega regime of plunging panama into a political crisis
panamanian ambassador juan b. sosa, who supports delvalle, said wednesday that santiago torrijos' decision to break with noriega will have a major impact on panama because of the close identification of the torrijos family with panama's defense forces. torrijos is believed to be the first member of the torrijos family to break ranks with noriega
omar torrijos dominated panama's political life from 1968 until his death in a plane crash in 1981. in a typewritten statement made public wednesday night, his nephew said a ``political, financial, moral and social crisis'' exists in panama and must be resolved
he said that a ``small political-military circle'' has betrayed the pledge of omar torrijos to return panama to constitutional rule
meanwhile, the panamanian embassy made public a copy of a letter by panama's ambassador to mexico, emilia arosemena vallarino, in which she announced her resignation because she was ``in disagreement with political events'' in her country. she had served in mexico for 18 years and was dean of the diplomatic corps there
at issue are the circumstances under which panama's new government took power two weeks ago. delvalle attempted to fire noriega but was fired himself hours later
the reagan administration, along with a number of panamanian diplomats and consular officers, have refused to recognize the successor government, regarding delvalle as the constitutional authority. he has remained in hiding for almost two weeks
today, high-level meetings were scheduled at which administration officials were considering a series of economic sanctions against panama
u.s. officials, who asked not to be identified, said that it is almost certain that the united states will withhold a $6.5 million payment due to panama on march 15 for canal-related operations
also being considered are measures that would have the effect of making some panamanian products less competitive in u.s. markets. state department figures show that panama's u.s. exports totaled $342 million last year, but commerce department statistics list that category at $388 million
the officials said panama may lose its right to participate in the caribbean basin initiative, under which some products are allowed duty-free access to the united states
to be eligible to take part, nations of central america and the caribbean must cooperate in combatting drug smuggling to the united states
the reagan administration has concluded that panama has not been cooperating, and two federal grand juries have handed down indictments accusing noriega of being a key figure in an international drug trafficking operation
but white house chief of staff howard baker denied wednesday that the united states is planning an invasion of panama, saying american troops there are merely holding regularly scheduled training exercises
jorge abadia, panama's foreign minister, this week accused the united states of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by staging military exercises along the panama canal
gov. evan mecham's former chief of staff testified today at the governor's impeachment trial that he would not have directed the state's public safety director to stonewall an investigation, as the governor is accused of doing
mecham, who faces removal from office by the state senate, is accused of trying to thwart an investigation into an alleged death threat by then-state prison construction chief lee watkins against a former mecham aide, donna carlson. the threat allegedly was made as ms. carlson was about to appear before a grand jury investigating mecham's campaign finances. watkins has denied threatening ms. carlson
mecham also is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
richard burke, the governor's first defense witness, was cross-examined by prosecutor william french in his second day on the stand
he acknowledged that he would not have made the statements that mecham is accused of making nov. 15 to department of public safety director ralph milstead
french quoted from statements milstead has testified mecham made regarding plans for officer frank martinez and lt. beau johnson to give statements to the attorney general's office about the alleged threat
would you under any circumstances, mr. burke, tell mr. milstead `i don't want frank or beau giving any statements to the attorney general.' would you say that?'' french asked
no,'' burke replied
would you say this: `don't tell the attorney general anything,''' french said
no,'' burke answered
burke, a former law school dean and federal prosecutor who came out of retirement last november to serve as mecham's chief of staff, said he believed mecham understood that a serious threat may have been made against carlson, although burke was not certain whether it was specified that it was an alleged death threat
i think all of us assumed that it was a crime, or a potential crime, or it wouldn't have been reported to us,'' burke said
french asked whether it was milstead's job to report the alleged crime ``and the governor would not have the authority to stop it.''
my impression of law enforcement, certainly that would be true,'' burke said
burke said, however, that he agreed with mecham's contention in a television interview several days after he was told about the alleged threat that he knew little about it
during house impeachment hearings in january, mecham insisted that the report to the department of public safety violated an unwritten rule against disclosing things that happen in the governor's office
the prosecution rested its case wednesday on the death threat allegation, the first of the three major charges against mecham
no man is above the law,'' prosecutor paul eckstein said in his closing argument. ``the evidence that has been put before you cries out ... for a conviction.''
defense lawyer fred craft argued that prosecutors had not proven mecham tried to obstruct an investigation because ``nobody told the governor that there was indeed an attorney general's investigation that he could possibly obstruct.''
mecham, 63, who ran an auto dealership before he was elected governor in a three-way race, has contended he handled the matter properly by having watkins' boss, then-department of administration director max hawkins, investigate
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham and remove the first-term republican from office
the governor also faces an april 21 criminal trial on charges of hiding the $350,000 loan, and a may 17 recall election
maricopa county superior court judge michael ryan said wednesday he was ``reluctantly'' granting a prosecution motion to delay the criminal trial, which had been scheduled to start march 22. the judge said more time was needed to decide pretrial motions and gather a large pool of potential jurors
mecham, the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades, has not attended the impeachment trial, but senators wednesday were shown a nov. 16 tv interview in which he denied knowledge of the alleged death threat. problems</head> more names of victims; corrects that charles shirley from ill. sted ark.; corrects that dennis sabot of n.d. sted iowa.</note>
the probe of the collision of two army blackhawk helicopters that killed 17 soldiers has found no link to mechanical problems that have grounded the military's uh-60s in recent years, an investigator says
i would say now there is no indication of any mechanical factor'' in tuesday night's crash, said chief warrant officer joe s. adams, one of three investigators from the army safety center at fort rucker, ala
we are looking at human and environmental factors. the human factors might include some restriction of vision,'' he said wednesday
both pilots were using night-vision goggles, which amplify light from the stars and the moon, allowing pilots to fly undetected at night. officials said they were trying to determine whether the choppers were flying without lights
the crash was the worst army aviation disaster since 248 soldiers, also based at fort campbell, died in a chartered plane crash in canada while returning from a mideast peacekeeping mission in december 1985
the 17 died instantly in the collision, the worst ever at the fort in southwestern kentucky, but eight bodies remained buried under the wreckage for hours, spokesmen said
the army's fleet of 820 uh-60s was grounded twice last may, once for inspection and once because of a design flaw. the fleet also was grounded in april 1985 and march 1986 after fatal crashes. in 1985, the army identified a defect in the main rotor assembly and ordered it corrected
last summer, officials said about 40 people had been killed in crashes of the helicopter since 1978
the collision occurred when a copter on a night training mission struck a formation of three other blackhawks on a separate mission, adams said
the formation was flying east at about 250 feet above the ground when the lead blackhawk was hit broadside by the lone aircraft, which was traveling north, army spokesmen said
a flight data recorder, installed in 100 of the army's helicopters, was recovered from the northbound craft and will be checked for signs of mechanical failure in the copter, adams said. the other craft had no recorder
the manufacturer, sikorsky aircraft of stratford, conn., sent a safety expert to assist investigators. adams said a report was expected in two to three months
investigators hoped that air traffic control tapes would reveal whether the pilots knew their copters were converging
the helicopters are not equipped with radar and the pilots, wearing the night vision goggles, were operating under visual flight rules, with visibility of at least one mile and a ceiling of 500 feet, adams said
the accident occurred on the kentucky-tennessee state line 6 miles from the copters' airstrip, about 60 miles north of nashville
the army identified the dead as: staff sgt. charles l. shirley, 32, of madison, ill.; billie d. bolin, 29, of greensburg, ky.; james m. guill, 33, of georgetown, ky.; richard l. alter, 29, of williamsport, pa. and clifford w. bath iii, 19, of charleston, s.c
also, michael a. jankowski, 19, of sussex, wis.; james draper, jr., 20, of fruitland, n.m.; jeffrey l. rivas, 26, of santa barbara, calif.; andrew j. franklin iii, 20, of advance, ind. and michael daniel, 32, of delaware, ohio
also, brian j. leblanc, 21, of cold springs, minn.; sgt. dennis c. sabot, 30, of bismark, n.d.; gregory t. dean, 24, of liberty, ky.; spec. 4 samuel a. hintz, 24, of sherrodsville, ohio and timothy s. sayer, 20, of worthington, ohio
shirley, sabot and hintz were from the 2nd battalion, 502nd infantry. identifications of the other two victims were withheld pending notification of relatives
he believed he was doing what was right, doing it for his country,'' jerry shirley of clarksville, tenn., said of his brother, an 11-year army man. ``it's something he wanted to do. he was a career man. he started when he was 17 and had a break and went back in. we accepted the risk.''
lt. col. charles adams, the post chaplain, said 35 chaplains on post, social service agencies and a support group of military wives have offered help to survivors. a memorial service was scheduled for next wednesday
there's a tremendous amount of shock and grief (but) there has been no recrimination from any of the people we have talked to,'' said adams
thirteen of the dead, most of them infantrymen, were in the blackhawk that had been flying in formation. the other victims were crew members in the second copter
the blackhawk, one of the army's newer helicopters, normally is operated with a crew of three and can carry 11 combat-equipped soldiers
it is a utility and assault aircraft designed for air cavalry and medical evacuations, said maj. phil soucy, an army spokesman in washington, d.c
soucy said there had been no move by safety investigators to ground the blackhawk fleet as a result of the accident. ^eds: leads with 5 grafs to update standings, picking up 6th graf pvs, `several racers ....'</head>
a 70-year-old man known as the ``father of the iditarod' pocketed $2,500 in silver ingots today for being the first to reach the half-way point of the 1,100-mile iditarod trail sled dog race
joe redington of knik reached the cripple checkpoint at 5:40 a.m. his nearest competitor, herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref, checked into ophir, 55 miles behind redington, at 11:10 p.m. wednesday
redington, a founder of the mushing marathon from anchorage to nome, now heads for the sulatna crossing and then to ruby on the yukon river. he has raced in all but two of the 16 iditarods, finishing three times in fifth place
four-time champion rick swenson of two rivers was running third. he checked out of takotna at 8:37 p.m. wednesday. he was followed by joe garnie of teller, jan masek of anchorage and deedee jonrowe of bethel
defending champion susan butcher of manley was seventh
several racers said that despite redington's lead, nayokpuk is now the musher to beat because of his strong dog team
i think it's going to take us quite a while to gain that kind of time back, unless he runs into some kind of situation up ahead,'' swenson said
a blizzard pounding alaska's southwestern coast threatened to turn into complicate things on the iditarod trail for the racers. if the gale-driven snow reaches inland to the iditarod trail, the going could turn slow
at the back of the pack, 290 miles behind the leaders, the oldest iditarod musher announced that he was dropping out of the race. norman vaughan, 82, said three of his dogs were in heat and he had whiteout conditions ahead
another musher, ray dronenburg of trapper creek, also scratched wednesday, saying several of his dogs were weak with a virus. that leaves 50 mushers in the race, which started saturday
a $30,000 first prize awaits the winner, who is expected to reach nome sometime next week. the next 19 finishers will split the rest of the $150,000 purse. five grafs to correct koop quote and status of new york program and to update with carballo giving speech instead of mann. pick up 10th graf pvs: ``discussions focused...'' ^by robert glass</note>
u.s. surgeon general c. everett koop said today he supports trying out a needle-exchange program for drug addicts in the united states to slow the spread of aids
while stressing that he was not proposing such a plan but rather supporting others who call for it, koop said drug abuse was the likeliest way aids, or aquired immune deficiency syndrome, could spread through the heterosexual population
i think we should have a pilot program in the united states,'' he said in an interview during the first international conference on the global impact of aids. about 1,000 health specialists from 63 countries are attending the three-day meeting, which opened monday at london's barbican center
under needle-exchange programs in europe, drug addicts can turn in used needles for new ones, reducing the risk of contracting aids from contaminated drug equipment
koop acknowledged that many people object to such schemes as abetting illegal drug abuse. ``we have to decide whether or not the risk of aids from needle-sharing is great enough to satisfy that objection,'' he said
if needle exchange could contain the epidemic, nobody should be against it,'' koop said
he said pilot projects should be conducted in more than one city and mentioned as possibilities new york and los angeles. he said a nationwide program shouldn't be considered until results of pilot programs in the united states and other countries are studied
a pilot project is proposed for new york, but koop criticized it for using volunteer methadone users. methadone is a substitute used to wean addicts off heroin, and the volunteers, having made the commitment to quit drugs, should not be exposed again to using needles, he said
also wednesday, dr. manuel carballo, chief of social and behavioral researcher for the world health organization's global program on aids, outlined the organization's strategy for slowing the spread of the disease. dr. jonathan mann, director of the who program, was to have given the speech but was unable to attend the final day's session
discussion focused on how to reconcile control of the disease with individual freedom and on international and national policy on aids and its prevention
a 33-nation gallup international survey on attitudes toward aids presented to the conference wednesday said that 47 percent of respondents in the united states favor testing the entire population for aids
koop said he was ``totally opposed'' to mandatory screening, arguing that only a tiny fraction of the population behaved in a way that courted risk
apart from north america, some parts of south america and some asian countries, concern among individuals about contracting aids is relatively low, the survey found
as far as becoming an epidemic was concerned, throughout the world there was a clear realization that this was likely to occur in the case of homosexuals, hemophiliacs, intravenous drug users and promiscuous people,'' the survey says
in terms of the risk of catching the disease, most of the peoples of the world were aware of the clear situations in which it could be caught,'' it added
but the survey says substantial minorities in many parts of the world do not understand how the disease is transmitted and said they would refuse to work with a person carrying the aids virus
there is a fear that one can get aids by means which are not supported by scientific practice, for instance sharing a drinking glass or via insect bites. ... other perceived risks, such as ... coughs and sneezes, friendly kissing ... appear to be identified...''
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. it is spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug users, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
the soviet union is continuing to ship arms to nicaragua at a fast pace despite efforts by the u.s.-backed contra guerrillas and sandinista government to negotiate a peace accord, the pentagon said thursday
during the first two months of 1988, the nicaraguans received 3,100 metric tons _ or 3,400 regular tons _ of weaponry and war materiel worth an estimated $100 million, the pentagon said
the equipment was delivered in 10 arms shipments in january and february, the defense department said
if that pace is sustained, the nicaraguans will receive at least 18,600 metric tons of weaponry this calendar year, compared with an estimated 21,700 metric tons delivered in 1987
last year's arms deliveries to nicaragua were valued by the pentagon at $505 million and arrived in 62 shipments
the january-february estimates are contained in an unclassified assessment of the nicaraguan military buildup that is updated periodically by the defense department for administration leaders. it was released on request by the pentagon's public affairs office
including the latest estimates, the pentagon maintains the nicaraguan government has received arms valued at more than $2.4 billion since calendar year 1980
the new update was prepared at a time when president reagan is working with lawmakers to fashion an aid program for the contra guerrillas. u.s. aid to the contras was cut off feb. 29 after the house refused to endorse an administration plan for military and humanitarian aid and then rejected a democratic alternative to provide just humanitarian aid
it also comes during a period of rising doubt about the future of peace negotiations. nicaraguan leader daniel ortega has dismissed roman catholic cardinal miguel obando y bravo as a mediator in the talks, and the contras have said they need more time to consider some of the sandinista proposals
secretary of state george p. shultz said thursday that south korea has accomplished a ``political miracle'' in its peaceful transition to civilian rule
i think the korean situation is one we've all watched very closely and worked on hard,'' he told members of the house foreign operations appropriations subcommittee. ``and in (south) korea they have managed to put a political miracle alongside their economic miracle.''
however, shultz said later that it would be bold to predict when u.s. troops could be withdrawn
he said president chun doo-hwan ``engineered this change and takes considerable pride in being the first leader of korea to pass the leadership to somebody else in a peaceful transition of power. so it's a major and important event.''
he promised u.s. support to the new government,
shultz was asked about reports that the 40,000 u.s. troops could be withdrawn by 1990. he replied that he thought no date could be set
the united states would like to see more stability in the korean peninsula, he said
but there is a very militaristic north korea, whose performance has been terrible,'' he went on
shultz said there was ``quite compelling'' evidence that north korean intelligence was responsible for blowing up an airliner
progress is most likely by taking small steps such as exchanging family members, he said, adding that the holding of the olympic games in korea will also be a positive element
richard gephardt opened a ``full force'' drive in michigan thursday, two days after finishing a poor fourth among democrats on super tuesday, and said, ``if we don't do well here obviously we aren't going to be able to continue in this race.''
most of the other democratic presidential candidates were in illinois campaigning for that state's primary, which is next tuesday. and gephardt, too, was joining the others in chicago thursday night at a dinner and town meeting
but he said as he arrived for a rally on the michigan statehouse steps, ``our real thrust, our real force is going to be in michigan.''
michigan's democratic caucus is march 26
we have a long road to go,'' gephardt said. ``let's go the next step. i think michigan is going to be a real test of every campaign. we're going to do well in michigan and when we do we'll be right back in the middle of this.''
gerphardt, fighting against talk that his campaign may be nearing an end, held up a copy of thursday's wall street journal which said he had failed the test of a successful candidate
i think the wall street journal is dead wrong,'' he declared
he met with legislators and local democratic officials in a state where he said his message will be well received
earlier in the day, he campaigned in south carolina, which holds caucuses on saturday
while the other democratic presidential hopefuls have spent most of the week focusing on delegate-rich illinois, gephardt is trying to portray michigan's voting as the next major test of the democratic campaign
we're going to be there in full force,'' gephardt said. ``after that, we'll see where we are and where we go.''
in michigan, said deputy campaign manager joe trippi, ``we need to win it or at least come in second to jesse,'' a reference to jesse jackson
trippi said as many as 70 paid staffers would be sent to michigan by next week, compared to roughly 20 staffers in illinois
we'll take virtually every organizer we have,'' he said
we had our bad day on super tuesday, but now we're back and we're still in the middle of this race,'' gephardt said
gephardt rejected any comparisons with new york rep. jack kemp, who dropped from the republican presidential race earlier thursday
he pointed to his strong showings in several early contests, including victories in iowa and south dakota, and said he has the backing of 80 members of congress, most of whom will be delegates to the democratic national convention this summer
unlike jack kemp, i have been in the middle of this race from the beginning,'' gephardt said. ``i have a delegate count that is within striking distance of being back in the leadership.''
throughout the day on thursday, gephardt continued to hammer at the central theme of his campaign, talking tough on trade. that's designed to appeal in south carolina, where the textile industry has been damaged by foreign competition, as well as in michigan with its auto industry
the united auto workers union, a major force in michigan democratic politics, is remaining neutral, but gephardt aides said they anticipated getting support from union locals and rank-and-file members because of his trade and economic positions. spies''</head>
three east germans crashed a flatbed truck through steel barriers and roared over glienicker bridge into west berlin on thursday in the first escape of its kind over the famed ``bridge of spies,'' officials said
bernd puhlmann, who drove the truck in the high-speed escape to the west, said a soviet soldier on the east german side of the bridge took aim at the vehicle but did not fire
pulhmann said he thought that empty propane tanks that had been loaded onto the truck may have accounted for the soldier's reluctance
because the soldier didn't know what was in the tanks, he probably did not dare to shoot,'' the 37-year-old puhlmann told reporters
puhlmann said he and his two friends decided while drinking beer about midnight to make the escape
two hours later, the 7{-ton truck plowed through two east german metal gates and a chainlink fence before racing onto the glienicker bridge, which has been made famous by numerous east-west spy exchanges
the truck sped across the bridge, smashing through another east german-built chainlink fence and tearing off a steel control gate in west berlin before coming to a halt, police said
with the truck demolished, the three escapees got out uninjured and called west berlin authorities, said a west berlin police spokesman who asked not to be further identified
this is the first time that anyone has broken through those barriers,'' said another police officer
glienicker bridge connects potsdam, east germany with west berlin. potsdam is on berlin's southwest outskirts
the truck's impact tore the 4-foot-high steel gate on the west berlin side of the bridge off its foundation and twisted the barrier into a half-circle
wrecked barriers could be seen on the east german side of the bridge as well
metal, glass, plastic and motor oil from the truck were strewn across the area
the demolished truck sat with its engine compartment smashed and bumpers dangling
puhlmann said he, gotthard ihden, 37, and werner jaeger, 28, all of potsdam, decided to try the escape because they were dissatisfied with political conditions in communist east germany
west berlin officials said the three may face charges of destroying property and driving dangerously
among the most famous spy swaps on the bridge was the feb. 10, 1962 exchange by the united states of convicted soviet kgb master spy col. rudolph abel for francis gary powers, whose u-2 surveillance plane was shot down over the soviet union
many refugees fled over the bridge to west berlin after the east german workers' uprising in 1953, but the barriers there had never been breached. labs</head>
the federal government needs to step up its supervision of clinical laboratories in order to end widespread fraud and cut the rate of dangerous and sometimes fatal misdiagnoses, congress was told thursday
fraud, gross overcharging, kickbacks and poor quality of care are rampant in this industry, and federal oversight has been non-existent,'' said rep. john dingell, d-mich., chairman of the house energy and commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations
dingell said there is a ``pervasive pattern of highly questionable financial arrangements between laboratories and doctors,'' with lab inducements ranging from cash discounts and ``frequent flyer'' mileage to paying the salaries of doctors' aides
some witnesses cited 20 percent to 40 percent error rates in pap tests, which detect cervical cancer in women, as an example of the dangers in unregulated lab procedures
shirley greening, representing the american society for cytotechnology, said labs have adopted a ``paps for profit'' mentality under which technicians' salaries have stagnated while their workloads have increased to dangerous levels
some cytotechs screen 200 to 300 slides a day or more. this means looking at one pap smear slide every one and a half minutes,'' she said. ``screening at this high-production pace produces fatigue and leads to careless errors.''
other problems include piecework pay systems that encourage production at the expense of careful diagnosis, she said, and ``considerable pressure'' to accept inadequate specimens and call them negative so doctors won't send their business to another lab
greening and others recommended mandatory proficiency testing for all diagnostic lab technicians, workload limits, more federal money to monitor labs through the medicare and medicaid programs, and required public disclosure of lab caseload volume, staffing, fees, quality control methods and results
massachusetts attorney general james shannon said one lab was billing the state medicaid program $14 for a complete blood chemistry test. after the investigation, he said, the price dropped to $2.30
investigators have recovered $1.5 million through settlements, shannon said, and massachusetts medicaid is expected to save up to $700,000 a year due to the lower prices
shannon said such billing practices were a nationwide problem
dingell cited several federal investigations, including one still in progress, which have found fraud and kickbacks involving hundreds of doctors and millions of dollars in southern california, philadelphia and elsewhere
he said the profession has become so lucrative that ``a convicted bank robber is now involved in the operation of one southwest lab, who has exclaimed you can make more money in the operation of clinical labs than you can from robbing banks.''
there are about 12,000 federally regulated labs in the country, about 6,700 located in hospitals. several hundred thousand facilities are not federally regulated, many of them in physicians' offices
dingell said the market for clinical lab testing is estimated at $20 billion a year, and 40 percent of that is federally funded through medicare and medicaid
he said representatives of the lab industry would be heard from at a later date. no pickup.</note>
prince charles escaped an avalanche while skiing today, but the snowslide killed one of his friends and injured another
buckingham palace identified the dead man as maj. hugh lindsay, a former equerry, or aide, to charles's mother, queen elizabeth ii. a woman in the party, patricia palmer-tomkinson, suffered leg injuries, the palace said
the palace said charles was not injured. but witnesses said the prince looked distraught, and one said he was weeping and shaking as a helicopter arrived to pick him up
charles' wife, diana, and sarah ferguson, his pregnant sister-in-law, were not on the slopes at the time, the palace said
swiss authorities said the snowslide on mt. gotschnagrat near klosters began about 300 feet above a group of six skiers that included prince charles. the prince and three other people were unharmed
the palace said the party was skiing off the main ski run and was stationary when the avalanche began at 2:45 p.m
all members of the party were in a position to take avoiding action with the exception of maj. lindsay and mrs. palmer-tomkinson, who were both caught in the avalanche,'' it said
lindsay, 34, was a serving army major and a friend of charles and diana. he was married to a buckingham palace press secretary who was expecting a baby, the palace said
peter balsiger, editor-in-chief of the zurich-based newspaper blick, was quoted as saying he was told charles, 39, helped dig one person out of the snow
the palace statement said a swiss guide and members of the royal party helped dig the victims free. it did not say whether charles was among the diggers
a french photographer told bbc radio he saw charles being comforted by someone as a helicopter took off with a stretcher
bbc tv news said the queen was understood to have spoken to the family at the chalet where they gathered after the tragedy
the 1988 good ski guide describes the run where the accident occurred as ``a slope of awesome steepness, dropping about 500 meters (yards).''
prince charles skied the area many times during his bachelor days and is credited with giving klosters its exclusive tag
the guide says: ``prince charles is no doubt pleased to have put (it) behind him; mercifully it is rarely open.''
they (avalanches) are extremely difficult to predict. that is what makes them so dangerous,'' said peter cliff, an alpine guide and leader of the cairngorm mountain rescue team in scotland
the most common is the snow-slab avalanche, when snow driven by wind creates a crusted surface, underlaid with air pockets, and is liable to fracture across the entire width of a slope
without warning, massive slides can be set off by temperature increases, new falls of snow or skiers and climbers
the royals arrived in switzerland on tuesday
charles, diana and the duchess of york, who is married to charles' younger brother prince andrew, posed for photographers at klosters on wednesday for photographers. the 28-year-old duchess, the former sarah ferguson, is expecting her first baby in august
illinois blacks will deliver their primary vote almost exclusively to favorite son jesse jackson next tuesday, but black leaders credit the monolithic vote to jackson's charisma and not a daley-style political machine
jackson, who has had his differences with the black hierarchy in his adopted hometown of chicago, doesn't need a machine to ensure the black vote, observers say
this is a movement vote that is bigger than the capabilities of any ward committeeman or political organizer,'' said don rose, a longtime chicago political consultant who predicts jackson will win up to 95 percent of the black vote in the illinois primary
but jackson's supporters are working hard to mobilize that vote and _ more importantly _ to make sure supporters realize the necessity of also voting for jackson's slated convention delegates in illinois
illinois' beauty pageant primary is separate from the election of 173 delegates to the democratic national convention
jackson is fielding full delegate slates in only 17 of the state's 22 congressional districts. he is one delegate short in four other districts and has no slate in the nearly all-white suburbs on chicago's northwest side
the black vote alone won't be enough to give jackson a victory in the illinois primary _ and may not be enough to lock up second place, rose said
he predicted the black vote would amount to between 23 percent and 25 percent of the entire democratic vote in illinois. ``if he gets 10 percent of the white vote, that would give him 30 percent and make it unlikely for him to carry the state,'' rose said
right now, there is a tremendous fervor in the community for jesse after the outcome of super tuesday,'' said chicago alderman danny davis, a black leader and jackson supporter. ``i've heard people ... talking about how it was the second coming.''
jackson returned in triumph wednesday to chicago, his political base for nearly two decades, reminding voters, ``i am a charter member of the underclass, the son of a teen-age mother who was the daughter of a teen-age mother. i was able to break the shackles.''
jackson rose to national prominence from chicago's predominantly black south side where he started a civil rights group called operation push in the early 1970s
he owns a home in a middle-class chicago neighborhood and regularly returns to push headquarters to speak at the group's weekly saturday meetings, which often take on the flavor of a church revival meeting
davis and other political observers predicted that jackson's chicago political base would help him win about 95 percent of the black vote in illinois and up to 10 percent of the white vote _ roughly the proportions he won in the super tuesday primaries
but they say he'll carry the black vote without relying on the type of ward-boss political machine that has permeated chicago history, most recently under the late mayor richard daley
there is not a black political machine in the formal sense,'' said rose, who worked for the late mayor harold washington, the city's first black mayor
there is a mobilized black vote _ the product of the harold washington years,'' rose said wednesday. ``jesse is able to pull it together and he will deliver an overwhelming black vote of 90 percent to 95 percent
but that's not the product of anybody's machine,'' rose said. ``that's a product of jesse's charisma and popularity among black voters.''
jackson had the support of washington in 1984 and of current mayor eugene sawyer this year. but he and washington were largely allies of political convenience, and jackson actively backed another black alderman over sawyer in the political fighting that followed washington's death last november
east st. louis mayor carl officer, a longtime jackson supporter, will deliver the democratic contender the bulk of the black vote in that southern illinois city, said several jackson supporters
jackson also will be counting on the black church, long a political base for him, to help mobilize voters, chicago alderman tim evans said. on sunday, he said, black ministers throughout the city likely will preach to their parishioners to vote for jackson. report that hijackers committed suicide and killed leader, identified as mother, and two committed suicide. picks up 5th graf pvs, `the hijackers ...</note>
a family of musicians demanding to be flown to london set off a bomb aboard an aeroflot jet and killed four people before an assault team stormed the plane and shot dead five of the hijackers, tass said today
the hijackers carried weapons and explosives aboard the plane in their instruments, the official soviet news agency said. in addition to the nine dead, 20 passengers were reported injured in tuesday's hijacking of the tupolev-154 plane, tass said
tass identified the 11 air pirates as members of a family musical ensemble from siberia known as the ovechkins. it gave no information on their motives
the hijackers set off the bomb while the plane, with 76 passengers, was on the ground near leningrad, tass said
the government newspaper izvestia said one of the hijackers died in the explosion. the newspaper said the surviving air pirates then killed their leader, identified as their mother, and that two of them committed suicide
the hijackers seized the plane tuesday as it was headed to leningrad after a stop in the ural mountains city of kurgan. the flight began in the siberian city of irkutsk
tass reported the incident on wednesday, but gave few details. it was the second hijacking of a soviet domestic flight in 1{ years
u.s. embassy spokesman richard gilbert said today that the embassy had been told no americans were aboard
the sovietskaya rossiya daily reported today that the cockpit crew had been relayed a message from the hijackers that they were to proceed to london
the pilots reported what happened to ground control,'' tass said. ``they were told that a refueling was needed to meet their demand and the airliner made an unscheduled landing.''
tass said a special assault team boarded the plane after it landed and that the hijackers opened fire
the bandits managed to set off an explosive device in the airliner's tail section. the plane caught fire,'' the agency reported. ``an air hostess and three passengers were killed as a result of the act of terrorism.''
other passengers were evacuated, but 20 were injured and were hospitalized, tass said
five of the 11 criminals were killed,'' it stated, without giving details. radio moscow said the other six would be tried in court
the bandits were the ovechkins, a family musical group from irkutsk'' in siberia, tass said. ``eyewitnesses pointed to three leaders among the criminal team _ vasily and oleg ovechkin and their mother, ninel ovechkin, a plump, fashionably dressed woman of over 50.''
tass said they brought their weapons aboard in their instruments
sovietskaya rossiya explained that the incident transpired over the course of the afternoon
the jet, which can carry up to 168 passengers, took off from kurgan at 1:08 p.m. moscow time, the paper said. shortly before 3 p.m., when the plane was nearing leningrad's pulkovo airport, one of the people aboard demanded that senior flight attendant tamara zharkaya take a note to the cockpit
the note said: ``we demand that you change course. fly to london. otherwise we'll blow up the plane along with the passengers,'' the newspaper reported
the crew kept their heads, the paper said. pilot valentin f. kupriyanov calculated how much fuel was left, then landed at an unidentified airfield near leningrad
after landing, the crew entered into negotiations with the bandits, asking them to give up their criminal intentions and not to endanger passengers' lives,'' the newspaper said
but the hijackers refused to listen, it said
several hours of negotiations had no result,'' the newspaper said
under these conditions, the only decision that could be taken was to render the criminals harmless,'' said sovietskaya rossiya
radio moscow said: ``in the shooting aboard the plane, most of the hijackers were killed, and the others were captured. they are to be tried in court.''
the last airliner hijacking attempt reported in the soviet union was on sept. 20, 1986, in the ural mountains city of ufa. media reports said the hijackers were armed members of the internal security forces. the reports said that five people, including two of the hijackers, were killed when authorities stormed the plane. the others were tried and sentenced
tuesday's hijack was at least the third fatal incident this year involving an aeroflot jet
on jan. 18, a tu-154 crashed at the caspian port of krasnovodsk, killing 11 and injuring at least 12
a tu-134 carrying 51 people crashed on feb. 27 while landing at the siberian city of surgut. tass said there were victims but gave no details
reports on aviation accidents and disasters were rare until about two years ago, when soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev embarked on a campaign for more open discussion of social and economic problems
a civil aviation ministry official said in november that aeroflot would begin reporting all injury accidents this year. primaries; note that the date for the democrats abroad primary has changed to march 22.</note>
