security police on thursday questioned the editor of a church-sponsored magazine after he charged that some voters were intimidated by the government in recent primary elections, a colleague said
during the feb. 22 elections, voters were required to line up at polling places behind their candidate or someone representing him
chief editor bedan mbugua called the system ``a mockery of democracy'' in monday's edition of beyond magazine, which is sponsored by the national council of churches of kenya. he charged that some voters were intimidated by administration officials into voting for certain candidates
ibrahim omondi, associate editor of beyond, said mbugua reported to security police, but no details of the investigation were available
the general secretary of the kenya african nation union, the country's sole legal political party, acknowledged mistakes during the primary, but he accused beyond of sloppy and unfair reporting
it is one-sided and self-serving,'' burudi nabwera said at a news conference. ``it is difficult to understand how the magazine could have drawn conclusions after looking partially at only five constituencies.''
general elections on march 21 will be by secret ballot
a former top federal education official has some news for parents struggling with college tuition bills
harold howe ii, who was u.s. education commissioner from 1965-68 under president lyndon b. johnson, says that at $12,000 a year, or roughly $60 a day during the academic year, a college education is ``a bargain.''
howe, writing in the march 9 issue of the chronicle of higher education, offered what he called ``an incomplete list'' of all the things that $60 buys, including:
_``a room and bath (often semiprivate) and three meals, plus heat and electricity.''
_``a variety of free or low-cost cultural, social and sports events as well as extracurriculars.''
_``special student facilities for socializing and meeting members of the opposite sex.''
_``what amounts to a club membership for recreation, including swimming, tennis, golf (except in cities) and other sports.''
_``access to ... libraries, laboratories, museums, field trips and guest lectures.''
_``the services of an army of food-service, clerical and other non-academic employees.''
_``the personal attention of faculty members with a wide range of skills and knowledge, whose main job is to pass on what they know to their students.''
_``free advice from a distinguished group of presidents, provosts, deans and other functionaries who believe that colleges should turn out graduates with both a moral compass and a body of knowledge.''
that's not bad for $60 a day,'' said howe, who is now a senior lecturer at harvard university's graduate school of education
he said students get all that ``for a daily fee that might get you a night _ but no meals _ in a holiday inn.''
in addition to providing all these services for students, ``colleges do great things for society,'' howe said, citing studies that have found ``college graduates pay more taxes, are more likely to vote, have a lower divorce rate, volunteer more often for good works in their communities and are less likely to go to jail.''
howe said secretary of education william j. bennett, who has often accused colleges of being overpriced and underproductive, should consider changing ``his tune and (urging) colleges to raise tuition, so that the goose that lays the golden eggs can continue to do so.''
instead of responding to bennett with ``salvos about inadequate faculty salaries (and) increasing maintenance costs,'' college presidents should point out ``what a bargain a college education is today,'' howe suggested
a british army land rover overturned during maneuvers in south wales, killing two soldiers and injuring four others, the army said thursday
the six men were traveling in the vehicle when the accident occurred at sennybridge in powys on wednesday, the army said
the four injured soldiers were hospitalized, and one was in critical condition
a 15-year-old boy was convicted of second-degree murder and sentenced to life in prison today for beating a classmate to death with a baseball bat so he could see what it was like to kill someone
rod matthews showed no reaction when the verdict was announced and his sentence immediately imposed. the verdict, issued at 2:10 p.m., followed nearly 10 hours of deliberation over two days
the victim's mother sobbed as the verdict was announced, and matthews' mother sat silently with lowered head
matthews' mental state was the focus of closing arguments wednesday in norfolk superior court
the jurors began their work after judge roger j. donahue explained again the various possible convictions available and outlining the basis for acquittal by reason of insanity
prosecutors, who were seeking a first-degree murder conviction for the nov. 20, 1986, slaying, depicted matthews as a dispassionate murderer who plotted for weeks to lure 14-year-old shaun ouillette to a secluded area ``to find out what it was like to kill somebody.''
defense attorney john philip white, calling for acquittal by reason of insanity, called matthews an irrational, ``diseased intellect'' who appealed for help before the killing but was ignored by a teacher and friends
matthews, tried as an adult, had faced a mandatory sentence of life imprisonment without parole if convicted of first-degree murder. if found guilty of second-degree murder, the maximum penalty is life imprisonment with a chance of parole in 15 years
if matthews had been found innocent by reason of insanity, he would have been evaluated by the state department of mental health, white said
district attorney peter casey portrayed matthews as a troubled youth who was prompted to kill by his own desires, not by mental illness
he did that because he doesn't care about anybody,'' said casey, who repeatedly jabbed an accusatory finger at matthews during closing arguments. ``what did it feel like? it was deliberate. ... he really wound up and hit him about the head.''
matthews chose ouillette as the victim after rejecting two other classmates as targets because two of his friends objected, casey said
ouillette, who moved to canton with his family about two years before the slaying, was selected because matthews felt he would not be missed, according to testimony during the week-long trial
matthews said he had plotted the killing for a month to experience what killing someone was like, according to testimony from two classmates who were shown the body by matthews before a pre-thanksgiving pep rally
ouillette's body was discovered in december 1986 after one of the youths sent police an anonymous letter. none of the teen-agers who knew of the slaying faces prosecution
white depicted matthews as a highly unstable youth whose use of ritalin, a drug used mainly to control hyperactivity in children, may have exacerbated his already unstable state
that contention is a smoke screen, casey said, citing medical experts' testimony that ritalin does not permanently alter behavior or trigger violence or hallucinations in normal doses
white also said matthews unsuccessfully sought help prior to the slaying in a letter to a teacher in which matthews described his desire to kill and light fires
had they said, `no, don't kill shaun ouillette,' in all likelihood shaun ouillette would not have been harmed,'' said white
the trial was attended each day by the victim's and defendant's families and dozens of residents of canton, a middle-class community of 17,000 people about 15 miles south of boston
the case has been compared to the 1982 trial of anthony broussard, then 18, and sentenced 25 years to life in san jose, calif., for killing his girlfriend the year before
broussard, who was tried as an adult, took at least 13 schoolmates to see the victim's body. the movie ``the river's edge'' was based on that case
the cuban prison system is generally constructive and humane for cooperative inmates but metes out ``harsh and cruel'' treatment to those who reject rehabilitation programs, according to a report released thursday
the report was prepared by the institute for policy studies, a liberal research group based in washington which sponsored a visit by a six-member delegation to cuba from feb. 26 to march 5
the delegation, which visited six prisons at various locations around the island and conducted more than 120 ``confidential'' interviews, said it found a number of ``constructive aspects'' to the cuban system:
_the great majority of prisoners work a regular work week at productive jobs under conditions similar to those of ordinary workers. many acquire practical skills during confinement and have opportunities to advance their education
_almost all the prisoners who work are paid, receiving the same rate as civilians except for certain discounts to cover cost of living
_the regular prison facilities were all clean and hygenic, there were no complaints of the use of ``instruments of torture'' and a system of conjugal visits was well established
but the report also found that prisoners who resist re-education or violate prison discipline are confined for extended periods, at times in ``extremely harsh punishment cells _ bare, tiny, dark, cold (or hot, depending on the season) _ sometimes with not enough food.''
one delegation member, aryeh neier, said the cells were five feet by seven, had no bedding, only a primitive sanitary system and housed three prisoners each
the delegation said it had heard reports of a few prisoners who wore no clothes or only undershorts and shoes
some prisoners who refuse to work are allowed sun only once a week for an hour or two and are confined to iron cages too small to take walks, the report said
until recently, uncooperative prisoners were allowed visits only once every six months but the delegation said new rules have reduced this to once every 60 days, the report said
but a cuban exile, reinaldo lopez lima, who said he spent 23 years in cuban prisons, told neier during the news conference that he spent eight of those years without a family visit. he described prison conditions as ``terrible'' and said he knew of a dozen prisoners who were killed early last year shortly before his release
under questioning, neier said he was satisfied that the delegation got an ``unfettered look'' at the cuban prison system. he said it would have been difficult for cuban authorities to restrict the delegation to ``showcase'' areas reserved for foreign visitors because he had maps drawn for the delegation by former prisoners
the visit came at a time when the reagan administration is making a concerted effort at the u.n. human rights commission in geneva to make cuba an agenda item at the 1989 commission session
in a speech to the commission on tuesday, the u.s. ambassador to the united nations, vernon walters, said that cuba has more than 200 prisons and labor camps and that there may be between 10,000 to 15,000 political prisoners
he said that a group of long-term political prisoners who have refused rehabilitation began a hunger strike a week ago ``to protest havana's attempts to misinform the world about prison conditions, torture and other mistreatment.''
neier noted that amnesty international, a london-based human rights group, claims to have the names of 600 political prisoners and said he believes the actual number in that category is only somewhat higher
the report said that the delegation interviewed at least 50 political prisoners, most of whom the group had selected in advance
the visit was undertaken at the suggestion of the institute for policy studies. in exchange, ipc agreed to seek similar access to u.s. prisons by a delegation of cuban legal experts
rock star george michael has credited the wife of democratic presidential candidate albert gore jr. with helping boost his album sales past 10 million
no doubt a few of those american sales came from tipper gore's efforts,'' michael said thursday in a statement released by his publicist, phil lobel
mrs. gore has spoken against obscene lyrics in rock 'n' roll music
michael said he has been notified that his ``faith'' album, which contains the hit single ``i want your sex,'' has sold more than 10 million copies worldwide
perhaps now she can help sell a few thousand more records since her husband won big in the primaries,'' michael said in perth, australia, where he is performing
gore, a u.s. senator from tennessee, won in six states during the super tuesday primaries
as americans like to say, there was much hoopla about nothing,'' michael said about the lyrics in the song. ``it was, after all, just a pop record.''
the nicaraguan contras on thursday dropped a demand that had blocked peace talks with their homeland's marxist government, agreeing to the open agenda proposed by the sandinistas
the rebel group made the announcement at a news conference here where its leaders bitterly criticized the united states for cutting off contra aid
the united states has once again abandoned an ally,'' said adolfo calero, one of six directors of the nicaraguan resistance. ``but we have been abandoned before. we will continue our efforts.''
calero said the rebels will now accept the proposed open agenda for talks in sapoa, nicaragua, and suggested the talks begin march 16
we are ready to go to sapoa,'' said calero, who will head the delegation
he said the nicaraguan resistance, as the contras are formally known, would no longer insist that the agenda include a program hammered out during talks mediated by nicaraguan cardinal miguel obando y bravo in guatemala last month. that included a 30-day truce, political amnesty, press freedoms, an end to the draft, and a dialogue with the opposition
the contras proposed instead that the sandinistas allow the ``internal opposition'' to attend the talks, but stopped short of saying they would insist on that condition
the change in the contras' position came one week after a reagan administration proposal to continue funding the rebels lost in a close vote in the u.s. house of representatives on march 3
calero called the united states ``an inconsistent and impermanent'' friend, in contrast to the soviets, who support the sandinistas
he and fellow director aristides sanchez said the aid cutoff might eventually hurt troops in the field, but insisted their morale was still high
we will never surrender,'' said calero
the sandinistas have previously accepted contra demands that obando y bravo, whom the nicaraguan government dropped as mediator, attend the sapoa talks as a witness
the contras, in turn, accepted organization of american states head javier baena soares as a second witness
calero said thursday that in previous communications the sandinistas have ``given every guarantee'' of the contra delegation's safety inside nicaragua
nicaraguan president daniel ortega had proposed the sapoa talks begin march 9, but the contras begged off, saying they were only notified the night of march 7
last week, they asked instead for a meeting in costa rica to discuss details of the talks, but thursday's proposal made no mention of a preliminary meeting
calero said he had kept the united states _ which he referred to as ``our ally, in quotes'' _ informed of the talks
pop singer andy gibb, younger brother of the three members of the bee gees rock group, died today in an oxford hospital after developing stomach pains, his record company said. he was 30
a spokesman for island records ltd. who spoke on condition he not be identified said he could not release the cause of death
he was 30 years old. he was taken ill with stomach pains on monday and was admitted to hospital for observation and then he died this morning,'' the record company said in a statement. ``the reason for death has yet to be announced.''
a spokesman for john radcliffe hospital in oxford, 52 miles northwest of london, confirmed gibb died there at 8:45 a.m
i can't give you any further information than that,'' said colin weston, the hospital's duty administrator
the record company spokesman said the australian-born gibb, younger brother of robin, maurice and barry who make up the bee gees, signed a contract with island records two months ago and was due to work on a new album this spring
gibb's hit songs include ``i just want to be your everything,'' in 1977, ``shadow dancing'' and ``an everlasting love'' in 1978 and ``(our love) don't throw it all away'' in 1979
gibb's manager, robert stigwood, said in new york he was ``very sad and deeply distressed, and sorry. i have been in touch with his parents and brothers. i will miss him.''
gibb's miami lawyer, john kozyak, said he received word of gibb's death from the miami manager of the bee gees
this is really a shock,'' kozyak said. the last time i saw him, he looked perfectly healthy to me. he was playing tennis.''
dick ashby, the bee gees' representative in miami, said gibb's mother, barbara gibb, was with him when he died
gibb lived in a penthouse apartment at venetia on biscayne bay in miami
last october, court papers filed in connection with gibb's bankruptcy proceedings in miami showed gibb earned only $7,755 in 1986 and lived rent-free while playing guitars loaned him by his brothers
kozyak said an investigation was under way into gibb's death
the doctor was going to talk to him this morning and arrange more tests, and he simply died,'' he said
gibb, who co-hosted tv's ``solid gold'' in 1981 and 1982, had six hit records in the late 1970s
he was born in australia but had lived in the miami area for several years
gibb got the venetia apartment in exchange for promoting the plush condominium complex. he had appeared at various celebrity charity events around south florida, including pro-celebrity tennis matches in miami and fort lauderdale
but he suffered financial setbacks in recent years and filed for bankruptcy last september. at that time he estimated his debts at more than $1 million and his assets at less than $50,000
gibb had been in london about a month. kozyak said gibb's bankruptcy was discharged from miami federal court in january and all of gibb's debts were settled
since then, gibb ``was back on his feet and in good spirits and trying to put together a record contract,'' he said
a seventh-grader was expelled and a classmate was suspended for 30 days for making at least three ``homemade bombs'' and bringing them to school, allegedly to get back at a teacher, officials said thursday
the boone county board of education took the action against the unidentified boys following hearings march 1 and 2, school officials said. a third youth had been suspended for 10 days but is back at the madison middle school
two bombs were found hidden in a restroom ceiling, and testimony at the hearings indicated the third was detonated somewhere outside school, principal joe tagliente said thursday
the containers found hidden in the ceiling contained some kind of fuel mixed with gun powder, tagliente said
according to the testimony, one of the boys had a problem with a teacher and was mad at him, and the student brought the bombs to school to blow up his car,'' tagliente said. ``the student denies saying it.''
superintendent kenneth mabe said one youth was expelled for the rest of the school year and banned from school property. the second was suspended for 30 days and placed on probation the rest of the school year, he said. both were required to seek counseling
both were accused of manufacturing the devices, tagliente said
the third student was not accused of making the bomb but was allegedly involved in the plot, he said
no criminal charges have been filed against the youths
