a nationwide sweep of mafia suspects has led to 96 arrests, authorities said thursday
more than 1,000 members of various agencies were trying to execute 160 arrest warrants for suspects in cities from palermo in sicily to milan in northern italy, authorities said
prosecutors in palermo said thursday they began the investigation in april based on statements by antonio calderone, who was arrested at that time in an investigation of the so-called alleruzzo gang of mafiosi that operated near mount etna in sicily. magistrates were also acting on statements made by other mafia informants, the prosecutors said
the italian news agency ansa said the crimes cited by calderone included the killing of police col. giuseppe russo and ambush of gen. carlo alberto dalla chiesa, the prefect of palermo and italy's top mafia fighter. his 1982 murder prompted an investigation that led to a 1985 anti-mafia sweep with 200 arrests
ansa said calderone also told authorities about the role of small crime families that operate on the flanks of the large mafia groups in the cities
italian news agencies said an unspecified number of people named in the latest arrest warrants were already in prison for other crimes
gary hart, who three months ago re-entered the democratic presidential race to ``let the people decide,'' has gotten the message and will call it quits on friday, sources said thursday
the former colorado senator polled no more than 5 percent of the vote in the super tuesday primaries and won no convention delegates. the day after the primaries, the federal election commission announced hart no longer was eligible for further federal matching funds
his departure from the race, expected to come at a friday morning news conference in denver, will mark his second departure from the 1988 democratic race
at a highly charged news conference last may 8, a defiant hart, at the time considered the democratic front-runner, quit the race following published reports about his relationship with miami model donna rice
when he rejoined the race in december, hart immediately shot to the top of the polls. but pollsters cautioned hart's numbers could be traced to name identification rather than support and early contests bore that out _ hart finished last in crucial early races in iowa and new hampshire
sources speaking only on condition of anonymity said hart would not endorse any of the surviving contenders when he makes his withdrawal announcement
in lansing, mich., george sallade, co-chairman of michigan friends for gary hart, said hart's speech scheduled for friday to a michigan state university political science class had been canceled. he said he expected a withdrawal announcement
`what this shows is that the american people expect the occupant of the white house to be saintly,'' sallade said
the hart campaign suffered an additional blow when colorado gov. roy romer and state democratic party chairman buie seawell threw their support behind massachusetts gov. michael dukakis on wednesday. both previously had been hart supporters, and seawell once headed hart's senate office in washington, d.c. legislature</head>
many people would like to see students perform community services, and a bill in the legislature would require all michigan high school students to do that to graduate
critics of the measure say students should concentrate on academics, such service should be voluntary, and the state shouldn't intrude on local control of education
the bill introduced wednesday by sen. jerome hart would require students to perform 40 hours of community service over the last three years of high school. it also would let them earn at least one-half course credit if they performed an additional 50 hours of service
rhett johnston, an aide to hart, said about 5 percent of the schools nationwide require community service as a condition of graduation. about 28 percent of the nation's 74,000 public high schools offer elective course credit for volunteer work
community service offers our young people the chance to discover, develop and display talents and skills they rarely use in school and it also provides hard-pressed community social agencies a corps of hard-working, dedicated and compassionate volunteers,'' hart said
it's pretty widespread,'' said barbara gomez, director of school-sanctioned youth community service programs for the washington-based council of chief state school officers, which represents state school superintendents
it's a grass-roots effort that's filtering up to the state level. there seems to be a big movement on voluntary service. ... i don't think it's something that is going to go away
our stance is that it's another way of learning. ... what goes on in the classroom is not the only way a child can learn,'' gomez said
two school districts in michigan _ detroit and bloomfield hills _ require community service to graduate. paid part-time jobs satisfy the requirement in detroit
you require what you value. we think this is a valuable experience,'' said gary doyle, deputy superintendent for the affluent bloomfield hills school district. ``reaching out and helping others gives students a better sense of self.''
but some education officials don't like the idea
it should be determined locally. if it's going to be a mandate, we would probably oppose it,'' said don elliott, executive director of the michigan association of school administrators
it may well be a good idea, but it should be something that each school district should consider on its own,'' said justin king, executive director of the michigan association of school boards
our position is any graduation requirement should be (a matter of) local control,'' said carl cohen, president of the michigan pta. ``we think that community service should be something that everybody should want to do.''
