crews delicately dismantled the pedal-powered plane daedalus on thursday and packed it up for the start of a journey to greece, where the 70-pound aircraft will attempt a record 74-mile flight over the aegean sea
pilots rolled the plane, which resembles a monstrous pink dragonfly, onto the tarmac at the dryden flight research facility, where it sat in stark contrast to the giant 747 shuttle piggyback jetliner at the nasa facility
engineers then separated the daedalus wings, packed the aircraft into a container and loaded it into a moving van. a planned demonstration flight was called off because of high winds in the mojave desert, 65 miles north of los angeles
daedalus will travel to masachusetts and will leave for athens aboard a c-130 transport on march 23. the target date for the flight attempt is march 30
the aircraft has been undergoing tests in southern california since october in preparation for the greek islands flight. the route, originally designed to duplicate the mythological daedalus' route from crete to the greek mainland, was changed slightly to ensure lighter winds
greek mythology dictates that daedalus became the world's first mortal to fly when he manufactured wings of wax and feathers. according to the story, his son, icarus, died because he flew too near the sun and the wax melted
the daedalus was designed and built by a team of students, faculty and alumni from mit. it will be pedaled between crete and santorini by one of five world class bicycle racers currently in training
if successful, the flight could last up to seven hours and would break the distance record for human-powered flight set in january 1987, when the eagle experimental airplane flew 37.2 miles over the mojave desert
the previous record was set in 1979 when the gossamer albatross crossed the english channel
the daedalus can travel at an altitude of 15 feet with a top speed of 14 mph and stretches 30 feet from propeller to tail. the pilot sits in a plastic cocoon, dangling from a 112-foot long styrofoam wing. a 10-foot propeller spins four feet from the pilot's face
when in flight, the temperature in the cockpit increases 20 degrees because of the exertion of the pilot. designers feel they have until may 15 to make the record attempt. after that, the weather will be too hot
the pilot will be selected by lottery
one of those in training, greg zack, 26, of wilmington, n.c., said he was physically prepared
it would be a big bummer if i didn't go,'' zack said. ``the whole project has been a team thing though, so no one will be flying alone. i can live with it if i'm not flying it.''
he added, ``it's a funny plane to fly. it's a lot of fun. there's not much to it, really. you can look around and enjoy flying. you aren't busy with the controls.''
heat and winds are the only adversaries, he said. ``if there are gusts more than 5 mph, then you try to guess where it is going to take you and try to keep control,'' zack said
the other potential pilots are frank scioscia, 27, scranton, pa.; glenn tremml, 28, new haven, conn.; erik schmidt, 25, boulder, colo.; and kanellos kanellopoulos, 30, vrahneika, greece
at first, louisiana's chief financial officer was amused by a phony memo bearing his name that told state employees to limit their restroom time or face some surprising reminders
in the march 1 memo, a ``restroom trip policy'' is outlined ``to provide a consistent method of accounting for each employee's restroom time and ensuring equal treatment of all state employees.''
all restroom stalls are being equipped with timed paper roll retractors,'' the memo said. ``if the stall is occupied for more than three minutes, an alarm will sound. thirty seconds after the alarm sounds, the roll of paper in the stall will retract, the toilet will flush and the stall door will open.''
but after his initial amusement, brian kendrick, the state's commissioner of administration, started thinking about how the memo was being spread, and whether that meant the state could economize on some office machinery
if we can find out where those copies are starting, we'll go in and take out some copiers,'' he said
if i had a dollar for every copy that's been made, i could have probably solved the state's money problems,'' kendrick said wednesday. louisiana faces a budget deficit projected as high as $200 million
