he's a very friendly dog,'' said nero's master, officer joseph faraguna. ``in all the arrests i've made with him, he's only bitten four times.''
tired of sitting on a boat while the fish ignore the fat worm on your hook? maybe they're fussy eaters; try a new kind of bait made in five fin-tickling flavors: bacon, strawberry, vanilla, corn and blood
catfish and carp really go for the taste of ``fish and stuff,'' says jack hurley, executive vice president of westin inc., an omaha-based food company that is spending $3.5 million to roll out the new product
the bait will be made from by-products of two food plants, fairbury food products in fairbury and platte valley foods in wahoo. the fairbury plant makes bacon bits and the wahoo plant makes onion rings and breaded vegetables
the drug-taking and sexual partners of aids-infected people would be told they're at risk of catching the deadly disease under a bill introduced in the new york legislature
the measure says doctors should have the power, without threat of legal penalty, to inform people in danger even over the objection of those infected with aids. the bill doesn't specifically allow doctors to use the names of the aids-infected people when informing intimates, but it does give physicians the right to use their discretion
the legislation, unveiled wednesday, also would require that counseling and education services be made available to people being tested for aids and for those close to them who are at risk of catching the disease
also under the bill, blood testing for exposure the hiv virus, which causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, would be limited to people who voluntarily agree and give written authorization to be tested
according to sponsors, the legislation would restrict release of the results of aids tests without a person's consent to the individuals being tested and to professionals directly involved in the medical care of that person. some information could be exchanged by public health and social services agencies, sponsors said
the bill protects confidentiality, protects the information, except to deal with an identified and legitimate health concern and treatment necessity,'' said state assemblyman richard gottfried, chairman of the assembly's health committee. ``you would not notify everybody in the neighborhood (of the presence of aids). you would not notify somebody's fellow workers.''
sponsors say the bill would limit discrimination against people with aids, the hiv virus or with aids-related complex in employment, housing, credit transactions and other areas
a violation of the disclosure rules would carry a misdemeanor criminal penalty of up to one year in jail under the bill, which also would establish improper disclosure as grounds of a civil lawsuit
current state laws require physicians to inform people when they are at risk of getting certain sexually transmitted diseases such as syphilis. the legislation proposed wednesday would make aids notification optional for doctors, and it would also give doctors the right to ask public health officials to do the notifying instead
tim sweeney, deputy director for policy of the new york city-based gay men's health crisis, said that a ``strong confidentiality bill can enhance public health and civil liberties.''
new york state, with 14,000 aids cases, has the nation's highest incidence of the disease. aids is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system. it is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
a man who was twice acquitted of charges he violated oak park's handgun ban has sued the community and several of its officials for $2.5 million
in the lawsuit filed wednesday in u.s. district court, don bennett accuses the suburban village, several officials and police officers of conspiring to harass him and violate his constitutional rights to free speech, due process and equal protection under the law
bennett, 45, a resident of the nearby hanover park, formerly owned a gas station and minimarket in oak park
bennett's attorney, michael d. johnson, said bennett sold his business in july after he was harassed by the village and its officials because of his outspoken opposition to the ban on handguns
the oak park attorney, raymond heise, said he had not received a copy of the lawsuit, but he denied the allegations
if mr. bennett interpreted that enforcement as harassment, that's his interpretation,'' he said. ``i don't know any day that he wasn't free to operate his business.''
on march 26, 1986, bennett was charged with violating the handgun ban after he chased and shot at two people who robbed his gas station. bennett was acquitted that fall
the lawsuit contends a police officer told bennett the following day to stop talking with the news media about his case, johnson said
bennett was charged with a second violation of the handgun ban on feb. 23, 1987, accused of brandishing a firearm while dealing with an unruly customer. he was later acquitted of that charge, too, johnson said
