herrington said that should the united states fail to build the physics research center, there could be a ``brain drain'' of mammoth proportions, as u.s. scientists go abroad to work on the best equipment
he urged congress to help the united states take the lead in high-energy physics ``and let the brain drain happen in other countries.''
the subcommittee's chairman, rep. tom bevill, d-ala., pressed herrington to get financial commitments from foreign nations before congress votes further money for the project
unless we can get allocated another billion dollars pretty soon and start it ... we could not possibly initiate the funding,'' bevill said. ``but if we had assurance 50 percent or 75 percent would be contributed by other countries, it would be a whole new game.''
herrington, however, said it was up to the united states to act first in order to draw foreign participation
rep. carl pursell, r-mich., said he was worried that depending on some foreign nations, such as japan, for funds would endanger u.s. commercial and security interests
the project ``may be pure physics in itself, but there are results that will translate into the industrial and strategic area,'' said pursell, whose district contains one of seven proposed sites for the super-collider
president reagan has proposed $363 million for super-collider construction in 1989, but critics in congress oppose such high spending on grounds it would divert money from other important research projects
the research center would include a 53-mile-around atom smasher to study the effects of high-speed collisions of subatomic particles
backers of the project contend it would produce practical technological benefits into the next century
bevill, however, said $6 billion in large, federally backed research projects have been discontinued the past five years
that isn't a good track record,'' he said. ``when you make mistakes on a small research project, that is one thing, but when we look at the size of this, it shocks us.''
besides michigan, six other states have sites that remain in competition for the project, which will produce 3,000 jobs and have an annual operating budget of $279 million
the states are arizona, colorado, illinois, north carolina, tennessee and texas
a marine embassy guard who for a time figured prominently in last year's moscow spy scandal will leave the military next month, the marine corps said thursday
cpl. arnold bracy, 22, of woodside queens, new york city, will be formally discharged on april 4, the corps said. a marine official who asked not to be named said bracy would receive an honorable discharge
bracy served as an embassy guard in moscow with sgt. clayton j. lonetree, 26, who was convicted last august of passing classified information to soviet agents after becoming involved with a russian woman
for a time last spring, bracy also faced a military court-martial because navy and federal agents were convinced he had conspired with lonetree and allowed russian kgb agents inside the embassy late at night to roam at will
those allegations were based in part on a confession signed by bracy after a lengthy interrogation. bracy later recanted that statement, saying it had been coerced, and all charges against him were dropped when military lawyers concluded they did not have any corroborating evidence to prosecute. picking up 4th graf `arguments are...' adds byline.</note>
former black panther johnny spain was freed on bail today after 21 years in prison for murder in connection with a bloody, aborted 1971 escape attempt from san quentin prison
spain, 38, whose two murder convictions were reversed, arrived at the front gate of the california medical facility shortly after noon to receive congratulations from friends and supporters
i feel great,'' he said. ``what this has meant in terms of 21 years in prison, it has been a very terrible and difficult time. i won't let anyone down who has supported me and there have been many who supported me.''
on wednesday, u.s. district judge thelton henderson ordered spain, released on $350,000 bail pending a hearing on the state's appeal of the overturning of the convictions in the slaying of two guards during the escape attempt
friends prepared to post the bond, but vacaville officials decided not to release him immediately because they had not received the necessary papers from the state parole board and the judge who ordered him freed
arguments are scheduled for monday in the state's appeal of henderson's 1986 order of a new trial for spain in the ``san quentin six'' case
mr. spain is entitled to sit and watch that argument and hear the rest of his life debated before him,'' lawyer dennis riordan said in asking henderson for spain's immediate release
the bail ruling was the second court victory in as many days for spain, who was imprisoned being arrested in 1966 for a murder and robbery in los angeles
on tuesday, los angeles superior court judge kathleen parker ordered spain paroled immediately from the sentence he has been serving for the 1966 murder
spain apparently joined the black panther party after entering prison. he later became the only inmate convicted of murder in the bloody san quentin escape attempt that killed militant leader george jackson, two other prisoners and three guards
authorities said spain, who was seen running out of a maximum-security unit with jackson, conspired with jackson in the attempted breakout
the other members of the san quentin six were either convicted of lesser charges or acquitted
in reversing spain's convictions and granting him a new trial, henderson said spain had been denied a fair trial by being required to wear heavy shackles for every court appearance during the five years of proceedings
in december, the state board of prison terms rejected spain's request for parole, saying he was unsuitable for release. henderson, however, ordered a new hearing, finding that the board had violated his previous order not to consider the overturned san quentin convictions in its deliberations
on feb. 11, the board voted 2-1 to grant spain parole in 1989. a dissenting board member asked for review by the full nine-member board, which is scheduled march 21
spain's lawyers said he would live in san francisco and work as an electrician while his case is on appeal. henderson's order allows him to travel within the state and visit his wife, whom he married while in prison, and two young sons in los angeles
in a bid to revitalize the flagging nuclear power industry, 14 members of congress introduced legislation thursday to encourage standardized plant designs and streamline the government's regulatory force
rep. carlos j. moorhead, r-calif., said the bill provides the ``means to assure that the nuclear power option is preserved for the future.'' it is co-sponsored by eight republicans and five democrats, most of whom serve with moorhead on the house energy subcommittee that will initially consider the bill
the legislation would reorganize the five-member nuclear regulatory commission into a ``nuclear safety agency'' headed by a single administrator _ a step already approved by a senate subcommittee and favored by a majority of the nrc commissioners themselves. all other federal regulatory agencies are headed by just one boss, and the nrc's commission format has long come under fire from industry and congress as too cumbersome
unlike the senate measure, moorhead's bill would take the additional step of authorizing one-stop licensing of future nuclear plants if they are built to standard, state-of-the-art designs
currently, nuclear plants must be licensed in several stages, from the start of construction to the actual production of power years later. that is necessary, in part, because most u.s. plants have been built to ``custom'' designs _ different from any other _ and hence must be given more scrupulous review
moorhead's bill would encourage the new safety agency to license both the construction and operation of any plant, subject to normal inspections, which adheres to pre-cleared designs. the system would be similar to those used in france and japan, both of which rely heavily on nuclear power and produce it more cheaply
enormous costs, safety concerns and the lengthy, complicated licensing process are among factors blamed for the moribund state of the u.s. nuclear industry. though 110 plants are now in operation and a few are still under construction, no utility has even applied to build a new plant since 1978
nrc chairman lando zech and even some critics of nuclear power have long argued for plant standardization on both safety and financial grounds. some american firms say they now have the technology to design ``meltdown-proof'' reactors, which, if standardized, would be less expensive _ perhaps by more than half _ than the plants that now require containment structures and massive backup safety systems
moorhead, noting that the u.s. geological survey has just cut its estimate of undiscovered oil in the united states by 40 percent, said it is ``undeniably clear that in the 1990s and beyond, this country will have inadequate supplies of electricity. instead of having oil buried in the ground, it now appears that we have had our heads buried. it's time we face the facts quickly and develop alternative energy supplies.''
rep. michael bilirakis, r-fla., pointed to an example in his own state as evidence of the advantages offered by plant standardization. the st. lucie 2 power plant, built to the same specifications as its sister, st. lucie 1, recently was licensed for operation after $1.5 billion in construction costs, he said
in contrast,'' bilirakis continued, the long island shoreham plant, which is the same size as st. lucie 2, cost more than $5 billion. if we can keep nuclear plant construction costs below $2 billion by building the same design only twice, he said, ``imagine what we can save if we build a standardized plant many times over.''
we rely on nuclear power for nearly 20 percent of our electric generation,'' said bilirakis. ``yet, the construction of nuclear power plants is at a standstill. the volatile situation today in the persian gulf points out that we simply must continue to develop domestic energy sources to reduce our dependence on foreign oil. safe, reliable nuclear power is the means at hand to do just that.''
contra rebels freed a u.s. peace activist they had held for nine days, turning him over to members of his witness for peace organization, the group's local director said thursday
edward griffin, the head of witness for peace here, said activist richard boren was released wednesday night near the isolated town of quilali, 187 miles north of managua
in a telephone interview, griffin said boren, 30, a volunteer from elkin, n.c., ``had a cold and was very tired, but otherwise was fine.'' he said he got news of boren's release by radio from other volunteers working in the area
no definite time was set for his arrival in managua
boren was seized along with 12 nicaraguans march 1 when ``contra troops forced him out of a private home at gunpoint,'' said witness for peace, an organization based in durham, n.c
the group is made up of american volunteers opposed to the regan administration's continued support of the contra rebels in their 6-year-old fight to overthrow nicaragua's leftist sandinista government
on tuesday, the government filed a diplomatic note of protest with the u.s. embassy against the contra abductions. the sandinistas claimed 12 men were taken by the contras, witness for peace said there were 13
boren was the second american witness for peace member seized by the contras. the first was paul fishcer, who was abducted in october in central chontales province and held for two weeks
witness for peace officials in north carolina and washington also announced boren's release
on monday, a spokesman for the u.s. state department said contra leaders in washington and florida had agreed to release boren as soon as the rebels could do so safely in front of reliable witnesses
president kurt waldheim, himself accused of war crimes, apologized on austria's behalf thursday for atrocities austrian nazis committed after adolf hitler made his native land part of germany 50 years ago
we must not forget that many of the worst nazi hangmen were austrians,'' he said in a tv speech. ``there were austrians who were victims and others who were perpetrators. as head of state of the republic of austria, i wish to apologize for nazi crimes committed by austrians.''
about 15,000 viennese gathered for a rally outside city hall on the first of four solemn days marking the ``anschluss'' of march 11, 1938, when german troops marched into austria and were greeteed by cheering crowds
among the speakers were survivors of concentration camps and paul grosz, who leads vienna's community of 6,000 jews
austria's jews ``cannot forget'' that 65,000 were killed by the nazis and many more thousands had to flee, grosz said. ``we should never let that stain of shame on the history of this city be forgotten,'' he declared
security was tight because of a bomb scare early thursday. police removed cars parked nearby two hours before the rally began. city officials prepared thousands of black ribbons bearing the words ``50 years, march 1938, never again.''
an exhibit called ``vienna 1938'' has been mounted at city hall. there are similar displays about the nazi era at linz, where hitler spent his youth; salzburg, innsbruck and graz, where the nazi swastika was raised over the city hall even before german troops arrived
dozens of events are planned during the four days
waldheim canceled a speech he was to have made at the official government ceremony friday _ some prominent austrians had threatened to stay away otherwise _ and substituted the televised address thursday in which he spoke of ``the avalanche of suffering'' after annexation
he did not mention his own service in hitler's army or a report last month on his conduct as a lieutenant in the balkans from 1942 to 1945
an international panel of historians, appointed by the government at waldheim's request, said he was in ``close proximity'' to war crimes, knew of them and did not try to stop them. the historians said they found no proof that he committed war crimes, but left the question of guilt open
in his 12-minute speech thursday, the former u.n. secretary-general indicated again that he will not leave office until his term expires in 1992. he announced plans for a ``moral renewal'' program to counter disillusionment among young austrians about public service
at the rally, grosz told the young: ``you are not the prisoners of an evil past, because if you know it you are free to form the present and the future creatively.''
hundreds of thousands of austrians joined the nazi party after cheering german soldiers who poured across the border march 11-12, 1938, made austria part of the third reich
huge crowds welcomed hitler when he entered his homeland in triumph. by then thousands of jews, intellectuals, socialists and austrian nationalists had been jailed in a roundup overseen by ss chief heinrich himmler
the nazis said 99 percent of austria's voters approved the annexation in a nationwide referendum in april 1938
austrians as both victims and perpetrators of nazism was a theme running through all pronouncements of major public figures as the anniversary observance began
chancellor franz vranitzky said in an interview with western news agencies that austrians should learn from the past rather than focusing on waldheim
in a survey conducted for a television documentary, 47 percent of 150 austrians polled late last year said annexation brought both good and bad results. only 15 percent of those polled said it was entirely bad
after 1918, when austria lost its vast empire, politicians of all parties had argued for union with germany as a way to rescue the economy and preserve the nation's german culture. the enthusiasm of many wanted when hitler gained control of germany in 1933
vranitzky said an important lesson of the 1930s was that divisions between political parties never should be so deep again
after world war ii, the past was suppressed the official view came to be that austria was hitler's first victim. the controversy over waldheim's wartime past has prompted a much more thorough investigation of the past
mayor helmut zilk, unveiling a plaque to vienna politicians who died in concentration camps, said thursday some austrian ``victims very quickly searched for victims of their own'' after 1938
we must openly admit this disgraceful fact and we should not try to minimize it or play it down by a comparison with other countries,'' he said
republican union members, against the wishes of their leaders, appear to be embracing the presidential candidacy of kansas sen. bob dole despite his poor record on labor issues
democrats far outnumber republicans in organized labor. and democratic union members, like democrats in general, have yet to unite behind any of their party's candidates
but dole, despite having what has been called one of the 20 worst voting records in the senate on labor issues, is the clear favorite of union members who say they are republicans _ about about one-fourth of the 19 million union members in the nation
dole, for example, garnered 53 percent of the republican union vote in tuesday's 12 southern primaries, according to exit polls
but with only 1 percent of the republican vote in the southern primaries coming from union households, their support for dole was no more than a drop in the bucket as vice president george bush swept the region
bush received 28 percent of the republican union vote in the super tuesday primaries, followed by former television evangelist pat robertson with 22 percent and rep. jack kemp of new york with 6 percent
labor political strategists see primarily two phenomena at work in the strong support for dole and in bush's weak showing among their republican members
dole is perceived incorrectly as less elitist, more moderate and more of a regular guy,'' said jerry clark, political director of the 1 million-member american federation of state, county and municipal employees
except on a few things like food stamps that affect agriculture, his voting record on our issues is terrible,'' clark said
the other factor is bush's identification with president reagan, who despite the afl-cio's vehement opposition, received about 45 percent of union members' votes in the 1984 general election
rex hardesty, a spokesman for the federation, contended dole's strong showing this year represents an anti-reagan vote
the drumbeat of union publications that reaganomics and reagan's conservative views should hold no appeal to trade unionists is getting through,'' he said
reagan had support from just two unions in 1980 _ the teamsters and the professional air traffic controllers organization. within a year of his election, he fired 11,000 patco members for going on strike and destroyed their union
the teamsters endorsed reagan again in 1984, but with much less enthusiasm than in 1980. later, the administration indicted their president, jackie presser, on charges of embezzlement and launched a legal effort to seize control of the union through a government trusteeship, contending that it is dominated by racketeers
in reaction to the takeover attempt, the teamsters sought refuge in the afl-cio, rejoining the federation after a 30-year absence and promising to not disrupt its political goal of putting a democrat in the white house
although they are now unlikely to make a democratic endorsement before the party's convention next july, labor leaders have agreed to unite behind whoever is the party's nominee
joan baggett, political director for the bricklayers union and a democratic party activist, said labor leaders clearly prefer to run against bush, believing fewer of their members will cross over to support him than did reagan
bush is now clearly linked with reagan, and our members have come to realize that reagan has not been particularly good for their interests,'' ms. baggett said
we don't want to run against dole,'' she added. ``he has a long voting record against our members' interests, but they don't know that. it's partly because, that with our lower political profile this year, we haven't told them.''
not everyone agrees
dole drew fewer negative responses than any other candidate in either party in a poll of members of the united food and commercial workers union
if our members have a preference as far as republicans are concerned, they would much rather have dole,'' said allen zack, a ufcw spokesman. ``he's developed a reputation as being at least a person you can deal with.''
