amnesty international officials accused gov. bob martinez on thursday of trying to rush the execution of convicted killer willie jasper darden, florida's most-often condemned man who is under his seventh death warrant
officials of amnesty international and other groups planned to go to the state capitol on friday to ask martinez to meet with darden's attorneys and listen to new evidence that they say could clear the inmate of the murder of a lakeland furniture store owner in a $15 robbery
supporters say darden, who is black, was the victim of racial prejudice in his trial
darden's is the most-litigated case involving a death row inmate, with nearly 100 judges involved in decisions. it has been before the u.s. supreme court four times
the latest time before the supreme court was monday, when the court turned down his claim that he received an unfair trial
the next day, the governor signed a seventh death warrant for darden and set his execution for march 15. that gave the inmate's attorneys less than a week to prepare his case. usually, at least 30 days are allowed
i think the governor is looking for some kind of ritualistic sacrifice that he can go through to prove he's tough on crime,'' said magdaleno rose-avila, national director of amnesty international's campaign to abolish the death penalty. he noted that the governor's popularity rating has been low in recent polls
the governor's spokesman said politics had nothing to do it, since martinez always has strongly supported the death penalty
the issues have been debated and resolved by the courts. there was no reason not to sign the warrant,'' said press secretary jon peck
peck said martinez had instituted a new policy recently to schedule executions on subsequent warrants in 20 days, rather than 30 days, which he said would have put the execution near the good friday and easter holidays
it seemed like kind of an inappropriate time,'' peck said
joe spicola, the governor's general counsel, said darden had exhausted all possible appeals. ``he is not going to abuse the process any further,'' he said
attorney mark olive said he did not know when he would be able to file a last-ditch appeal on darden's behalf
amnesty international planned to organize supporters in florida and european countries to call or cable the governor's office friday to protest the execution
i think there will be public outrage like they've never seen if they execute willie darden,'' rose-avila said
no other florida inmate has survived as many death warrants, few have been as celebrated and only one other inmate has been on florida's death row longer
when martinez signed darden's sixth death warrant earlier this year, soviet dissident andrei sakharov, american actress margot kidder and british rock star peter gabriel urged clemency. sakharov won the 1975 nobel peace prize for his defense of human rights in the soviet union
darden, 54, has been on death row since jan. 29, 1974. a prolific writer, he has been called the ``poet of death row.''
darden's supporters cite sworn statements from a minister and another lakeland resident saying he could not have been at the furniture store when owner james turman was killed
the rev. sam sparks said turman's wife had told him that all blacks looked alike to her and that her identification of darden was unimportant because lawyers had told her darden committed the crime. helen baum, formerly helen turman, recently denied having made that statement to sparks and reaffirmed her identification of darden
christine f. bass, a lakeland secretary, said darden's car had broken down near her home and he waited for a tow truck from 4 p.m. to 5:35 p.m. on sept. 8, 1973. her house was eight miles from the furniture store. prosecutors say the crime occurred about 6 p.m
