nasa officials warned congress on thursday that the space station program would be destroyed if money is diverted to build an unmanned scientific and manufacturing facility in space
at the same time, the space station budget came under attack elsewhere in the capitol, when rep. edward p. boland, d-mass., pressed for more money for housing programs next year and said if that money is not allocated, then congress will ``kiss goodbye to the space station.''
boland, whose house appropriations subcommittee handles funding for housing programs as well as independent agencies including the national aeronautics and space administration, said his panel would take money for housing from the budgets for nasa and the national science foundation unless congress changes the overall budget priorities
boland said ``it would take $1.5 billion to restore'' the cuts in housing funds to the level needed. unless congress finds another source for those funds, he said, ``you can kiss goodbye to the space station,'' new rocket boosters and other improvements in the space program
in another part of the capitol, andrew stofan, the retiring head of the space station program in the national aeronautics and space administration, said he would strenuously oppose any attempt to take money from the space station budget to pay for a commerically developed ``industrial space facility.''
nasa, which is under congressional and white house pressure to make use of an unmanned scientific and manufacturing facility, recently said it would seek to lease an orbiting laboratory for five years at $140 million a year. some congressmen want that money to come out of space station funds
i see no use for it (the isf) as far as developing the space station is concerned,'' said stofan, who is retiring after 30 years with nasa. ``if the $700 million came out of developing the space station, i would definitely say no.''
some nasa officials and members of congress fear that forcing the agency to accept the isf or another facility like it is a move by station opponents to kill the project altogether
stofan testified at a hearing of the house space science subcommittee, which is considering the administration's request for $1 billion in the fiscal year that beings in october to start construction of the space station
if we get less than the $1 billion we ask for ... we will have a program, but not on the schedule we have today,'' stofan said. he said any skips in the schedule waste far more money than they save
after budget cutters got through, nasa's 1988 request for $767 million for the space station was cut to $425 million
that $350 million less will cost us $1.4 billion'' by the time the station is completed,'' stofan said. and, he said, it will delay completion of the station by one year
he said any cut in the nasa budget will have disastrous results just as the agency is trying to spring forward again from the calamities that began with the explosion of the space shuttle challenger in 1986. nasa has requested $11.5 billion in 1989, an increase of $2.5 billion over 1988
rep. jack buechner, r-mo., who is a member of the house budget committee as well as the space science subcommittee, said he thought nasa will get only a $1 billion increase
as we are standing on the springboard ready to dive in the water, they are draining the pool,'' he said
the schedule, stofan said, calls for the first elements of the station to be launched in the first three months of 1995, it will be ready for temporary visits by astronauts a year later and will be completed in the first three months of 1998
again and again, stofan was asked by committee members about the industrial space facility
he said the private houston firm that is developing the facility _ which would be carried into orbit by the space shuttle _ tried to find commercial customers for it but couldn't. under the nasa proposal, the government would lease back 70 percent of the space
there is no advantage to building the isf before the space station is ready, stofan said. he said it should be built only if there is a commercial demand for it
thomas moser, director of the nasa's space station program office, said the isf would have only double the usefulness of carrying a spacelab in the shuttle's cargo bay. he said a permanently manned space station would be 50 times as useful as the isf
one of seven secret undergraduate societies at yale university has decided to admit women in 1989, according to published reports
the move by the scroll and key will leave two secret clubs off-limits to women, including skull and bones, whose alumni roster includes vice president george bush and conservative columnist william f. buckley jr
a group called wolf's head also does not admit women
among scroll and key's alumni is a. bartlett giamatti, the president of major-league baseball's national league and former president of yale, the new haven register reported thursday. the decision to admit women was reported by the new york times and the register
the secret societies are exclusive social clubs that select children of former members and other selected students for membership in their senior year. the clubs meet in privately owned buildings on or near campus and have individual initiation rites and rituals
the societies have come under criticism; similar clubs at harvard and princeton have been the targets of lawsuits
it creates a whole system of shooting people straight to the top,'' said byrony romer, a sophomore and co-coordinator of the yale women's center. ``it is such a strong power base.''
scroll and key, which was founded in 1842, is the second-oldest of the yale secret societies
a $150,000 payment to a friend of attorney general edwin meese iii for work on an iraqi pipeline project ended up in a stock-trading account that was apparently used to benefit meese's finances, a published report said thursday
the money, a legal fee intended for attorney e. robert wallach, went through two accounts before being deposited in october 1985 in a pooled account used to trade stocks on behalf of wallach, meese and others, docments obtained by the los angeles times showed
the discovery indicates the fees wallach received for lobbying the white house, with meese's help, on the pipeline project were later used to meese's financial advantage, despite vigorous denials by lawyers for both meese and wallach, the paper said
meese played a key role in securing u.s. government support for the iraqi pipeline when he arranged a white house meeting between pipeline promoters and former national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane and discussed the project with former israeli prime minister shimon peres
meese's lawyers denied meese knew anything about the payment to wallach and said he had no way of knowing of any possible benefits he might have received from the money
and george g. walker, wallach's attorney, told the times, ``we will categorically deny that any monies mr. wallach received ever went into mr. meese's account or were used for his benefit.''
but highly unusual stock-trading practices by w. franklyn chinn, the financial adviser who managed both meese's and wallach's money, suggest that meese did benefit from trades made with the wallach fee, the newspaper said
a swiss financier, bruce rappaport, who was the pipeline's chief promoter said he deposited the $150,000 with chinn, who controlled accounts for wallach and meese at the time. rappaport has said he hired wallach because of his washington contacts, including meese
the payment to chinn was made less than two months after meese helped wallach arrange a meeting between rappaport and mcfarlane on june 24, 1985. mcfarlane assigned a national security council aide to find a way to insure the pipeline so that it could be financed and built. the pipeline was never constructed
chinn was able to pool the $150,000 with other funds and use the money to buy blocks of stock. he then could allocate the most profitable trades to meese's account after learning how the deals came out, according to a recent report by the democratic staff of the senate governmental affairs oversight subcommittee
the senate staff report concludes that nearly a third of the stock purchases allocated by chinn to meese's account, called meese partners, required more money than his account contained at the time they were made
over an 18-month period, chinn was able to turn about $50,000 into about $95,000 through investments for meese _ a return of better than 80 percent
last week in geneva, rappaport said the $150,000 was transferred to chinn's business account at the bank of america in san francisco in august 1985 on instructions from wallach
a government investigator who reviewed the financial records of meese, wallach and chinn said that on aug. 15, 1985, chinn transferred $150,000 from his bank of america business account to the stock trading account he maintained for his business at the san francisco office of bear, stearns &amp; co., a brokerage house
chinn maintained several trading accounts for clients at bear, stearns, including the one for meese
independent counsel james c. mckay is investigating meese, chiefly because of his role in the pipeline affair. key to this aspect of the inquiry is a 1985 memo to meese in which wallach cited a proposal to make payments to the israeli labor party in return for israel's guarantee not to interfere with the pipeline to be built by iraq, its longtime enemy
sen. albert gore jr. said thursday the democratic party is bound for another election-year disaster if front-runner michael dukakis wins its presidential nomination
we have tried a mike dukakis approach time and time and time again and people of this country are just not buying it,'' gore said during a visit to children's memorial hospital
the people want a president who understands it's necessary to fight for working men and women, not a technocratic manager,'' the tennessean said
for those who want another election blowout and see the democratic party losing 49 of 50 states, vote for mike dukakis.''
in two days of campaigning for illinois' march 15 primary, gore has portrayed the massachusetts governor as too liberal for the american electorate
he has mostly ignored the state's favorite sons _ sen. paul simon and jesse jackson _ except to acknowledge they have a home-field advantage
gore is staying at the palmer house, one of the city's grand old hotels, and he began his day a few yards away, shaking the hands of rush-hour commuters as they left the elevated trains that circle downtown
later, he and his wife, tipper, took a private tour of the hospital on the city's north side
in the lobby, the gores met about a dozen young patients and their parents who were surprised by the glare of the television lights
is this a nice place?'' gore asked sam goad, 8
no,'' the boy replied. ``after a while it gets boring.''
in remarks to hospital workers and patients, gore said he would overhaul federal medicaid and medicare programs and other health services, preferably without a tax increase
i'm not proposing additional taxes,'' he said. ``i believe that by changing priorities, eliminating wasteful spending in areas that have been intentionally overlooked by the reagan administration ... it is possible to avoid a tax increase
i have indicated that it can't be completely ruled out.''
gore touted his 12 years in congress, saying he sponsored legislation to protect consumers of infant formulas and to make it easier for children to get organ transplants
he planned to campaign in central illinois on friday before moving on to south carolina and washington. aides said he would return to illinois on sunday
the nation's potential onshore oil discoveries may be about 40 percent less than had been believed, according to new studies by the u.s. geological survey
using a new method of estimation, the survey concluded there is a 50-50 chance that undiscovered crude oil totals 33.4 billion barrels, well below the 54.6 billion estimated in a 1981 study, according to figures provided to scientists at a research meeting in denver last week
ozzie girard, deputy assistant director for engineering geology, said thursday the major part of the change came from disappointing drilling results
but some of the change results from a much lower price prevailing over the last two years, when the latest work was done. the 1981 work assumed a price of $30 a barrel, while the new study assumes a price of $18
the survey believes that the uncertainty of the estimates is just as important as the estimates themselves. it said there is a 90 percent chance that undiscovered oil lies between 19.6 billion barrels and 51.9 billion barrels. that range in 1981 was 41.7 billion barrels to 71 billion barrels
the estimates do not include known reserves, outlined by actual drilling, or probable reserves believed to be findable in or adjacent to a known field if new exploratory drilling were undertaken. they also do not include oil and gas offshore
the minerals management service, which is preparing new offshore estimates, three years ago lowered its estimate of offshore oil from 27 billion barrels to 12.2 billion
participants at the denver meeting also were advised that the survey now estimates that reserves of undiscovered natural gas at 254 trillion cubic feet, down from the previous estimate of 427 trillion
the potential gas committee, an industry group operated by the colorado school of mines, said last year that in 1986 about 400 trillion cubic feet of gas remained to be discovered in the categories corresponding to the service estimates
girard said the service was not counting at least 100 trillion cubic feet of gas in difficult-to-produce tight sands formations that the committee includes. the service also does not count gas in certain shale formations that the committee counts
neither body counts gas locked in coal seams, which the committee termed ``enormous,'' perhaps 400 trillion to 800 trillion cubic feet. some of that gas is being produced commercially in alabama
the committee has gradually lowered its estimates of undiscovered gas, including probable reserves and reserves offshore, from about 900 trillion cubic feet in 1980 and 1982 to 765 trillion cubic feet in 1986
industry reaction to the new estimates was mixed
we are very upset,'' said terry uhl of the american gas association. people will not pay attention to the differing classifications and it amounts to ``misinformation and disinformation'' to say that undiscovered gas is only 254 trillion cubic feet, uhl said
charles dibona, president of the american petroleum institute, said he was unable to say what the numbers mean, and the institute does not even keep track of such estimates. ``you never known until you drill,'' he said
the figures issued in denver were preliminary, girard said, and the survey expects to issue detailed findings asking for public comment sometime next month
thousands of chinese police patrolled the tibetan capital of lhasa on foot and in trucks thursday, and foreigners there said hundreds of people have been arrested in the past six days
the anniversary of the outbreak of a bloody 1959 tibetan uprising against chinese rule passed thursday without major incident, said foreigners in lhasa contacted by telephone from the southwest china city of chengdu
however, more than 100 trucks carrying armed police drove through the main streets of the city of 150,000 in a show of force and several dozen police with machine guns stood in front of the city's holiest temple, the jokhang, said benjamin watson, a tourist from new york city
watson, who speaks tibetan, said an estimated 300 people had been arrested since a clash saturday between police and tibetans demanding independence
the official news agency xinhua also said the situation in lhasa was normal thursday. it said 100 top tibetans gathered in lhasa to denounce the riots and ``those who conduct evil doings under the guise of lama (monks).''
thousands of monks and lay tibetans stoned police and lighted bonfires in the city saturday at the close of a major prayer festival. it was the first major confrontation between tibetans and chinese authorities since a series of protests in september and october left at least 14 people dead
chinese authorities have said two people _ a policeman and a tibetan _ died in saturday's violence. several foreign sources in lhasa initially estimated the deaths at eight. watson said many tibetans maintain 24 people were killed, including 21 tibetans and three police
there was no way to confirm the figures
several foreign travelers said they saw three monks being arrested at drepung monastery on the eastern fringe of the city, bringing the total of drepung monks reported under arrest to about 40
chinese authorities have not allowed foreign reporters to enter lhasa this week
an ethnic tibetan from nepal, who reached chengdu after saturday's clashes, said he believed up to 500 people were arrested
several travelers said they had been allowed to enter the 1,300-year-old jokhang temple on wednesday and thursday and did not see signs of fighting or damage. police stormed the temple saturday and tibetan monks told westerners in lhasa that 16 of their colleagues had been killed there by police
saturday's rioting began at the temple where monks had convened on the final day of the 10-day annual ``moinlam qenmo'' prayer festival. monks shouted pro-independence and pro-dalai lama slogans and threw rocks at police
march 10 is the 29th anniversary of a tibetan revolt against chinese rule that resulted in the flight of the dalai lama, spiritual leader of the tibetans, and 100,000 followers, and a bloody crackdown by the chinese army
on that day in 1959, thousands of tibetans surrounded the norbulinka, the dalai lama's summer palace in lhasa, amid rumors their god-king would be kidnapped by the chinese army
on march 17, the dalai lama fled from the palace and led his followers to exile in india. on march 20, the army attacked the palace, and quashed the rebellion after three days of fighting
in new delhi on thursday, about 200 tibetan refugees clashed with police during a rally marking the anniversary of the abortive uprising. seven tibetans and nine policemen were injured
in a statement from his home in exile in dharamsala, northern india, the dalai lama called on tibetans to ``honor the courage of our brethren in tibet who have taken to the streets to draw attention to their suffering under chinese colonial rule.''
china took control of tibet in 1950 and claims the mountain region has been part of chinese territory for seven centuries. many tibetans disagree, and hold deep antagonisms toward the chinese because of the communist government's past suppression of tibetan language, customs and religion
proposed legislation to ensure the federal government complies with its own environmental laws is unconstitutional, unneeded and could undercut efforts to clean up such facilities as the hanford nuclear reservation, reagan administration officials said thursday
members of a house subcommittee insisted, however, that the department of energy and other agencies have ``thumbed their noses'' at efforts by the environmental protection agency to enforce federal environmental laws at federal facilities
lawmakers also said that epa has been less than forceful in its efforts to force compliance with the laws, while the department of justice has obstructed those efforts
it's a shame that some in the federal government have taken the position they are above the law,'' said rep. thomas luken, d-ohio, chairman of the transportation, tourism and hazardous materials subcommittee of the house energy and commerce committee
the subcommittee's hearing focused on five bills that were introduced late last year amid mounting criticism that the energy department and other federal agencies are dragging their feet over cleaning up federal facilities, including the hanford reservation in central washington
the general accounting office has said there may be over 1,000 hazardous waste sites at hanford, the legacy of 40 years of plutonium production for nuclear weapons. the waste is both highly radioactive and chemically toxic
the scope and the complexity precludes quick solutions,'' joseph salgado, a doe undersecretary, said of the clean-up at hanford and other facilities
salgado said that a compliance agreement with epa and the state of washington covering clean-up of hanford was a top priority of doe
but rep. ron wyden, d-ore., said after the hearing that doe promised almost a year ago to come up with an agreement and a plan for hanford
we still don't have a program, a schedule or anything,'' said wyden, adding that a new justice department interpretation of some environmental laws might even preclude states from getting involved in enforcement efforts
this is just another message that the administration isn't serious about hanford clean-up and is just throwing up more obstacles,'' said wyden
wyden and rep. al swift, d-wash., are among the sponsors of the package of bills that would establish a special environmental counsel to enforce the laws, broaden the authority of the epa and the states in environmental matters at federal facilities and create a special doe department to handle environmental issues
salgado said that the five proposed bills were unneeded and that his department acknowledged their responsibility to comply with federal environmental regulations
the department of energy's critical national security mission must not be jeopardized by an environmental protection and safety program too weak to assure excellence, or by one so rigid and oppressive that these missions cannot be accomplished,'' he said
salgado said doe believes that the present framework of state and federal laws are ``adequate and appropriate.'' campus</head>
gallaudet university students declared thursday that elisabeth ann zinser, the new president of the school for the deaf, is unwelcome on the campus and vowed to keep her out, although a congressman wants her to learn firsthand about the students' concerns
students have been protesting the selection of zinser, who is not deaf and does not know sign language, and their demonstrations have halted virtually all instruction for four days. they have promised to continue their protests until she resigns
they threatened to seize the president's campus house and office, if zinser made her way past students blocking entrances to the school
zinser's whereabouts thursday could not be determined. university officials would not reveal at which hotel she was staying
student leader greg hlibok said students were willing to meet with zinser, but intend to tell her and jane bassett spilman, chairwoman of the school's board of trustees, that ``there will be no dialogue, no compromise. that's what we're promising.''
we want her out, and we intend to tell her she isn't welcome here, that she's not our president,'' hlibok added
rep. david bonior, d-mich., who is a member of gallaudet's board of trustees, said in a statement thursday he suggested to zinser that in the next few days she consult with the faculty, students, staff and alumni ``to experience the passion with which they view the appointment of hearing president.''
the time is long overdue for gallaudet university to have a deaf president,'' bonior said. ``the university has for generations been an international mecca for excellence and opportunity in deaf education
the question before us is _ how long will it be able to sustain this important role without a deaf president?
i hope dr. zinser and the board of trustees will be sensitive to this urgent need as they begin to try to heal the wounds and move forward to enhance the fine traditions of this institution.''
earlier, in an interview with the washington post, bonior said he told zinser that federal aid for the school may be jeopardized if she refuses to leave the post she was named to sunday night
about 75 percent of the school's $76 million operating budget comes from federal funds. the rest comes from tuition and grants
zinser, who left an administrative position at the university of north carolina at greensboro to take the gallaudet job, said wednesday she was assuming her post immediately instead of waiting until the original july starting date
she also lamented that campus protests have disrupted classes, and said she would take unspecified steps to restore order if the protests, which have been peaceful so far, took a violent turn
besides calling for zinser's ouster, the students want spilman's resignation, and a deaf majority on the 20-member trustees board, which now has four deaf members
as zinser attempted to start her job, support for the protesters grew
late wednesday, democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson issued a statement supporting the students, and called on gallaudet's board of trustees to ``resolve this dispute equitably
the problem is not that the students do not hear. the problem is that the hearing world does not listen,'' jackson said
sen. paul simon, d-ill., another democratic presidential hopeful, on thursday called for zinser's resignation
simon, a longtime member of the senate labor and human resources subcommittee on the handicapped, which has jurisdiction over funding for gallaudet, said zinser's appointment was a ``slap in the face to the entire purpose of the university.''
vince dollard, a spokesman for the national technical institute for the deaf, in rochester, n.y., said two buses and several cars, carrying at least 100 students from the school, were to leave at midnight for washington to join the gallaudet protest
a rally was being held on the rochester campus in support of gallaudet thursday afternoon
in addition, some east coast leaders of the national association of the deaf, a 20,000-member deaf rights group based in silver spring, md., will gather in washington on friday, spokesman fred weiner said
and activist abbie hoffman, who lectures to universities on student protests, said, ``what's happening at gallaudet is obviously right there in the front,'' he said, ``and they're going to win their battle.''
he said he has urged members of three electronic bulletin-board networks, with a total of 16,000 members, to support the students' efforts by tying up gallaudet's switchboards with calls of support for the students
a long and often acrimonious battle between north carolina and tennessee over discharges from a champion international paper mill ended with approval of a compromise, but environmentalists said their fight may not be over
the mill in canton, n.c., produces raw paper stock for milk and juice cartons and envelopes and discharges wastes into the pigeon river. residents downstream in tennessee had complained for years that the wastes stained the pigeon dark brown, killing game fish and reducing the potential for recreational revenues
tennessee officials agreed wednesday to grant champion a variance on its water quality standards. the compromise will allow the mill to continue operating by forcing it to cut its discharges significantly
this has been hanging over our heads for about three years,'' oliver blackwell, manager of the mill
we still have a lot of work to do,'' he said, noting that it could take months before a revised wastewater discharge permit can be issued by the epa. ``this is a big step but we recognize we don't have the permit yet.''
environmentalists pledged to keep an eye on the plant. nelson ross, one of the founders of the dead pigeon river council in tennessee, called the agreement only an intermediate step toward cleaning up the river
we're going to construct picnic areas, ramps for whitewater enthusiasts,'' said ross. ``we're going to develop some parks along the shores of the pigeon river and heaven help champion if they don't follow through and clean up the river like they've pledged to do.''
in accepting this revised permit, champion has agreed to operate under the most stringent environmental limits of any mill in north america and possibly the world,'' said blackwell. ``it's going to be difficult but i'm encouraged.''
the canton plant employs about 2,300 people, with an annual payroll of about $73 million. an additional 8,000 jobs depend on champion's purchases and contracts
the compromise drew praise from north carolina gov. jim martin and tennessee gov. ned mcwherter, who have been directly involved in the negotiations
this is the first agreement reached to clean up the pigeon river in the 80 years since the paper mill began operations,'' said mcwherter. ``it is a significant breakthrough in improving the river's quality and allowing us to develop the area's economic potential.''
the two states weren't so complimentary in recent years
in 1983, tennessee sued champion and the north carolina environmental management commission, contending the discharge made the river unsuitable for fishing, swimming, boating or drinking
when north carolina granted champion a new permit in 1985 to dump wastewater into the pigeon, which begins south of canton and flows into cocke county, tenn., it placed no limit on the color of the discharge. at tennessee's urging, the environmental protection agency canceled the permit and took juristiction
the epa's first proposed permit said the river could be no darker than 50 color units _ about the color of ginger ale _ when it reached the tennessee border about 60 miles north of the paper mill
enviromentalists have said the color level in the river in cocke county ranged from 600 to 800 units
the proposed five-year permit, which must be approved by both states, calls for a reduction in the color discharged from the mill by 50 percent, with additional reductions when river levels are low
the compromise calls for tennessee to grant champion a variance from the 50-unit standard. the revised permit allows about twice that
champion already has applied for a variance from north carolina, which must be approved before the wastewater permit is granted by the epa
blackwell said the modernization of the plant and environmental control equipment to comply with the new standards within the required three-year time frame would cost the company about $100 million. violations</head>
the u.n. human rights commission said thursday that israel had violated human rights in southern lebanon and expressed concern about similar allegations in iran and afghanistan
the resolution ``strongly condemns israel's persistence in violating human rights manifested in acts of aggression, bombardments of civilian populations, detentions and other arbitrary practices.''
the vote was 26-1, with 15 abstentions. the united states was the lone dissenter
the resolution expresses grave concern at ``the continuation of the acts of aggression and the arbitrary practices of the israeli occupation forces in southern lebanon which constitute a flagrant violation'' of international law
it calls upon israel to stop such actions and urges israel's allies to pressure the government to end ``its aggressive and expansionist policy in southern lebanon.''
the commission also adopted a resolution expressing ``deep concern about the numerous and detailed allegations of grave human rights violations'' in iran. the vote was 20-4, with 15 abstentions
the resolution referred to a report by the commission's special investigator, salvadoran jurist reynaldo galindo pohl, which cites allegations of torture, arbitrary arrests, unfair trials and religious persecution in iran
it expresses ``deep concern'' at allegations that torture and maltreatment ``are common in iranian prisons during interrogation and before and after the final verdict.''
the resolution urges iran to answer galindo's requests for information and to allow him to visit the country, which it has refused to do so far
the vote on the afghanistan resolution was 29-7 with six abstentions. the soviet union, byelorussia, east germany, bulgaria, ethiopia, nicaragua and india voted against the measure
soviet chief delegate viladimir lomeiko said it was unbalanced and ``permeated with the spirit of confrontation'' at a time significant progress was made in u.n.-mediated efforts to secure peace in afghanistan
vandals protesting alleged elitism at brown university damaged 10 oil portraits of early school supporters
it appears to be a protest against the white elitist male orientation of the founders of the university,'' eric broudy, spokesman for the school, said wednesday
the vandals spray-painted the message ``elite? who us?'' across the paintings in the manning chapel, broudy said
a group calling itself ``the coalition for creative subversion'' claimed responsibility and called on the school to ``diversify itself,'' broudy said
the vandalism occurred feb. 17, one day before a seminar on class and elitism was held in the room, said eric widmer, the dean of student life
widmer said it will cost more than $15,000 to restore the portraits, which are more than a century old. ``i don't know that a value could be placed on the paintings, but they're certainly part of the history of brown,'' he said
the group's letter, sent to the campus newspaper and distributed around campus, contended that incidents from brown's history show that the school is racist, sexist and biased against certain religions
another way brown perpetuates these discourses is by choosing to hang paintings of wealthy white men on its walls,'' the statement said
former nebraska gov. bob kerrey officially entered the race for the u.s. senate on thursday, while maverick mayor bernard sanders launched his campaign for vermont's sole congressional seat
i would like to be your next senator,'' kerrey, a 44-year-old democrat, told 300 supporters in omaha before starting a two-day swing through the state
no other democrat has declared for the nomination. sen. david karnes, appointed to fill the term of the late edward zorinsky, and rep. haul daub are seeking the gop nomination
i can promise you i will never betray you. and i will never dishonor the respect i have for you,'' said kerrey
despite high popularity ratings, kerrey declined to run for re-election as governor in 1986 because he said it was ``time to move on.''
kerrey ended months of speculation last november when he said he would run for the senate. since then he has been criss-crossing the state, saying his main issues are trade policy, the federal budget, education and agriculture
a great and glorious future will not happen unless we do the unglamorous work today,'' he said thursday
sanders, four-term mayor of burlington, vermont's largest city, and a longtime critic of the concentration of wealth in america, said he would fight for national health care, disarmament, tough environmental laws, affordable day care and higher taxes on the wealthy and corporations
although sanders, 46, has long claimed socialist leanings, he said he would run as an independent candidate
four democrats and one republican have declared their intentions to run for the seat being vacated by republican james jeffords, who in turn is seeking to fill the seat of retiring republican sen. robert stafford
