if a hotshot student can graduate law school and start work at $70,000 a year for a big-name law firm, surely we can pay child care workers more than $12,000 a year and teachers more than $16,000 a year, and nursing home workers more than the minimum wage,'' sanders said in montpelier, the state's capital
the state's highest court on thursday rejected claims of an unfair trial and left standing the convictions of four men in the 1983 gang rape of a woman on a tavern pool table
in a pair of unanimous rulings, the massachusetts supreme court rejected defense objections to the prosecutor's handling of evidence, to the trial judge's decision to keep television cameras turned away from the victim and to other matters
bristol county district attorney ronald pina welcomed the ruling, saying he hoped it would end the lingering controversy over the case and encourage women everywhere to prosecute rapes
defense attorney david h. waxler said he was reviewing the opinion for possible grounds for further appeal
the unfortunate aspect of this sort of decision is that future prosecutors rest more comfortbaly in the knowledge that they need not turn over exculpatory evidence, and that's unfortunate,'' he said. ``it's the old saying: tough cases make bad law.''
the dramatic account of the rape given by the victim, a young mother, and the lengthy televised trial in superior court in 1984 drew unwanted national attention to the working-class neighborhoods of new bedford and sparked an intense debate over rape. it also brought agony to the portuguese-american community in the fishing city 60 miles south of boston
six young men of portugese descent were charged in the case; four were convicted of aggravated rape
daniel silvia was sentenced to nine to 12 years; joseph vieira, six to eight years; and john cordeiro and victor raposo, nine to 12 years each
the victim, also of portuguese ancestry, left new bedford and was killed in a single-car crash outside miami in 1986 at age 25
according to court records, the woman entered big dan's tavern on march 6, 1983, to buy cigarettes. she ordered a drink and spoke briefly with another woman, and they watched a game of pool. when she declined an offer of a ride from cordeiro and raposo, the court said, she was knocked down, dragged to thje pool table and raped, the judges said
eventually, clothed only in a shirt and one shoe, the victim escaped and ran into the street, where she flagged down a passing truck.''
on appeal, vieira and silvia claimed the prosecutor failed to make a timely disclosure of certain evidence that might have helped the defense, depriving them of their rights to due process. they also argued that the district attorney suppressed until after trial a witness's recorded account of the victim's condition and statements shortly after the rape
and they argued that young prejudiced the defense theory that the victim consented to the sex. they also complained about the exclusion of an allegedly false prior complaint of rape by the woman
in their separate appeal, cordeiro and raposo argued that young's order keeping courtroom cameras away from the woman prejudiced their right to a fair trial. they also claimed that young erred in refusing to instruct the jury on consensual rape
the high court dismissed each claim
an angolan official said thursday his government would never agree to giving rebel leader jonas savimbi a role in running the country if an end to the civil war is successfully negotiated
manuel pedro pacavira, angola's new ambassador to the united nations, indicated that savimbi would have to leave before there could be any reconciliation between officials of his marxist government and unita, savimbi's organization
some elements of unita could deserve different treatment ... but not savimbi,'' pacavira told reporters at a luncheon. ``he is a crook, incoherent ... doesn't care about consequences.''
savimbi's group _ the national union for the total independence of angola, or unita _ receives financial aid from the united states and south africa
before peace is achieved, pacavira said, south africa must cease its help to unita and there must be an ``understanding'' that the united states will end its assistance
a major stumbling block to ending the 12-year civil war is the presence of 40,000 cuban troops in angola. state department officials say the angolans have agreed in principle to withdrawal of the troops
pacavira said angola is prepared to remove the troops ``within limits'' once outside aid to unita stops and south africa grants independence to namibia under a united nations plan
the angolans have not provided a timetable for any troop withdrawal, but pacavira said he expects another ``ministerial meeting'' between officials of luanda and washington in march or april
assistant secretary of state chester crocker, who has tried for seven years to negotiate a solution in angola, held discussions with angolans in january. the state department said it is awaiting new proposals from angola
pacavira said the united states can continue to play a role as mediator, but angola is also ready to hold discussions with officials of white-ruled south africa. the cubans would have to be included in the talks, he said
pacavira dismissed a statement made by south african defense minister magnus malan who suggested that pretoria is willing to deal directly with the soviet union on angola
his statement has nothing concrete and constructive,'' pacavira said. ``it is just an exercise to distract public opinion.''
