george bush said thursday he is ``tired of being embarrassed'' by scandals surrounding public officials and unethical behavior by high government officials. he pledged he would create a special white house ethics panel if elected president
bush, arriving in illinois on the heels of his stunning super tuesday victory, also promised he would set up a budget deficit summit with congressional leaders on ``day one'' of his administration _ an echo of a stand taken by gop presidential rival bob dole
bush told the governor's club luncheon at the chicago hilton said that in such a summit scenario, ``i am personally going to head the executive branch negotiating effort.''
we're going to meet. we're going to talk. maybe, even, we'll shout, but we're going to solve this problem,'' he said
bush has said on several occasions that he would seek to bring people into government ``who want to serve, not to profit'' but he has steadfastly refused to criticize any reagan administration officials, including attorney general edwin meese, who is under investigation by several grand juries
former top white house aides michael k. deaver and lyn nofziger have been convicted in court cases involving their lobbying activities after leaving the administration
at a news conference shortly after his speech, bush was asked whether his call for a special white house panel on ethics was a criticism of the way things had been done during the reagan administration
no, because i was asked this in an interview ... and i said i don't know of anybody who has a higher standard of personal ethics than the president, always above any possible conflict of interest,'' he replied. ``certainly, nobody should imply criticism. i'm just saying what my priorities would be in the future.''
asked to name public officials who had caused him embarrassment, bush said, ``i'm not going to be specific in terms of names. i'm going to be generic.''
bush said, ``i'm just saying how i would do it.''
he said in his speech, ``i am personally disturbed at the breaches of ethics i have seen in the past few years in government. once elected, i'd appoint an ethics panel to work right there in the white house. i'd have them draft a new and specific code of ethics.''
when a congressman goes bad or someone in the executive branch violates the public trust, it hurts,'' he said. ``i'm tired of being embarrassed. i'm tired of seeing our children seeing things that should embarrass us all. people at all levels of government should come to serve, not to profit.''
clearly, i have big plans,'' he told the audience of republican boosters, who sat silently through the speech
at the outset of his talk, bush told his audience ``there's no complacency'' in his campaign in the wake of his near sweep of the super tuesday competition
bush's announcement that he would personally oversee deficit-reduction negotiations also seemed an implied criticism of reagan
in the aftermath of the wall street crash last oct. 19, reagan set up a negotiating team to work out a deficit-reduction compromise with capitol hill leaders
but with the exception of some meetings in the white house with congressional figures, reagan left the actual bargaining to chief of staff howard baker, treasury secretary james baker and budget director james miller
those negotiations produced a two-year, $76 billion budget reduction plan, which included $23 billion in new taxes
bush, from the start of the campaign, has said that he would not try to win the gop nomination by ``jumping away'' from reagan or by criticizing the president
i'm not going to try to move up the ladder by knocking someone else down,'' the vice president has said
and in thursday's speech, there was plenty of praise for the president
i am proud to have been part of a m ajor change in public policy,'' he said. ``they call it the reagan revolution because it was revolutionary. ... you know the results. greatest peacetime economic growth in our history, strengthened defense, the soviets come to the bargaining table
but it's not a complete triumph. it's only a beginning,'' he said
police arrested a 17-year-old who allegedly donned a sheriff-style uniform and posed as a lawman in order to have sex with a professional escort
the youth was arrested on charges of impersonating a public officer and released on $3,000 bond, authorities said thursday
austin vice investigator earl hall said the youth entered a motel feb. 24 wearing a brown uniform, a heavy police-type jacket and a gun belt with .38-caliber snub-nose pistol
the youth identified himself as a member of the sheriff's department of williamson county, working on a prostitution case, hall said. the man called an austin escort service and then asked for a room in which to make an arrest, he said
when the escort arrived at the room, the youth told her she was under arrest for prostitution but implied he would let her go if she had sex with him, hall said. they left the motel after the manager came to the room and asked the youth to pay for it, he said
the youth was then refused rooms at two other motels, hall said
at a fourth motel, the youth said he was an austin police officer, paid for a room and had sexual intercourse with the escort, hall said. he then released her, saying no charges would be filed, he said
the woman then got her boyfriend, who confronted the impersonator at a gas station and took his gun belt and briefcase in an effort to learn his identity, hall said
the youth reported a robbery to police. they arrested the woman and her boyfriend that day but released them
the youth was arrested the same day when he allegedly tried to reclaim his property at the police station. he was released pending further investigation, then rearrested wednesday on the impersonation charge
the soviet union has bought an additional 100,000 metric tons of u.s. corn for delivery this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries, the agriculture department said thursday
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 100,000 tons of corn would be about 3.94 million bushels
corn prices recently have been averaging about $1.84 per bushel at the farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around $7.25 million
officials said the latest sale involved 50,000 tons that had been reported by exporters as headed for japan, and 50,000 tons for ``unknown destinations.''
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
with the latest purchases, the soviets now have bought 3.27 million tons of corn, plus more than .9 million tons of wheat; 813,300 tons of soybeans, and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal. hours</head>
president reagan would veto any bill requiring him to tell congress about all covert actions within 48 hours after they start, defense secretary frank c. carlucci said thursday
carlucci, who was national security adviser before being named to the defense post last november, made the statement as a house intelligence subcommittee continued hearings on a bill overhauling the procedure for white house cooperation with capitol hill on intelligence matters
administration officials had suggested previously that a presidential veto of such legislation was likely, but carlucci's statement marked the first time a top administration official had flatly promised a veto
the house bill and a similar piece of legislation in the senate were a response to the iran-contra affair, in which u.s. arms were secretly sold to iran and some of the profits diverted to the contra rebels in nicaragua. final action on the senate bill is likely next week when the democratic-controlled chamber returns from a one-week vacation
in the case of the iran-contra affair, reagan withheld notification from congress about the sale of arms to iran for 10 months in 1986. but he has promised to tell congress about all future covert operations
at some point, we have to rely on trust,'' carlucci told the subcommittee. he noted that ``if a future president sets out to deceive a congress, no amount of statutes will stop him.''
carlucci said that either the senate or house bill ``surely will'' be vetoed by reagan
current laws require that congress be notified of all covert operations, except under extraordinary circumstances. in those latter cases, the law only requires ``timely notice'' but it does not define that phrase. the pending bills would spell out that notice must be sent to capitol hill within 48 hours after a covert action starts
reagan believes the bills are an unconstitutional limit on his authority, carlucci said
i can think of no step by the congress which would do more harm to the process of rebuilding an atmosphere of trust and candor between the branches than unilaterally to lay claim to prerogatives which the president firmly believes are vested in the executive by the constitution,'' he said
rep. matt mchugh, d-n.y., chairman of the intelligence subcommittee, supported the bill and noted that ``in the case of the arms sales to iran, the president construed current law as permitting him to withhold notice for more than 10 months after the covert sales had been authorized.''
if he had done so (as the law generally requires),'' mchugh said, ``he would surely have heard some strong objections and might have spared the country a serious foreign policy setback and himself a major political embarrassment.''
but carlucci argued that ``the failures of the iran affair were human and managerial. no statue can prevent these mistakes.''
we will not put the mistrust which caused the iran-contra affair behind us until we trust each other again,'' carlucci said
brent scowcroft, national security adviser to president ford and a member of the tower commission that investigated the iran-contra affair, testified that ``the excessively restrictive language proposed seems a case of throwing out the baby with the bath. it is not possible to eliminate every opportunity for abuse by the executive without at the same time paralyzing the ability to act.''
he said the legislation arises from the belief that congress would have opposed the arms sales and derailed them if it had been notified
but ``there is no evidence to support this assumption,'' scowcroft said. ``indeed, as it was, the president was confronted, by his principal advisors, with views strongly in opposition to the iranian arms sales.'' graf pvs, some conservative</note>
jack kemp ended his republican presidential campaign thursday, saying george bush has won ``the reagan wing of the republican party'' and hinting that he'd welcome the no. 2 spot on the ticket
kemp, whose campaign as the true conservative heir to ronald reagan never caught on with voters, endorsed no candidate. he said of his rivals, ``they're all reagan conservatives.''
the new york congressman bowed out at a capitol hill news conference, flanked by his family and some of the house members who backed his candidacy. he evoked cheers from moist-eyed supporters with a vow that ``no way'' would this be his last campaign for the white house
kemp, 51, said he would not seek re-election to the house seat from buffalo that he has held for 18 years. he did not rule out running for the senate from new york but said he had no plans to do so
he called the notion that he might be asked to be the republican vice presidential candidate a ``very flattering and awesome thought.''
he said he didn't expect it but added, ``would i think about it? the answer to that is yes.''
kemp entered the presidential race in april 1987 after years of preparation to position himself as the candidate of the republican right wing
but his campaign never caught on with republican voters, and he consistently finished behind bush, bob dole and former television evangelist pat robertson in the gop primaries
less than three weeks ago in a debate with his rivals, kemp declared that the nomination of bush or dole would signal the death of the ``reagan revolution'' of conservatism. but in withdrawing, kemp said that bush had won reagan's republican constituency
we were competing for the reagan wing of the republican party, and he won,'' kemp said
it's very clear that george bush ran on the reagan agenda. and i think that the vote for george bush, with all due respect, today is a vote'' for ronald reagan, kemp said
it's simply to recognize that i was running against ronald reagan. and that's a surprise because i am his strongest proponent, at least in terms of the ideals that were launched back in 1980.''
kemp spoke by telephone with bush and the other gop candidates wednesday night. bush chief of staff craig fuller, with the vice president, said bush's ``respect for the congressman has grown over the course of the campaign.''
kemp never was able to coalesce around his candidacy even the conservative movement within the republican party that he claimed to lead
some conservative leaders said that while they would like to see kemp on the ticket, they doubted he had displayed enough political drawing power to be asked to join it
robertson said, ``with jack kemp's withdrawal today, i am more and more being urged by conservatives to stay in the race as a rallying point for conservatives and conservative principles.''
portions of the 3 or 4 percent he's been getting should come over to me,'' robertson said
kemp's best showing in the primaries was 13 percent of the vote in new hampshire. on tuesday in 17 gop contests, the best he scored was a dismal 7 percent in massachusetts
kemp won just four delegates from 712 at stake in super tuesday contests. kemp had 35 committed delegates _ but most of those were handed to him by bush in a michigan compromise designed to prevent robertson from claiming a victory
daniel l. casey, executive director of the american conservative union, said that with kemp gone from the race, many conservative republicans could be expected to focus their efforts on trying to shape the republican party platform. beyond that, he said, they may push for a conservative running mate and turn attention to congressional and other local races
it remains to be seen whether or not the leadership in washington of the conservative movement will establish a working relationship with the bush campaign,'' said casey
campaign spokesman john buckley said kemp spent $15 million on his effort, and departs with debts of less than $100,000
we balanced our budget,'' kemp said
sen. paul simon is counting on a strong showing in his home state of illinois next tuesday to restore his eligibility for federal matching funds before a cutoff is triggered, a campaign spokesman said thursday
simon became ineligible for matching funds by winning less than 10 percent of the vote in two successive primaries, but election law stays the cutoff for 30 days
the matching funds can continue to flow during the 30 days, and eligibility is restored when a candidate receives at least 20 percent of the vote in another state primary
we are not in jeopardy,'' said simon's press secretary terry michael. ``there is zero chance that we won't get 20 percent next tuesday.'' in fact, he said, simon is counting on cleaning up in all but three of the state's 22 congressional districts
michael conceded those three chicago districts to the state's other native son, jesse jackson, who expects he will win much more than that
federal election commission spokesman fred eiland said that after simon fell below the 10 percent threshhold in south dakota and vermont, he would have had to get 20 percent in one of the super tuesday states this week
since he did not campaign for super tuesday and failed to do achieive the threshhold, his ineligibility for matching funds will be effective march 31 unless he does well in illinois, eiland said
rep. jack kemp, r-new york, also has fallen below the threshhold but since he dropped out of the race on thursday, he will be allowed to receive matching funds to pay off any leftover debts. however, he could not use those funds to resume campaigning
the same is true of former colorado sen. gary hart, if he drops out of the race friday as aides have said he would do
the matching funds are provided from the taxypayer-supported fund. every donation of $250 or less that a candidate raises is matched by the public fund. to qualify, a candidate must raise at least $100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less
michael said simon has whittled down his loan debt, which stood at more than $500,000 at the beginning of february, to about $45,000, and has some $100,000 in cash on hand
the campaign raised $932,000 during february through events and direct mail and got $364,000 in matching funds
simon has received a total $2.2 million in matching funds so far
one year has passed since four teen-agers made a suicide pact and died together in a locked garage here, but local officials say the worst thing they could do is commemorate the deaths
all psychiatrists tell us don't memorialize it in any way,'' said school superintendent john habeeb. ``it could only cause trauma. it will be business as usual on friday.''
last march 11, thomas olton, 19, thomas rizzo, 18, and sisters cheryl and lisa burress, ages 17 and 16, were found dead of carbon monoxide poisoning in olton's idling car
reporters descended upon the school and officials worried that other troubled youths seeking glorification might try to imitate the four
our fear was that the blitz could trigger some students that were already unstable,'' habeeb said. ``after all, it's very romantic to get your name in the paper.''
charlotte p. ross, president and executive director of the youth suicide national center in washington, d.c., said studies in the past year tend to discount any ``copycat'' theory of adolescent suicides
there's an enormous amount of suicidal behavior among young people,'' ms. ross said. ``since bergenfield, studies have cast shadows and a lot of doubt that suicide is like the measles. you can't catch it.''
even so, bergenfield has worked hard to avoid any repeat of the tragedy
in the past year, bergenfield high school has given a part-time drug and alcohol counselor full-time status _ authorities found traces of cocaine in the blood of all four of the dead youngsters, and two had been drinking
the school also hired a psychiatrist for grades 7-12, and hired two outreach workers for its community response team. the response team, comprised of mental health professionals, clergy, teachers and police officers, began immediately after the suicides
it's an example of an outstanding response,'' ms. ross said. ``they've worked very hard. we don't know how many suicides came close and were prevented.''
bergenfield's strategy will be part of a manual on adolescent suicide due for release in the spring by the federal centers for disease control and will play a part in guidelines being assembled in california for municipalities there, she said
bergenfield has done such a good job that the federal government denied two grant applications for the community, saying other municipalities needed the money more, habeeb said
he said the school's programs have cost about $80,000, and new jersey has sent a $35,000 state grant for substance abuse programs in town
robert j. gallione jr., the recently elected mayor of this community of 26,000 residents and a job counselor at columbia university, says the money is well spent
the focus of the past year has been on reaching out to youths and identifying teen-agers who feel alienated. special attention is paid to dropouts, since three of the four suicide victims had left school
habeeb said bergenfield's low drop-out rate of 1.5 percent can lead to dropouts being stigmatized
gallione added that a mayor's advisory committee on youth gives teen-agers a chance to suggest ideas that might not naturally occur to adults
one recent suggestion was a town-sponsored battle of teen rock bands. gallione called that a good approach to disaffected youths, who often find a safe haven in music
while school officials work on prevention, others in town want to forget
four 15-year-old sophomore girls, who didn't want to give a reporter their names, said the suicides are not talked about much anymore
the mayor said such an attitude is not a bad thing
there was a lot of negative focus but it's been offest by other things we do in the community,'' gallione said. ``people have to come to see another side of us _ just a traditional community.'' years</head>
an increase in the federal minimum wage from $3.35 to $5.05 an hour was tentatively approved thursday by the house education and labor committee
the original bill before the committee called for an increase of 50 cents in 1989, 40 cents in 1990 and 40 cents in 1991 to $4.65
the committee adopted, on a vote of 18-14, an amendment by rep. carl c. perkins, d-ky., which added a 40-cent increase in the fourth year, on dec. 31, 1991
the full committee was unable to take action on all the pending amendments and will continue debate on the bill next week
the senate has a companion bill, sponsored by edward m. kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the labor and human resources committee, which would raise the minimum wage to $4.65 over a three-year period
the perkins amendment was approved essentially along party lines except that two democrats, reps. austin j. murphy of pennsylvania and timothy j. penny of minnesota, joined the republicans in opposing the proposal
murphy is chairman of the house labor standards subcommittee, which had approved an increase to $4.65. he said that legislation was ``crafted so that it will be accepted by the full house and the executive branch. if we accept this (perkins) proposal, it will not be accepted.''
rep. stephen j. solarz, d-n.y., read from a letter written by labor secretary ann mclaughlin, who said senior white house advisers would recommend to president reagan that he veto any legislation increasing the minimum wage
so it doesn't matter what we do, the executive will be against it,'' solarz said
the house committee also voted 20-13 on an amendment by rep. tommy f. robinson, d-ark., to increase the ``tip credit'' for restaurant workers
current law allows employers of workers who regularly receive tips _ such as waiters and waitresses _ to count the tips as earned wages equivalent to 40 percent of the minimum wage. thus, a restaurant owner could pay a worker $2.01 an hour, with the remaining $1.34 - 40 percent of today's $3.35-an-hour minimum wage _ coming from tips
under the robinson amendment, the tip minimum would be raised to 50 percent of the minimum. thus, if the minimum wage were increased to $5.05 an hour, an employer could pay a $2.52 hourly wage, with the other $2.52 coming from tips
the biggest argument of the session came over the amendment by perkins who said his proposal ``does not go far enough, but it is a start.''
it gives the american worker some level of decency,'' perkins said
he said his amendment would still not bring workers up to what is described by the federal government as the ``poverty level,'' a family of three earning approximately $9,500
rep. dick armey, r-tex., who opposes any increase in the minimum wage because he said he would destroy jobs, proposed an amendment to raise the base to $20 an hour
i don't think we ought to be pikers,'' he said. ``it would put minimum wage workers on the par with members of congress.''
rep. augustus f. hawkins, d-calif., the committee chairman, called the proposal ``absurd.'' armey said he thought the entire discussion was absurd because the committee refused to discuss the number of jobs that would be lost because of the minimum wage increase
armey, an economist, said different studies show anywhere from 300,000 to 800,000 job opportunities would be lost because of the increase. hawkins said there was not support for such projections
the former leader of a white supremacist group testified thursday that the founder of the right-wing group the order gave him $75,000 in stolen money in 1984 to fund his organization
glenn miller, 47, former leader of the white patriots party in north carolina, said robert mathews, killed in a shootout with the fbi near seattle in december 1984, gave him the money on a visit in august 1984
he explained that it was stolen from banks and armored cars,'' miller said
miller said mathews told him that his group was ``sitting on $3.5 million. he said that they were working on an inside job that would net them $50 million.''
zillah craig, mathews' girlfriend, testified wednesday that she traveled around the country with mathews and helped him distribute $2 million, part of $3.6 million stolen from an armored car in june 1984 at ukiah, calif
both miller and ms. craig testified in the sedition trial of 14 men. ten defendants are charged with sedition, five are charged with conspiring to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent, and two are charged with interstate transportation of stolen money
miller said robert miles, one of the 14 defendants, once told him that he could receive more money for his organization
miller said mathews told him several leaders of the white supremacist movement had received money, among them defendant louis ray beam. miller said mathews also claimed to have given money to william pierce, head of a reputed white supremacist group called the national alliance
pierce also wrote a book of fiction called ``the turner diaries,'' which government witnesses have testified formed the basis for the order's plan to overthrow the government and establish an all-white nation in the northwest
miller, who was captured at ozark, mo., by the fbi, has pleaded guilty to a firearms charge and sending a threat through the mail
the soviet union said thursday it feels free to keep sending military aid to the kabul government even after it withdraws its troops from afghanistan
it rejected a u.s. demand that foreign military aid to both sides in the afghanistan war cease simultaneously once a peace settlement is reached. the united states aids the afghan rebels
nikolay kozyrev, a senior soviet specialist in asian affairs, said that except for sending new troops to afghanistan, the soviet union was not committed to halt any kind of assistance to kabul. he noted that the two countries had contractual ties now for seven decades
kozyrev, introduced as an ambassador-at-large, came to geneva as head of a small soviet delegation assigned to follow the indirect peace talks between pakistan and afghanistan. u.n. undersecretary general diego cordovez is mediating the talks
kozyrev's appearance at a news conference organized by the soviet mission to the u.n. office in geneva marked the first time a soviet official took a public stand on the negotiations since the talks started almost six years ago
he said the question of a cutoff of soviet aid never was a subject of the u.n.-sponsored peace talks. he termed the u.s. demand for a ``symmetrical cessation'' of military aid, spelled out at a state department briefing last friday, ``an attempt to interfere with the internal affairs of afghanistan and with the bilateral relationship'' between kabul and moscow
kozyrev said the u.s. demand would be tantamount to moscow calling for a cut-off of u.s. military aid to pakistan
a u.s. mission spokesman, chris henze, said there would be no immediate comment from robert peck, the assistant deputy secretary of state who is in geneva to follow the talks. kozyrev said he was in touch with peck
the chief afghan negotiator, foreign minister abdul wakil, said last week draft documents of the settlement provided for u.s. aid to the islamic guerrillas to cease simultaneously with the start of the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 soviet troops
the united states is the main supplier of arms to the guerrillas fighting the marxist kabul government, with shipments reported worth about $700 million last year and including shoulder-fired stinger missiles
kozyrev told reporters that after agreement was reached on all main elements of the projected peace package, negotiations bogged down because of pakistan's insistence on the settlement's being accompanied by formation of a broad-based transitional government in kabul
pakistan argues that only such a government, replacing the soviet-backed one headed by president najib, would be able to oversee implementation of the agreements and ensure a safe return of more than 5 million refugees from pakistan and iran
kozyrev sidestepped a question on whether negotiations could continue after next tuesday's target date set by moscow. soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has said moscow will bring home its troops starting may 15 provided the settlement is signed by march 15
pakistan, which adjoins afghanistan, supports the guerrillas and acts as their spokesman at the geneva talks
cordovez met separately with the two delegations thursday for a total of five hours. he said there would be no formal negotiation session friday, but he would meet privately with the two sides
cordovez said earlier that final agreement was not imminent
also on thursday, the 43-nation u.n. human rights commission adopted by a 29-7 vote a western-sponsored resolution expressing concern at what it said were continued widespread violations of human rights by afghan authorities, despite some improvement. six nations abstained and mozambique was absent
the soviet union intervened militarily in neighboring afghanistan in late 1979 and its troops stayed on to fight anti-marxist guerrillas
