nine years ago, federal health officials set nine goals for reducing fatalities from injuries in the united states by 1990. thursday, officials predicted at least six of those goals will be met
the fatality rates from many types of injuries _ such as car accidents, house fires and drownings _ have dropped since 1979, when the u.s. department of health and human services announced its 1990 goals, the centers for disease control reported thursday
but in some cases, the rates have not fallen as far as the government had hoped, the cdc said. while authorities expect to meet the goals on reducing deaths from car crashes, childhood household accidents, house fires and gun accidents, the goals for reducing deaths from falls and drownings won't be met
achieving the 1990 objectives ... will require the coordinated efforts of federal, state and local agencies, ... academic institutions, professional associations and private entities,'' the atlanta-based cdc said in its weekly report
here, from the cdc report, are the nation's 1990 goals for reducing deaths from injuries, and the progress being made:
_ reducing the nation's annual motor vehicle fatality rate, from 23.6 such deaths per 100,000 americans in 1978 to 18 per 100,000 in 1990: by 1984, the rate had fallen to 19.6, and the goal is projected to be met, in part because of a reduction in alcohol-related fatalities
_ reducing the motor vehicle fatality rate for children under 15, from 9 per 100,000 in 1978 to 5.5: by 1984, the rate had fallen to 6.6, and the goal is projected to be met
_ reducing the death rate from falls from 6.2 per 100,000 in 1978 to 2.0: the rate had fallen only to 5.1 by 1984, and the goal is not expected to be reached. people over 65 continue to have high death rates from falls _ for example, in 1984, 10.2 such deaths per 100,000 people age 65-74, and 147 per 100,000 people over 84
_ reducing the death rate for children under 15 in home injuries from 6 per 100,000 in 1978 to 5: the 1984 rate was 4.9, already meeting the objective
_ reducing the drowning rate from 3.2 per 100,000 in 1978 to 1.5: the rate had fallen only to 2.3 in '84, and the goal is not expected to be met
_ reducing the number of deaths in residential fires from 5,401 in 1978 to 4,500: the objective was reached in 1984, when 4,466 americans died in such fires
_ reducing the number of deaths in firearm accidents from 1,806 in 1978 to 1,700: the goal was met in 1984, when 1,668 such deaths were reported
_ reducing the suicide rate among 15-24-year-olds from 12.1 per 100,000 in 1978 to 11: the rate is going up, not down. it was 12.2 per 100,000 in 1984, up slightly from 1978 and up about 200 percent from 1950. the cdc noted that various suicide prevention approaches have been tried in communities, but the effectiveness is not known
_ reducing the homicide rate among black males aged 15-24 from 70.7 per 100,000 in 1978 to 60: this goal will probably be met, according to cdc researcher dr. richard sattin. the rate had fallen in 1984 to 61.5. this goal was set recognizing the high homicide rate among young black men, sattin said, noting that the national homicide rate in 1984 was 8.4 per 100,000 americans
jesse jackson is the favorite son and front-runner in south carolina's democratic caucuses saturday, leaving the division of the remaining delegates among the other presidential candidates as the only question mark
jackson was born and raised in south carolina, one of two states he won in his 1984 presidential race
jackson, who plans a homecoming campaign trip friday, has the overwhelming support of the state's black voters, who make up more than one-third of the electorate, and got an average of 10 percent of the white vote in other southern states on super tuesday
between a quarter and a half of south carolina democrats traditionally remain uncommitted at the caucus meetings to give themselves more maneuvering room through the nominating process. they usually choose a candidate at the county or state convention
that leaves few delegates for the rest of the field. but in a tight national race in which no candidate appears to be able to capture the majority of delegates, every one helps
this certainly increases the importance of south carolina because the delegate count is so close,'' said kevin gray, state coordinator for jackson
the candidates are relying on grass-roots organizing, telephone banks and direct mail to lure democrats to the caucus; none is buying television advertisements
tennessee sen. albert gore jr., who plans to campaign in the state on friday, has the largest organization in the state and the most endorsements from elected officials, who wield strong influence at the caucuses
gore also has the momentum from his strong showing across the south tuesday, which lessened the perception among some south carolinians that he's not electable
missouri rep. richard gephardt, who traveled across the state wednesday and thursday, has a skeletal organization. but his few endorsements are the biggest _ former govs. dick riley and robert mcnair and all of the south carolina democratic congressmen who have chosen sides
dukakis has an even smaller local organization
all of the competing state campaigns except gore's has conceded that jackson will win the lion's share of the 44 delegates at stake
i don't think there is any doubt that jesse jackson will win,'' said bill prince, gephardt's state coordinator
house speaker robert sheheen, gore's state chairman, said ``there's really no way of knowing'' whether the tennessee senator can upset jackson. ``we're not conceding anything to anybody.''
gore, who is the only candidate with an outside chance of upsetting jackson, is promoting his strong ties to the south and a strong defense, which plays will in the palmetto state
gephardt is hoping to use his trade policy to gain votes in the state, which has seen its largest industry _ textiles _ severely weakened by cheap foreign imports
but most political scientists and campaign officials agree that because the democratic field is so large and so close together and because a large number of delegates probably will remain uncommitted, the results saturday will be inconclusive
take riley's assessment thursday, for example: ``jackson will do very well. gore is well organized. dukakis will get a piece of the vote and gephardt will get his share.''
south carolina's democratic leaders decided against following the crowd on super tuesday, when all of the other southern states held primaries
they decided to nestle in the days of old,'' clemson university political science professor steve wainscott said thursday. hawk.</note>
residents of this sprawling military base and neighboring towns mourned again thursday for victims of an army aviation accident, this time 17 soldiers killed in a helicopter collision
the members of the elite 101st airborne division died tuesday when helicopters on separate night training missions slammed into each other
the crash was the worst in fort campbell history and the worst army aviation accident since 248 fort campbell soldiers died dec. 12, 1985, when a chartered jet bringing them home for christmas from a mideast peacekeeping mission crashed in canada
i think any soldier will tell you that when you fly as many hours as they do and perform the exercises they do, you can expect things to happen,'' said charlie c. gentry, a motel owner in clarksville, tenn., the closest town to fort campbell
even so, he said, ``to me it's kind of like hearing about maybe a real close friend i had in high school, and hadn't seen for a while, getting killed in a car wreck. so even though i didn't know them there's more of a feeling of loss than with other news stories.''
army crash investigators listened to air traffic control tapes and interviewed witnesses in an effort to learn the cause of the accident. spokesmen said specifics would not be released until a full report was made, probably within 90 days, but said some details emerged from talks with air controllers and witnesses
one of the helicopters was leading a formation of three uh-60 black hawks headed east at an altitude of about 250 feet toward the airfield, investigators said. the lead aircraft was struck broadside by another black hawk that was flying alone about six miles from the airfield. the remaining two aircraft were not damaged and landed safely
the formation of three helicopters was returning infantry troops from a live-fire exercise, said fort campbell spokesman maj. randy j. schoel. aircraft flying over the reservation under visual flight rules, as the four copters were, are not generally tracked by control tower radar, and are responsible for avoiding each other, schoel said
the pilots were wearing night vision goggles that amplify available light and were supposed to have been in radio contact with the fort's control tower, the army spokesman said
generally the (helicopters' running) lights are dimmed to the point where they are not visible to the naked eye, but they are obvious to someone wearing goggles,'' schoel said
he added, ``fort campbell flies every night with night vision goggles. it's as routine here as driving at night in your car.''
gentry, manager of the winner's circle motel about 200 yards from the fort's main gate, lowered the motel's american flag to half-staff
further down the commercial strip at the snow white pawn shop, owner morrell v. boyd noted some of the signs businesses were putting up. one, at an army surplus store read: ``our prayers are with you, fort campbell.''
people are putting up signs on the marquees, but it goes deeper than that,'' said boyd, 51. ``it's sort of a helpless feeling, too. you're not sure what to do.''
a welcome center for the families of victims was being prepared on the post and memorial services were scheduled for next wednesday at the fort's chapel
gentry said the mourning among those in the community would be tempered by an appreciation of the risks the servicemen undertake regularly
there's a lot of loss, but a lot of pride, too,'' gentry said. ``i feel a lot of pride in those guys.''
applicants started phoning a few hours after china announced it would accept the peace corps for the first time and the agency said thursday it is eager for negotiations with the chinese to set the terms of the program
though the concentration is likely to be on english teachers, china still must decide what special skills it wants the volunteers to have, where they will serve and how large the peace corps program would be
the agency also will have to put volunteers for the program through a rigorous testing program that rejects four out of five applicants, said arlen erdahl, director of recruiting for the peace corps
we'll be just as careful as we always are,'' erdahl told a news conference
the united states, in a drive for better relations with china, had been giving chinese officials information about peace corps programs for years and began discussions of the issue in 1984
on wednesday, foreign minister wu xueqian announced during an appearance at the national press club that china had agreed to accept volunteers and would work out the details with u.s. officials
a few hours later, karl and katherine brandt of lexington, s.c., heard a radio news report about it and phoned the regional peace corps office in atlanta to volunteer
we've always wanted to do something like this; we visited some peace corps people in grenada once and when we heard about china we decided this might be a neat idea,'' brandt said in a telephone interview
the 55-year-old chemist said he and his wife, a nurse, have never lived outside the united states but ``we'd be interested in going to china.''
the peace corps has been sending american teachers, technicians, professionals and community workers to foreign cities and villages since 1961, when president kennedy started the agency to improve america's overseas image
the biggest country to accept volunteers had been india, which had peace corps programs between 1962 and 1976, but china is the most populated country and erdahl said america's ``fascination'' with that nation is likely to spur applications for the corps
he noted, however, that while applicants for the peace corps are asked to state their preferred assignments, they are not guaranteed being sent to a specific country
there are currently 64 countries with peace corps programs. the process of establishing the agency's relationship with china will be the same as it was for the others. it could take between two months and two years
this is just the starting gong,'' said john scales, the agency's general counsel
after a series of meetings, china will make a formal request for a peace corps presence, a team of agency officials will visit the country and the two sides will hammer out an agreement on numbers of volunteers, where they will do their work and what they will do
erdahl and several other peace corps officials who appeared at the news conference suggested that they expected china to be most interested in peace corps english teachers. the agency has become a specialist in teaching english as a second language and runs such programs in 33 countries. million, sted $69 million</note>
a special program to store grain in river barges in the fall of 1986 to make way for the new harvest cost taxpayers nearly a dollar a bushel to operate for four months, according to the general accounting office
overall, the $62 million cost was sharply higher than the storage fees normally paid by the government for grain inventories in elevators and farm bins. the program was announced in august 1986 as one of a number of emergency measures to help relieve pressure on elevators getting ready for another bumper corn harvest
the gao, an investigative agency of congress, said in a recent report to rep. bill alexander, d-ark., that the agriculture department awarded storage contracts to a dozen grain companies. a total of about 64.9 million bushels of grain _ 98 percent corn and 2 percent soybeans _ was loaded on 1,253 barges along the illinois, mississippi, missouri and ohio rivers
all of the barge grain originated from the corn belt states of illinois, indiana, iowa, michigan, minnesota, missouri, nebraska, ohio and wisconsin, the gao said. most had been in country and terminal elevators in those states, but some had been stored by producers on their farms
eventually, the department's kansas city commodity office, which handled the program, disposed of most of the barge grain by trading it to the contractors for grain they had stored in inland elevators. the remainder was sold, redeemed by farmers or returned to storage elsewhere
we estimate that the additional cost of the special barge storage program, over and above the normal costs for shipping, storing and disposing of the grain, was about $44.8 million, or an additional cost of 69 cents per bushel to store the grain for an average of four months,'' the gao said
the estimate by gao was made because the department's agricultural stabilization and conservation service ``did not separately accumulate total cost data for the program.'' however, gao said its estimates were based on reviews of contracts and other information provided by the agency
the estimated cost of storing the 64.9 million bushels of grain was about $62.2 million, or 96 cents per bushel,'' the gao said. ``this includes the additional cost of the program (about $44.8 million) and the cost that would have been incurred in the normal course of storage (more than $17.3 million).''
corn market prices nationally averaged $1.73 per bushel when the program was announced and dropped to $1.40 in october 1986, the peak of the new harvest
investigators said they estimated the department's kansas city commodity office paid the 12 contractors about $45.5 million and that an additional $16.7 million went to others for charges related to the barge-stored grain
the gao said the kansas city office ``agreed with our methodology and results'' in estimating the payments
a judge who suggested during his re-election campaign that his opponent should stay home with her young children has been turned out of office in a landslide
state district judge john mckellips' ex-wife and six children had endorsed his opponent, assistant county attorney mary anne bramblett, in tuesday's democratic primary
ms. bramblett outpolled mckellips 32,412 to 10,752 and she is assured of taking office because there is no republican on the november ballot
ms. bramblett, a political newcomer, attributed her victory to a negative image that may have started with mckellips' bitter divorce in 1985. lillian mckellips sued for divorce, claiming mckellips was having an affair with his 1984 campaign manager, margaret randle
mckellips married ms. randle two months after the divorce was granted. he gained publicity again last summer, when police were summoned to the courthouse to quell a quarrel between him and his new wife
last month, lillian mckellips and the couple's six children endorsed ms. bramblett, citing mckellips' treatment of them. a couple of weeks later, in an address at a sheriff's deputies' meeting, mckellips questioned ms. bramblett's qualifications, partly because she is a mother
she had to take some time out for maternity leave to have two small children, so i don't know how much time she's actually spent working as an attorney,'' he told the deputies
while attacking his opponent for taking time off to care for her newborns, mckellips criticized working mothers by linking absent mothers to overcrowded prisons
the next day, the judge amended his comments, saying ``it would have been more correct to have used the term `parent' rather than `mother.''
ms. bramblett, whose children are 3 and 4 years old, said at the time: ``everybody got the clear message that (mckellips believes) i am not qualified to be a judge because i'm a woman and a mother.''
county judge luther jones, who recruited ms. bramblett to run, said the victory was ``truly an epochal event in el paso's legal history. the image of both the attorneys and the entire judiciary have suffered immeasurable harm during the mckellips tenure on the bench.'' response; picks up 9th graf pvs, the audit</note>
a shortage of track inspectors has contributed to worn railroad switches in csx transportation co.'s baltimore-pittsburgh division, a federal agency said thursday in an audit prompted by a series of freight train accidents
the federal railroad administration, which is part of the transportation department, said that track along main routes is generally in top condition in the division, which includes the district of columbia and parts of maryland, pennsylvania, virginia, west virginia and new york
but the audit also found that ``the training, equipping, and numerical strength of the maintenance of way forces in this division are inadequate, a factor which threatens the company's capacity to maintain the quality of its track over the long term.''
maintenance of way employees inspect track. because manpower levels are low, the audit said, ``the districts assigned each csx track inspector are too large to be covered by a single individual. inspectors compensate by focusing their efforts on main line track, which is almost uniformly in excellent condition
but the trade-off lies in cursory inspections of turnouts,'' or switches that allow a train to move from one track to another, the audit said. ``the declining condition of these turnouts have been a major problem on the line.''
worn turnouts or improperly performed track maintenance were factors in several of the csx derailments occurring in 1987,'' the audit said
it said turnouts throughout the division were ``replete'' with loose adjustable rail braces, missing cotter pins and other problems. ``the entire gamut of defective turnout conditions addressed by fra track standards could be found in one form or another'' in the division, it said
csx, in a statement issued from its rail transport group in jacksonville, fla., said it already had begun a retraining program _ taught in part by railroad administration instructors _ for track inspectors, foremen, road masters and others working on the tracks
in addition, it said it had reached an agreement in the last few months with the brotherhood of maintenance of way employees ``to increase the number of people involved in track inspection.'' it did not specify how many would be added
the statement noted that the audit had found a well-maintained signal system, and had expressed no ``overriding concerns'' about the transportation of hazardous materials
the audit also said the railroad administration detected ``an apparent engineering problem'' in several sections of csx track near confluence, pa. it added that csx already has begun to reconstruct or move switches in the area
last may, a csx chemical tanker train derailed in confluence, splintering a control tower and killing its operator, and forcing nearby residents to evacuate. it was the third derailment in the southwest pennsylvania community in five months
csx trains also were involved in two derailments last year in the washington area. in june, 21 cars from a 134-car train derailed, temporarily halting subway service from suburban silver spring, md., and takoma park, md. in september, 14 cars on a csx train derailed in northeast washington, damaging 500 feet of metro subway track, an electrical power station and a warehouse
although accidents prompted the audit, none were specifically addressed in the document. as part of the audit, more than 1,800 miles of track were inspected last fall. us pork</head>
a move by the agriculture department to crack down on illegally high traces of a suspected cancer-causing drug found in hog carcasses has eased concern in japan that pork imports from the united states may be tainted, officials said thursday
japan had initiated a program to hold and test all u.s. pork imports, which american livestock interests feared might jeopardize foreign sales. the drug involved is sulfamethazine, commonly used by swine producers to prevent certain kinds of disease and as a feed additive to promote faster growth
lester m. crawford, administrator of the department's food safety and inspection service, said usda and japanese officials have agreed on testing requirements for pork shipped to japan
crawford said japanese officials ``have been favorably impressed with u.s. efforts'' initiated on march 7 to increase testing of pork products for sulfamethazine residues in the 100 largest u.s. pork plants
u.s. pork produced after march 7 must carry a statement on the export certificate that the product originated from one of the 100 plants undergoing increased residue testing,'' he said. ``japan will not further test these products for sulfamethazine residues.''
pork exported before the new controls went into effect will be tested further for the drug, either in japan or the united states, he said
i am very pleased with this agreement,'' crawford said. ``along with our increased testing, it ensures the safety of u.s. pork products and reaffirms the integrity of the u.s. pork industry.'' update with lawsuit by rockettes. 1st 5 grafs for release 6 p.m. est.</note>
chita rivera, whose left leg has been held together by 12 screws since a car accident two years ago, says she never doubted she'd be dancing again one day
now, the longtime broadway star, who is touring the country in a revival of ``can-can,'' has asked the producers to add more dancing to her new role, she said in an interview with parade magazine
i'm not a pollyanna; it hurts to dance,'' said rivera, 55. ``but you don't keep telling yourself that.''
she sometimes felt like quitting during physical therapy, when ``i would feel like i was going to hit the ceiling.'' but her positive side prevailed
there are some people whose spirits are so high, their determination so great, that you practically have to shoot them to get them down,'' she says. ``i guess i'm one of those people. the spirit is the strongest thing there is.''
meanwhile, five rockettes are suing radio city music hall and the producers of the touring show, charging them with false advertising and violating the agreement with the dancers' union
the touring company advertisements say that 14 rockettes are dancing with rivera in the production, according to bernard b. cohen, attorney for the five. however, he said, only four real rockettes are in the 39-city tour, which started jan. 29
instead of dancing with chita rivera, the real rockettes are doing a tap dance on the unemployment line,'' he said
the contract between radio city and the dancers' union, the american guild of variety artists, specifies that only rockettes on the official roster be hired for productions featuring the rockettes, cohen said
the five dancers are seeking $2 million in damages
radio city has maintained that the five could not handle the dance routine and that the ``imposters'' are new rockettes
the producers of the show are kan kan national co., the troika company inc. and trice talent payment inc. conference</head>
former secretary of state henry a. kissinger said thursday that israel should hold early elections in order to resolve an ``intolerable'' political problem
in a television interview taped for broadcast this weekend on the syndicated ``one on one'' interview program, kissinger also reiterated his position that israel should give jordan the occupied gaza strip and densely populated parts of the west bank
gaza was under egyptian control before israel captured it in the 1967 mideast war, but kissinger said it should now be given to jordan. he did not explain
kissinger said israel and the united states should stay away from an international peace conference proposed by secretary of state george p. shultz
i think there should be elections in israel. it's desirable. you have a prime minister and a foreign minister who are cutting each other up,'' he said
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, head of the right-wing likud bloc, and foreign minister shimon peres, who leads the labor party, have both considered moving the elections up from november
each side is trying to line up the united states and other foreign countries in their support. it's an intolerable situation. so the earlier they have an election and get unified, the more important it is,'' kissinger said
kissinger, who mediated israeli agreements with the arabs in the mid-1970s, said he would prefer that the united states help negotiate peace between the sides without interference from the other four permanent members of the u.n. security council _ the soviet union, china, england and france
i'd prefer shultz to do it alone,'' he said
all the other countries will press for israeli withdrawal to its 1967 borders, he said. ``i think those will guarantee the destruction of israel,'' kissinger said
he said a formula must be found under which israel would give back some of those territories but retain sufficient lands to guarantee it a defensible buffer zone
a former black panther convicted of murdering two guards in a bloody 1971 san quentin escape attempt walked out of prison on bail thursday, almost two years after a judge ordered that he get a new trial
i feel great. ... i'm just very happy,'' johnny spain told reporters at the front gate of the state prison at vacaville, 50 miles east of san francisco
i won't let anyone down who has supported me and there have been many who supported me,'' he said, adding he was prepared to deal with the challenges of living on the outside after 21 years behind bars
spain was hugged and congratulated by attorneys and investigators who worked on his case, and members of their families
attorney dennis riordan said spain had promised to attend a play in san francisco on thursday night with the 10-year-old daughter of one of his supporters. riordan said spain would remain in the san francisco area until at least wednesday for court appearances, then planned to visit los angeles to see his wife and children
some $100,000 of spain's bail has been posted but $250,000 in property must be guaranteed by wednesday, riordan said, adding that he anticipated no problems
u.s. district judge thelton henderson, who had previously granted spain a new trial in the ``san quentin six'' case, a state lawyer's request wednesday to delay bail until the state parole board reconsiders his case
spain, 38, has been behind bars since december 1966, when he was arrested for a murder and robbery in los angeles
he later became the only prisoner convicted of murder in a 1971 uprising in which george jackson, widely known for his book of prison writings, ``soledad brother,'' was killed, along with two other prisoners and three guards
authorities said spain, seen running from a maximum-security unit with jackson, conspired with him in an escape attempt that led to the killings
henderson reversed spain's convictions in 1986, saying he had been denied a fair trial by being required to wear heavy shackles for every court appearance during the five years of proceedings
the state's appeal of the ruling is to be argued monday before the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals
on tuesday, los angeles superior court judge kathleen parker ordered spain paroled immediately from the sentence he has been serving for the 1966 murder, a sentence that had kept henderson from granting bail earlier
she found that the parole board had improperly lengthened his sentence nearly six years by applying regulations passed in 1976 to disciplinary violations committed in 1970 and 1971
riordan said spain had spent twice as long in prison as the average sentence for a similar crime
lawyers said spain would be living in san francisco and working as an electrician while his case is on appeal. henderson's order allows him to travel within the state and visit his wife, whom he married while in prison, and two young sons in los angeles
iran has begun constructing crude launch pads for silkworm missiles on the island of abu musa in the persian gulf, potentially expanding the area within which it can menace shipping, u.s. military sources said thursday
the defense officials, who agreed to discuss the matter only if not identified, stressed that american intelligence agencies so far had failed to detect any effort by iran to actually send silkworm missiles over to the small island
iran has built similar launch pads at other sites on its main coastline without ever deploying any actual missiles, one source noted
but it's still significant because it would really extend the coverage of these missiles ... if they deployed silkworms there,'' another official said
the silkworm is a chinese-built variant of an old russian missile that can be fired from mobile launchers on land against ships. the missiles have a range of about 50 miles and while not particularly accurate, they carry a large warhead packed with conventional explosives
according to u.s. sources, iran has acquired more than 100 silkworms and stored the majority of them at a large naval base at bandar abbas near the strait of hormuz, the sole entrance to the persian gulf
although concrete launch pads aren't essential for the silkworm truck launchers to operate, the iranians nonetheless have constructed such pads at several sites along the coastline overlooking the strait. as a result, american warships escorting tankers in and out of the gulf normally go to battle stations for the passage and navy jets provide air cover just in case a missile attack is mounted
abu musa is a small, iranian-controlled island inside the strait of hormuz, roughly 50 miles into the gulf and almost in the middle of the waterway. it long has been used by iran as a base for gunboats that have attacked commercial shipping
if iran were to deploy silkworms on abu musa, ``it would be doubling the arc (of space) that it can threaten,'' one source said thursday
it definitely would extend our area of vulnerability up into the gulf,'' another official agreed
we'd have to get pretty serious about (watching) that island,'' added a third source
all the officials stressed that construction on the island had begun only recently and was proceeding slowly
but it is assessed to be silkworm firing platforms,'' said one
the united states has been escorting reflagged kuwaiti tankers in the gulf since last july. kuwait, a key ally of iraq in the iran-iraq war, requested the protection after iran began singling out its ships for attack
the 16th convoy operation of 1988 and the 38th overall began tuesday night and was said to be proceeding uneventfully on thursday, with two tankers steaming southbound from kuwait toward the strait of hormuz along with a navy frigate. reagan</head>
rep. larry smith on thursday introduced resolutions that would deny foreign aid and trade privileges to mexico, the bahamas, peru, bolivia and paraguay for alleged failure to cooperate with u.s. anti-drug efforts
smith, chairman of the house foreign affairs committee's task force on international narcotics control, said the five countries were wrongly certified by president reagan on march 1 as cooperating with drug enforcement programs
some of these `cooperative' countries have even actively frustrated our efforts to stop the production of drugs and their trafficking into the united states,'' smith, d-fla., told reporters. ``it's time the president stands up and does more than just saying no.''
smith and reps. benjamin gilman, r-n.y., and dante fascell, d-fla., chairman of the house foreign affairs committee, said the purpose of the resolutions was not necessarily to cut off aid to the five countries but to focus public attention on the certification process and determine whether it can be improved
under comprehensive anti-drug legislation enacted in 1986, the president must certify annually that major drug-producing and shipment countries have ``fully cooperated'' with the united states, or they face loss of a year's worth of military and economic development aid and u.s. support for international development bank loans
countries that are ``decertified'' also may suffer a wide range of trade sanctions at the president's discretion. these include a 50 percent boost in import tariffs, abrogation of airline agreements, loss of u.s. sugar quotas and a halt in preferred u.s. customs treatment
reagan recently certified all the 24 major drug countries as fully cooperating with u.s. anti-drug efforts except for panama, afghanistan, syria and iran, which were decertified, and for lebanon, laos and paraguay, which were certified for ``national interests.''
under the law, congress has 45 business days _ until may 13 _ to overrule any of reagan's recent aid certifications and 30 days _ until april 19 _ to disapprove of further trade privileges for any countries the president certified as fully cooperating
smith said mexico should be penalized because it is the primary source of heroin and marijuana entering the united states, and the smuggling route for one-third of the cocaine destined for u.s. consumption
he said opium production has increased at least 30 percent and eradication has fallen by one-third since 1984. smith said laundering of illicit drug profits is extensive and that mexico provides safe haven for hundreds of drug traffickers indicted in the united states
smith criticized drug enforcement efforts by the other four countries, especially the bahamas, which he said is the major transit point for half the cocaine and marijuana entering the united states
at a hearing that smith headed thursday, assistant secretary of state elliott abrams said that ``while we believe that mexico is capable of even greater effort against narcotics trafficking, we also believe that mexican cooperation ... is substantial and justifies the president's decision to certify mexico.''
oil workers returned to work thursday after the government began firing strikers, whose walkout paralyzed oil and gasoline refineries for two days, the government-owned state petroleum co. said
the strike began tuesday, hitting hard at public transportation and at factories that depend on oil or gasoline to operate
about half of state petroleum's 7,000 workers were estimated to have gone out on strike
brazil's conservative government gave strikers until thursday to return to work or be fired. in previous strikes, the government carried out similar threats
how many strikers were dismissed this time was not disclosed, nor did the government say whether anyone would be reinstated
the government deployed troops to take over refineries and gasoline stations tuesday and arrested labor leaders
it rationed gasoline and motorists lined up for hours. many buses and taxis in major cities went out of service
the federation of petroleum workers had rejected a 30 percent wage increase which the government offered on condition that there would be no strike for one year. the average petroleum worker earns $350 a month, compared to $100 a month for other government employees
saul soliz, leader of the union, said the no-strike condition was a government maneuver designed ``to divide the labor movement against the interests of workers.''
the union said that the government planned to finance the wage increase by firing 1,500 workers
the government conceded that there would be some dismissals to finance the pay increase, but said they would not exceed 500
john r. bolton, the justice department's liaison with congress, will become the assistant attorney general directing the department's civil division, attorney general edwin meese iii announced thursday
bolton, who has been assistant attorney general for legislative affairs since december 1985, will be taking charge of the largest litigating division in the justice department
bolton, 39, succeeds richard willard, who left the department in february to join a washington law firm
the civil division, directly responsible for 20,000 pending cases, represents the government in constitutional litigation involving federal statutes, torts, contract claims and federal regulatory matters
increasing competition within the city's drug trade prompted a suspected dealer to lead police to a rival's secret stash of heroin, authorities said thursday
no arrests were made, but 443 small bags of heroin were confiscated wednesday, police said. the bags were worth $20 each for a total street value of $9,000, said detective william gallagher
the tipster cooperated with police because of growing competition among dealers in the north camden neighborhood, the worst drug area in the city, gallagher said
we couldn't lock him up even though we know this guy is a drug dealer because he didn't have any on him. we got the stash, said, `thank you, very much,' and he split,'' gallagher said
the owner of the drugs was not at the scene when officers william durham and michael comuso uncovered the stash 10 feet under a loose brick in the archway of a vacant house, gallagher said
durham and comuso had looked for the drugs for about a week, combing through piles of trash and vacant and abandoned houses, which gallagher described as the favored hiding places for drugs
the tipster decided to help the officers after his rival began cutting into his territory, gallagher said
there's some conflict of interest up there,'' he said, adding that drug dealers from colombia and the dominican republic are trying to take over a neighborhood where black and other hispanic dealers have traditionally worked
north camden is the hot spot right now. the traffic just flows through there, especially on thursday and friday after payday,'' he said
he declined to release the name of the tipster, saying such action might make the man a target for retaliation from his rivals
in a way, the new spirit of cooperation is an asset for law enforcement officials who spend hours each day patrolling the blighted area, he said
but i also foresee where somebody's going to get hurt up there,'' he said. ``they'll shoot you in a heartbeat.'' tv evangelist scandals with watergate, remarks at press conference, picking up 8th graf `the last...'</note>
the rev. jerry falwell on thursday likened the tv evangelism scandals with the watergate affair and said ``the cause of christ is better off'' because of them
the crisis that ended the nixon administration ``made it much tougher for politicians since then,'' falwell told the national association of evangelicals
in the days ahead, it is going to be tougher for national (ministry) leaders to misbehave,'' he said. ``not impossible, but tougher.''
falwell, a fundamentalist preacher who is not a member of the association, appeared for the first time before the group, which has 50,000 members and represents 72 denominations
an admission of sin last month by tv preacher jimmy swaggart and allegations last year of sexual and financial misconduct by jim bakker have led to a new code of moral and financial ethics for religious broadcasters, fallwell said
i think the days of the rolls-royces and rolexes ... the days in which social status is gauged by financial trappings, are over,'' falwell said at a luncheon sponsored by the national religious broadcasters, an affiliate of the nae
falwell said that the swaggart controversy had had little effect on his own ministry and that he did not believe it had equaled the general impact of the bakker revelations on the religious broadcast industry
it seems that all the fallout that was going to occur, occurred last year,'' he said at a news conference after the luncheon
however, he said that if similar scandals had occurred to him or other, more conservative, ministers, ``we would be out looking for other employment.''
i'd rather be dead'' than be immoral, he said
bakker, who admitted a tryst with a church secretary and who has been accused of financial improprieties, was expelled from the assemblies of god church
swaggart, who has been accused of paying a prostitute to perform lewd acts, was suspended by the denomination and expects to return to the pulpit
after bakker resigned as head of ptl, falwell headed the ministry for several months before stepping aside
falwell accepted an invitation to speak before the nae in 1983 but withdrew after criticism from fellow fundamentalists. the fundamentalist side of protestant christianity maintains a theological separation from the more broadly based evangelical organization
falwell's ``old time gospel hour'' is broadcast around the world on some 350 television stations. he is founder of the moral majority movement and pastor of the 21,000-member thomas road baptist church in lynchburg, va., the largest in the country
turning to politics, falwell praised former religious broadcaster pat robertson but said he endorsed george bush for the presidency, even though falwell had ronald reagan not to choose bush as his vice president
i'd love to see a bush-kemp ticket,'' he said referring to new york congressman jack kemp
on the other side, falwell said, ``i can't think of a single democrat running this year who i could hold my nose and vote for.''
in a presidential preference poll conducted late wednesday, some 100 nae board members endorsed bush, followed by kansas sen. robert dole, kemp and robertson. among democrats, they favored rep. richard gephardt of missouri
the last-place finish for robertson ``confounded conventional wisdom that he would be the near-unanimous choice of evangelical leaders,'' said richard cizik, research director for the nae in washington
but it was no surprise to those trying to gauge the support for robertson within the evangelical movement over the past two years. in two previous polls, its leaders also placed robertson fourth among the gop candidates
they just don't consider robertson to be the most qualified for the job,'' cizik said
among democrats, gephardt was slightly favored over sen. albert gore of tennessee, with massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, sen. paul simon of illinois and jackson, a baptist minister, trailing in that order
bush received 40 percent of the votes on the gop side. dole got 32 percent, kemp 17 percent and robertson 12 percent
gephardt was ranked first among democrats by 37 percent of the board members. gore received 33 percent, dukakis 16 percent, simon 11 percent and jackson 5 percent
in two previous two polls, in march and october last year, dole was the winner with more than 40 percent of the votes, followed by kemp, bush and robertson
although evangelicals are considered conservative and orthodox in their religious views, they represent a broad spectrum of political ideology and the board members are ``not necessarily a reflection of the rank and file,'' said cizik
the nae, conducting a series of workshops and seminars for some 500 delegates, includes denominations as diverse as reformed and pentecostal. among its members are baptists, lutherans, presbyterians and mennonites. assurance other studies will be done</note>
ash and sludge produced by gas scrubbers that remove sulfur dioxide at coal-fired plants generally does not need to be regulated as hazardous waste, the environmental protection agency said thursday
however, small quantities of waste produced in cleaning boilers and purifying water do meet the definitions of hazardous wastes and the agency said it will consider whether to bring them under hazardous waste regulation
the conclusions were contained in a report to congress on power plant wastes required by 1980 amendments to the federal hazardous waste law. those amendments exempted such waste from regulation until completion of the study. epa now has until september to decide what wastes, if any, to regulate as hazardous
the agency said it would defer studying wastes from oil-fired plants, and coal combustion outside the utility industry. spokeswoman robin woods said the schedule for those studies had not been decided, but the agency intended to complete them
coal plants produce a lot of waste _ in 1984 about 69 million tons of ash and 16 million tons of sludge from smokestack gas scrubbers used to remove sulfur dioxide, a pollutant that helps form acid rain. epa said that in the year 2000 ash probably would be 120 million tons and scrubber waste 50 million tons
utilities spend $800 million a year in disposing of the waste at $2 to $31 a ton, and the requirements for handling and disposal under hazardous waste regulation would increase that to $70 per ton or $3.7 billion
ash and sludge may contain small quantities of arsenic, barium, cadmium, chromium, lead, mercury and selenium. in general, these do not leach out of the material in landfills to the extent that would make them hazardous, though some samples ``did indicate hazardous levels of cadmium and arsenic,'' epa said
intravenous drug addicts appear to be spreading aids in the united states at a higher rate than homosexuals, whose chances of contracting the disease could decline, u.s. surgeon general c. everett koop said thursday
addressing the first international conference on the global impact of aids, koop said surveys in the united states indicate that male homosexuals have ``undergone a very serious and positive change in behavior'' to reduce their risk of contracting aids
we might even expect a decline in the rate of aids reporting from this group in a year or so,'' he told about 1,000 health specialists from 63 countries at london's barbican center. the three-day conference closed thursday
by contrast, koop said, intravenous drug abusers have yet to realize they face a high risk of contracting aids from sharing blood-contaminated needles
over the years, we've been singularly unsuccessful in penetrating the drug-addicted culture with every other public health message we ever had, including the one that says stop'' using drugs, koop added
the u.s. official last january predicted a rise, but not an explosion, in the number of aids cases among heterosexuals
in an interview with the associated press earlier thursday, koop said public health officials must find ``some innovative and creative ways'' of reaching drug abusers, who now pose the greatest risk of spreading aids to the uninfected u.s. population
i think the major problem that we have in the states is how to reach the intravenous drug abuser, which class seems to be the one that is spreading the disease most rapidly at the present time,'' koop said
according to the centers for disease control in atlanta, 63 percent of the 55,167 cases of aids reported in the united states have been among male homosexuals or bisexuals, 17 percent among intravenous drug abusers and 7 percent among those who fall into both categories
koop said health policymakers should consider setting up a pilot needle-exchange program to determine whether it could cut the rate of aids infection among drug abusers who share needles
under needle-exchange programs tried in western europe, drug addicts can turn in used needles and syringes for free, sterile equipment. there are conflicting opinions on whether such programs have slowed the spread of aids
while stressing he was not proposing such a plan but rather supporting those who call for it, koop said drug abuse was the likeliest way that aquired immune deficiency syndrome could spread through the heterosexual population
the geneva-based world health organization and the london school of hygiene and tropical medicine organized the conference to assess the economic and social impact of the aids epidemic, which has spread to at least 133 countries
speakers discussed problems ranging from the aids threat to the mining industry of zambia, to efforts to prevent the spread of infection in british prisons
aids is a disease in which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers
aids is most often transmitted through sexual contact, but can also be transmitted through transfusions of tainted blood or blood products. aids can also be passed from mother to child at or before birth
secretary of state george shultz said thursday his plan for bringing arabs and israelis to the negotiating table is ``the only game in town'' and outlined details for the first time in public
shultz, testifying on capitol hill, also indicated that the united states would continue to push the plan even if israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir rejects it when he holds talks in washington next week
people have looked at our ideas, and while nobody is saying yes, nobody wants to say no, because it's the only game in town,'' shultz said
people will probably _ would even dodge and object and so on, but we're going to keep working and see if we can't bring something out of this,'' he added
shamir has opposed the shultz plan because it sets a timetable for negotiations between israel and the arabs on the future of the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip
president reagan, meanwhile, said in an interview thursday that ``a great element'' of israel's coalition government supports the peace plan and that he will try to persuade shamir to drop his objections to the proposal
i believe that peace is inevitable,'' reagan said. ``we may have some differences there as to how to achieve it but i don't think anyone believes that we can go on just with a constant state of warfare and unrest (in the middle east).''
shultz, in testimony to the house appropriations foreign operations subcommittee, said the united states feels ``time is awasting'' and wants talks between israel and arab countries to begin by may 1. the talks would be under the auspices of the five permanent members of the u.n. security council _ the united states, the soviet union, china, england and france
it is essential, particularly from the standpoint of the arab side, that there be an auspices for these negotiations, something that gives them legitimacy,'' he said
we proposed that this conference initiate these bilateral negotiations, that it be a body that can receive reports from the parties on the status of their negotiations, but that ... the conference will not be able to impose solutions or veto agreements reached.''
in what appeared a slight shift, shultz did not insist as he has in the past that the soviets could only participate if they resumed the diplomatic tiesthey broke with israel in 1967
however, i have told the soviets ... that whether they come to a conference or not, they cannot expect to play a genuinely involved role in middle east affairs'' until they re-establish official relations with israel and ease their restrictions on jewish emigration, he said
in the plan he presented to israeli and arab leaders last week, shultz stipulated that all the participants must recognize u.n. resolution 242 and 338, which call for israel to return lands it captured from the arabs in the 1967 mideast war. in return, the arab states would have to recognize the jewish state's right to exist
shultz did not speak directly of the three months of israeli-palestinian clashes in which more than 80 arabs have been killed. but he referred to it, saying that ``people's minds are a little more open now than they've been in some time, and we should take advantage of that.''
under the plan, the palestinians would be represented by a joint delegation with jordan, shultz said
the initial negotiations would address ``transitional arrangements'' for three years of palestinian self-rule, he said. the united states would present a draft proposal as a preliminary working paper
such negotiations could be concluded within six months because much of the preparatory work has been completed, he said
the transitional arrangement could be put into place within three months after the end of the negotiations. immediately following the six-month negotiations, the sides would begin yearlong talks on the final status of the territories, he said
republican presidential candidate bob dole jabbed at vice president george bush on thursday, saying his rival for the gop nomination was ``hiding from america.''
dole, after touring a rehabilitation hospital, stepped up his attacks on the vice president for not agreeing to one-on-one debates before next tuesday's illinois primary
i don't think he wants to stand up without notes and talk about issues,'' dole said. ``it's not a strength of his. his strength is to run these tv ads that distort somebody's record.''
dole apparently was referring to television spots that the bush campaign has used to raise questions about the kansas senator's position on taxes. dole blames his campaign's failure to effectively counter the ads for his loss in new hampshire
i think he's going to play it safe,'' dole said of bush. ``he's not going to debate bob dole. he wouldn't dare debate bob dole for two hours without notes, without roger ailes.''
ailes is a media consultant
at nearly every campaign stop since he arrived in illinois on tuesday, dole has hammered away at bush and challenged him to speak out on the issues
it's almost impossible to separate bush from (president) reagan because he's been standing next to him for seven years,'' dole said. ``unfortunately, i didn't have time to stand there. i had to get reagan's program passed.''
dole also is questioning bush's ``electability,'' saying he would be a stronger candidate for the party to field against democrats in november
my view is it's going to be a very tough, tough race for george bush,'' said dole. ``he does not attract democrats or independents.''
dole said he would seek out supporters of rep. jack kemp now that the new york republican has pulled out of the presidential race. he expects to soon receive the endorsement of rep. henry hyde, r-ill., a key kemp backer in the state
dole said he faces a ``steep hill to climb'' to defeat bush
i have to do very well in this state,'' dole said
does that mean winning? that means doing very well.''
dole seemed to be backing off slightly from statements on wednesday that illinois was a must-win state for his struggling candidacy, but he dismissed questions from reporters on whether he was scaling down his expectations in the state
dole's first stop on thursday was to the rehabilitation institute of chicago, where he toured the hospital and greeted patients, many of whom were confined to wheelchairs
the medical center is just a short distance away from another hospital where dole underwent surgery 40 years ago for wounds he suffered in world war ii
one woman patient told dole, ``you're not going to get bushwhacked in the midwest.''
dole gave words of encouragement to some of the patients and told them how it was difficult for him to regain the use of one of his arms which had been paralyzed
i don't give up easy. i'm like everybody in this building,'' dole said after his tour. ``you wouldn't walk out of here if you gave up easy. so i'm a fighter.'' week</head> defense of accord; deletes 15th graf pvs, the source, as now outdated; picks up 8th graf pvs, in december</note>
a pact allowing japan to retrieve plutonium from u.s. nuclear wastes would leave the united states without ``effective control'' over reprocessing of the hazardous material, the general accounting office has concluded
the gao, the investigative arm of congress, also found fault with the agreement's provisions to guard against proliferation of plutonium, the principal element in nuclear weapons, and said it deprived congress of its ``oversight function.''
opponents of the accord said they had failed to work out a compromise with the state department and may move to kill the agreement next week
the accord, signed last november, gives japan advance permission for 30 years to recover plutonium from the fuel the united states supplies for its nuclear power plants after it is used
congressional opponents wanted the united states to have the right to review the use of plutonium in any future japanese facilities on a ``case-by-case'' basis, and to be able to suspend the agreement in a terrorism threat or other national security situations
the congressional foes also sought to have the agreement reviewed every five years
these changes would require renegotiating the terms with japan, which the state department declined to do, said a congressional source, speaking only on condition of anonymity
a leading opponent, sen. alan cranston, d-calif., said ``it is extremely unfortunate the state department has rejected a compromise agreement. it is a bad agreement. it has serious flaws.''
cranston, chairman of the senate asia subcommittee, called on the reagan administration to withdraw the accord. ``otherwise,'' he said, ``it faces growing opposition'' in congress
the gao report was written by milton socolar, a special assistant to the u.s. comptroller general, and was dated feb. 29. it was obtained thursday
the report said the agreement does not meet various requirements of the atomic energy act. it said giving ``blanket approval'' to japan for reprocessing plutonium ``would leave the united states with no effective control over the life of the proposed agreement.''
a u.s. official involved in the negotiations said, however, the ``safeguard concepts'' in the pact are adequate and that the agreement could be suspended in the event of proliferation or a terrorist threat
the official, speaking only if not named, said the agreement ``makes sure terrorists cannot get into the facilities.''
in december, the senate foreign relations committee, in an unusual move, voted 15-3 to return the pact to president reagan and asked that it be renegotiated. opponents argued it sets a precedent to encourage potentially hazardous trade in plutonium, which is a potent cancer-causing agent
opponents also complained the plutonium would be shipped over alaska and possibly other areas of the united states
on tuesday, the state department said the plutonium would be shipped ``in accordance with rigorous physical protection and safety requirements.''
a statement issued by the non-proliferation office said planes carrying the plutonium soon will be able to fly non-stop from europe to japan, taking a polar route. this would avoid overflights of the united states, canada or any other country
the administration is, therefore, prepared to rule out air shipments of plutonium under the agreement from overflying or landing in the united states, except in the case of aircraft emergency,'' the statement said
under the agreement, japan would ship the spent nuclear fuel to reprocessing plants in britain or france, which would separate plutonium from the waste. the plutonium then would be shipped back to japan by air
the congressional source said the statement was designed to ease the concerns of sen. frank h. murkowski, r-alaska, but did not basically alter the flaws in the agreement
also, the source said, richard n. perle and frank gaffney, former defense department officials, wrote members of congress urging rejection of the agreement as ``seriously flawed'' and complaining that the pentagon was not permitted to play a meaningful role in the negotiations with japan
forty-five tons of plutonium could be airlifted from europe to japan by the year 2000 under the pact. it takes 15 pounds to make a bomb
congress has until april 25 to block the agreement with japan or it takes effect
secretary of state george p. shultz on thursday called u.s. foreign aid embarrassingly low compared with the effort made by western european countries
he was challenging rep. david r. obey, d-wis., who chaired a hearing at which shultz testified
mr. chairman, you talked about burden sharing, but if we compared our effort in that regard with our european friends, i think we would see a somewhat embarrassing picture,'' shultz said
he was immediately supported by the member who had been questioning him, rep. john edward porter, r-ill
it's shameful, mr. secretary, it's absolutely shameful,'' porter said. ``i certainly agree with you.''
shultz was apparently referring to figures for 1986, compiled by the organization for economic cooperation and development, which show that total u.s. development aid is high _ $9.56 billion for 1986 _ but low as a proportion of u.s. wealth
the oecd calculates that u.s. aid amounted to 0.23 percent of the country's total production. by that measure norway was at the top of the list with 1.2 percent of its production, an effort more than five times greater. the united states was close to the bottom of the list. only austria was lower, with 0.21 percent
shultz also made a comparison with the soviet union
the fact of the matter is ... the soviets are spending considerably more than we are in what we classify as as economic and security assistance,'' he said. ``and their economy is half the size of ours. so that our effort is relatively small.''
according to the u.s. agency for international development, the soviets spent $3.68 billion on economic aid in 1986, equal to 0.33 percent of their national production
obey had begun the hearing with an explanation of why congress provided smaller amounts for aid than had been requested by the administration for countries where the united states has military bases
we felt that the united states is getting the shaft from our allies in terms of burden sharing around the world,'' he said
and we feel it's the obligation of our european allies to carry a greater share of the load in supporting common defense efforts. ... so it's not that we have any policy dislike for spain or for portugal or for greece or for any of the other countries involved,'' he said
it's simply that when the u.s. taxpayer spends $1,100 on average to support military and foreign expenditures, and the (west) german taxpayer spends $450 and the spanish taxpayer spends $113 and the average for europe is $318, we feel those are not good conditions under which we ought to be making large commitments of expenditures,'' he said
obey, who chairs the foreign operations subcommittee of the house appropriations committee, also complained of administration proposals to lower spending on some domestic programs for education and low-cost housing. satellite</head>
the corporation for public broadcasting told congress on thursday it needs $200 million to replace an aging satellite system that is due to expire in 1991
donald ledwig, cpb president, told a house energy and commerce subcommittee that unless the satellite system is replaced, the skies will go dark for public radio and television stations that rely on it to receive programming from the public broadcasting service
without funding for the satellite, there would be no way to replace it unless we pulled it out of our budget,'' which would leave little money for anything else, ledwig said
cpb is asking congress to authorize $395 million for cpb's general operations for the year beginning oct. 1, 1991. the board also proposes its federal support be increased to $411 million in fiscal year 1992 and to $427 million in fiscal year 1993. the $200 million for a new satellite system would be additional
the reagan administration in its recent budget proposal asked congress to freeze cpb's funding at its current level of $214 million for fiscal years 1989 through 1991 and did not include any funds for a new satellite system. congress previously had authorized cpb to receive $228 million in 1989 and $233 in fiscal 1990
rep. edward markey, d-mass., chairman of the telecommunications subcommittee, has introduced legislation that would split the difference between what cpb wants and what the administration is proposing
some on the subcommittee, however, said that at a time of soaring budget deficits, public broadcasters cannot count on increasing their federal support
rep. michael g. oxley, r-ohio, said public broadcasters should consider limited advertising between programs an a way to fill their budget gaps
i am troubled by the intransigence of the (public broadcasting) system on this important question,'' oxley said
the public broadcasting act prohibits advertising on public radio and tv stations, but oxley said this raises constitutional free-speech questions
maj. hugh lindsay, who was killed thursday in an avalanche while skiing with prince charles, was a career army officer who became a favorite aide of queen elizabeth ii
handsome, urbane, fun-loving and an expert skier, lindsay was out on the slopes at a resort in klosters, switzerland with the 39-year-old heir to the british throne when he was caught in an avalanche
buckingham palace said charles escaped unharmed
the prince helped dig out lindsay, according to press association, britain's domestic news agency, but the major was dead by the time he was airlifted to a nearby hospital
lindsay, 34, was a close friend of charles and princess diana
last july, diana and prince edward, the youngest brother of prince charles, made a surprise appearance at lindsay's wedding to sarah brennan at the 10th-century church of st. nichola in compton, surrey outside london
mrs. lindsay, who works in the buckingham palace press office, is expecting the couple's first child in may
lindsay was a major in the british army when he was appointed an equerry, or aide, to the queen in october 1983. he spent three years working closely with her before returning to full-time army duty with the prince of wales' 9th-12th royal lancers in 1986
he was the perfect equerry, which means he was the perfect courtier,'' said anthony carthew, court correspondent for independent television. ``he was very good-looking and urbane and witty
he was very popular with the queen ... popular indeed with the whole royal family.''
he also said lindsay was a very strong skier
in his spare time, lindsay played in a seven-man blues band called ``sweatband,'' which appeared at balls and society parties. baroness isabelle van randwyck, a school friend of diana, also played in the band
lindsay was vacationing at klosters in 1986 with charles and diana when sarah ferguson made one of her first public appearances before the announcement of her engagement to prince andrew, charles' brother
the major was playfully prodded with an umbrella by diana and sarah at the races at royal ascot last june, to the crowd's delight
the u.n. human rights commission accepted fidel castro's invitation thursday to send its first delegation to cuba to investigate allegations of human rights abuses
the 43-nation body approved without a vote the decision drafted by four latin american countries to accept the invitation cuba extended wednesday
plans are for a six-member delegation, including the chairman of the u.n. commission, to visit the caribbean island this year and report to the 1989 meeting
before the decision, the united states and latin american countries led by argentina, colombia, mexico and peru, spent a day negotiating acceptable conditions for a visit
in another action thursday, the commission condemned chile's military government for violations including murder, kidnapping and torture by security forces, continued curbs on basic civil rights and intimidation by authorities
a resolution passed 34-0 cited ``acts of extreme violence from all sources in chile which have exacerbated the climate of insecurity.'' seven countries abstained, including the united states, japan and brazil, and two did not vote
armando valladares, a former cuban political prisoner who heads the u.s. delegation to the rights commission, told a news conference the two-year u.s. effort to have the commission examine cuba had forced castro's hand
this visit has not been a voluntary gesture by cuba,'' he said, speaking in spanish with simultaneous translation
a day of negotiations produced ``conditions and guarantees'' for an impartial visit that did not exist when cuba extended the invitation wednesday, said valladares, who was released from 22 years in a cuban prison six years ago. he called the commission decision ``a triumph for human rights.''
an official of the u.n. center for human rights, k.f. nyamekye, said it was understood that the six members _ commission chairman alioune sene of senegal and five others to be chosen geographically _ would meet in geneva for a week in may or june to plan their work
cuba has been cited for such human rights violations as torture and mistreatment of political prisoners by the united states and international organizations, including amnesty international
castro's government denies the charges and fought the u.s. effort to put its human rights situation on the agenda of the commission, which meets every year for six weeks. debate intensified this year when valladares, who wrote a book about mistreatment and torture in prison, was chosen to lead the u.s. delegation
after thursday's decision, the united states withdrew a resolution calling for the u.n. secretary-general to examine the human rights situation in cuba and report to the commission
valladares said the plan adopted ``goes far beyond what we had originally asked for. it is very important
a member of the cuban delegation said it would not have a statement thursday
the document approved is brief and does not give conditions of the visit, saying only that a six-member team ``should visit cuba in order to observe the human rights situation'' and prepare a report
sene told the organization the investigating team would have unrestricted access to information while in cuba
they will visit cuba for ``about five days'' in july or august, then reconvene in geneva in january to consider and adopt their report, said nyamekye
dartmouth college suspended two members of a conservative student newspaper for two years thursday and another for two terms for harassing a black professor in his classroom
a fourth student staffer for the independent dartmouth review was placed on disciplinary probation for one year for disorderly conduct
the four white students had faced possible expulsion over a feb. 25 confrontation with music professor william cole over a review article criticizing his class and his teaching ability
the article and the confrontation had drawn allegations of racism against the review and prompted demonstrations by black students at the ivy league school
the penalties imposed by the student-faculty dartmouth committee on standards take effect wednesday, the end of the current academic term
christopher baldwin of hinsdale, ill., john quilhot of fort wayne, ind., john sutter of st. louis, and sean nolan of lexington, mass., were charged with harassment, disorderly conduct and invasion of privacy
baldwin, a junior who is the review editor, and sutter, a senior who is its executive editor, were suspended until the fall of 1989, or six terms
quilhot, a sophomore photographer, was suspended for two terms. nolan, a freshman contributor to the paper, was placed on probation. dartmouth operates on a three-term college year
baldwin said the students will appeal
i knew we were going to get a sentence like that when we walked into the hearing,'' baldwin said. ``the hearing was conducted in a lynch-mob hysteria.''
they did what was politically expedient, not what was right,'' he said
the disciplinary panel found all four guilty of disorderly conduct for failure to leave cole's classroom after being asked repeatedly to leave
baldwin was guilty of harassment for initiating and persisting in a ``vexatious oral exchange'' with cole, and sutter was guilty of repeated ``aggressive, confrontational and particularly vexatious'' behavior, the committee said
cole, a specialist in african-american music and author of books on jazz musicians john coltrane and miles davis, sued the review for libel five years ago over an article questioning his competence and saying he ``looks like a used brillo pad.'' cole later dropped the suit
during nearly 16 hours of hearings last weekend, the four students proclaimed their innocence and denied any racial motivation
founded in 1980 with support from such conservatives as patrick buchanan and william f. buckley, the review repeatedly has been accused of insensitivity to blacks, women and homosexuals
baldwin led the group that approached cole in a recital hall after the professor finished a class
baldwin said the review wanted to give cole another chance to respond to an article in the review several days earlier. in that article the review printed remarks, including profanities, that cole made in a telephone interview
witnesses who testified before the committee last weekend agreed that cole became agitated and yelled and cursed when the four approached him. cole testified that he felt harassed and provoked, and he accused the review of bigotry
the invasion of privacy charge arose because cole was photographed and tape-recorded without permission
one witness, luzmila johnson, head of the afro-american society at dartmouth, testified that sutter uttered a racial slur as he left the recital hall. sutter vehemently denied the charge
two years ago, 12 people, most of them review members, mounted a sledgehammer attack on symbolic anti-apartheid shanties on the college green
three of the students were suspended. seven others received community-service sentences, including baldwin
dartmouth has nearly 4,100 undergraduates, nearly 7 percent of them black. bush</head>
republican party officials said thursday they intend to award puerto rico's 14 gop national convention votes to vice president george bush and are considering calling off the primary to do it
we haven't canceled the primary, but we are considering every way possible not to have one,'' gop vice chairman and local bush campaign manager jose dapena thompson said. ``the reason is simple: the nomination of george bush has been practically assured.''
however, the underlying issues at stake turn more on statehood for the u.s. commonwealth than on presidential politics
the republican primary is scheduled for march 20, when voters are to cast ballots for slates committed to bush; his main rival, sen. bob dole, r-kan.; or any other republican candidate as a write-in
bush needs 1,139 votes to win the gop presidential nomination. his total thursday was 705
dole's campaign chairman in puerto rico, alejandro cruz, agreed with dapena thompson, but he, too, was unsure whether it was possible to cancel the primary, or somehow to require dole's 14 delegates to vote instead for bush
the republican party will meet saturday to review its alternatives
a democratic primary also is set for march 20, at which 51 puerto rico's national elegates are at stake
the main issue for both parties is the political status of the commonwealth, whose citizens enjoy most every right and obligation as other americans with the exception that they cannot vote for president or congress, and pay no federal taxes
the popular democratic party of gov. rafael hernandez colon favors a continuation of commonwealth or limited autonomy. the opposition new progressive party, which has strong ties with the national republican party, wants puerto rico to be the 51st state
our first goal is statehood and we have to be united to fight for that,'' said dapena thompson, the mayor of the south coast city of ponce and the new progressive party's vice chairman
four presidential candidates _ two republicans and two democrats _ have sided with deaf students at gallaudet university who want a hearing-impaired person to head their school
sen. bob dole, r-kan., was the first to support the idea with a letter on feb. 18, before the selection of elisabeth ann zinser was made. zinser, who was named the school's president on sunday, is not deaf and does not know sign language
in his letter, dole noted the accomplishments of gallaudet, which is the nation's only school for the deaf, and asked, ``isn't it time for the university to once again lead the way, instead of following it, and place a deaf individual in a position of public responsibility?''
vice president george bush's support came next, in a letter march 1 to the committee searching for a new school president
as an entity funded by the federal government, gallaudet has a responsibility to set an example and thus to appoint a president who is not only highly qualified, but who is also deaf,'' he wrote
the march 6 appointment of zinser, an administrator at the university of north carolina at greensboro, set off demonstrations by students, alumni and faculty at gallaudet that have virtually paralyzed the campus
the protests drew support from two democratic presidential hopefuls
democrat jesse jackson on wednesday issued a statement supporting the demonstrations and saying, ``the problem is not that the students do not hear. the problem is that the hearing world does not listen.''
illinois sen. paul simon, also running for the democratic nomination, on thursday called for zinser's resignation
simon, a longtime member of the senate labor and human resources subcommittee on the handicapped, which has jurisdiction over funding for gallaudet, said zinser's appointment was a ``slap in the face to the entire purpose of the university.''
simon, who wears two hearing aids to compensate for a hearing impairment, cited the job listing placed by the school's presidential search committee, which said, in part:
broad and deep knowledge of deafness and the variety of issues important to the higher education of hearing impaired persons is necessary.''
even if elisabeth zinser were deaf,'' simon said, ``the fact that she doesn't meet this qualification demonstrates that she is not the best candidate for the job.''
tate said more than half the campaign's 300 staffers were being laid off
she declined to say who among the national staff was being let go, saying workers were still being notified thursday evening
it is significant _ it ranges from the top to the bottom in every department,'' she said of the layoffs
some of the layoffs had been planned for the period following super tuesday, regardless of its outcome, she said
but dole's campaign was reeling from its complete, 17-state loss on that day. vice president bush won in 16 of the states and took a giant step toward the gop nomination
you have a much different campaign staff when you're trying to compete in 17 states at once'' rather than one at a time, she said
she said the key members of dole's traveling staff would be unaffected by the cutbacks, naming press secretary mari maseng, adviser thomas rath, campaign chairman william brock and consultant kim wells
she said the campaign would keep ``a full complement'' of staff in illinois
the news of the cutbacks came as dole continued to campaign in illinois _ a state he said on wednesday that he had to win
on thursday, he appeared to back off on that contention, saying instead he had to ``do very well'' in the state. he dismissed questions from reporters on whether he was scaling down his expectations in the state
at one point, however, he addressed the possibility of dropping out, saying: ``i've been in this business long enough to know that there comes a time you have to say, well, maybe it would happen.'' bush</head>
