a storm dumped heavy snow in utah, colorado and wyoming, covering some mountain areas with up to 28 inches, shutting down highways and abruptly ending spring-like weather in the region
the storm also generated high winds in the central and southern rockies and the central and southern plains, creating blizzard conditions in some areas
winter storm advisories, watches and warnings were posted in the rockies and northern plains through friday. up to 16 inches of snow were expected in colorado's mountains overnight
in utah's mountains, 28 inches of snow blanketed brian head by thursday morning. elsewhere in the state, little cottonwood canyon got 18 inches, and big cottonwood canyon and solitude 8 inches
snow was heavy in parts of western wyoming, with a foot of new snow at casper mountain and rock springs, and wind gusts to 50 mph created blizzard conditions
more than 200 miles of interstate 80 were shut down in southern wyoming between laramie and rock springs, and numerous roads in wyoming were closed
about 4,000 state employess left work early in cheyenne and caspar, and many schools closed early
snow also fell over parts of western and central montana and south dakota
as the storm moved eastward, the temperature fell dramatically. rapid city, s.d., had a high in the low 70s on wednesday, but readings climbed only into the mid-30s early thursday afternoon
temperatures elsewhere in the northern high plains were 20 to 30 degrees lower than readings on wednesday
gusty winds also buffeted western kansas, the nebraska panhandle and southern new mexico, where ruidoso had winds up to 63 mph
rainshowers were scattered across the carolinas into northern georgia as a storm system slowly moved into the atlantic ocean
heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 1.20 inches at fayetteville, n.c., 0.91 inch at charlotte, n.c., 0.86 inch at florence, s.c., 0.82 inch at key west, fla., and 0.67 inch at hickory, n.c
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 21 degrees at yellowstone park, wyo., to 89 degrees at cotulla, texas. the morning low was 3 degrees at gunnison, colo
friday's forecast called for snow from the plains of wyoming and northern colorado through the upper mississippi valley, showers and a few thunderstorms scattered across the central plains and lower missouri valley, from much of kansas and western missouri into central iowa and southern wisconsin, and mostly sunny or partly cloudy skies elsewhere
high temperatures were expected to reach the 40s, 50s or 60s across much of the nation, with readings in the 20s from wyoming to the northern great lakes and across northern new england, in the 30s from the northern rockies through the central intermountain region, the central high plains into central wisconsin and northern michigan as well as central new england, in the 70s across the southern california coast and from the upper rio grande valley through northern texas, the lower mississippi valley and gulf coast into much of florida, and in the 80s across southern texas
african governments more than nature now cause the famines that threaten millions of lives, a reagan administration official told congress thursday
although natural factors are still present and important in each of these countries, man-made factors predominate and drive the seemingly intractable emergency situations and ever-escalating needs,'' said charles l. gladson, assistant administrator for africa of the agency for international development
he listed as the ``most obvious'' factors:
_internal strife and civil wars
_policies that fail to give incentives to farmers to grow enough food
_poorly developed infrastructure, such as roads and railroads
_governments incapable of coordinating relief
gladson's testimony was prepared for a hearing by the house select committee on hunger and the foreign affairs subcommittee that deals with africa. the hearing dealt with the crisis in angola, mozambique, ethiopia and sudan
even in the best of times, ethiopia cannot feed itself with its current policies,'' said roy stacy, deputy assistant secretary of state for africa
the u.s. government alone spent over $600 million for emergency aid to save lives, but without incentive farming policies such assistance does not result in recovery and provides little resistance to the next drought,'' he said
according to the hunger committee, a drought in ethiopia has again resulted in crop failures and a food deficit of 1.3 million metric tons, with 5.2 million to 8 million people at risk. it said the u.s. government has provided more than $100 million in aid in the current crisis
the administration view was endorsed by rep. tony roth, r-wis
ethiopia, mozambique and angola _ is there some reason that mother nature has singled out these three countries by chance? i don't think so,'' he said
all of these countries share one other common trait: their disastrous agricultural yields can be directly attributed to the failures of collectivized farming and to a patent disegard for human life,'' he said
all three have communist governments
he complained that a proposed resolution on famine relief, introduced by rep. tony p. hall, d-ohio, and mickey leland, d-texas, contained no condemnation of the ethiopian government of mengistu haile-mariam for withholding food as a means of combatting rebel forces
he also criticized the proposed resolution for suggesting that the u.s. government prevent refugees from crossing borders or going into relief camps
it seems to me altogether inappropriate for it to to be a policy of the u.s. government to prevent people from voting with their feet and escaping from a brutal dictatorship,'' he said
two 13-year-old girls were found guilty of involuntary manslaughter thursday in the slaying of a 12-year-old boy who was forced to drink lighter fluid and suffocated with a plastic bag over his head
police said the girls feb. 8 helped two teen-agers get into the victim's apartment, where the boys attacked antonio r. cooley for not letting them use a videotape recorder
the 15-year-old boys sprayed cooley with insecticide and forced him to drink charcoal lighter fluid while he screamed for his life, authorities said. a deputy coroner said cooley was suffocated with a bag
as judge arthur o. fisher of juvenile court read the verdict in the non-jury trial, the two girls sat almost motionless, and one mouthed a curse. the other clutched a stuffed bear and sobbed lightly as she was led away
they were also found guilty of grand theft for helping steal cooley's stereo and videotape recorder
the girls, whose identities were not released because of their age, were being held in a youth detention center
the judge could order them held for a year, and state officials then could decide whether to hold them until age 21, siad assistant prosecutor debra armanini. no sentencing date was set
the judge said the girls helped the two boys get into cooley's apartment while his father was at work, knowing the boys intended to beat cooley and steal several electronic items
prosecutors are seeking to have the two 15-year-olds tried as adults on charges including aggravated murder and aggravated robbery
defense attorneys argued the girls did not know cooley was to die. but the judge said even if the girls had warned cooley, as they testified, they still were guilty for not trying to prevent the attack
a 13-year-old accomplice has pleaded guilty to involuntary manslaughter and theft and awaits sentencing. the defense at the girls' trial contended the 13-year-old kept the girls in a back room while the older boys did the killing
i think the verdict sends a message across this city that the courts are not going to permit anyone, no matter what their age, to take part in a scheme or plan to snuff out another life,'' said assistant prosecutor mathias heck jr
col. jean-claude paul is a household name in the capital port-au-prince, but one that few people are comfortable speaking out loud
paul was indicted wednesday on drug trafficking charges in u.s. district court in miami, but many radio stations in the haitian capital chose not to broadcast the news. of those that did, only one, the roman catholic station radio soleil, identified paul by name
we're not yet going to announce the news ... for security reasons,'' a reporter at the independent station radio metropole said thursday, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``we've already received threats. we'll announce the news when it's formally made public.''
paul has been prominent in the impoverished caribbean nation of 6 million since he was promote to colonel and given command of the 700-man dessalines battalion in january 1986
the battalion, quartered in a low-slung, mustard colored building adjacent to the national palace, was involved in almost every incident last summer in which soldiers broke up peaceful anti-government demonstrations. more than 30 people were killed and 200 wounded
opposition leaders blame the battalion for standing by idly nov. 29 while gunmen in the capital killed at least 34 people, forcing the cancellation of what would have been haiti's first free presidential vote in 30 years
paul refused requests to be interviewed at that time. his colleagues and superiors have publicly defended and shielded him
leslie manigat was elected president jan. 17 in balloting boycotted by the opposition and marked by widespread irregularities
a communique three weeks ago by army chief of staff gen. carl nicolas rebutted the ``so-called involvement of (paul) in affairs of drug trafficking.''
col. gary leon, a spokesman for the military, refused a request thursday by the associated press for biographical information on paul
nevertheless, a sketchy picture of paul emerged from interviews with acquaintances, colleagues and foreign observers, most of whom spoke on condition their names not be used
paul was born in 1938 to a family that supported dictator francois ``papa doc'' duvalier
his father was a high-ranking member of the tontons macoute private militia. it was organized by duvalier to throttle political opposition and challenge the power of the army, which launched several coups against duvalier after his election in 1957
paul's brother alexandre was haiti's consul general to the bahamas and the united states, based in miami, until the duvalier family dictatorship ended in february 1986 with the flight of jean-claude duvalier to france following popular demonstrations
as a young officer, paul was a protege of francois duvalier's finance minister, clovis desinor. he rose through the ranks during the 1970s and served with the elite leopards counterinsurgency squad before taking command of the dessalines battalion
rumors of paul's alleged involvement with cocaine trafficking surfaced in march 1987 when his ex-wife, marie merielle delinois, was arrested in miami on drug charges. she pleaded innocent, was released on $250,000 bond and promptly fled
paul and his brother antonio face three drug counts _ conspiracy to distribute, distribution and attempted importation of cocaine into the united states. they could face up to 45 years in prison and $375,000 in fines if they are convicted. ms. delinois was also indicted
jean-claude paul's activity in cocaine smuggling is well known,'' said one western diplomat in a recent interview. ``he has a landing strip near thomozeau,'' a village about 90 miles northeast of the capital near haiti's border with the dominican republic
raymond joseph, publisher of the brooklyn, n.y.-based newspaper ``haiti observateur,'' said the colonel has several houses in and around the capital, in addition to a cattle ranch in thomozeau
paul, a short, stocky man who customarily wears a ring, bracelet and necklace of heavy gold, lives above his salary of $1,800 a month, said joseph
the mission of dessalines battalion is to help police provide order in the capital. paul is seen most frequently in public providing security for top government officials
the western diplomat said paul is popular with his troops and pays them extra from his own pocket
he (paul) ignores the chain of command,'' said the diplomat, who added that paul incorporated about 100 tontons macoutes into his battalion and helped others flee haiti at the end of the duvalier dictatorship
he is capable of making a coup d'etat,'' the diplomat said
howard stern, a radio personality known for his outrageous, innuendo-laced broadcasts, is the target of a federal investigation begun after he bragged on the air about getting drugs for someone, according to a published report
the new york daily news on wednesday said it learned of the investigation from a letter to the newspaper from michael levine, a drug enforcement administration agent
levine said stern, who has come under fire from the federal communications commission for his broadcasts, bragged on his morning radio show monday of getting drugs for an unidentified guest on his cable tv special ``howard stern's underpants and negligee party,'' shown feb. 27
maybe somebody should have warned him (stern) that he was admitting to the commission of a federal and state felony,'' levine said
the daily news, citing unidentified sources, said that dea agents had taken the unusual step of clearing the investigation with the u.s. attorney's office. because of stern's habit of making outrageous statements on radio, investigators wanted to know if the office would press charges, the newspaper said
robert stutman, head of the new york dea office, said levine's letter was written without his office's knowledge. he declined comment on any investigation
stern, whose morning radio program is heard on wxrk-fm in new york and on wysp-fm in philadelphia, could not be reached for comment. a message left at the new york station was not immediately returned thursday
stern's radio broadcasts are filled with veiled and obvious references to sex and other bodily functions. he testified at an fcc hearing in april, and the commission warned him to avoid certain sexual innuendoes and double entenderes
the fcc said stern's broadcasts ``dwelt on sexual and excretory matters in a pandering and titillating fashion that was patently offensive as measured by contemporary community standards.''
but because the fcc's own standards for decency may have been unclear, the commission said it was forced to limit its sanction against stern to a warning. becomes youngest state prisoner, quote from mother. picks up 8th graf pvs, `defense attorney ...'</note>
a 15-year-old boy who beat a classmate to death with a baseball bat to find out what it was like to kill someone was convicted of second-degree murder thursday and sentenced to life in prison
rod matthews, who was 14 when he lured shaun ouillette into the woods with a promise of fireworks, showed no emotion when the verdict was announced. he had been expressionless throughout the weeklong trial, sitting with his eyes downcast
matthews will be eligible for parole in 15 years
carrying a portrait of her son and choking back tears, jeanne quinn, the victim's mother, said she had hoped matthews would not be eligible for parole, which would have been the case if he had been convicted of first-degree murder
he planned this. i'm sorry. fifteen years. no, i'm sorry, that's wrong,'' said mrs. quinn. ``shaun is not coming home in 15 years, is he? he's not ever coming home.''
the trial in this suburb 15 miles south of boston was highlighted by graphic descriptions of the slaying and testimony from two young people who described how matthews plotted the killing and then took them to see the bludgeoned body in the woods in canton
matthews' family, including two sisters and a brother, was escorted out of court by officers shielding them from journalists. kenneth matthews, the father, said he felt his son belonged in a treatment facility rather than in prison
matthews becomes the youngest of more than 6,500 inmates in the state's prisons, possibly the youngest ever, said correction department spokeswoman mary mcgeown
it's terrible,'' said matthews' mother, janice. ``a child shouldn't be persecuted and forced to go through something like this. they're children. god only knows how much worse it's going to make his condition.''
defense attorney john philip white had argued that matthews should be acquitted by reason of insanity. he portrayed him as a mentally unstable child whose pleas for help were ignored by teachers and friends, and as someone adversely affected by taking the drug ritalin to control hyeractivity
white said after the verdict that he was concerned about matthews' safety at the adult prison at walpole and about ``the suicidal ideation he has shown.''
norfolk county superior court judge roger j. donahue said defense attorneys could appeal the verdict within 30 days. donahue rejected a defense motion to reconsider the sentence and classify matthews as a juvenile
the jurors had deliberated for nearly 10 hours over two days before making their decision
norfolk county assistant district attorney peter casey called the decision an ``appropriate, well-counseled verdict.''
the widely publicized case was compared to the trial of anthony broussard, 18, sentenced to 25 years to life in 1982 in san jose, calif., for killing his girlfriend. broussard took at least 13 schoolmates to see the victim's body and the movie ``the river's edge'' was based on that case
two child behavior specialists testified that matthews did not experience classic symptoms of psychosis and that continued use of ritalin could not have triggered violent behavior
but a doctor said monday that matthews' irrational conduct may have been exacerbated by the drug, which matthews had been taking since the third grade
two friends of matthews', rob peterson and jonathan cash, testified earlier this week that matthews told them of his desire to kill in the fall of 1986. they said two potential victims were mentioned and rejected before matthews decided on ouillette
no charges were filed against peterson and cash
matthews chose ouillette because he felt he would not be missed, the teen-agers said. ouillette, 14, was relatively new to canton, his family having moved there two years before the slaying
witnesses said matthews befriended ouillette before he lured him to the wooded area after school on nov. 20, 1986. he hit ouillette on the head with a baseball bat at least three times. matthews recalled ouillette cried for help, the friends testified
matthews took peterson to see the body several hours after the slaying and they hid a knife matthews planned to use to cut off ouillette's arms and legs
several days later, peterson and cash went with matthews to see the body after a pre-thanksgiving pep rally at canton high school
police found the body on dec. 15, 1986, after receiving an anonymous letter sent by cash
matthews told a psychiatric counselor after the slaying that he first decided to kill someone after viewing the videotape ``faces of death,'' which depicts animal and human deaths
about 200 students from the national technical institute for the deaf rallied thursday in support of demands by students at washington's gallaudet university for a hearing-impaired president
we will keep the spirit. the spirit shall never die,'' said scot atkins, a spokesman for the ntid students. ``it's time for a deaf president at gallaudet.''
the protests came in response to the appointment of elisabeth ann zinser, who can hear, as president of gallaudet. the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf has not had a hearing-impaired president in its its 124-year history
gallaudet students have said zinser is not welcome on campus, and they have called for the resignation of jane bassett spilman, chairwoman of the school's board of trustees
at ntid, students carried signs with slogans such as ``it ain't over till the hearing ladies quit'' and ``deaf people have been ready to function forever,'' and chanted, signed and waved their arms over their heads
deaf people can be president. we can do anything we want. and the idea that we can't is just nonsense,'' said student linda whitmore, through an interpreter. ``i plan to work with hearing people when i graduate.''
ntid, with an enrollment of 1,250, is a part of rochester institute of technology and offers two-year programs in such fields as business, computers, engineering and architecture
some of the students go on to gallaudet or to rit, said ntid spokesman vince dollard
two busloads of students and numerous cars with a total of about 150 people were scheduled to leave the campus at midnight for a rally friday in washington
atkins said thursday's rally and the support for gallaudet's students has nothing to do with ntid, whose director and president both can hear
they've been very good to us and we've been very good to them and we have no problem with the way things are here,'' he said
armenian nationalists claimed wednesday that ethnic clashes in the southern soviet republic of azerbaijan killed more than 1,500 armenians
the armenian revolutionary federation made the claim in statements issued by its headquarters in athens and an office in nicosia. there was no way to verify the report
soviet officials have said 32 people died in the unrest last week, but armenian nationalists in moscow have said the toll was much higher. foreign correspondents have not been allowed to travel to the region
the violence against the armenian population has reached the scale of a massacre,'' said the group
the federation said more than 1,500 armenians have been confirmed dead as a result of ``mob attacks.''
tension between armenians and residents of azerbaijan erupted in violence feb. 28 in the azerbaijan city of sumgait. the unrest was triggered by armenian demands that nagorno-karabakh, a predominantly armenian region in azerbaijan, be annexed to neighboring armenia
simom ainedjian, spokesman for the armenian group in nicosia, told the ap the group's sources were contacts in armenia. the statement from athens cited reports from sources in moscow, karabakh and the armenian capital of yerevan
the statement said moslem azeris, natives of azerbaijan, attacked the christian armenians in sumgait. it said the azeris blew up many armenian buildings ``with the result that the tenants were buried in the ruins.''
a group affiliated with the federation, the armenian national committee, also said in athens wednesday that more than 1,500 people were killed in the clashes
a spokesman for the committee identified its source as armen sahakian, an armenian dissident living in moscow
we've had similar information from other dissidents and in telephone calls with people living in yerevan, but he is our main source,'' the spokesman, jirayr beudjian, told the associated press
beudjian said sahakian had met with people that fled to moscow from the two republics
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev met with the leaders of armenia and azerbaijan in moscow wednesday to discuss the ethnic unrest
seagram co. said thursday it is buying the makers of tropicana orange juice in a $1.2 billion transaction dubbed the ``screwdriver deal.''
we have already broadened our base with seagram's (wine) coolers, and tropicana is another step in this direction,'' chairman edgar m. bronfman said in announcing the purchase of tropicana products from beatrice u.s. food corp
the deal will be financed initially with a combination of bank loans and short-term borrowings, said the canadian liquor and beverage giant
market watchers jokingly called the sale the ``screwdriver deal'' in a reference to the popular cocktail made of vodka and orange juice
montreal-based seagram is best known for its distilled spirits and wines but in recent years has moved into the manufacturing of wine coolers and sells cocktail mixers such as tonic, seltzer and ginger ale under the seagram's name
seagram is also acquiring french cognac producer martell &amp; co
securities analysts said the move into the orange juice business was a logical step for seagram
they understand the business, and it's growing, unlike most of their liquor products,'' said ian osler, an analyst with prudential-bache securities in toronto
however, the new york credit-rating firm standard &amp; poor's corp. said the pending sale had negative debt implications for both seagram and beatrice
s&amp;p said the deal would reduce seagram's dependence on distilled spirits but increase the company's debt load, raising questions about seagram's ability to absorb both tropicana and martell
tropicana, with headquarters in bradenton, fla., had sales of about $750 million in its last fiscal year, which ended feb. 29, said marcelline thomson, a seagram spokeswoman
seagram earned nearly $423.5 billion on sales of $3.3 billion in the fiscal year ending jan. 31, 1987, and reported a profit of more than $402.4 million on sales of $2.6 billion for the nine months ending oct. 31, ms. thomson said
beatrice u.s. food corp., based in chicago, is a division of beatrice co., whose holdings include hunt's tomato products, wesson oil, swift-ekrich inc. meats, peter pan peanut butter and orville redenbacher popcorn. other detail; picks up 11th pvs `hanspeter kirchhofer ...' and subs 15th `charles, diana ... to conform</note>
an avalanche roared down on prince charles's skiing party thursday, killing a close friend. the future british king was unhurt, but a witness said he trembled and wept as a rescue helicopter arrived
swiss officials had warned earlier thursday of possible avalanches in the area
the dead skier was identified as maj. hugh lindsay, 34, a former aide to queen elizabeth ii, the prince's mother. buckingham palace said another skiier, patricia palmer-tomkinson, suffered leg injuries
press association, the british domestic news agency, said charles helped dig the victims out of the snow
charles was not injured, and his wife diana and pregnant sister-in-law the duchess of york were safe in a chalet at the time of the avalanche, said the palace statement issued in london
there were calls in britain for members of the royal family to take more care. press association said the dutchess of york, the wife of charles's younger brother prince andrew, had a fall earlier in the day from which she emerged wet and shaken. she was told to spend the afternoon resting
prince andrew was not on the ski trip
queen elizabeth and her husband, prince philip, were attending an official engagement in london when informed of the avalanche. the queen later talked to charles, 39, at the alpine chalet where the royal party had stayed since arriving tuesday
witnesses on the mountain said charles, the prince of wales and heir to the throne, looked distraught after the avalanche buried two of the six people in his party. one said he was weeping and shaking when the helicopter came
buckingham palace said charles and the others were off the main ski trails near an extremely steep run, and were stationary when the snow began to move
charles has vacationed in the klosters ski area for years, knows it well and is considered good on the slopes
the party, including a guide, was on mount gotschnawang when the snow rushed down from about 100 yards above at 2:50 p.m., said officials of the grisons canton, or state
lindsay and mrs. palmer-tomkinson were flown to a hospital in davos, the officials said
according to the palace statement, ``all members of the party were in a position to take avoiding action with the exception of maj. lindsay and mrs. palmer-tomkinson who were both caught in the avalanche.''
another statement thursday night said: ``the prince of wales and the whole party are naturally extremely distressed by this tragic accident which resulted in the death of their close friend maj. hugh lindsay and serious injury to mrs. patti palmer-tomkinson.''
hanspeter kirchhofer, an investigating magistrate in davos, said mrs. palmer-tomkinson was being treated for fractures of both legs and was ``doing well under the circumstances.''
the gotschnawang station on the cable car, which skiiers ride up the mountain, is at 7,540 feet and the prince's party had skied down to about 5,800. the swiss federal avalanche research institute had warned of considerable avalanche danger above 5,200 feet in northern grisons
lindsay was the 12th snowslide victim of the winter in switzerland
earlier thursday, a polish mountain climber was killed on the north wall of mount eiger, about 95 miles to the southwest
charles, diana and the duchess of york posed for photographers wednesday at klosters. the 28-year-old duchess, the former sarah ferguson, is expecting her first baby in august
lindsay was a close friend of charles and diana, who attended his wedding last july. he frequently accompanied them on their annual ski holiday at klosters
mrs. palmer-tomkinson and her husband, charles, also vacation with the royal couple at klosters
harold brooks-baker, publisher of the burke's peerage directory of the aristocracy, said his representative in switzerland told him the royal party was warned of the avalanche danger
we have constantly suggested to the royal family that they be more prudent,'' he told a reporter. ``they constantly act as though nothing can harm them. ... after all, these people don't belong just to families but to the world.''
charles had a spectacular crash on gotschnawang in 1979, landing on his hip and escaping unhurt. secretary's testimony.</note>
gov. evan mecham's last chief of staff testified thursday that he would not have responded as the governor did to reports that another official threatened a former mecham aide who was a grand jury witness
but richard burke, a former u.s. attorney and justice deparment official who was the first defense witness at mecham's impeachment trial, refused to say whether he thought the governor obstructed the investigation of the alleged threat
i don't think i should comment on that,'' burke said, as members of the arizona senate pressed him for a legal opinion. ``i think the governor would have a very different view of that than i would.''
mecham, 63, is accused of obstructing justice by telling the state's top police official not to give the attorney general information about the alleged threat
he also is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 from a state fund, but the senate is hearing testimony on the obstruction charge first
mecham, who has not appeared at the impeachment trial since it began feb. 29, also faces a criminal trial april 21 on felony charges of concealing the $350,000 and a recall election may 17
the first-term republican is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades
burke, who tried to reorganize the chaotic mecham offices in the two months before the governor's impeachment, said he believed that the reported threat was serious and that mecham should have fired the accused aide, lee watkins, much earlier than he did
i certainly took it as a serious threat,'' said burke. ``it wasn't a threat of tiddlywinks. i think all of us assumed it was a crime or a potential crime or it wouldn't have been reported to us.''
according to testimony in the impeachment trial, mecham first was told nov. 13 that watkins threatened former mecham adviser donna carlson, saying she might go ``on a long boat ride'' if she talked to a grand jury investigating finances of mecham's 1986 campaign
watkins has denied threatening ms. carlson. last week he refused to testify when called as a prosecution witness
ralph milstead, director of the department of public safety, said he was told nov. 15 by mecham to refuse any request for information by the attorney general. he has said he did cooperate, however
mecham has testified in house impeachment hearings that he may have told milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general
in other developments, a secretary to peggy griffith, the official who first reported the alleged death threat, said that her boss often exaggerated things and that she questioned mrs. griffith's version of what occurred
but when senators asked her for examples of exaggerations, the secretary, terri elaine fields, paused and said, ``i can't even think of any right now.''
under questioning by mecham attorney fred craft, burke said the governor was ill-served by his subordinates because they did not give him complete information on the alleged threat quickly enough
but on cross-examination, house prosecutor william french honed in on mecham's exact instructions to milstead: ``would you say this: `don't tell the attorney general anything?'''
no,'' said burke
would you say this to col. milstead: `never. don't give him any help?''
no,'' said burke
burke, in apparent agreement with a number of prosecution witnesses, said political loyalty impelled the governor to ignore staff warnings and support watkins
why was mr. watkins not let go at an earlier date?'' asked democratic sen. lela alston
burke replied that mecham ignored nearly unanimous advice from his staff to fire watkins
i think the governor felt a great deal of loyalty to mr. watkins,'' said the witness, ``because mr. watkins hd been very active and supportive of his campaign.''
prosecution witnesses have suggested watkins won favor by raising money for mecham's campaign. they said watkins told of being rewarded with a state job and intimated he had information which could bring down the mecham administration
a two-thirds vote in the senate is required to convict mecham on impeachment charges and remove him from office. senators then could take another vote and forbid him from holding state office again
a swiss tycoon involved in a plan to build an iraqi oil pipeline attended an event thursday with shimon peres, whom he allegedly tried to bribe into guaranteeing the line's safety
bruce rappaport joined the foreign minister at a haifa university symposium on heart disease, which rappaport financed. he denied offering peres a bribe and said he would ``tell all at the appropriate time and place'' about the $1 billion pipeline project
peres angrily brushed aside questions about the pipeline case, which also has been linked to edwin meese iii, the u.s. attorney general
my name is not connected with anything and i don't want you to connect it,'' peres said, interrupting a reporter. ``did anyone say they gave me anything? did anyone say they promised me anything? please, a little fairness.''
rappaport told reporters israel lost $60-$70 million because the project was not built _ the sum it was to receive for promising not to bomb the line
he said peres, then prime minister, gave the guarantee after consulting yitzhak shamir, who then was foreign minister, and two other cabinet ministers
there was never a question of giving this sum to ministers or a political party and the only one who would have benefited from the deal would have been the israeli treasury,'' the israeli news agency itim quoted rappaport as saying
in washington, independent counsel james mckay is investigating whether meese violated a law that prohibits payment of bribes to foreign officials by u.s. companies and authorizes the attorney general to intervene to block them
the investigation stems from a 1985 memo to meese from his longime friend e. robert wallach, who had been hired as legal counsel by rappaport to help secure u.s. support for the pipeline project
wallach's memo says payments were planned to the israeli labor party, which peres leads, in connection with the pipeline. meese has said he does not recall reading the portion that mentioned payments to the party
a treaty requiring nations to prosecute or extradite terrorists who commit acts of violence on the high seas was signed by 23 countries thursday, including the united states
agreement comes more than two years after palestinian terrorists hijacked the italian cruise ship achille lauro and killed an american passenger
representatives from 53 other nations, including the soviet union, israel, egypt and libya expressed approval of the document, the first maritime convention against terrorism
i have a very vivid memory of the achille lauro and i can only feel the deepest emotion today,'' said u.s. ambassador maxwell rabb, who signed for the united states. ``this document corrects a tremendous void in the law of terrorism.''
the treaty still must be formally ratified by the governments that signed
a u.s. government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he expected most of the 53 other countries would sign within a year. he said many representatives wanted their governments to review the treaty before signing
the palestine liberation organization sent observers to the treaty conference
the treaty requires ratifying countries to make it a crime to commit violent acts against ships or the people aboard them. it also covers oil rigs or platforms anchored to the bottom of the sea and the people aboard them
the countries agree to either prosecute or extradite terrorists who commit violent acts at sea. a country whose citizens are victims of an attack can seek extradition of the terrorists
the treaty was the final document of a 10-day conference of diplomats and international law specialists convened by the london-based international maritime organization, an agency of the united nations
italy, egypt and austria requested the convening of such a conference in 1986, following the achille lauro hijacking. the ship was seized off egypt and many passengers were austrian
the u.s. government official said the treaty ``clarifies which countries have the criminal jurisdiction to prosecute people who commit acts of violence on vessels outside their territorial waters.''
he said it fills ``a gap in international anti-terrorist law.''
in october 1985, four palestinian terrorists hijacked the achille lauro, killing leon klinghoffer, a 69-year-old passenger from new york confined to a wheelchair. at the time, the united states accused italy of releasing mohammed abbas, the accused mastermind of the hijacking who was later convicted in absentia by an italian court of the murder
president reagan said thursday the reunification of germany could result from efforts to resolve east-west differences over berlin's divided status
reagan spoke in an interview with the washington correspondent of zdf television, which broadcast excerpts on its evening newscast
the u.s. president repeated a suggestion that the olympic games be held in both halves of divided berlin. he also said he hoped berlin could become an international meeting place and an air traffic transportation center
reagan was asked about the possibility of a future reunification of the two germanys as a consequence of improved east-west dialogue
maybe out of these things (talks about berlin's status) reunification could grow,'' reagan replied
the president said holding the olympic games in berlin would be an ``important contribution toward peaceful development between east and west.''
reagan first suggested the games be held in berlin during a visit to the city last year
reagan said the berlin wall would continue to be an important issue in talks with soviet officials
the german state was divided into communist east germany and pro-western west germany following the defeat of adolf hitler's third reich in world war ii
a tobacco-company representative who telephoned jurors during a $17 million liability suit against the makers of pall mall cigarettes did not break the law, a district attorney said thursday
we're not sure of the specifics of the calls but in essence it was simply a case of trying to be friendly or trying to help _ even being a bit nosy,'' frank carlton said in detailing the findings of a state investigation
the investigation followed january's trial of a suit brought against american brands inc. by the family of nathan henry horton, who died of lung cancer after smoking two packs a day of unfiltered pall malls for more than 30 years
a mistrial was declared in the case when jurors couldn't agree on a verdict
allegations of attempted jury tampering later surfaced, and norman clark, a jury consultant for the defense, said he had called jurors at one point to inform them that the judge was sick and that the day's session had been called off
what occurred was improper but being improper is not a crime,'' carlton said
the truth is there is not supposed to be contact with jurors during trial for any reason. even innocent contact can be misconstrued, as it was in this case.''
dirt collapsed in a gully where three boys were digging a hole, burying the youngsters and killing two despite neighbors' efforts to save them, police said. the third boy dug himself out
joel rogers and damon deakin, both 13, died wednesday evening, said police spokesman tony herrera
residents of the trailer park where the three lived saw the teen-agers digging in the gully then saw a cloud of dust, herrera said
neighbors who heard screams pulled joel out and were trying to revive him when officers arrived, herrera said. paramedics pulled damon out about 15 minutes later, he said
damon was pronounced dead at the scene and joel was pronounced dead at university of new mexico hospital
one of the boys, 14, whose name was withheld, dug out and went for help, herrera said
dave wild, a resident of the trailer park, said he had warned the boys of the danger of digging in the dry gully, or arroyo, but they continued to play, and moments later he saw a cloud of dust
i didn't think anything of it,'' he said. ``then i remembered the kids digging. i ran out and one of them was yelling that the other two were trapped inside. i jumped into the arroyo and started digging
i kept digging until i got to a foot, then i reached his head,'' he said. ``i pulled him out and he wasn't breathing.''
