iraq and iran said thursday they would stop rocketing each other's cities, but within hours both had launched new missile attacks
iraq fired three long-range missiles at tehran on thursday and two into qom. the iraqi news agency said the attacks brought to 51 the number of missiles fired at tehran since feb. 29
iran's official islamic republic news agency said iranian revolutionary guards fired two missiles into baghdad. iran has reported firing 27 missiles into the iraqi capital since feb 29
there was confusion over the timing of a possible cease-fire
an iraqi statement broadcast over baghdad radio and monitored in nicosia said the bombardment of tehran and other iranian cities would halt by 4 p.m. friday if the iranians stopped firing at iraq's cities
iranian prime minister hussein musavi said that iran would halt attacks on iraqi cities if iraq stopped attacking iranian cities, tehran radio reported
musavi said he was responding to a call by turkish prime minister turgut ozal, who asked iran and iraq to stop the ``war of the cities'' by thursday at 5 p.m
ozal sent messages to iran and iraq on wednesday asking them to end the bombardments on population centers
twenty diplomats and their families drove to turkey on wednesday night after evacuating tehran, the independent turkish hurriyet news agency reported. it said the group included diplomats from norway, finland, the netherlands, denmark, west germany and syria
iraq claimed that tehran triggered the latest round of the ``war of the cities'' by hitting baghdad with two missiles feb. 29
so the last bombardment should be iraq's before the cessation goes into effect,'' the statement said. ``if the enemy iranian regime attacks any of our cities ... in retaliation for the last iraqi bombardment, we will continue attacking.''
the statement came after a meeting of top iraqi officials chaired by president saddam hussein
iranian envoy mohammad ja'afar mahallati told a news conference at the united nations that iran would honor any unconditional truce called for by secretary-general javier perez de cuellar. he said iran would not fire back if iraq got in the last shot before any deadline set by perez de cuellar
we can respond to anyone _ but unconditionally, unconditionally,'' he said
the u.n. chief did not respond to mahallati's call. sources close to perez de cuellar said iran also insisted he condemn iraq for starting the missile duel, something he was unwilling to do
iran's islamic republic news agency said scores of civilians were killed or wounded in the latest iraqi missile attacks
in the event of a complete halt to the air and missile attacks by the iraqi regime, we too will stop these attacks,'' musavi told the state-run radio
but if the rulers of iraq refrain from accepting this request by turkey, we will strengthen the intensity of our retaliatory measures,'' he said in the broadcast, monitored by the british broadcasting corp
musavi said his nation was eager to defeat iraq on the ground and to end attacks on civilians
we believe that the war must take place chivalrously on the battlefields and that extending the hostilities to residential areas to victimize women and children signifies only the impotence of the party that started such a crime,'' he said
the all-swiss international committee of the red cross called the missile exchange a ``very grave violation'' of international humanitarian law. a statement issued in geneva said the icrc made a ``solemn appeal'' to end what it called ``this tragic escalation'' of the war
the official iraq news agency said ``a number of civilians'' were killed thursday in iranian shelling
iran said its warplanes attacked basra and al-amarah farther north
cities in western or central iran reported hit by iraqi warplanes on thursday included isfahan, hamadan, arak, dezful, shustar, shahr-e kord and burujerd. a mosque and a school were hit in isfahan, and two schools and a hospital were destroyed in shahr-kord, tehran radio said. iraq reported its planes also raided khorramabad, guilan-e-gharb, and sar-e-pol-zahab. spree</head>
a jury thursday convicted a man of murder and arson in a grisly crime spree that left five people dead, a verdict returned one day after a second jury in the rare ``dual trial'' convicted a co-defendant
one jury was selected for each defendant at the trial to save time and to prevent the possibility of publicity from one trial tainting potential jurors for a second
carl ``butch'' campbell, 28, and robert ahalt, 42, were accused of beating three people to death in a bar in 1986 during a robbery, then killing campbell and ahalt's girlfriends the next day in the women's homes
one of the women, who was six months' pregnant, was sexually mutilated and forced to eat glass before she and her fetus died. the bar and the women's homes were set afire
it was only the second time in new york legal history that two juries have been called on to listen to one case and give two verdicts
during the trial, the defendants sat at the same table, but the two juries sat on opposite sides of the courtroom, one in a specially built jury box
the juries and evidence were color coded. the jury considering ahalt's case wore blue lapel tags, and campbell's jury wore yellow tags
most testimony involved both cases, but when a witness was providing information that involved only one defendant, the other jury was taken from the room. the defendants testified in front of their own jury only
campbell, convicted thursday, faces a sentence of 115 years to life in prison. ahalt could receive up to 125 years to life. sentencing was set for april 7
each defendant was charged with three counts of arson, five of intentional murder, five of murder during the commission of a felony, in this case, robbery, and one of murder during a sexual assault
campbell was acquitted of a charge of murder during a robbery at the home of one of the women and both murder counts in the slaying of the woman at the other home. ahalt was acquitted of murder during a sexual assault
attorneys for both men had objected to the dual juries and said they would appeal the verdicts
state supreme court justice donald mark had originally said that the verdicts would have to be delivered at the same time
but four hours after the ahalt jury reached its decision wednesday night, campbell's attorney waived his client's right to have the verdicts announced simultaneously
killed at dick's 43 lounge were the bar's 75-year-old co-owner martha gruttadauria; her sister-in-law concetta amatore, also 75, and colin tuttle, 56, a patron
the next day, dorreen grachus, 28, and evelyn allen, 38, were found slain in their homes a half-mile apart. grachus, campbell's girlfriend, was pregnant. allen, ahalt's girlfriend, was beaten to death, police said
firefighters found all five bodies during fires
the first dual trial was held in 1984 in nassau county and involved two young men who were drag racing and were charged with criminally negligent homicide when their cars slammed into another car, killing the driver
that case has been appealed to the state's highest court, largely because of the dual trial format, said bruce whitney, a nassau county assistant district attorney. picks up 4th graf pvs, `railey has ...'; subs 18th graf pvs, `mrs. railey's ...' to correct first name to billie jo sted peggi; adds one graf with details on railey turning temporary custody over to minister.</note>
a former minister left two telephone messages for his wife the night she was choked nearly to death, describing his whereabouts in keen detail and giving times, and warning her to lock the garage door, according to tapes released thursday
walker railey told police he found 39-year-old margaret ``peggy'' railey unconscious on the floor of the garage at their lake highlands home shortly after midnight last april 22, choked with a cord. she remains in a coma
railey, 40, senior pastor of the prominent united methodist church of dallas at the time of the attack, claimed his family was the victim of a racially motivated attack. after a suicide attempt and reported refusal to testify before a grand jury, he resigned and moved to san francisco, leaving his children, ages 2 and 5, and wife in texas
railey has denied attacking his wife and vows he is innocent. he has not been charged but his lawyer said he was a prime suspect, and police hope to have railey answer more questions
prosecutors released the answering-machine messages for the first time thursday
if you want to, go ahead and lock the garage door and i'll park out front,'' railey said on the tape. ``it really doesn't matter to me at this point. my concern is that you're safe.''
one of the biggest discrepancies with the tapes is the time element. in the first message, railey told his wife he didn't have his watch on but thought it was about 10:30 p.m
telephone company records, however, indicate he placed the call at 12:04 a.m., dallas county assistant district attorney norman kinne said thursday
in the first message, which lasted more than 1{ minutes, railey told his wife twice to lock the door and described his step-by-step trail conducting research at two southern methodist university libraries
he explained that he had to leave one library when it closed and was on his way to another, and later called to explain that he was on his way home
i'm not calling on the private line because i know you're already asleep,' he said in the message saying he was on his way home, ``but in case you get up with the kids, i just wanted you to know that i'm on my way home. it's 12:30. i'll be home by about 12:45. love you, dear. bye bye.''
after waffling on the time in his first message, railey noted without hesitation in the second that the time was 12:29 a.m., a figure kinne said was confirmed to the minute by telephone company records
he told police he arrived home at 12:40 a.m. and found his wife unconscious
kinne initially refused to release the tapes, prompting abc news to file suit. the network's suit failed but kinne he decided to release the material after an appeals court ruled it was up to local officials to decide the issue
the attack occurred after railey appeared at an easter service in a bullet-proof vest, claiming racially motivated death threats had been made against him and his family because of his pro-civil rights stands
he produced typed letters that threatened his life, but police traced them to a typewriter in his church. the day police were scheduled to question him further, he attempted to commit suicide and left a note saying demons were torturing him
railey became less cooperative, eventually appearing before a grand jury last july when he reportedly cited his 5th amendment rights against self-incrimination 43 times
mrs. railey's mother and legal guardian, billie jo nicolai, filed a civil suit accusing railey of the crime. he has not yet responded to that lawsuit and must do so by monday
railey moved to san francisco late last year and signed a year's lease for an apartment with dallas psychologist lucy papillon
that apartment's telephone number is unlisted, and the associated press could not reach him for comment thursday
ms. papillon has reportedly told grand jurors that she and railey were having an affair and that he was with her at her home during part of the evening when mrs. railey was attacked
railey gave temporary legal custody of his children to a minister at the church where railey served. route</note>
eastern airlines inc. was held in contempt of court thursday for taking steps to sell its eastern air shuttle to its parent company, texas air corp., for $225 million
u.s. district judge john h. pratt ruled that the financially troubled miami-based airline had flouted his july 2, 1987 injunction directing eastern to maintain the status quo under its contract with a union that represents 12,000 employees of the airline
the preliminary injunction was issued in an different case last summer after the international association of machinists and aerospace workers, afl-cio, challenged eastern's plans to transfer ground crews and baggage handlers to a new subsidiary called air ground services inc
at the time, pratt ruled the proposed transfer of 6,000 iam members to the new subsidiary could not take place unless eastern bargained with the union
in thursday's opinion, pratt said the eastern's financial troubles ``do not change the fact that it proposed a `spin off' of the air shuttle ... in clear violation of our july 2, 1987 order, which, whatever doubts eastern had as to its meaning and application, it made no attempt to have clarified or modified.''
the judge noted that eastern announced the deal a day after it dropped its appeal of the preliminary injunction
pratt scheduled a march 18 hearing to determine what sanctions should be imposed against the airline
the court's order today sends a message to texas air that it is not above the law and it too must comply with the railway labor act,'' the union said in a statement from its district 100 headquarters in miami
an airline spokesman, robin matell, said: ``eastern's view is that the court's ruling is incorrect and we intend to file an expedited appeal. ... we are confident the court will rule in our favor.''
pratt agreed with the union's claim that steps taken last month toward the sale of eastern air shuttle _ which operates between boston, new york and washington _ to texas air amounted to a change in the status quo of the machinists' working conditions and therefore violated the injunction
the sale was announced last month pending federal aviation administration approval, which is not expected for at least another month
we find that the proposed `spin off' of eastern's air shuttle operations ... is not fundamentally different from the proposed `spin off' of eastern's fleet services employees to air ground services'' that was barred last summer, the judge said
the judge also determined that the ``proposed transfer to texas air significantly changes the working conditions of iam members'' and is therefore a major dispute under the railway labor act
the judge accepted the union's contention that spinning off the air shuttle could undermine the machinists' bargaining position with the company. if less than 50 percent of the spin off company's employees opt to join the iam, machinists who transferred to the new subsidiary from eastern would be without union representation, the judge noted
since texas air would be in control of the air shuttle operations including its labor policy, it will control the hiring,'' the judge said. ``it can thus manipulate the composition of its employees and alone determine whether such employees will qualify for union representation.''
the reagan administration thursday appealed a federal judge's order declaring unconstitutional regulations that would have cut off federal funding to family planning clinics that offer abortion counseling
the administration filed notice it was asking the 1st u.s. circuit court of appeals to overturn the march 3 ruling. no date was set for arguments
the ruling by u.s. district judge walter jay skinner was announced the day the regulations were to take effect. in response, the administration ordered health and human services offices nationwide not to enforce the regulations
the rules would have prevented federally funded family planning programs from providing abortion counseling, abortion referrals, and engaging in lobbying or legal action to increase availability of abortions
if the clinic also performed abortions, it would have to maintain separate facilities for those patients if it wanted to continue to receive federal funding under a provision of the public health service act of 1970
skinner said the regulations violated a woman's rights to privacy and to choose an abortion. ``abortion referral and abortion counseling are constitutionally protected speech under the first amendment,'' he said
about 5 million low- and moderate-income women receive services at the 4,000 clinics nationwide that would have been affected by the regulations announced in february by hhs secretary otis r. bowen
federal judges in colorado and new york had issued temporary injunctions against the regulations but skinner was the first to rule on their constitutionality
he ruled on an injunction requested by the massachusetts, the national family planning and reproductive health association and 13 other local and national family planning groups
diseases that now kill or cripple millions of children probably will be wiped out by the end of the century, a leading american health expert said thursday
the news on child survival is very good,'' said dr. william foege, head of the task force for child survival and former director of the centers for disease control in atlanta
by the end of the century we hope that measles will be reduced by 90 percent and that measle deaths, which are now over 2 million a year, will be reduced by 95 percent.''
measles was just one aspect of the optimistic vision foege presented to some of the world's leading experts on children, health and third world development
attending the meeting are barber conable, president of the world bank; james p. grant, director of unicef, the u.n. children's fund; halfdan mahler, head of the world health organization; leaders of more than a dozen other international aid agencies, doctors and health ministers from 11 developing countries
they will review a project that already is saving millions of lives and plan other efforts for the remainder of the century
the three-day symposium, at a 16th-century former monastery on the shores of lake annecy, is sponsored by the task force for child survival, whose members are unicef, the world health organization, the world bank, the u.n. development program and the rockefeller foundation
since the early 1980s, the organizations have been working together on an international campaign to immunize children against polio, diphtheria, whooping cough, tuberculosis and tetanus. the project, aimed particularly at developing countries, has been a great success
chinese officials said they believe 85 percent of china's 110 million children under age 7 will be vaccinated by the end of this year
the number of the world's children vaccinated against the five diseases has risen from 5 percent in 1974 to 50 percent today. experts attending the conference say predict virtually every child in the world will be immunized by the early 1990s
in a little over a decade, a public health revolution has quietly taken place,'' said dr. ralph h. henderson, director of the expanded who immunization program
he said the vaccination campaign against measles, neonatal tetanus, tuberculosis and whooping cough is saving the lives of more than 1 million children a year in poor countries. another 200,000 children are being saved from the paralysis of polio, henderson said
dr. ken warren of the rockefeller foundation called the project ``the single most remarkable example of international interagency cooperation i've ever seen.''
the task force took as its model a campaign against smallpox begun in 1966. in october 1978, the world was declared free of the disease
henderson said eradication of polio in the americas by 1990 is achievable and foege said experience gained in the next two years in the americas will allow the task force ``to set a reasonable date for eliminating polio from the world.''
polio already has been overcome in the united states, although cases sometimes are reported among immigrant groups
a world without polio would be a fitting gift from the 20th to the 21st century,'' henderson said
sen. bob dole said thursday he would not drop out of the republican presidential race, but confirmed that he had canceled all television advertising in advance of next tuesday's critical illinois primary. he also ordered deep layoffs in his campaign staff
even as dole issued a statement saying he was ``no dropout,'' campaign aides said dole had discussed abandoning his presidential bid. the kansas senator's campaign was gravely weakened by vice president george bush's sweep of 16 primaries on super tuesday
one aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said dole's private polls showed bush with a lead of between 15 and 20 percentage points in illinois, reflecting a significant jump for the vice president in the 48 hours since bush's stunning showing in this week's primries
an abc news poll released thursday night suggested bush led dole in illinois by a wide margin _ 58 percent to 31 percent
in his statement, dole did not say explicitly whether he would stay in the race if he lost illinois next tuesday. one aide said: ``i think it's clear to dole that it's do or die.''
several campaign sources said dole met with campaign manager bill brock and other aides over the last few days in illinois and discussed the possibility of quitting the race in the wake of bush's commanding lead in the race for national convention delegates
but dole decided to stay in
in his statement, issued in washington and illinois, dole ``categorically denied rumors'' that he would quit
bob dole's no dropout. i'm in this one to win,'' he said
in his statement, dole confirmed the sweeping staff cutbacks, but said they were sparked by the fact that the campaign no longer needed to run in so many states at once
dole said no cuts were involved in states with primaries after next tuesday
dole's statement also confirmed he had ordered his television ads shut down in illinois. but one source said the campaign may air a 30-minute paid broadcast in the closing hours of the illinois campaign
in the meantime, dole took another shot at bush
he said if the vice president still refuses to meet him in a series of one-on-one debates, they should agree to back-to-back, live one-hour press conferences staged before the illinois primary
the people of illinois and america have a right to see where george bush and bob dole stand on the issues,'' he said in his statement
bush, campaigning in illinois, was asked about the reports of dole considering withdrawal
i just heard that. i don't know anything about it,'' he told reporters in champaign, ill
bush's chief of staff craig fuller said the vice president was aware of the reports that dole was talking with aides abut whether to continue his campaign. he said bush's reaction was: ``we'll go about our business, do our job.''
earlier, campaign spokeswoman dale tate said more than half the dole campaign's 300 staffers were being laid off. many were still getting the word thursday evening
dole continued campaigning thursday in illinois. at one point he obliquely addressed the possibility of dropping out, saying: ``i've been in this business long enough to know that there comes a time you have to say, well, maybe it would happen.''
tate declined to say who among the national staff was being let go
it is significant _ it ranges from the top to the bottom in every department,'' she said of the cutback
some of the layoffs had been planned for the period following super tuesday, regardless of its outcome, she said. she said the key members of dole's traveling staff would be unaffected by the cutbacks, naming press secretary mari maseng, adviser thomas rath, campaign chairman william brock and consultant kim wells
tate said the campaign would keep ``a full complement'' of staff in illinois
