representatives of major u.s. protestant, eastern orthodox and roman catholic bodies have declared their solidarity with 18 organizations effectively silenced by south africa's government for opposing apartheid
officials of the national council of churches, including protestant and eastern orthodox denominations, pledged continued backing of the anti-apartheid efforts, and urged u.s. sanctions against south africa to spur ``peaceful change.''
archbishop john l. may of st. louis, president of the national conference of catholic bishops, called the new repressive measures an ``intolerable affront to the dignity'' of south africans, and voiced support of those working for ``a more just and democratic society.''
gideons international, which has supplied bibles to hotels, hospitals, prisons and schools since 1889, was cited for ``outstanding achievements in scripture distribution'' by the layman's national bible association
the interfaith association, which promotes bible reading, said the gideons have distributed over 400 million bibles in 137 countries. the 93,000-member organization currently places a million bibles every 15 days
presbyterians have ``got to figure out how to respect each other and learn from each other in our differences,'' says the moderator of the presbyterian church (usa)
isabel rogers, who holds the top titular office in the 3-million-member denomination, a merger of southern and norther branches, told a regional meeting:
my yearning is to identify ways to enable people in congrgations to talk to and listen to each other in trust.''
the u.s. supreme court has turned down a two-year-old legal effort to overturn an action by a former southern baptist president that voided a convention vote and helped consolidate power of a fundamentalist wing
the disputed parliamentary procedure occured in 1985 when the rev. charles stanley of atlanta headed the denomination, and a group of opponents have fought it since through district and appeals courts, which held they couldn't interfere in church matters
the supreme court declined to review those lower-court decisions
southern baptist home and foreign mission boards report that contributions to their denomination's program for world hunger relief in 1987 declined for the second year in a row
sums given fell to $8.9 million, a decline of 2.3 percent
the president of the rabbinical council of america says reactions of jewish groups to the riots in israel's occupied territories should be conveyed directly to israel's government and not made in the public media
rabbi milton h. polin, head of the orthodox body, said this applied to ``all expressions of support or criticism of israel.'' he said some advertised ``fringe'' jewish reaction has been ``especially odious.''
the presidential biblical scoreboard magazine, put out by right-wing evangelicals, has issued its 1988 survey ratings, scoring republican contenders from 40 to 95 and democrats from 0 to 15
comparing the candidates on a variety of what were termed family-moral-freedom issues, the magazine said the higher the score the more supportive the candidate is of bible-based issues
among the issues were abortion, abortion funding, capital punishment, school prayer, pornography, homosexuality and national security
the highest mark of 95 was given republican pat robertson, and the highest given a democrat was 15 to albert gore jr. except for paul simon, with a 5 score, the other democrats were marked zero
as he stripped and cleaned the ak-47 assault rifle on his desk, federal judge miguel angel izaguirre said he has good reason to try to stop latin american cocaine from reaching the streets of the united states
in 20 years, the youth that is taking all this cocaine will be running america and influencing latin america _ with the mentality of cokeheads,'' he said. ``north america's influence in this region is tremendous. so we latin americans have to try to ensure that american youth does not take cocaine.''
the 41-year-old izaguirre is the federal judge in this caribbean coastal town. he also is a weapons buff and student of military history
men, like arms, are proven on the field of battle,'' he said in an interview in his cramped and cluttered office that also contained an uzi submachine gun. ``and this is my field of battle.''
he has survived two attempts on his life, he said _ one with an incendiary bomb, the other a machine-gun attack on his home during which he returned fire with his soviet-made ak-47
i love the ak,'' he said. his arsenal of weapons, he explained, is ``to defend myself against the medellin cartel.''
the medellin cartel, named for the city in colombia where it is based, is believed responsible for more than 80 percent of the cocaine smuggled into the united states
they have tried to bribe me with money, women, airplanes and yachts,'' he said
leaning against the wall were five segments of hollowed out honduran redwood ostensibly intended for assembly into rustic doors. they are evidence from the biggest drug bust in u.s. history _ the confiscation in november of four tons of cocaine by u.s. federal agents in florida. the drug, shipped from the northern honduran coast, was hidden in the hollows
according to our information, the shipment was 8,000 kilos (almost 9 tons). so more than half of it got through,'' he said
u.s. authorities were greatly concerned when, over the past few years, honduras became an increasingly important transshipment point for colombian cocaine
izaguirre has been cited as a key man in joint u.s.-honduran efforts to reduce the flow
the judge said honduras, with its long and relatively unguarded coast and scores of clandestine air strips, provided the ideal midpoint for northbound shipments
when i came here in june 1987, i found a series of cases, all of which were being dismissed for lack of evidence. ... other judges had certain fears, some got sick, some left,'' he said. but within two months, he had handed down the first conviction and prison term for cocaine trafficking in honduran judicial history
he has convicted 10 others on drug charges, and has nearly three dozen suspected traffickers in jail awaiting judgment. two major traffickers based here, the colombian luis guerrero and the cuban-american rafael gonzalez, were extradited to the united states after being arraigned by izaguirre. they are both serving terms in u.s. prisons
izaguirre said he has given the maximum penalty under honduran law to all the drug traffickers he has convicted _ five years in prison and a 5,000 lempira ($2,500) fine. he complains, however, that the law is too lenient and would like to see penalties increased. he said the law provides the same penalties for cocaine trafficking as it does for marijuana trafficking
the judge _ divorced four times and the father of five children _ carries his weapons with him wherever he goes
if it befalls me to die in this post, then i'll die, without the slightest fear,'' he said
he keeps a .357 magnun revolver on his desk within easy reach
the judge insists he has no political ambitions, but maintains contact with a number of the country's political leaders
i tell them it is imperative that we verify the origin of the parties' funds. because if we don't, we're running the grave risk that the traffickers get their people elected to congress. then they reform the constitution in their favor, they gut the anti-narcotics law; they destroy us.''
though u.s. authorities have expressed concern that drug money has corrupted some officers in honduras' armed forces, izaguirre said the cooperation given him by the military has been ``total.''
he said his interest in the military began when he was 12 years old, with the reading of karl von clausewitz, the 19th century prussian general and writer of military strategy
i was two centimeters (about an inch) too short to get into the military academy,'' he said. ``but if i had, i'm sure i would have made general.''
in hopes of making greeks more familiar with their ancestors' ideas, the education minister has ordered high school students to start taking daily classes in ancient greek in september
the decision by education minister antonis tritsis was reached after months of public debate by scholars and educators, but some teachers claim the language used by homer, plato and the great greek dramatists might confuse young students and be too hard for them to learn
ancient greek ideas should have a living medium in the world today,'' tritsis said in an interview, ``and i think that living medium is the greek people who continue to speak the same language as the ancient greeks.''
he added that high school students 13 to 18 years old will be the first to take compulsory ancient greek, but that eventually 6-year-olds will start learning the language through word-games
we want every young greek to be directly familiar with the great wealth of his ancestors and those ancient greek works that have influenced the world,'' said tritsis, an american-trained architect
european literature began with homer's poems about the legendary greek heroes of the trojan war, the ``iliad'' and the ``odyssey.''
plays by aeschylus, sophocles and euripides in the 5th century b.c. are studied and performed in translation all over the world. plato's philosophic dialogues and thucydides' histories contain ideas that shaped western thinking for centuries
although greek classical scholars and university professors say they welcome tritsis' project, schoolteachers protest that ancient greek is too difficult for all but the most talented linguists
while ancient greek shares an alphabet and a wide range of vocabulary with the present-day language, its grammar and structure are much more complex
it is a fallacy that ancient greek can be easily grasped by every schoolchild,'' christos doukas, who heads the athens-based high school teachers' union, said in an interview
but tritsis said greek is a very conservative language. he indicated it would be much less difficult for greek students to learn ancient greek than it would be for american high school students to learn old english, which was spoken in england from around 400 to 1100 a.d., or even the english of chaucer and shakespeare
the difference in language between shakespeare's english and modern english or chaucer and modern english is greater than that between homer and heroditus and the greek spoken today,'' he said. ``despite changes in forms ... the vast amount of words and expressions are the very same language we use today.''
junior high students now study ancient greek literature during four 45-minute classes a week. but they read texts that have been translated into modern greek
tritsis wants students to begin reading the texts in ancient greek
high school students take a two-year basic course in ancient greek and read some of the original literature. however, they are not examined on the ancient greek texts. tritsis wants those studies continued at a higher level entirely in the original greek
the students will continue their usual studies of modern greek and their two classes a week of either french or english
the teachers, however, argue that language lessons should focus on modern greek, which a difficult language to master but still easier than ancient greek
learning ancient greek from original texts will only confuse schoolchildren,'' said doukas of the teachers union. ``instead we should all spend more time and energy concentrating on the greek we speak today, itself a rich and expressive language.''
in a major reform of the greek school system in 1976, compulsory ancient greek was dropped from the state high school curriculum as a ``dead'' language, irrelevant to modern educational needs
now 15- and 16-year-old students intending to go to university usually take a two-year basic course in ancient greek, but scholars say that isn't enough to keep the heritage alive
ancient greek has to be introduced at a much earlier stage in a child's education, when it helps to develop his imagination, judgment and memory,'' said constantine trypanis, a former culture minister and retired oxford university professor of byzantine and modern greek studies
the study of ancient greek language and literature in the original is of cardinal importance if that tradition of culture is to survive.''
economics and the irs may be undoing an idea hailed as a possible antidote to rising college costs: tuition prepayment plans
when duquesne university in pittsburgh pioneered such a plan in 1985, it seemed a natural. at a time of soaring tuitions, families could buy higher education ``futures'' contracts. the idea was that parents would pay a lump sum _ less if their child was young, more if older _ and investments by the college would swell those funds to cover tuition costs down the road
at duquesne, for example, the family of a 1-year-old eligible for college in the year 2005 could have paid a lump sum of $8,630 last fall to cover the projected four-year tuition of $102,604. but a family of a 12-year-old hoping to enroll at duquesne in 1994 would have had to put up $19,410 to cover the projected four-year tuition of $48,747
so far so good. parents purchase peace of mind at a discount, knowing the plan guarantees four years of college as long as their child is accepted. the school, in turn, gets a virtual lock on a future student, hedging against future enrollment declines
but it hasn't worked smoothly for duquesne or the several other colleges that followed its example, nor for the five states that have adopted tuition futures plans for public colleges since 1985
duquesne announced last week it was recommending suspension of its program because of higher-than-expected tuition increases and lower-than-anticipated earnings on investments. the board of directors is scheduled to make a final decision march 17
similar programs at the university of detroit and canisius college in buffalo, n.y., are likewise at a standstill and not taking new applicants
three of the five states that enacted tuition futures plans for public colleges _ tennessee, indiana and michigan _ are in limbo because the internal revenue service has yet to rule on the tax status of investment earnings from those plans
wilson fadely, an irs spokesman in washington, refused to comment on when such a ruling might be handed down
people contact me and say they are interested,'' said lawrence a. jegen, chairman of the board setting up indiana's program. ``they have a thirst for a regimented investment program so they know that if they put their money on the table, their children's or grandchildren's tuition will be guaranteed.''
but jergen said the plan might not be operating july 1 as originally hoped because of difficulties in predicting future tuition levels and because of the pending irs ruling
a state-sponsored program that began last august at the university of wyoming is going strong and has signed up 332 future students. florida officials say they hope to start accepting applicants next fall
michigan officials remain confident they will eventually get their program off the ground despite the questions raised by duquesne, and despite the fact that state law forbids them from accepting a single student until the irs rules
we'll have no problem at all paying for the program out of public investments,'' said richard cole, higher education adviser to gov. james blanchard
duquesne's heart was in the right place, but it appears their financial brains were in the wrong place,'' said michigan treasurer robert bowman. ``they couldn't even gauge their own tuition.''
but prepayment programs have been controversial from the start. a number of colleges _ fairleigh dickinson university in new jersey, for one _ considered and rejected the idea because of the built-in risks and unpredictability
keith briscoe, president of buena vista college in storm lake, iowa, called the idea a ``gimmick'' that ``overlooks students' best interests'' because it deprives them of the chance to select a school freely
the national association of independent colleges and universities, which represents about 1,000 private institutions, has likewise criticized them as inflexible
even backers concede they are a high-risk gamble for both parents and schools
a state or college offering the plan must accurately predict future tuition and investment trends for years ahead _ or risk losing money honoring its tuition guarantees
parents, for their part, are gambling that their child will want to attend a given college, and will qualify for admission. if for any reaon the child doesn't attend the school in the prepayment plan, refunds are often limited to the amount parents actually paid in. that means parents stand to lose tens of thousands of dollars in investment income
what happened at duquesne was exactly what so many states and private colleges had feared all along: bond markets weakened last year and undercut the plan's investment income. tuitions went up more than anticipated: by 7.95 percent instead of the predicted 6 percent
the result was that the 622 alumni families who had signed up found themselves with a far more generous bargain than duquesne ever intended, or could afford
duquesne may be unique, or it may be the likely outcome for many of these programs. there's just not enough history to determine the real viability of programs like this,'' said ron gambill, executive director of the tennessee student assistance corp., the agency that will administer that state's program once the irs rules
some, like richard anderson, director of the federally funded forum for college financing at columbia teachers college, believe duquesne's program must have been, ``first and last, a marketing tool,'' a premeditated financial giveaway aimed at attracting future students
it's true we wanted to offer a program that was going to be attractive,'' said duquesne spokeswoman ann rago. ``however, the changes in the economy were drastic. we never said our program was forever. we started our program to help people, specifically alumni families. it was not just a marketing a tool.''
if this had been another issue, liberal sen. howard metzenbaum and conservative sen. james mcclure might have quietly hammered out differences between their rival bills to make certain that plastic pistols can't get through airport metal detectors
but history has taught that a gun control engagement is never fought with silencers, even in rare instances like this one, when rival sponsors have identical goals: stopping terrorists, especially at airports
so once again, bitter enemies of past gun control struggles are following the usual rules of engagement _ high-powered lobbying, full-page advertisements, fund-raising appeals and doomsday rhetoric
sparking the latest debate is a weapon not even on the market. red eye arms of winter park, fla. says it has a patent for plastic weapons, but won't start making handguns for at least two years _ and then only for military and police use
we would never allow anyone to build an undetectable civilian handgun,'' said company vice president dwight brunoehler
metzenbaum, d-ohio, and mcclure, r-idaho, have vastly different approaches to require that the guns be made detectable. both would ban manufacture or importation of any guns that did not meet their standards
metzenbaum's bill would require a minimum weight of metal to ensure that an alarm would be triggered at today's magnetometer settings. its target is not only future plastic guns, but pint-size metal pistols that are not detected today
the federal bureau of alcohol, tobacco and firearms estimates there are three small metal guns that could get through most magnetometers now used. the gun owners' lobby estimates there are countless other models
mcclure's legislation targets plastic guns only, and has no minimum metallic requirement. however, it would require that guns be detectable, by either including some metal, a serial number engraved or stamped on metal, or a substance detectable by x-ray machines used for luggage
using today's technology, mcclure's bill would require more sensitive magnetometer settings, more alarms, and therefore more airport passenger inconvenience _ some say gridlock
brunoehler, of red eye arms, says his firm has developed a computer chip for plastic guns that would make the lower settings unnecessary. the chip would emit a signal that would make it appear that an enormous amount of metal was passing through the machine, he said
federal aviation administration spokesman fred farrar said the faa is aware of the chip, but believes it could be disabled by drilling a hole in it or even placing the weapon in a microwave oven
while these are the technical points for debate, a congressional gun fight often ranges far beyond the issues at hand and this one is no exception
the principal gun owner's lobby, the national rifle association, told its 2.8 million members in a fund-raising letter last year that metzenbaum's real goal is ``the first federal gun ban bill in america.''
if sen. metzenbaum's bill passes, the next thing will be some government official knocking at your door to weigh your guns for inspection,'' said the nra, which backs the mcclure bill
to handgun control inc., the most visible lobby for pistol regulation, the issue is what the group calls the nra's extremism. ``cop-killer bullets, mail-order handguns, machine guns...has the nra gone off the deep end?'' says hci ads, which have different police chiefs using those same words
handgun control supports metzenbaum. so do a dozen law enforcement organizations
both sides are simply waving flags so believers will send money to handgun control inc. and to the national rifle association,'' says john aquilino, a former nra official who now publishes his own gun owners' newsletter. ``they're making advertising agencies very wealthy. it's flag-waving and fund-raising.''
the latest battle reflects new political realities that surfaced in 1986. then, the major law enforcement organizations joined forces with handgun control advocates to fight nra-backed legislation to ease many restrictions of the 1968 gun control act
the presence of uniformed policemen lobbying their local lawmakers began to neutralize some of the nra's seemingly invincible clout
nonetheless, the gun lobby attained many of its goals two years ago with passage of the mcclure-volkmer act, which changed a number of provisions of the 1968 law. but the invigorated gun control-police alliance was able to retain, as part of that fight, a ban on interstate sales of handguns
now, the same coalition of police and gun control advocates is back on the detectability question. but jerald r. vaughn, executive director of the international association of chiefs of police, says of his fellow police lobbyists, ``we're still babes in the woods when it comes to the political process.''
yet, the nra has taken an unusual turn by backing mcclure's bill. the group normally opposes any legislation that could bring more restrictions on firearms
only last may, nra governmental affairs director james jay baker told a house panel, ``the nra believes that the only workable approach'' to the detection problem is better security at airports
he said ``attempts to dictate metallic content of firearms or chemical composition of non-metallic components of firearms'' were unnecessary
their position from day one has been, there shall never be any law on guns,'' said n.t. ``pete'' shields, chairman of handgun control inc
all of a sudden this issue of plastic handguns has made them compromise this whole concept. i think they have come a long way, but i think they're trying to address it with smoke. mcclure's bill is impractical. you would bottle up the airport.''
baker said in an interview, ``the nra has moved a long way on this issue. we decided to take the bull by the horns and deal with the terms as framed by the other side. if they're interested in detectability, it can be done with no interference with existing firearms.''
metzenbaum's most prominent senate ally is strom thurmond, a conservative south carolina republican and ranking republican on the judiciary committee. metzenbaum and thurmond tried to win passage of their legislation last december, but it was tabled by a 47-42 vote
metzenbaum, in an interview, called mcclure's bill ``purely cosmetic.''
mcclure, also in an interview, said he rejects any arbitrary metallic standard, and called any potential inconvenience ``part of the price you pay for having secure airports.''
the lincoln town car, long a best-seller at ford motor co.'s lincoln-mercury division, continues to confound the skeptics
the body style, originally introduced as the 1980 lincoln continental town car has had a stronger increase in sales since 1983 than have european luxury cars, according to a ford analyst
after test-driving the 1988 signature series town car, i can see why
the auto, a big, heavy monster still with the basic design it had in the late 1970s, practically drove itself (although critics might note that for a price of nearly $28,000 the car should do a lot of things)
i didn't have to remember to turn on the headlights. they did that themselves, sensing when outside light was low, thanks to an auto lamp on-off system
the headlights also switched from low to high beams automatically and turned themselves off when the ignition was turned off. i didn't have to remember to lock the doors before i drove off
the car has an automatic system that locks them once ignition is on, all doors are closed, the transmission is shifted through reverse and someone is in the driver seat
i didn't even have to remember to switch the rearview mirror to ward off headlight glare from other vehicles. the test car had the optional (for $89) automatic dim day-night mirror that flipped to protect driver eyes from glare every time a vehicle approached the rear. it flipped back to normal when no vehicle was close behind
so, all i had to do was get inside, start up the car, shift and step on the gas pedal. away i went, along with 4,100 pounds of sheer automotive force
if you want that size of car and that configuration (rear drive, big weight, luxury domestic), there aren't many choices _ probably the town car or a cadillac, said ford analyst ray windecker. sales of town cars have increased 90 percent since 1983, while sales of all cadillac models have fallen 8 percent
european luxury car sales also haven't risen as fast as they have for town cars, he said, citing a 39 percent boost at mercedes-benz and 62 percent at bmw. overall, the u.s. luxury car market is up 35 percent from 1983, he added
town car sales in the 1987 model year totaled 136,085, up from 119,180 in the 1986 model year, windecker said
the plant producing the big cars has been on overtime nearly every day. the demand is that great, he said
however, he added sales likely will decline a bit in the current model year because the plant is building a newly designed lincoln continental and work on those models is expected to curtail some town car production
town car buyers are older, with median age of 60. (actually, 53 percent are over age 60.) forty percent of buyers are retired, and median income is $58,000 a year, ford said. thirty-eight percent are at least college grads
besides appreciating the many automatic features on the town car, those buyers can enjoy standard, heated outside side mirrors and lighted thermometer that tells the outside temperature. there's an expansive interior _ no complaints about a cramped back seat here _ and carpet is 30-ounce cut pile
also part of the 219-inch-long vehicle is a trunk that is huge, even with a full-sized spare tire inside. the hood, where the mighty 5-liter, electronic fuel-injected v-8 resides, juts out front so far i nearly hit the back of another car at a stop sign before i realized i wasn't in one of those down sized vehicles with little hoods i'm used to
i did find the interior cloth upholstery (navy in the test car) showed some spills, and i couldn't slide in the seat. rather, i had to lift myself and settle in
with so much weight and such a big engine coupled with automatic transmission, fuel economy suffers, with only 17 mpg listed for city driving. a fill up can be costly _ one gas station visit left me $20 poorer
and, the car had a somewhat mushy suspension
consumer reports said buyer surveys showed 1983-85 town cars ranked better than average in its trouble index and average in the 1986 model year, the last year available
the town car continues to show what a big american car can be and likely will be for the foreseeable future
despite talk that it's just a matter of time before large, rear-drive american cars disappear from showrooms, a ford official says the company plans on keeping the popular town car around for some time
ann job has covered the auto industry for the associated press, the detroit free press and the detroit news, where she is now assistant news editor

base price $26,179
as tested $27,732

type: front-engine, rear-drive, 6-passenger, large luxury sedan
engine: 5-liter, electronic fuel-injected v-8
mileage: 17 mpg (city) 24 mpg (highway)
top speed: not available
length: 219 inches
wheelbase: 117.3 inches
curb wt: 4,093 pounds
assembled by: ford, wixom, mich
options on test car: traction-lok axle ($101); white-sidewall tires ($200); leather-wrapped steering wheel ($115); automatic dim day-night mirror ($89); body side protection molding ($70); ford jbl audio system ($454)

delivery charge: $524
on the fringes of the multi-ethnic empire that the communists seized from the czars, minorities emboldened by mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms are clamoring for a greater say in their future and challenging the dictates of moscow
in recent weeks, armenians by the tens of thousands have marched in the streets, estonians have massed at a monument in their capital and police have locked lithuanian activists in their homes to keep them from marking the brief period lithuania was an independent country
in the most dramatic incident, some members of two neighboring nationalities in the southern caucasus republics have directed their hostility not at moscow, but at each other
a rancorous territorial dispute has caused bloodshed, injuries and deaths involving the armenians and neighboring azeris, and some fearful azeris, natives of the azerbaijan republic, have fled their homes
the violence, and the palpable swelling of nationalist feelings on the soviet periphery, pose one of the greatest problems yet for general secretary gorbachev's kremlin, which is trying to enact nationwide standards of discipline and efficiency, but also to decentralize economic control
events have also poignantly shown how much the soviet union, far from being an ethnic melting pot, is still the uneasy conglomeration of disparate peoples that was dubbed by one disapproving 19th-century visitor to russia, adolphe de custine, as ``a prison of nations.''
in the 70 years of soviet power, the moscow-based communist party and government have viciously fought centrifugal forces they feared might split the country into its ethnic components, and the current party program adopted in 1986 under gorbachev speaks of a ``single soviet people.''
but the soviet union extends from central europe to the far east and is peopled by more than 100 ethnic strains and speaking 120 different languages or dialects. they range from the dominant russians, who make up more than 40 percent of the population of 284.5 million, to the aleuts, a far northern tribe with fewer than 500 members
gorbachev has called the formulation of a comprehensive policy to ensure national unity while granting each ethnic group its own cultural and linguistic rights ``the most vital, fundamental issue of our society.''
the unique feature of our culture is that it is multi-ethnic,'' gorbachev said in february. ``nationalism in any form is blind. attempts at self-isolation lead down a spiritual blind alley.''
underlining the importance of working out a new policy on nationalities, gorbachev said the central committee, the communist party's policy-making body, would hold a special plenary session to discuss the matter
the day gorbachev made those remarks, feb. 18, demonstrations began in yerevan, the armenian capital, to protest the central committee's refusal to permit the joining of the nagorno-karabakh region, part of azerbaijan since 1923 despite its largely armenian population, to armenia itself
the protests swelled, with some witnesses claiming that more than 1 million people had taken to yerevan's streets. whatever the size, the rallies were the largest unsanctioned gatherings in soviet history
some in the crowd proclaimed that the future of the contested region that is smaller than the state of delaware will demonstrate how gorbachev's entire national reform program is to proceed
karabakh is a test of perestroika (gorbachev's reforms),'' declared some of the banners carried by chanting and singing armenians
although in theory and under the 1977 constitution, all of the country's nationalities are equal, the russians and their slavic cousins, the ukrainians and byelorussians, have a firm hold on the actual levers of power
the ruling politburo shows clearly the extent of slavic domination. a dozen of its members, including gorbachev, are slavs, while only one is not _ foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze, a georgian
despite official rhetoric lauding the equality of nations, russian pre-eminence is even enshrined in the soviet national anthem, whose first stanza begins: ``an unbreakable union of free republics has been forged forever by great russia.''
the 15 constituent soviet republics have been tightly controlled by moscow over the years, but gorbachev's drive for greater citizen participation, plus his campaign for ``glasnost,'' or openness, have stirred both hopes and doubts about how far moscow will allow ethnic minorities to go
at the same time, gorbachev has ignored the penchant of his predecessor, leonid i. brezhnev, to let local elites run the economic and social affairs of their republics, providing they adhered to the dictates of moscow
it was the replacement by gorbachev of kazakhstan's ethnic kazakh party chief by a russian that sparked two days of rioting in the central asian city of alma ata on dec. 17-18, 1986, in which two people were killed and 200 injured
the recent outbursts involving armenians and azeris may strengthen the hand of kremlin conservatives who think gorbachev's reforms undermine the traditional submission of distant nationalities to the central russian power structure
the more candid exploration of the legacy of dictator josef v. stalin promoted by orbachev has also brought calls from baltic activists to extend glasnost to cover the forced incorporation of latvia, lithuania and estonia into the soviet union in 1940
we want to raise the consciousness of people so they remember they have the right to be free,'' said the lithuanian activist jadvyga beliauskiene last month as police prevented activists from publicly marking the 70th anniversary feb. 17 of lithuania's declaration of independence
a group of estonians gathered in tallinn on feb. 26, the 70th anniversary of estonia's declaration of independence from soviet russia. dissident sources in moscow said 2,500 to 3,000 people attended, and official media confirmed the rally took place
the contested region in azerbaijan shows in microcosm the problems faced by the kremlin on a national scale in formulating a nationalities policy that takes all pieces of the country's human mosaic into account
the small region is more than three-quarters armenian, but has residents of 48 other groups
soviet nationality groups recently in the news:
russians _ 137.4 million, slavic, spread throughout the country but native to the european region west of the ural mountains. russian is the mother tongue of 99.9 percent of the russian nationality
kazakhs _ 6.6 million, central asian, former nomadic tribes that settled in the area that now forms kazakhstan. kazakh is spoken by 97.5 percent of the population and 52 percent of kazakhs also claim fluency in russian
azeris _ 5.5 million, also known as azerbaijanis, turkish, native to the area west of the caspian sea and concentrated in the azerbaijan republic. azeri is spoken by 98 percent, and 29.5 percent speak russian
armenians _ 4.2 million, turkish, native to the region between the caucasus mountains and turkey. armenian is spoken by 91 percent, and russian by 39 percent
lithuanians _ 2.9 million, baltic, native to the region northeast of poland and along the baltic sea. lithuanian is spoken by 98 percent, russian by 52 percent
latvians _ 1.4 million, baltic, native to the northwestern area of the country along the baltic sea. latvian is spoken by 95 percent and russian by 57 percent
estonians _ 1 million, baltic, native to the northwest region along the baltic coast. estonian is spoken by 95 percent, and russian by 24 percent
housing construction plunged 14 percent in 1987 from the previous year as rising interest rates and high apartment vacancies took their toll on the industry, a new survey says
the report by the f.w. dodge division of mcgraw-hill information systems co. said wednesday that only three of the nation's top 10 metropolitan areas _ washington, d.c., detroit and philadelphia _ showed any pickup in construction activity last year
treasury secretary james a. baker iii says the federal reserve should be independent, but the central bank does not have to be ``totally sheltered from outside advice or criticism.''
baker defended the reagan administration wednesday against charges that it tried to pressure the central bank for easy money to avoid an election-year recession
baker testified before the joint economic committee of congress
deposits are up at savings institutions and mortgage rates are down, the government says
the federal home loan bank board said wednesday that net new deposits increased at the nation's 3,135 federally insured s&amp;ls in january for the fourth consecutive month
the bank board said mortgage rates dropped by nearly half a percentage point in early february when compared with early january
effective rates on typical 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages for single-family homes dropped from 10.97 percent in early january to 10.5 percent in early february
the united states will liberalize the sale of high technology to china and china has agreed in principle to accept peace corps volunteers
the reagan administration announced wednesday it lifted a five-month suspension on high-tech transfers after the chinese said they were not sending silkworm anti-ship missiles to iran
details of the peace corps plan are yet to be resolved
the nation's industrial heartland will prosper in the next few years, but lagging population growth threatens the region's political clout and share of federal programs, a public policy group says
the loss of jobs from the region was another point of weakness in the 18 northern states stretching from minnesota to new england, the northeast-midwest institute said wednesday in its study, ``the state of the region.''
vice chairman manuel h. johnson of the federal reserve board told congressmen he opposes their plan for an international body to lift some of the debt burden from third world countries
johnson said he prefers free-market solutions, such as mexico's effort to exchange old debt for new bonds. some observers have called the results of mexico's program disappointing
johnson spoke wednesday before subcommittees of the house banking committee
united artists communications inc. and united cable television corp. have announced a merger agreement that would produce a concern ranking among the nation's biggest cable companies
the companies declined to estimate the value of the cash-and-stock deal wednesday, but one analyst said the new company was being capitalized at about $3.8 billion
the product of the two denver-based companies is to be called united artists entertainment co
