usg chairman robert j. day said wednesday in a letter to stockholders that desert partners lp's unsolicited $42-a-share tender offer for their shares was ``wholly inadequate'' and ``coercive.''
day also questioned the value of junk bonds and warrants comprising a portion of desert partners' offer
desert partners in turn told usg to stop attempting to block the buyout offer
chrysler corp. and the united auto workers union could be meeting over a bargaining table as soon as next month if 140 local union leaders meeting here today agree to a request for early contract talks
local union leaders said wednesday they favor early talks and uaw vice president marc stepp has said ``the earlier the better.'' however, it is unclear if chrysler will agree to union demands to set an early strike deadline
texaco inc. has asked a federal bankruptcy judge to authorize a credit agreement allowing the company to borrow up to $3 billion to finance its chapter 11 reorganization plan
texaco sought protection from creditors under chapter 11 last year to avoid liens stemming from a $10.3 billion award granted rival pennzoil, after a texas jury found texaco illegally had derailed pennzoil's takeover of getty oil co
women business students are more eager for leadership positions than they were in the 1970s and men are more likely to accept the change, a wharton school study concludes
the improvement in relations between the sexes is dramatic,'' wharton professor ross a. webber wrote for the latest issue of human resources management journal of the university of michigan business school
clearly significant social change has occurred during the 10 years separating the two investigations,'' webber said
the stock market's recent rally bogged down wednesday. the dow jones average of 30 industrial stockss fell 6.80 points to 2,074.27
bond prices were little changed
the dollar rose slightly against most major currencies. gold prices also were higher
copper futures prices settled at the highest levels in three weeks wednesday on indications of tightening supplies and rising demand
rising interest rates and plentiful apartment vacancies contributed to a 14 percent decline in new housing starts last year, according to a report by a private business information concern
the report wednesday by the f.w. dodge division of mcgraw-hill information systems co. said only three of the nation's top 10 metropolitan areas _ washington, d.c., detroit and philadelphia _ showed any pickup in construction activity last year
high vacancy rates and high mortgage rates took a heavy toll of apartment and one-family building alike last year,'' said george a. christie, chief economist for f.w. dodge
in other news, the stock market's recent rally bogged down wednesday as blue chips gave up some of their gains from the day before. the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up 24.70 points on tuesday, dropped back 6.80 to 2,074.27
nevertheless, advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 4 to 3 on the new york stock exchange
confidence has continued to spread lately on wall street that the economy remains healthy nearly five months after black monday on oct. 19
in addition, stock prices have been less volatile lately than they were as recently as early january, suggesting that investors' mood is less subject to sudden change
analysts say investing institutions have grown more eager to put some of their cash reserves into stocks, in order to show in their first-quarter reports to clients that they participated in the recent market rally
bond prices finished little changed. the yield on the treasury's bellwether 30-year issue slipped to 8.51 percent from 8.52 percent
the dollar rose slightly against major currencies late in the day as world markets remained transfixed by the surging british pound, analysts said. gold prices were also higher
crude oil prices edged upward and refined products ended mixed. market analysts said there were few developments to influence trading
crude oil futures have crept higher in lackluster markets in the absence of any major influential developments
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, settled at $15.49 per barrel on wednesday, up 4 cents from tuesday's close
refined products traded on the exchange were mixed
wholesale heating oil slipped .46 cent to 43.03 cents a gallon. some analysts attributed the decline in heating oil to milder weather, which reduces demand
but an expected increase in demand for gasoline was credited for a 0.29 cent rise, to 44.00 cents, in the april contract for wholesale unleaded gas. analysts said distributors have been carrying low inventories, and demand is expected to pick up with the imminent arrival of the spring and summer driving seasons
crude oil trading was stalled by conflicting reports about saudi arabia's support for a meeting of the opec pricing committee, said john azarow, senior trader for shearson lehman hutton inc
some members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries have called for a meeting of the committee because the price of opec oil has slipped to between $13 and $14 a barrel. at their last meeting in december, opec oil ministers reaffirmed their intention to maintain prices at $18 a barrel
prices on world markets have fallen because of moderate demand for oil, price discounting by opec members and an increase in output by non-opec producers
new york clothing designer alexander julian plans a return to his native tar heel state this summer with a new men's clothing store that he hopes will be the beginning of a national chain
julian, who also is designing uniforms for the charlotte hornets, a new national basketball association entry, will open a retail store here in july, said a spokesman for the designer
as a native north carolinian, alexander has a great affinity for the state,'' barry miguel, creative director for alexander julian inc. of new york, said in a recent telephone interview. ``at the same time, he feels charlotte is a growing city and a growing marketplace.''
julian was not available for an interview
the new stores will sell an upscale line of clothing and accessories called the alexander julian collection
we've expanded our men's collection,'' miguel said. ``we have more sportswear now than previously.''
julian, the 39-year-old son of a chapel hill haberdasher, is considered one of the nation's top clothing designers. although he resides just outside new york, in greenwich, conn., he makes no secret of his love for his native state
julian also shares the state's passion for basketball. that's why hornets owner george shinn approached julian last year about designing uniforms for the expansion team, which will begin play in the 1988-89 nba season
i felt like i wanted to lead the league in something the first year,'' shinn said at the time. ``i felt that being best dressed was the way to go.''
for his design work on the basketball team's uniforms, julian is being paid 10 pounds of north carolina barbecue, delivered once a month to his office on new york's east side office
julian's company is readying its 3,200-square-foot prototype store for the july opening, said company president, marty staff. the store's interior will be designed by walker &amp; associates of new york, which has done design work for bloomingdale's and calvin klein shops
a second store will open in late summer in atlanta, followed by another in the northeast corridor, miguel said
we hope to have 30 to 40 stores in the next five years,'' he said
cluett peabody &amp; co. will continue to produce the colours by alexander julian line for men and levi strauss &amp; co. will still make the colours by alexander julian for women, staff said
julian, who is chairman and part-owner of the new company, plans to visit the charlotte store frequently, miguel said. several venture capital firms also own stock in the company, including harvard management co. and new enterprises associates of san francisco, he said
campeau corp. is renewing its attempt to block federated department stores inc.'s ``poison pill'' takeover defense, contending the plan wrongly denies federated shareholders the chance to choose between rival buyout offers
campeau, which is competing with r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. to acquire federated, filed a brief tuesday in federal court to revive its request for an injunction against the plan
the toronto-based company called the rights plan a ``show stopper'' that would block campeau's $6.18 billion offer for federated
the plan makes a hostile takeover attempt more expensive by allowing federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a heavy discount
campeau suspended its attack on the poison pill after the company appeared to be close to an acquisition agreement with federated in late february. however, when the federated board met to consider accepting campeau's offer on feb. 29, it also began reviewing the macy bid
macy, which last week signed a $6.1 billion definitive buyout agreement with federated, on tuesday began a tender offer for federated's common stock. under the offer, macy will pay $74.50 per share in cash for approximately 80 percent of federated's stock. macy plans to swap shares in a new company, macy's-federated inc., for the remaining 20 percent of federated's shares
analysts have valued the macy bid at $6.1 billion
campeau is offering $75 in cash per share for 80 percent of federated's stock and $44 in cash per share for the remaining 20 percent. the campeau bid, which has an aggregate value of $68 per share, totals $6.18 billion
macy also went to federal court tuesday, seeking an injunction against the campeau bid. macy contended the campeau offer, which was amended from an earlier $68-a-share outright cash bid, actually was a new offer and under federal law must remain open past its march 15 scheduled expiration
if the macy request is granted it effectively would put the campeau offer on a more equal footing with the macy bid, which is scheduled to expire april 4, by reducing pressure on federated shareholders to make a choice
under federal law, a new offer would have to remain open for at least 20 business days after publication or submission to stockholders
campeau's bid was announced march 2. if it is considered a new offer, it could not legally expire on march 15 as scheduled
federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer, owns department stores including bloomingdale's, lazarus, rich's, abraham &amp; straus, bullock's and burdine's
macy holdings include nearly 100 department and specialty stores and campeau, a real estate developer, owns allied stores corp
united artists communications inc. and united cable television corp. have agreed to combine their operations into a $3.8 billion concern that would rank as one of nation's biggest cable companies
the transaction, disclosed wednesday and approved by the directors of both denver-based companies, would create united artists entertainment co., which would have interests in both cable television and motion picture theaters
the two companies had agreed on an all-stock merger shortly before the october stock market crash, but canceled the deal soon after, citing disagreement over the terms and uncertain market conditions
they announced in january that they had resumed their discussions
the new deal is subject to approval of the companies' shareholders and federal regulators and favorable tax rulings, among other conditions, the companies said. they said they hoped to complete the deal later this year
in trading on the new york stock exchange, united cable rose $2.87{ a share to $32.62{. in over-the-counter trading, united artists rose $2.25 a share to $29.75
the new company would have about 2.3 million cable subscribers by the end of the year, said stewart d. blair, chairman and chief executive of united artists
that would place the new concern behind only the two industry leaders in terms of subscribers, tele-communications inc. and american television and communications inc., according to paul kagan associates, a media research and investment concern in carmel, calif
tele-communications, which also is based in denver, currently owns 65 percent of united artists and 23.7 percent of united cable. its stake in the new company would be about 52 percent, the announcement said
under the new agreement, united artists' stockholders would receive one share of the new company for every share they currently own of united artists. united cable shareholders would be eligible to convert each of their shares into either $35 in cash or a share of stock in the new company and the separable right to sell a share of the new company's stock under special terms
the cash portion of the offer would be available on up to 49 percent of united cable's 46.4 million fully diluted shares
william j. elsner, senior vice president and chief financial officer at united cable, said the october agreement had been criticized for failing to include a cash alternative
sharon armbrust, a senior analyst for paul kagan associates, estimated the new company was being capitalized at about $3.8 billion
that figure includes $2.4 billion in stock, $600 million in existing debt and $800 million in new borrowing needed for the cash portion of the deal
blair would be chief executive and vice chairman of the new company. united cable's chairman, gene w. schneider, would be chairman of the new company
united artists has about 800,000 subscribers and recently agreed to acquire the cable television division of daniels &amp; associates, which has about 380,000 subscribers. united cable has about 1.1 million subscribers
united artists also is one of the nation's biggest motion picture operators with about 2,050 motion picture screens and plans to boost that total by the end of the year to about 3,000 through acquisitions and construction
the announcement said the new company would operate the cable operations under the name united cable and the theatrical operations under the united artists name
several major newspapers are hoping that putting an ``island'' of advertising in their sea of stock tables will help attract more national advertisers to the medium
the first ad buyer to participate in the unusual effort is national car rental system inc
the minneapolis-based company said wednesday it would spend $2 million through the end of the year to put quarter-page ads in what is being called a new ``island'' position on the first page of the stock table sections of 16 newspapers in the nation's 20 biggest markets
the ads, which will be surrounded on four sides by stock quotations, will appear a minimum of 26 times starting march 17 in each newspaper, according to lewis carbone, a national marketing executive
a committee of the national advertising bureau, a trade organization, came up with the idea for the unusual ad position and, along with national's ad agency, chiat-day inc., persuaded the 16 newspapers to sell it
michael davies, head of the newspaper bureau panel and editor and publisher of the hartford courant, said the committee looked at a dozen proposals for displaying advertising more distinctively before deciding on this approach
he said the committee wanted to find a way to help an ad message stand out without disrupting normal reading patterns
putting an ad in the stock tables seemed appropriate, he said, because people usually look for individual stock prices rather than reading through the entire section. ``this doesn't interrupt the flow of reading a page,'' he said
but some big newspapers turned down the idea
the new york times rejected it because ``it would make it too hard for the reader to get through the stock tables,'' according to spokeswoman nancy nielsen
the wall street journal also balked. bernard t. flanagan, vice president for marketing, said the placement would be ``an inconvenience to the reader.'' ``in a sense, we want to make it as easy as we can for readers to look up their stock quotes,'' he said
flanagan said the ad placement also ``takes prestige away from the page.''
newspapers have seen their share of national advertising spending decline steadily in recent years as national advertisers turned to television
newspapers took in 15.9 percent of total national ad spending in 1950, but fell to below 6 percent in 1986
last year, national advertisers spent $3.5 billion in newspapers, or about 5.8 percent of their total spending of $60.6 billion, according to an estimate by the ad agency mccann-erickson inc
but robert zach, media director for chiat-day, said the rising cost of television time is making advertisers more receptive to alternative ways to reach customers
davies said he expected other advertisers would take an interest in the new ad position and that other newspapers would embrace the idea
the 16 newspapers that have sold the space to national include: the atlanta journal and constitution, chicago sun-times, dallas morning news, detroit free press, hartford courant, houston chronicle, los angeles times, miami herald, minneapolis star and tribune, phoenix gazette, rocky mountain news, san francisco chronicle and examiner, seattle times, st. louis post-dispatch, st. paul pioneer press and dispatch and tampa tribune. mortgage rates</head>
home mortgage rates fell at the quickest pace since 1986 early this year, partly because of the broad decline in interest rates in the wake of the october stock market crash, according to the government
the stock market collapse also played a role in boosting net deposits at the nation's savings institutions during january for the fourth straight month, the federal home loan bank board reported wednesday
effective rates on typical 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages for single-family homes dropped to 10.5 percent in early february from 10.97 percent in early january. rates on the most popular type of adjustable rate mortgages, those with caps on how much the rate can change, fell to 8.74 percent from 8.98 percent over the same period
the decline in commitment rates is consistent with the softening of mortgage demand that generally occurs during the winter months,'' said james barth, the bank board's chief economist
however, the recent declines were the sharpest since 1986...and appear to have reflected mainly large deposit flows...after the stock market collapse...and an across-the-board decline in interest rates,'' he said
mortgage lending by s&amp;ls in january declined to the lowest level since february 1985. savings institutions lent $13.1 billion in mortgages, down more than the usual seasonal dropoff from $21.7 billion in december
contributing to the reduced lending volume was a lingering skittishness on the part of potential home buyers following the oct. 19 collapse in stock prices,'' barth said in a statement
the spread between fixed-rate and adjustable-rate mortgages narrowed to 1.76 percent, the smallest difference since last spring. the proportion of mortgages being closed with adjustable rates edged down from 65 percent in december to 63 percent a month later
but the popularity of adjustable-rate loans remains far higher than last spring, when they represented 20 to 30 percent of the market
a separate survey of mortgage rates by the federal home loan mortgage corp. indicated 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged 9.85 percent last friday, down slightly from 9.87 percent a week earlier and sharply lower than 10.61 percent on jan. 1. this survey does not include add-on fees, known as points, which are included in the bank board's averages
the bank board also said net new deposits at the nation's 3,135 federally insured s&amp;ls increased by $5.6 billion in january, following a $2.6 billion increase in december. that compared with net withdrawals of $2.1 billion in january a year ago
barth said deposits normally increase from december to january, but he added, ``nearly half of the most recent improvement represented non-seasonal factors. undoubtedly, the precipitous decline in the stock market remains one of these factors.''
nervous investors, seeking a safe haven for their money, increased deposits by $6.2 billion in october and $3.2 billion in november
the last four months represent a sharp reversal of the trend in recent years, which has been described as a slow-motion run on thrift institutions. there were net withdrawals of $3.3 billion in 1986 and $13.7 billion in the first nine months of 1987
the securities and exchange commission says new york's anti-takeover law is an unconstitutional impediment to interstate commerce
the sec also contended wednesday that the statute conflicts with the williams act, the 1968 federal law regulating corporate takeovers
the agency made its arguments in a friend-of-the-court brief filed in a suit brought by salant acquisition corp. against manhattan industries inc., one of the nation's biggest makers of men's shirts and sportswear
proliferation of state anti-takeover laws since the supreme court upheld indiana's takeover statute last year has heightened the issue of whether the federal or state governments should take the lead in regulating corporate takeovers
the new york law prohibits a bidder who acquires more than 20 percent of a company's stock from completing a takeover or other major business transaciton with the company for five years, unless the bidder gets approval from the target's board of directors
the statute gives corporate management virtual veto power over whether the company will be acquired,'' sec general counsel daniel l. goelzer wrote in the brief
the law effectively preempts the williams act, he argued
goelzer said ``the structure and the legislative history of the (williams) act make it clear that congress believed that...it should be the shareholders _ the owners of the corporation _ who make the decision,'' not the management
the sec, which regulates the nation's securities markets, is intervening in the case in u.s. district court in manhattan on the side of salant
salant, a unit of salant corp., another major apparel maker, began a $95 million hostile takeover attempt of manhattan industries in february
manhattan industries had sought to block the $16-a-share buyout offer salant launched on feb. 2. u.s. district judge louis l. stanton last week denied manhattan industries' request for a court order blocking the tender offer but did not rule on salant's constitutional challenge
manhattan industries said wednesday it had entered into negotiations about a possible merger with salant
the sec took a similar position when the supreme court considered a challenge to indiana's anti-takeover law last year, but the court upheld the law
in another current battle, the sec has indicated it was considering whether to file briefs in suits challenging the newly enacted delaware anti-takeover law, which is structured somewhat similarly to new york's law
matsushita electric industrial co. ltd. says it may export to japan some of the approximately 1 million large-screen color television picture tubes it will make each year in this western ohio city
the $160 million matsushita plant is to open in spring 1989 with 240 people and production of 400,000 tubes, company officials said wednesday
that will expand to about 400 jobs once full production is reached in two or three years, said fumio kanazwa, president of the subsidiary matsushita electronics corp
the company announced it planned to build a plant in troy last december, but disclosed no details until wednesday
kanazawa declined to specify under what conditions matsushita would export tubes to japan, where matsushita already makes some large-screen tubes, but said it would not depend just on the yen-dollar exchange rate
the plant will make 29- and 33-inch tubes, although it could be reconfigured to produce smaller picture tubes, said yasuhiko yamaguchi, who will be president of american matsushita electronics corp
production at troy will represent slightly more than 10 percent of the total picture tube production by matsushita, which had total 1987 revenue of more than $36 billion
matsushita, which makes panasonic, quasar, technics and national brand consumer electronics, began producing televisions in the united states with acquisition of the quasar plant from motorola in 1974, spokesman justin camerlengo said
matsushita has been buying about one-third of its picture tubes in the united states, he said
honda of america on monday became the first japanese automaker to export to japan when it shipped off 540 accords made at its marysville plant
honda, the fourth-largest automaker in the united states, plans to export 4,000 accords to japan this year and 50,000 u.s.-built cars to japan annually by 1991
officers of usg corp. are urging the building materials company's shareholders to reject a $1.9 billion hostile takeover offer as inadequate and coercive, and say the company might sell a major stake to a third party
usg chairman robert j. day wrote shareholders wednesday that they should reject the unsolicited $42-a-share tender offer by desert partners lp, a group led by texas oilmen jack e. brown and cyril wagner jr
usg also disclosed in a securities and exchange commission filing that it may sell a substantial stake in usg to a third, unidentified company
placing a big block of shares in friendly hands, a maneuver known as the ``white squire'' takeover defense, would make it more difficult if not impossible for desert partners to acquire control of the company
desert partners on march 1 launched a tender offer of $42 in cash for each of 21.5 million shares of usg stock. the group also offered to acquire the balance of usg's 50.8 million outstanding shares with securities it valued at $42 a share. desert partners already owns about 9.9 percent of usg stock
day questioned the value of securities portion of desert partners' offer, saying it consisted of junk bonds and warrants ``purportedly worth $42 per share.''
paul colitti, a usg spokesman, said the company believed the $42-per-share cash portion of the offer also did not reflect usg's true value
usg stock fell $1.62{ to $36.50 a share wednesday on the new york stock exchange, indicating investor doubts about the seriousness of desert partners' offer
desert partners responded to usg's decision late wednesday with a letter to the company's board saying it was prepared to negotiate its tender offer
desert partners also chastised usg for considering selling a chunk of the company to a third party, in what the texas group called an attempt to block its takeover bid
we are certain that your stockholders would much prefer your entering into prompt good-faith negotiations with us rather than your continuing to devote effort and expense to defensive tactics that can only erode the value of usg shares,'' desert partners said in its letter
colitti said usg's discussions with another party did not necessarily mean a deal was imminent
desert partners bought its usg shares last year for about $44.30 a share in a previous takeover attempt that fizzled when the texas group was unable to arrange the necessary financing
desert partners also is seeking shareholder purchase rights that take effect friday and that were triggered by the tender offer
the purchase rights, part of usg's ``poison-pill'' takeover defense, would allow all shareholders except desert partners to buy additional new usg stock, making completion of a takeover prohibitively expensive
desert partners has filed a lawsuit in u.s. district court in chicago challenging the legality of the poison pill and has said it will seek to elect six directors to usg's 15-member board at the company's annual meeting in may
usg, based in chicago, is a leading producer of gypsum and building materials, with about 100 plants nationwide
consumer prices rose 8.3 percent in february but only 2.8 percent in the last half of the month, an indication that the government's inflation-fighting program is working, the central bank said
the bank of mexico report wednesday noted the rate was well below the 15.5 percent in january
it said there was the prospect, ``based on the two-week variation of 2.8 percent and the favorable behavior of the principal fiscal and financial variables, of strong further reductions in the inflationary rates.''
as part of its program, called the economic solidarity pact, the government has said prices on officially regulated items will be frozen for the month of march and the peso, which has been steadily devaluing against the dollar, will be held steady
a minimum wage increase was held to 3 percent for the month, below what was expected
the biggest price increases, both for the month of february and the last two weeks of the month, were in furniture and domestic goods, including appliances, soaps and paper articles, the bank said. for the month, prices on those articles jumped 16.2 percent
health and personal items, clothes and shoes and educational services were among others with substantial increases
also rising were rent; some foods, including basics such as cooking oil, processed milk, corn and wheat flour, rice and beans; automobiles; insurance; books, newspapers and school materials; alcoholic beverages, and cigarettes
the cities with the highest increases were matamoros, across the border from brownsville, texas, the northern city of chihuahua and cordoba, in the gulf coast state of veracruz
those where inflation was held down were navojoa, in the northwestern state of sonora; tulancingo, northeast of mexico city; and la paz, in southern baja california
bringing down inflation, which hit a record 159.2 percent for 1987, currently is the main target of the government's economic program
the pact, announced in mid-december, calls on business, industry and labor to cooperate with the government in holding down prices
former merchant banker lord patrick spens was arrested thursday in connection with the case stemming from guinness plc's 1986 takeover of distillers co. plc
fraud squad detectives arrested spens, 45, a former managing director of merchant bankers henry ansbacher and co. ltd., at his home in the southeast england town of gould and took him to a london police station for questioning, scotland yard said
he was the fifth man to be arrested in the case
scotland yard said it is investigating the alleged purchase of 2.15 million guinness shares for 7.6 million pounds, the equivalent of $14 million, from ansbacher clients during the guinness takeover of distillers, a scotch whiskey and gin maker
spens resigned from his 100,000-pound-a-year post at ansbacher in january 1987 under pressure from the bank of england, and told reporters his alleged role in the guinness affair was perceived as an error of judgment
i acted properly and i don't think there was anything inappropriate in what i did,'' he said
police are investigating guinness's tactics during its 2.6 billion-pound takeover of distillers
guinness, a major brewer, has admitted arranging for the illegal repurchase of its stock in an apparent effort to boost its share price and make its cash and stock offer for distillers more attractive than a rival bid from argyll group plc, a supermarket operator
at the center of the investigation is deposed guinness chairman ernest saunders, who remains free on 500,000 pounds bail after being charged with 40 offenses
others facing charges are former morgan grenfell merchant bank director roger seelig and businessmen sir jack lyons and gerald ronson
shopowners in the greek capital pulled down their shutters on thursday to demand the return of the traditional afternoon break abolished by the government last month in favor of continuous working hours
athens' 15,000 twxi drivers also locked up their taxis for a day to protest anti-pollution measures. the ban restricts half of the taxis from entering the center of the city on weekdays according to license plates that end in odd or even numbers
shopkeepers gathered at a downtown theater and later marched to parliament to press their claim for a different set of work hours. large department stores and supermarket chains, however, disregarded the strike call and remained open
the new store-hours, in effect from feb. 1, replaced more than 40 different work-schedules for different kinds of shops, with a continuous 50-hour work week
the stock market headed lower today, giving back some of its recent gains
the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropped 6.63 to 2,067.64 in the first half hour of trading
losers slightly outnumbered gainers in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 505 up, 524 down and 495 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 24.11 million shares as of 10 a.m. on wall street
analysts said traders were disappointed by the dow jones industrial average's inability to make a run at the 2,100 level after reaching new early-1988 highs lately
investors evidently are skeptical about the market's ability to put together a sustained rally less than six months after the october crash
those traders who have been buying are quick to step in and take profits when prices move up, brokers say
a good many market participants are already looking ahead to next week's scheduled monthly report on the trade deficit, trying to figure out whether the figures are likely to maintain the favorable trend of the past couple of reports
today japan said its trade surplus fell in february from its comparable level a year ago
losers among the blue chips included international business machines, down | at 116, and ford motor, down \ at 44~
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks slipped .10 to 151.38. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up .40 at 299.98
on wednesday the dow jones industrial average dropped 6.80 to 2,074.27
advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the nyse, with 871 up, 636 down and 459 unchanged. big board volume totaled 210.90 million shares, against 237.68 million in the previous session. that could be cleared. a version moving on general news wires.</note>
the list of american high-technology goods china is allowed to buy will start expanding again because the reagan administration has determined the chinese are not selling silkworm missiles to iran
china also says it wants a commodity the united states is sending to 64 other countries: peace corps volunteers
under an agreement announced wednesday at the conclusion of a three-day visit by chinese foreign minister wu xueqian, the united states will lift a five-month suspension on liberalization of high-tech products china is permitted to buy from american companies
the restriction was imposed in october to protest what the united states said was sale of chinese silkworm missiles used by iran to attack neutral shipping in the persian gulf
during his visit, wu continued to deny that such sales were ever made directly by china. without commenting on that assertion, the administration said it was satisfied with what the chinese are doing now
we are encouraged by chinese statements and actions regarding iran's acquisition of chinese anti-ship missiles, silkworms,'' state department spokesman charles e. redman said
we have therefore decided to resume the export control liberalization process for china,'' he said
this means experts from the state, commerce and defense departments will resume reviewing the list of high-technology products now banned for sale to china to see if any items can be removed. sales of high-technology products cleared for chinese purchase before last october have been continuing
among the technologies that could be cleared for export to china are computers, electronic components, communications gear and metallurgical processes
the decision removed an irritant in the relationship. ``clearly they weren't happy about it, but we weren't happy about the silkworms,'' said a reagan administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity
wu also assured the united states that china would go along with a united nations resolution banning all arms sales to iran, the u.s. official said. according to u.s. estimates, china sold nearly $1 billion worth of arms to iran in 1987
wu said at a national press club luncheon on wednesday that u.s. officials showed how upset they were about the silkworms by raising the issue 20 times during the three days of talks
he once again denied china ever sold weapons to iran, but when asked if chinese weapons were getting to iran through other countries he said, ``we have no idea.''
he gave an upbeat assessment of relations and called for more trade and more people-to-people contacts between chinese and americans. then he revealed that after years of u.s. requests, china had agreed in principle to accept peace corps volunteers
since the program began in 1961 under president kennedy, many nations' feelings about peace corps projects have reflected their overall view of relations with the united states
in india, for example, the largest country to have had peace corps volunteers, the welcome mat was put out in 1962 when ties were strong and was withdrawn in 1976, when relations soured. there are now peace corps volunteers in 64 countries
the program in china is likely to concentrate on english teaching, but further discussions will be needed to determine how large the peace corps contingent will be and what it will do
it will be good news for our country and i believe for the chinese people if the peace corps can send its volunteers to the most populous nation on earth,'' said sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., who served as a volunteer in the dominican republic in the 1960s. ``we could learn much about each other.''
rep. stephen j. solarz, d-n.y., chairman of the house foreign affairs subcommittee on asia called the peace corps agreement a ``potentially important step.''
i feel confident that these ambassadors for the american way of life will have a positive impact upon ties between the largest nation in the east and the largest nation in the west,'' solarz said
amid the good feeling they said was generated during the wu visit, u.s. officials had little comment on the issue of tibet, where chinese authorities are clashing with groups seeking tibetan independence
redman, the state department spokesman, said secretary of state george p. shultz raised the issue of human rights in tibet, but provided no details
in his press club remarks, wu denounced a proposal by the dalai lama, the religious leader of tibetan buddhists, who is living in exile in india. the dalai lama's proposal includes a withdrawal of chinese troops from tibet
wu said of the dalai lama, ``he is an exile who attacks and smears the people's republic of china.''
jaguar plc said thursday that it sold 3,873 luxury cars in february, a record for that month
compared with the same month a year ago, european exports rose by 28 percent to 554 and sales to the united states and canada jumped 42 percent to 258, the company said in a statement
sales to japan, australia and middle east markets also rose, while british sales were up 40 percent to 1,360, the company said. figures; also moved on general newswires</note>
a four-year dispute over allegations the army was fraudulently overcharged for helicopter spare parts has been resolved, with bell helicopter textron inc. agreeing to pay the government about $88 million, the army said today
the settlement, one of the largest ever in a defense contracting case, grew out of findings by pentagon auditors of numerous accounting and inventory irregularities at the fort worth, texas, company, pentagon sources said wednesday night
maj. phil soucy, an army spokesman, today confirmed a settlement had been reached and was scheduled to be signed on friday. a company statement said, ``we believe a settlement is in the offing.''
the army is fully satisfied with this settlement and believes it has recovered every dime out of this that we can get,'' said soucy
the pentagon sources said that in reaching the settlement, federal prosecutors had agreed to drop any potential criminal or civil charges and that bell helicopter would not acknowledge any wrongdoing
soucy agreed there would be no further prosecution in the case, but said the government had always hoped to strike a reasonable settlement rather than go to trial because of the case's complexity
this was a very complex case that turned on a bad accounting system (at bell helicopter) that was used in connection with contracts worth billions of dollars,'' the spokesman said
reached late wednesday, carl harris, a bell helicopter spokesman, read from a prepared statement which acknowledged there had been ``settlement discussions.''
we believe a settlement is in the offing,'' the statement said. ``we are hopeful it will be soon. however, we are not able to comment until a final agreement is reached. the terms that are currently under discussion will not have a material effect on bell helicopter textron in 1988.''
according to soucy, the settlement will require bell helicopter to pay $69 million directly to the u.s. treasury within the next 30 days. the company also will have to allow the army to assume possession of any or all of a spare parts inventory valued at about $11 million
in addition, bell will forego claims to about $6 million worth of interest on contract progress payments withheld by the army and about $1.5 million in legal fees. offsetting that will be a $1.1 million payment by the army to bell to cover a separate contract that got sidelined in the dispute
when a number of smaller provisions are added in, ``the final value of this settlement is roughly $88 million,'' soucy said
the spokesman said most of the overcharges came as a result of an accounting problem that dealt with the handling of contracts between 1983 and 1985. during the period, bell switched to a computerized accounting and inventory system that had the effect, among other things, of accelerating the company's requests for army progress payments for work performed
bell agreed to implement a new accounting system that met the army's approval in october 1985
the defense contract audit agency had originally identified about $107 million in overcharges by bell. soucy said subsequent investigation ``uncovered a number of overlapping amounts and duplication in the books.''
the overcharges never amounted to $107 million, soucy said, but he declined to estimate how much they did total
soucy said the company had also agreed to implement a business ethics program for its employees and to acknowledge ``our right to audit their books and documents.''
bell helicopter is a wholly owned subsidiary of textron inc., a conglomerate based in providence, r.i. in fiscal 1987, the parent company ranked as the pentagon's 18th largest contractor, with $1.55 billion in defense work
bell helicopter holds contracts from the army for such major helicopter programs as the ah-1 cobra attack helicopter, the uh-1 iroquois utility helicopter and the oh-58d kiowa light helicopter
a house committee is conducting its own investigation of the case. graf pvs bg'ng, chrysler's three-year ...</note>
early contract talks between chrysler corp. and the united auto workers union could help the company and its workers heal their recently-battered relationship, a labor expert said
the fact that both sides appear to be pushing for it reflects a desire for some stability,'' said harley shaiken, a labor and technology expert at the university of california at san diego
the uaw's 140-member national chrysler bargaining council, representing 71,700 workers at 49 local unions, was to meet here today to decide whether to start talks as soon as next month
uaw president owen bieber, in detroit to attend a conference on aging work forces, said he would urge the council to agree to early talks. but he declined to comment on possible establishment of an earlier strike deadline to accompany early talks
chrysler's three-year contract expires sept. 14. talks usually begin in mid-summer, but chrysler asked to start negotiations after its failed attempt to sell its 28,000-worker acustar inc. parts subsidiary
the no. 3 automaker last week canceled plans to sell acustar because of uaw opposition including threatened plant-by-plant strikes that could have crippled production. chrysler instead decided to sell or close four acustar plants within 18 months
in response to the acustar proposal, workers also stopped participating in union-management programs critical to improving productivity and quality and have not returned because of unresolved conflicts with the company, uaw leaders said
uaw vice president marc stepp wanted the council to agree to early talks, which local union leaders said wednesday could help prevent plant closures and movement of work by chrysler to outside companies or countries
i'm positive our membership would be 100 percent in favor of that. as long as we're talking about jobs they would be more than willing,'' said local 1264 official fred o'brien at chrysler's key sterling heights stamping plant
shaiken said an early settlement also would help chrysler and its workers put the acustar conflict behind them ``and basically settle into a pattern for the next few years.''
a key issue in the decision was whether chrysler also would accept an early strike deadline or insist on a target deadline without giving the union the right to strike if no settlement is reached
uaw spokesman peter laarman said the union preferred ``to actually start the clock'' rather than simply set an artificial bargaining deadline
chrysler chief negotiator anthony st. john told the detroit news on tuesday that the company did not want an early strike deadline, but the company would not comment wednesday
chrysler eventually is expected to agree to the pattern contract established last fall at ford motor co. and general motors corp. that includes job protection not included in chrysler's present contract
the gm and ford contracts forbid layoffs except when production falls because of slow sales, make it harder for the companies to move production outside the company or country and forbid plant closings that were not announced before talks started
o'brien said going to the table early would limit the time chrysler has to announce further plant closings and make it easier for the union to battle the possible closings of the four acustar plants
chrysler buys the largest percentage of outside parts of any big three maker _ 70 percent compared with 30 percent at gm and about 50 percent at ford _ and o'brien said workers want to prevent further outsourcing
stepp said he also wants the ford profit-sharing formula in the next contract. ford workers tuesday received profit-sharing checks averaging more than $3,700 from ford's industry-record 1987 profits of $4.6 billion
chrysler has no profit-sharing plan
united auto workers union members in kenosha, wis., have rented a billboard in this detroit enclave to ask chrysler corp. chairman lee iacocca to keep their plant open and save their jobs
chrysler has announced it will close the former american motors corp. car assembly plant in kenosha at the end of the 1988 model year, eliminating 5,500 jobs. chrysler acquired the plant when it bought amc last year
the billboard, located along interstate 75 in hamtramck, says: ```iacocca, keep your word to kenosha!' uaw local 72 kenosha.''
the uaw and wisconsin officials contend chrysler promised to modernize the plant and keep it open for five years of making dodge omni and plymouth horizon subcompacts. chrysler denies it gave any guarantees
we hope this will generate interest and motivate iacocca to change his mind,'' said rudy kuzel, spokesman for local 72
the local paid $4,200 for one month's rent on the sign, which is a few blocks from chrysler headquarters in highland park
we will not crawl off in a corner,'' kuzel said wednesday. ``they want us to lie down, play dead and wait to see how we are going to be buried.''
top chrysler and uaw leaders met in milwaukee on wednesday to discuss the kenosha plant and benefits for workers should it close. unlike other chrysler workers, those at kenosha and other former amc plants aren't covered by the supplemental unemployment benefits provision of the chrysler-uaw contract. thruout</note>
a federal appeals court today lifted a stay that had prevented the arbitrageur accused of threatening to kill ivan boesky from leaving federal detention and moving into a private psychiatric hospital
the 2nd u.s. court of appeals denied the government's motion for a continuation of a stay. the effect is to allow john mulheren to be moved to the private hospital
u.s. district judge whitman knapp had ruled wednesday that a three-hour examination by a court-appointed psychiatrist indicated that mulheren presented no threat to either himself or the community and released him from the metropolitan correctional center
but assistant u.s. attorney robert gage said he opposed releasing mulheren to the private hospital, and obtained a ruling from the 2nd u.s. court of appeals staying the matter until today's ruling
the government had argued that the private facility, the carrier foundation in montgomery township, n.j., was not secure enough to house mulheren, the senior partner at jamie securities co
however, knapp said, ``he's no danger at the moment, and if he's kept under proper surveillance there's no reason to believe he will become dangerous.''
mulheren, carrying a loaded assault rifle, was arrested feb. 18 by the police outside his rumson, n.j., home
he is being held on a criminal complaint that he threatened to kill admitted insider-trader boesky and michael davidoff, boesky's former head trader. the men have reportedly implicated mulheren in possible securities law violations
mulheren's lawyers argue that he is a manic depressive who had failed to take his lithium, a drug used to control impulses, the day of his arrest
knapp said he could not explain mulheren's actions, but agreed with the psychiatrist that they were an ``aberration.''
one of his defense lawyers, peter bennett, said wednesday that mulheren had not been getting the drug properly while in federal custody
