grain and soybean futures closed moderately lower thursday on the chicago board of trade as traders showed little buying interest
of overriding concern was an expectation that a march 31 government report on spring plantings will show a broad increase in crop acreage, said ted mao, grain specialist with shearson lehman hutton inc
other maret pressures include the large soybean crop now being harvested in south america, an increase in world vegetable-oil production and the lackluster prospects for new grain export sales to the soviet union in the near term, mao said
it's a combination of all that in the atmosphere of a market that's been kind of on the defensive and it's just feeding on itself temporarily,'' mao said
