after almost 70 years of tallying livestock sales at the historic pens of the fort worth stockyards, the livestock market news service said its reports are headed for their last roundup
government officials have issued daily or weekly reports on sales at the pens since around 1920, but said wednesday that so few cattle and hogs are sold in the city still nicknamed cowtown that regular sales reports will be halted march 31
the oldest cattle pens in fort worth date to 1887. but as urban growth has swallowed the stockyards, cattle raisers have turned away from the maze of traffic lights and freeways to competing auctions in small towns, said rick wahrmund, statewide director of the livestock market news service
ronnie steen, who has been reporting stockyard sales since 1976, said sales have dropped to between 200 and 300 cattle a week for months, from an average of about 5,000 weekly in 1976. daily auctions have long since been replaced with a weekly cattle auction on mondays
we don't have enough cattle to know what the market is,'' steen said. sales volumes of at least 500 are needed to establish clear market trends for farmers, ranchers and others who use the information
the u.s. department of agriculture began issuing daily livestock reports from the fort worth stockyards around 1920, when annual sales regularly topped 6 million cattle, 1 million hogs and 400,000 sheep
retailing giant gb-inno-bm s.a., one of belgium's biggest companies, proclaimed a ``poison pill'' takeover defense thursday to thwart potentially hostile acquirers
the company said it issued new bonds with warrants to five friendly companies, which if fully exercised would create 6.1 million new shares, inflating the total shares outstanding by nearly 20 percent to 37.1 million shares. this would make it difficult for a hostile bidder to buy the retailer
its stock value soared 51 percent last week on rumors that a takeover bid might be imminent
since belgium does not have any disclosure rules for investors in publicly traded companies, it was not clear whether a takeover might be planned
the company said it knew of no parties interested in acquiring it, but undertook the takeover defense in the interest of protecting shareholder value and supporting management policies. it said the unusual movement of the shares in recent days had ``created uncertainty.''
the move by gb-inno-bm came against a background of sudden management uncertainty caused by a hostile takeover fight surrounding belgium's biggest company, societe generale de belgique s.a. italian investor carlo de benedetti has been vying for control of societe generale
a unit of pirelli spa arranged a $2.3 billion credit line thursday through sbci swiss bank corp. to finance its takeover bid for firestone tire and rubber co., sbci said
veere inc., a unit of pirelli and pirelli societe internationale sa, will use $1.93 billion dollars to finance the $58 dollar-a-share bid for the u.s. tire maker, the bank said
the bid by the milan-based tire maker was announced monday after being rumored for more than a week
the remainder of the credit line will go to refinance ``certain obligations of firestone,'' the bank said. it did not elaborate
the bank also did not state the terms of the credit facility, which is being fully underwritten by swiss bank corp. and credit suisse
pirelli has said it will spin off part of firestone to france's michelin &amp; co. but pirelli's offer was made after firestone already had agreed to sell its tire business to japan's bridgestone corp. for about $1.25 billion by setting up a joint venture that would give the japanese company a 75 percent stake in firestone's factories and retail network
analysts have said they expect bridgestone to make a counter offer
