share prices rose sharply on the london stock exchange thursday after britain's top treasury official, chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson, said a further steep rise in the pound against the west german mark could not be sustained
trading was heavy in selected stocks, with oil shares setting a fast pace on good gains in crude oil prices
at the close, the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was up 19.3 points at 1,834.6
the pound surged on world currency markets monday and tuesday after the bank of england stopped selling pounds to prevent the british currency from rising too sharply. the pound retreated wednesday and thursday when the central bank renewed its pound sales
lawson's comments in parliament calmed fears that a strong pound, which increases the price of exports, would make british companies less competitive, dealers said
they said there was a general feeling in the market that the british government will not let the pound go much above 3.10 marks without taking steps to halt the rise
the pound fell in late trading to 3.06 marks from 3.08 marks late wednesday. report are for week ended tuesday. all other figures are for the week ended wednesday.</note>
assets of the nation's 240 money market mutual funds rose $1.41 billion in the latest week, setting a record, the investment company institute said thursday
the rise, to $280.06 billion in the seven-day period ended wednesday, followed a $1.37 billion drop in the funds' assets the previous week to a revised $278.65 billion, according to the washington-based mutual fund trade group
the funds' assets previous record high was $280.02 billion in the week ended feb. 24
the investment company institute said that in the latest week, assets of 210 general purpose funds fell $306.5 million to $81.50 billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds rose $1.29 billion to $116.39 billion, and assets of 113 institutional funds rose $423.7 million to $82.17 billion
the seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in the week ended tuesday to 6.05 percent from 6.10 percent the previous week, according to donoghue's money fund report, a trade journal based in holliston, mass
the 30-day average yield fell to 6.12 percent from 6.17 percent, donoghue's said
the average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 43 days, down from 45 days, donoghue's said
separately, the newsletter bank rate monitor said its survey of 100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield available on money market accounts fell to 5.73 percent as of wednesday from 5.74 percent a week earlier
the north palm beach, fla.-based newsletter said the effective annual yield available on special savings accounts, called super now accounts, remained unchanged at 5.17 percent
bank rate monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.83 percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 6.85 percent the previous week. yields were 7.15 percent on 1-year cds, down from 7.16 percent; 7.55 percent on 2{-year cds, down from 7.57 percent; and 8.02 percent on 5-year cds, down from 8.04 percent
a joint board of directors for hollywood's two top acting unions voted to authorize a strike for march 21 against television and radio advertisers, with cable television residuals a top sticking point
the vote by the directors for the screen actors guild and the american federation of radio and television artists came late wednesday, actors guild spokesman mark locher said thursday
in 1987, actors were paid about $400 million for radio and television commercials, according to advertisers. the unions said the members earned $520 million
it's our bread-and-butter contract,'' said locher. ``it certainly means survival to most actors between jobs.''
if actors strike it will be the second labor action by a hollywood talent union this month. the writers guild of america struck studios and producers on sunday
in new york, chief advertising group negotiator john mcguinn warned thursday that a strike could last as long as six months, and urged advertisers to resist signing any interim agreements with the unions. mcguinn made his comments at a television advertising seminar
talks between sag-aftra and the joint policy committee of the american association of advertising agencies and the association of national advertisers have been held in manhattan. the two management agencies represent 400 advertisers and about 300 agencies, spokeswoman dorothy forget said
negotiations for a new three-year contract began january 11, with the old contract expiring on feb. 6. the joint union membership voted 93 percent for a strike authorization on march 2, and talks broke off on march 7
the joint sag-aftra membership is more than 100,000. the unions negotiate jointly on the issue of commercials
advertising negotiator mcguinn and guild national executive secretary ken orsatti, the chief bargaining agent for the actors, both cited the matter of residuals from commercials shown on cable television as one unresolved point
actors currently receive no residuals from cable television showings of their commercials after they have earned their first $1,000 in payments from showings on regular, prime-time television
orsatti noted that virtually all commercials chosen for cable television have met the $1,000 requirement
orsatti also said advertisers want to take away the 10-year-old cost of living clause in the commercial contract. he said a cost of living raise has been the only kind of increase actors have had in the last two contracts
deteriorating viewership of network television over the past six years has kept other commercial residual increases in check, orsatti said
management has used the argument that the erosion in the network area was caused by cable,'' orsatti said, ``but they are unwilling to consider any formula which restructures cable payments so that the performer has an opportunity to somewhat make up for those dollars lost on the network side.''
orsatti said the union wants to negotiate actors' payments for commercials shown on cable tv based on subscribers, wit an actor receiving a one-day session fee of $333 for the first 20 million subscribers, and another session fee for each additional 30 million subscribers thereafter
mcguinn said the advertisers offered to pay one session fee for 13 weeks of cable use, regardless of any previous use of the commercial on broadcast newtorks. he said the union's proposal would be too costly
orsatti said several formulas have been discussed
union members on thursday accused eastern airline's parent company of trying to financially cripple the air carrier to win wage concessions
the primary focus of our new management seems to have strayed from safety to cutting operating costs,'' eastern pilot john knudson told a rally of 1,500 union members and supporters
union representatives said frank lorenzo, chairman of eastern's parent texas air corp., has stripped eastern of valuable assets and has hired merrill lynch to amass a $200 million strike fund
under lorenzo, eastern management also has asked pilots to fly in unsafe conditions and has harassed flight attendants, union officials said
a three-year contract with the airline's 12,000 members of the machinists union expired at the end of december. negotiations have failed to produce a new agreement and the issues are now in federal mediation
lorenzo purchased the miami-based airline in 1986. giant texas air also owns continental airlines, people express, new york air and other aviation subsidiaries
these management practices of frank lorenzo are in direct contrast to the policies of the other six major carriers, and they will spread like a cancer to the rest of the industry if they are ignored now,'' knudson said
paula musto, a spokeswoman for eastern, said the rally was a union attempt to gain public support during contract negotiations
we feel that it's public grandstanding while we're in the midst of contract negotiations with our largest union,'' ms. musto said
protesters, who rallied a block from the philadelphia offices of eastern and merrill lynch, said they did not want boycotts of either company but wanted to raise public awareness about what they called union-busting practices
demonstrations will be scheduled in other cities, including houston, denver and los angeles, said joseph b. uehlein, an afl-cio official who is coordinating a national campaign against lorenzo and merrill lynch
eastern has sold the airline's most valuable assets, such as wide-body planes and its computerized reservation system, to subsidiaries for less than market value, uehlein and other union officials said
in complaining about the airline's safety concerns, knudson, who has been with eastern for 21 years, said he was grounded for six days in september 1987 after refusing to fly a plane with a broken altitude alert
the warning device, which tells pilots when they have strayed from a set altitude, is required on all civil passenger planes, he said. knudson said he was reinstated when eastern failed to show sufficient cause for his grounding
knudson also said his co-pilot had been asked to fly more than the 30 hours allowed during a seven-day period
nancy tauss, a flight attendant and vice president of the transport workers union, said eastern management had searched flight attendants and fired others for technicalities
our people go to work each day not knowing if they're going to be fired,'' she said
ms. musto said work rules, ignored for years, were being enforced recently
of eastern's 32,000 employees, 7,000 belong to the transport workers union and 3,600 belong to the air line pilots association, union officials said. their contracts expire later this year
eastern lost $182 million on total revenue of $4.4 billion in 1987 and has lost $500 million since airline deregulation in 1978, ms. musto said. since jan. 20, sted jan. 8.</note>
the stock market took its sharpest drop in nearly two months thursday, giving back some of the gains from its early-1988 rally
the selloff hit both the blue chips and the smaller secondary stocks that had been especially strong of late
the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 48.24 to 2,026.03, its largest loss since falling 57.20 on jan. 20
declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 3 to 1 on the new york stock exchange, with 419 up, 1,202 down and 382 unchanged
big board volume totaled 197.26 million shares, against 210.90 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index fell 2.56 to 148.92
analysts said traders were disappointed by the dow jones industrial average's inability to make a run at the 2,100 level after reaching new highs for the year on tuesday
investors evidently are skeptical about the market's ability to put together a sustained rally less than six months after the october crash
those traders who have been buying are quick to step in and take profits when prices move up, brokers say
a good many market participants are already looking ahead to next week's scheduled monthly report on the trade deficit, trying to figure out whether the figures are likely to maintain the favorable trend of the past couple of reports
on thursday japan said its trade surplus fell in february from its comparable level a year ago
point-plus losers among the blue chips included international business machines, down 2~ at 113}; ford motor, down 1} at 43]; alcan aluminium, down 1~ at 28]; merck, down 3| at 160|; international paper, down 2[ at 43}, and dupont, down 2| at 84\
afg industries fell 5 to 31|. forstmann little &amp; co. said it had decided after studying the matter not to make an offer to acquire afg
on the plus side, colt industries jumped 4~ to 18[ in active trading. the company said it agreed to be acquired by a group including its top executives for $17 a share
k mart dropped { to 34] after trading higher for most of the session on the company's report that earnings for its fiscal fourth quarter ended jan. 27 were $1.58 a share, up from $1.41 in the like period a year earlier
as measured by wilshire associates' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market lost $39.96 billion, or 1.50 percent, in value
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 226.80 million shares
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials fell 6.21 to 306.25, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index was down 5.22 at 263.84
the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market dropped 3.52 to 376.76. at the american stock exchange, the market value index closed at 296.00, down 3.58
gold and platinum futures prices made strong gains thursday, partly in response to a rise in the price of crude oil to $16 a barrel for the first time this month, analysts said
on other markets, stock-index futures fell sharply; grain and soybean prices retreated broadly; and livestock and meat futures were mixed
the sharp increase in energy futures prices on a rumored production cut by the organization of petroleum exporting countries had inflationary implications that supported precious metals futures, analysts said
there's a view in the market that inflation's going to be picking up toward the end of the year and that inflation is going to be more of a concern than recession at year end,'' said fred demler, metals economist for drexel burnham lambert inc. in new york
in addition, talk of physical tightness developing in the cash platinum market after two quarters of price weakness helped spur buying of platinum futures, and some of that buying interest spilled over into the gold market, demler said
demler said the gold and platinum markets were oversold and due for an upside correction to bring futures prices more in line with reality
silver futures declined slightly
on new york's commodity exchange, gold settled $7 to $8.40 higher with the contract for delivery in april at $444.50 a troy ounce; silver was 3.3 cents to 3.7 cents lower with march at $6.265 a troy ounce
platinum settled $16.80 to $18.50 higher on the new york mercantile exchange with april at $498.10
the rumors of opec production cuts that fueled the jump in energy futures on the new york mercantile exchange were later denied, but oil prices fell only slightly from their highs of the day
market players still expect opec nations to take measures aimed at boosting prices, said bob baker, an analyst for prudential-bache securities inc. in new york
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 44 cents to 51 cents higher with april at $16 a barrel; heating oil was .72 cent to 1.07 cents higher with april at 43.93 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .66 cent to 1.14 cents higher at 45.14 cents a gallon
inflationary fears also contributed to a sharp drop in stock-index futures on the chicago mercantile exchange, analysts said
the chicago mercantile exchange's contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 6.75 points lower at 262.90, nearly a full point below the spot index
grain and soybean futures closed broadly lower on the chicago board of trade with little buying interest in the face of bearish fundamentals
traders expect a march 31 government report on spring plantings will show a general increase in crop acreage, said ted mao, grain specialist with shearson lehman hutton inc
other market pressures include the large soybean crop now being harvested in south america, an increase in world vegetable-oil production and the lackluster prospects for new grain export sales to the soviet union in the near term, mao said
wheat settled 4} cents to 9 cents lower with march at $2.90 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with march at $1.97} a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 6 cents lower with march at $1.81\ a bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents to 6 cents lower with march at $6.03} a bushel
live cattle futures finished slightly lower on the chicago mercantile exchange on expectations of increased slaughters next week, analysts said. feeder cattle were mostly higher
pork futures retreated on ideas that ham supplies were sufficient to satisfy eastertime demand, said tom o'hare, analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
live cattle were .08 cent lower to .02 cent higher with april at 72.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .48 cent higher with march at 81.55 cents a pound; hogs were .28 cent lower to .05 cent higher with april at 43.32 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .50 cent to .75 cent lower with march at 51.65 cents a pound
the dollar was mixed thursday as trading in the other major currencies continued to dominate foreign-exchange markets
gold prices advanced sharply amid a confluence of factors. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price of $442.50 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. est, up $6.35 an ounce from $436.15 late wednesday
the british pound, which has soared in recent trading sessions, gave up some ground to profit-taking after britain's chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson said sterling would be unable to sustain a further advance
in london, the pound fell to $1.8435 from $1.8460 late wednesday. in later new york trading, sterling slipped to $1.8462 from $1.8475 late wednesday
with the slippage in the pound, traders turned not to the dollar, but to other currencies, said james mcgroarty, a vice president at discount corp
the french franc fell and the west german mark gained following rumors that french president francois mitterrand might not run for re-election in may, mcgroarty said
the dollar has been very much sidetracked by all this,'' he said
he said trading in the dollar remained listless as the market awaited the release of several economic reports from washington: retail sales and producer price figures on friday, and balance of trade numbers next week
in europe, currency dealers said the mark gained against most other major currencies in late trading after the bank of france withdrew its support for the franc against the mark
in tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 128.20 japanese yen from 128.08 yen at wednesday's close. later, in london, the dollar fell back to 127.85 yen, and in new york, it rose marginally to 127.955 yen from 127.95 yen late wednesday
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late wednesday's prices, included: 1.66345 west german marks, down from 1.66895; 1.3785 swiss francs, down from 1.37905; 5.6665 french francs, up from 5.6530; 1,236.625 italian lire, up from 1,232.50; and 1.25685 canadian dollars, down from 1.2537
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late wednesday, included: 1.6640 west german marks, down from 1.6685; 1.3785 swiss francs, unchanged; 5.6725 french francs, up from 5.6485; 1.8720 dutch guilders, down from 1.8750; 1,236.625 italian lire, up from 1,231.50; and 1.2564 canadian dollars, up from 1.2532
gold prices surged amid a variety of factors, said stephen platt, an analyst with dean witter reynolds inc. in chicago
there was nervousness in bullion markets about the upcoming economic reports and about rising energy prices, platt said
the benchmark u.s. crude oil jumped 51 cents to $16 a barrel on the new york mercantile exchange after reports that officials of the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries were studying a plan to cut production
rising energy prices are believed to be a harbinger of higher inflation, and gold is considered a safe haven during inflationary periods
gold also rose because it may have been oversold recently, platt said
bullion soared $7 on the commodity exchange in new york, closing at $443.20 a troy ounce
in london, gold jumped to a late bid price of $443 a troy ounce, up from $436.50 bid late wednesday
in zurich, switzerland, it rose to $442.50 bid from $437 bid late wednesday
earlier, in hong kong, gold closed at $438.42 bid, up from $438.01 bid at wednesday's close
silver bullion rose in london to a late bid price of $6.36 a troy ounce, from $6.31 bid late wednesday. but it fell on the commodity exchange, slipping 3.3 cents to $6.265
the two broadest measures of the nation's money supply fell in late february, the federal reserve board reported thursday
the fed said the measure known as m2 fell to a seasonally adjusted $2,947.5 billion in the week ended feb. 29 from $2,953.1 billion the previous week
an even broader measure, m3, fell to a seasonally adjusted $3,722.4 billion from $3,724.4 billion
the narrowest measure of the money supply, m1, fell to a seasonally adjusted $755.1 billion from a revised $762.1 billion
m1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. m3 is m2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000
in judging its monetary policy, the fed has indicated it is monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the difference between short- and long-term interest rates. it also has shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply measures
the fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for m2 and m3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. the fed has not set a specific target range for m1 since early 1987
in other reports:
_the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and industrial loans at major new york city banks rose $1.3 billion, compared with a decline of $1.07 billion a week earlier
_the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal reserve system at the discount window averaged $378 million a day in the week ended wednesday, up from $187 million a day in the previous week
_the federal reserve said net free reserves averaged $615 million in the latest two-week period, down from a revised $879 million in the previous two-week period
_the federal reserve bank of st. louis reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $271.2 billion in the two-week period ended wednesday, down from $272.4 billion two weeks earlier
the state-owned rover group said it lost money in 1987, but far less than it lost in 1986
the latest shortfall totaled 26.8 million pounds, or $49.3 million _ a fraction of the record 892.1 million-pound net loss the previous year, before it sold its leyland bus and truck divisions
at the time the 1986 loss was the equivalent of $1.09 billion
the group achieved an operating profit of 27.9 million pounds, or $51.3 million, in 1987, its best result for 19 years, the company announcement said. last year, the group posted an operating loss of 355.6 million pounds
it's land rover division surged ahead last year, increasing operating profits from 1.6 million pounds in 1986 to 22.5 million pounds, or $41.4 million, in 1987
the group's largest company, austin rover, turned an operating loss of 166.6 million pounds into a profit of 5.1 million pounds, or $9.4 million, last year
the group, whose models include the popular rover sterling and range rover, exported nearly 174,000 vehicles for just over 1 billion pounds, or $1.85 billion _ a 69 percent increase over 1986
total sales at 513,000 vehicles were up 11 percent, the company said
farmers group inc., a leading insurer, said thursday its board unanimously rejected an unsolicited $63 per share, or $4.4 billion, tender offer from the u.s. susidiary of british bat industries plc
farmers also said it was urging shareholders to reject the offer
the action by farmers had been expected since the company has consistently spurned bat's overtures since the the british company proposed a friendly $60-per-share merger in january
bat's louisville, ky.-based unit, batus inc., launched the sweetened hostile tender offer a week ago after farmers' repeatedly refused to meet and discuss a merger. the tender offer expires march 30
batus had no comment on the rejection by farmers
the price being offered by batus is still well below the $70 to $80 per share that some analysts say farmers should be able to attract, although batus officials have insisted their offer represents a fair price
farmers' stock was trading in the mid-$40 range before batus made it initial proposal. it closed thursay at $60 per share, down 75 cents
meantime, the companies in the past week have filed a flurry of legal actions in the takeover fight
farmers filed suit in federal court in reno, nev., where it is incorporated, challenging batus' efforts to place a proposal before shareholders at the farmer's may 20 annual meeting urging that merger negotiations be held
batus has filed suit in nevada, nebraska and south carolina seeking to block enforcement of laws restricting takeovers in those states
wang laboratories inc.'s stock fell more than 20 percent thursday as the company said customers were delaying orders, cutting into the company's projected revenue and profitability
wang's class b stock fell $3.50 a share to $12.87{ in consolidated trading on the american stock exchange
in response to questions from securities analysts, wang said it expected its revenue in the third fiscal quarter ending march 31 to be up 4 percent to 6 percent from the year-earlier level, instead of 10 percent to 12 percent as previously projected
wang also said it expects third-quarter profits to be about 3 percent of revenue, instead of 3 percent to 5 percent as previously projected
the lowell, mass.-based maker of minicomputers and office-automation equipment said it continues to expect to achieve its goals for revenue and profits for the full fiscal year, indicating that orders expected for the third quarter will be recorded in the fourth quarter instead
wang also said its new family of wang integrated image systems, which allow users to manipulate data, text and images on the same terminals, were proceeding as planned and ``generating a higher-than-expected level of customer interest.''
fred wang, the president and chief executive, said some of the slowing of orders may have come from customers' doubts about the economic outlook, which has brightened recently
a powerful house committee chairman told the secretary of energy thursday the reagan administration's plan to sell the naval petroleum reserves in california and wyoming ``doesn't look good.''
privatization means let somebody have it so they can make some money,'' rep. jamie whitten, d-miss., told secretary john herrington, after recounting how he stopped the sale of the elk hills oil reserve in california as a young member of congress in 1943
i have a long memory,'' said whitten, who is chairman of the appropriations committee and as such, a member of the subcommittee on energy and water development before which herrington appeared. according to his account, the potential 1943 buyer would have taken oil from the field for immediate use and repaid the navy at such a slow rate that it would have taken 450 years to square accounts
though still called naval petroleum reserves, the two oil fields have been controlled by the energy department in commercial production since the mid-1970s
whitten's objections were seconded by the ranking republican on the subcommittee, rep. john t. myers of indiana, who said, ``i've never understood why you wanted to sell that and pump in new oil'' into storage in the strategic petroleum reserve in lousiana and texas
the elk hills field, 22 percent owned by chevron corp. and the rest by the government, is ``not a reserve, it's a cash cow'' being milked for money by a revenue-hungry congress, herrington said
we had no business selling oil from there (elk hills) at $8 and $10 a barrel'' in the price collapse of 1986, said herrington. but the department did not have authority to suspend production as a private owner would have done, he said
the administration's budget request assumes that sale of the two oil fields will bring in $3.5 billion over the next two fiscal years. the department's consultants said proceeds could be $4.3 billion, and herrington told the subcommittee the amount ``could be as high as $7 billion'' if congress allows the sale
you're going to have to get 3 million barrels a day or 4 million barrels a day into the economy on an asap basis and you can't do that at elk hills,'' said herrington
thus, he said, it makes sense to sell the naval reserves and use the money to buy oil for the louisiana-texas stockpile because elk hills can produce only about 115,000 barrels a day and the teapot dome reserve in wyoming can produce only about 3,000 barrels a day
the salt domes of the gulf coast now hold 540 million barrels of crude oil, roughly the equivalent of 90 days of imports, and can pump oil to refineries at the rate of 3.5 million barrels a day
if the sale goes through, the department proposes to use the money to increase additions to the strategic reserve from 50,000 barrels a day to 100,000 barrels a day
